## Chapter 1: People Moving Through Time

### The G.I. Generation's Dominance (1989)

- **1989 Presidential Inauguration**: George Bush Sr.'s parade featured two major generational floats—Kennedy's 1961 inaugural and Bush's own
- Bush, Kennedy, and others represented the **G.I. Generation** (born 1901-1924), celebrating their arrival into national leadership in the 1960s
- By 1989, aging G.I.s realized this would be their last moment of triumph—"last time America would salute the triumphant Presidential arrival of a World War II combat vet"
- **30-year presidential monopoly (1961-1990)**: Age range 17 to 43 at Pearl Harbor Sunday, all belonging to one generation—unprecedented in American history

### G.I. Generation Lifecycle Imprint

- G.I.s have been "confident and rational problem-solvers" across all life phases
- Youth: victorious soldiers, built Rose Bowl highways; later: rocket builders and Presidents in democracy's economic triumph
- **"Lost Generation"**: Era of public engagement, they brought "cheerfulness, public spirit, and collective muscle" to every problem
- Older generations saw them as powerful but complacent; younger generations (post-1960) viewed them as friendly but overly "made in the U.S.A."
- G.I. contempt for America now seems like lost dose of virtue—no more "right stuff" or certainty about the future without G.I.s at the helm

### The Transformation of Old Age

- The term **"senior citizen"** emerged only with the first G.I. presidents—a new concept in modern vocabulary
- Early 1960s elderly: America's unhappiest, loneliest, and poorest bracket—politically Republican-leaning and hostile to government
- By late 20th century: complete reversal—over-65s are now happy, socially assertive, wealthy (thanks to inflation-indexed government benefits)
- **Elderly poverty rate**: Dropped from highest of any age bracket (mid-1960s) to well below children and young adults today
- Circa-1990 age groups: heaviest-voting, most Democratic-leaning, overwhelmingly support big government
- **Key insight**: This transformation reflects generational aging, not demographic trends alone

> "Separate generations are aging in place."

### The Four Living Generations (1969 and 1990)

- **Railroad analogy**: Lifecycle as a single track with multiple trains (generations) rolling through phase-of-life stations
- At any station, we see different trains arriving—each looks different from the next
- **Replacing the G.I.s** at midlife station: the **Silent Generation** (born 1925-1942)
  - Too late for WWII combat, too early to feel heat of Vietnam draft
  - "Unobtrusive children of depression and war"—conformist "Lonely Crowd" generation
  - Grace Kelly, Elvis Presley, Hugh Hefner, Gloria Steinem, Gary Hart, Mike Dukakis, Jim Henson, MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour
  - By 1990: sentimental pluralists, easy touches on every issue
  - Dominate helping professions, provided America with most committed civil rights advocates and public interest lawyers
  - Known as sexual swingers, feminists, out-of-the-closet gays—a quarter century ago unassociated with peak adult power

### The Boom Generation

- **At the rising-adult station**: The **Boomers** (born 1943-1960)—"best-known of all American generations"
- Babies of optimism and hubris: Beaver Cleaver and Mouseketeer, prom queens, school SAT scores declined 17 straight years
- Student strikers, flower-child hippies, draft resisters, Hamilton Jordan and Jody Powell, yuppies, singles avoiding attachment
- Gilda Radner, Oprah Winfrey, grass-roots evangelicals, Lamaze parents, Oliver North, William Bennett, out-bran eaters, Perrier drinkers, Earth Firsters, antidrug crusaders
- **Typical Boom couple (age 40 around 1970)**: Had been married almost two decades, with children nearing college age—family income rising swiftly
- Emulated elders, envied juniors, disliked suggestion that any one set of values was superior to another
- Contrast with "thirtysomething" couple of today: woman worked since college, possibly married, aspiring to buy possibility stagnating/falling behind inflation—at most two children
- Values: intensely self-immersed, remote from envy of people older or younger than themselves
- **Self-satisfaction**: High and remarkably unrelated to income or family status

### The Thirteenth Generation

- **At the coming-of-age station**: Wearing "shades, averting the critical glare of the adult world"
- First babies American women took pills *not* to have; children of sharply rising divorce and poverty rates
- Pupils in experimental classrooms without walls, latchkey kids, precocious Gary Coleman and Tatum O'Neal, pubescents of sex-obsessed 1970s
- Valley girls, college students criticized by one blue-ribbon commission after another
- Post-AIDS social scene singles, inner-city drug entrepreneurs, "boomerang" children living at home after college
- Best-qualified recruits in military history, hard-nosed invaders of Panama, defenders of Persian Gulf oil
- Late 1960s: 21-year-olds were considered radicals, the conscience of America, drew respect of adult world they were attacking
- Today: kids in early twenties recognize America is a most Republican-leaning age bracket
- **Associate smoothly with elders**, who express disappointment in how they are turning out
- **"13er Generation"**: No consensus name, labeled by reputation as "bad"—also recognition that it is 13th since American independence
- Last train taking on passengers—adult America heralding its departure

### The Millennial Generation Emerging

- **Tots entering childhood**: Today's collegians would hardly recognize
- Brief childhood vignettes: "Everybody's Baby" Jessica McClure (Midland well rescue), diapered stars of *Raising Arizona* and *Three Men and a Baby*
- KinderCare Kids, "Baby M" and Hilary Morgan at center of custody disputes, inner-city kindergartners in uniform
- "Doonesbury" kids saved from crack house, George Bush's Hispanic grandchildren, high school Class of 2000 (President Bush, former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, others already engaged in smarter, better-behaving, more civic-spirited wave)
- **Any community treating children this way in late 1960s** would have been condemned as culturally totalitarian
- By early 1980s, adults began to look upon childhood quite differently—spawning a new Millennial Generation (first will come of age around year 2000)
- **Adding close to four million new passengers every year**—two trains reaching the end of the line: very old Lost, peers of Eisenhower, Truman, and F. Scott Fitzgerald; and smattering of supercentenarians from Franklin Roosevelt's Missionary Generation

### Generational Constellation Framework

**Figure 1-1: Living American Generations (1969)**
- Progressive (1843-1859): Age 109+
- Missionary (1860-1882): Age 86-108
- Lost (1883-1900): Age 68-85
- G.I. (1901-1924): Age 44-67
- Silent (1925-1942): Age 26-43
- Boom (1943-1960): Age 8-25
- Thirteenth (1961-1981): Age 0-7
- Millennial (1982-?): not alive

> "Leaving aside the very old and very young, America today has four generations that form what we call a generational 'constellation,' the lineup of living generations ordered by phase of life."

- Constellation always aging, shifting, moving up one lifecycle notch roughly every 22 years
- Youths come of age, rising adults reach midlife, midlifers move on (or reach advanced old age), new set of babies enters youth
- **"Whenever the constellation shifts up by one notch, the behavior and attitudes of each phase of life change character entirely."**
- This transformation happened between late 1960s and now; also between WWII and Vietnam, WWI and WWII, Gay Nineties and WWI—indeed, through all of American history

### The Lifecycle as Historical Snapshots

- Generational constellation establishes snapshot impression of American lifecycle at any moment (17th century through present)
- In any decade, childhood, young adulthood, middle age, and old age composite impressions derive from very different generational lifecycles
- Placing together these snapshots across decades reveals evolving American lifecycle—picture becomes "hopelessly confusing"
- **"In this book, we suggest looking at the American lifecycle as it has actually been lived by each generation, from childhood through old age."**
- Using railroad analogy: viewing lifecycle from perspective of *trains* rather than *stations*
- At any moment, we see as many different lifecycle stories as the number of generations then alive
- **Great generations as people moving through time**: each possessing a distinctive sense of self shaped by "age location"—its own life, its explanation shaped by epochal events during its lifecycle

### Age Location and Peer Personality

- **"Age location"**: Phase of life experiences separating youth from adulthood
- During childhood and especially during coming-of-age, each age location produces a **"peer personality"**—a set of collective behavioral traits and attitudes expressed throughout generation's lifecycle trajectory
- Because peer personality of each generational type shows new manifestations in each phase of life, and because determined by the constellation into which it is born (pattern forever shifting), the ongoing interplay of peer personalities gives history a dynamic quality

> "How children are raised affects how they later parent. How students are taught affects how they later teach. How youths come of age shapes their later exercise of leadership—which, in turn, substantially defines the coming-of-age experiences of others."

### Push and Pull Between Generations

- This push and pull moves history continuously with other alternating patterns: public action vs. private introspection, secularism vs. spiritualism, cultural suffocation vs. liberation, fragmentation vs. consensus, overprojection vs. underprojection of children
- **Startling pattern emerges**: A recurring cycle of four distinct types of peer personalities, arriving in the same repeating sequence
- From 16th century forward, cycle has been constantly turning, showing only one aberration when it skipped a beat (omitted hubristic G.I. type)
- Each generation has its own unique story, shaped by trends (rising living standards, improving technology, expanding population, shifting geography), but we see similar human dramas repeating again and again

### Four Generational Types in Recurring Cycle

- Generations come in cycles, moreover, so do their collective moods
- **Constellational era**: Each of the four possible layerings of peer personalities possesses its own recognizable *mood*
- A generation layer themes in place, one after the other (Lost, G.I., Silent, Boom, 13th, and so on)
- Mood of a constellation itself shifts over time—constellation with outer-focused doers in midlife and inner-focused moralists is young, will set a national mood of boldness
- Opposite positioning: Some constellations encourage national mood of patience; others encourage rejuvenation
- Some fight wars well, others badly; some defer crisis, others congeal it

> "Looking back over American history, we find a correspondence between recurring patterns in generational constellations and recurring types of historical events."

### Historical Correspondence with Generational Cycles

- **Four great periods of colonial emergencies** culminating in the Glorious Revolution of 1689; the American Revolution; the Civil War; and twin emergencies of the Great Depression and World War II
- All occurred at almost exactly the same constellational moment—just as first Boom-type midlifers were entering elderhood and the G.I.-type youths were coming of age
- (The Civil War occurred nearly on schedule, roughly a half generation early)
- **Five great spiritual awakenings**: From the Puritans' "City on a Hill" (1630s) to the Boomers' "Consciousness Revolution" (late 1960s)
- Without exception, all five began at the same constellational moment—just as first G.I.-type midlifers were entering elderhood and first Boom-type children were coming of age

### Recurring Cycle Helps Forecast the Future

- This recurring cycle of generational types and moods helps us not only to understand the past, but also to forecast how the future of America may well unfold over the next century
- Cycle delivers no specific timetable about wars, stock-market crashes, or scientific discoveries
- **Does offer approximate calendar and itinerary of major changes** that America can expect in the next decade and century—and important predictions about how today's children will grow up, today's adults will grow old, and today's elders will be remembered

### Two Related Theories: Age-Location Perspective and Social Moments

**Theory merges two traditions of scholarship:**

1. **"Age-location" perspective on history** (building on "generations approach"—mostly European school of sociology by Karl Mannheim, José Ortega y Gasset, and others)
   - Most historical narratives tend to separate age group, especially the midlife or leadership age group, as a continuous, living entity over time
   - Reader rarely learns how earlier events, experienced at younger ages, influence later behavior at older ages
   - **Examining history by age location** shows how events shape personalities of different age groups differently according to their phase of life, and how people retain those personality differences as they grow older

2. **"Cohort-group" concept** (group of people born over limited span of years) is central to our theory
   - **Definition**: "We define a generation as a special cohort-group whose length approximately matches that of a basic phase of life, or about twenty-two years over the last three centuries."

### Age Location Shapes Generational Experience

- Intuitively, everyone recognizes the importance of age location
- A generation's place in history affects everything from the nurture it receives from elders to the nurture it later gives its young
- **Today's Silent Generation** (fiftyish and sixtyish): Can recall the smothering style of their own upbringing in the 1930s and 1940s, in sharp contrast to the "hurried" children they raised in the "look-up" 1960s and 1970s
- Everyone also recognizes how the same event can have very different meaning for generations in different phases of life
- **Consider the Great Depression as its Pearl Harbor sequel**: For children (Silent), it meant tight protection; for rising adults (G.I.s), teamwork and challenge; for midlifers (Lost), a new sense of responsibility; for elders (Missionaries), opportunity for redemption long-held visions

### Comparing Depressions Across Generational Age Locations

- Compare the depression 1930s with the disequilibrium 1970s
- Depression time: fragmented children (13ers) grow up quickly and on their own; rising adults (Boomers) fragment and turn inward; midlifers (Silent) speed up to a new sense of adventure; elders (G.I.s) defend institutions under siege from the young

> "The lesson? There is no such thing as one universal lifecycle. To the contrary, neighboring generations can and do live very different lifecycles depending on their respective age locations in history."

### Age Rising While Time Moves Forward: The Generational Diagonal

- While observing (or trying to predict) phase-of-life behavior, we must remember that the age of each generation is *rising* while time moves *forward*
- We can visualize age location along what we call the **"generational diagonal."**
- Tracing this diagonal allows us to connect the event, the age, and the behavior of the same generation over time

### Social Moments Define and Shape Generations

- This approach alone tells us little about how generations shape history
- **Second proposition**: "Generations come in cycles. Just as history produces generations, so too do generations produce history."
- Central to this interaction are critical events called **"social moments"**—which alternate between "secular crises" and "spiritual awakenings"
- **Social moment**: Hits its people in different phases of life, helps shape and define generations; and because generations in different phases of life can together trigger a social moment, this helps shape and define history—and hence, new generations

### Social Moments and Generational Cycles

- Throughout American history, social moments have arrived at dates separated by approximately equal phases of roughly forty to forty-five years
- Most historians look upon this rhythm as, at most, a curious coincidence
- Authors look upon it as **key evidence that a generational cycle is at work**, ensuring a rather tight correspondence between constellations and events
- Correspondence is not exact—but the average deviation from what the cycle would predict is only three or four years—a small margin of error for a theory applied over four centuries

### Four Generational Types: Idealist, Reactive, Civic, and Adaptive

- Authors label the four generational types: **Idealist, Reactive, Civic, and Adaptive**
- With one exception, they have always recurred in a fixed order
- During a **spiritual awakening**: Idealists are moving into rising adulthood while Reactives are appearing as children
- During a **secular crisis**: Civics are moving into rising adulthood while Adaptives are appearing as children
- Later in life, these generations trigger another social moment and thus keep the cycle turning

**Among today's living generations:**
- Centenarians (old Missionaries) and rising-adult 13ers are **Idealists**
- Very old Lost and coming-of-age 13ers are **Reactives**
- Senior-citizen G.I.s and baby Millennials are **Civics**
- Midlife Silent are **Adaptives**

- First and third types are what we call **"dominant" in public life**—Idealists through redefining the inner world of values and culture, and Civics through rebuilding the outer world of technology and institutions
- Fourth and second types are **"recessive" in public life**, checking the excesses of their more powerful neighbors—Reactives as pragmatists, Adaptives as ameliorators

### Complete Generational Cycle

- The passage of four generations, Idealist through Adaptive, completes one full generational cycle over the course of four twenty-two-year phases of life (a total duration of roughly ninety years)
- From the 1584 Puritan birthyear forward, we can trace five such cycles through American history—of which three (Colonial, Revolutionary, and Civil War) are fully ancestral
- A waning fourth (**Great Power**) comprises the eldest 28 percent of the American population at the beginning of 1991
- An emerging fifth (**Millennial**) includes the youngest 72 percent
- Within these cycles, we identify eighteen generations, from John Winthrop's Puritans to Jessica McClure's Millennials
- **Recurring pattern of awakenings and crises**: While each era has produced its special variations, the basic pattern has persisted unchanged since the late sixteenth century, when the peers of Sir Philip Sidney, Francis Bacon, and William Shakespeare—men the age of the Puritans' fathers—triumphed in war, glorified science, and praised the order of the universe

### Future Generational Constellation

**Figure 1-2: Future Generational Constellation**
- Missionary (1860-1882): Age 108+ (1991), not alive (2013)
- Lost (1883-1900): Age 90-107 (1991), 112+ (2013)
- G.I. (1901-1924): Age 66-89 (1991), 88-111 (2013)
- Silent (1925-1942): Age 48-65 (1991), 70-87 (2013)
- Boom (1943-1960): Age 30-47 (1991), 52-69 (2013)
- Thirteenth (1961-1981): Age 9-29 (1991), 31-51 (2013)
- Millennial (1982-2003): Age 0-8 (1991), 9-30 (2013)
- Unnamed (2004-?): not alive (1991), 0-8 (2013)

- This projection reminds us not just of our own personal mortality, but also of the mortality of our generation
- Like a person, a generation is allotted a limited time for each phase of life
- Ultimately, most of what we associate with our generation—styles, habits, and artifacts—will disappear
- We leave behind no more than what we persuade or oblige younger generations to take from us
- Thus will all of us someday join the heritage of American civilization

### America as Generational Study

- America offers what may be mankind's longest and best case study of generational evolution
- Since the 18th century, observers have found this country unique for the freedom enjoyed by each successive generation to develop and act upon its inclinations
- When **Alexis de Tocqueville** visited America in the 1830s, he observed how generations mattered far more here than in Europe
- How in America "each generation is a new people"
- Tocqueville may have overstated the case—as we shall see, generational change in the Old World played a key role in triggering the Colonial cycle in the New World—back when most settlers still believed themselves culturally, part of Europe
- Since then, generations in America have often shared a similar mind-set, a sort of sympathetic vibration, with their transatlantic peers
- Like America, Western Europe also had its romantic radicals in the 1840s; its *Blut und Eisen* realists in the 1860s; its disillusioned *génération du feu* of World War I soldiers; and its *nouvelle résistance* student movements in 1968

### Global Generational Patterns

- Tocqueville's main point remains sound: Far more than the Old World—with its tradition-shaped culture, inherited parish elites, hierarchical religion, and habits of class deference—America has always been unusually susceptible to generational flux, to the fresh influence of each new set of youth come of age
- In recent decades, as other societies have grown more open and mobile, this distinction between America and other societies may be disappearing
- Were Tocqueville to travel through today's world, he might find many countries with generations born "new"
- Shifts in peer personality have recently coursed through modern societies in all continents: From Eastern Europe to the Pacific Rim, from the Middle East to Latin America, new generational waves are breaking
- Examples: In Poland, Lech Walesa was born too late to remember WWII atrocities committed there by German and Soviet armies; Today's emerging "Thaw Generation" of Soviet leaders can recall the 20th Soviet Congress in 1956, when Khrushchev first challenged the late Joseph Stalin

### Generational Phenomena: Isolated vs. Cyclical

- Events may be **isolated phenomena**—or they may reflect **generational cycles** in these other societies
- If the latter, theory would not reflect anything uniquely American, just human nature working itself out in a world relatively unbound by tradition
- So what's going on in America, and where are we today?

### National Life of the Late 1830s

- Reflect on the national life of the late 1830s, just after Tocqueville had written *Democracy in America*
- The last of the great civic heroes of 1776—the Patriots of Bunker Hill, the Constitution framers in Philadelphia, the Cassandra-creators of *E Pluribus Unum*—were passing away
- **Thomas Jefferson** and **Eli Whitney** had both died a decade earlier, **James Monroe** and **John Quincy Adams** within the last five years
- **James Madison** was in his mid-eighties, **Noah Webster** and **Aaron Burr** in their late seventies
- Their passing was already being lamented by the likes of the fiftyish **Daniel Webster**, who wondered how America could cope without these men of "massive solidity" whom the "iron harvest of the martial field" had united "happily and gloriously" in a "great and common cause"
- Others in their fifties and sixties—**Andrew Jackson's** Democrats and **Henry Clay's** Whigs—complained about a gridlocked Congress and gestured nervously over mechanistic compromises and issues of character
- On the great unresolved issues of the day—from slavery to western settlement—America drifted without direction

### Rising Younger Generation (Late 1830s)

- Meanwhile, a rising younger generation of evangelicals, utopian reformers, and transcendentalists (the likes of **Ralph Waldo Emerson**, **William Lloyd Garrison**, **Elizabeth Cady Stanton**, **Brigham Young**, **Frederick Douglass**, and **John Brown**) were redefining American culture according to fresh, self-discovered values
- **Abraham Lincoln** and **Jefferson Davis**, both reaching age 30, were showing signs of stern principle
- Farther down the age ladder, hardscrabble children—**Ulysses Grant**, **Stonewall Jackson**, **Andrew Carnegie**, and **Mark Twain**—showed far less interest in philosophy than in action
- Their peers were beginning to come of age amid criticism from older adults, who found them shallow and reckless
- **Does this all sound familiar?** It should—in the late 1830s, generational types were lining up in just about the same constellation (from elderly Civics to teenage Reactives) that we see in present-day America

### The Same Constellation Recurring

- We find much the same constellation back in the late 1740s, as memories of the young patriots of the Glorious Revolution—by then dead or quite old—gave way to confusion about the future
- Midlife leaders and preachers lacked their old sense of collective purpose
- Gripped by a refined, highly analytical mind-set, they saw life as complicated, political choices as burdensome
- Colonial society wobbled along, no one knowing exactly where
- At these moment, an introspective cadre of preachers and moralists ranging in age from their late twenties to mid-forties (including **Jonathan Edwards**, **John Woolman**, **Benjamin Franklin**, and **Samuel Adams**) were drawing spiritual zeal from their peers' recent "Great Awakening"
- A pugnacious, liberty-loving troop of kids was just setting out to explore, fight, and strike it rich (**Daniel Boone**, **Patrick Henry**, **Ethan Allen**, and **Benedict Arnold** were on the edge of puberty)
- **John Adams** and **George Washington**, both teenagers burning with personal ambition

> "Sound familiar? Here again, it should. Here again, the constellation was turning to a position much like today's."

### Living Off Past Achievements (1750s and 1840s vs. Today)

- Americans alive in those two past eras, just like Americans today, felt themselves living off the achievements of the past
- They saw their present world as comfortable but lacking direction, perhaps crumbling in its foundations
- They looked forward to their own future and the future of their children with a mixture of guilt and anxiety
- In the late 1980s, Americans look up a journal and read a serious-minded essay entitled "The End of History" or tune to a pop radio station chanting lyrics like "no new tales to tell," the lyrics of boredom

> "When history loses urgency, people tend to live at the expense of the future despite their better judgment."

### What We Find Today

- **Today**: Splintered families, downwardly mobile 20-year-olds, razor-thin savings rates, threats to the global environment, an eroding sense of national mission, and pyramiding entitlements for older generations crowding out investments needed by their heirs
- As was true around 1750 and 1840, Americans in the early 1990s have only the vaguest sense of what the future holds—for their society as a whole, and for each living generation

### The Cycle as Predictive Tool

> "Here is where the cycle can help. The story of civilization seldom moves in a straight line, but is rich with curves, oscillations, and mood shifts. The ebb and flow of history often reflect the ebb and flow of generations, each with a different age location, peer personality, and lifecycle story."

- By viewing history along the generational diagonal, by searching the cycle for behavioral clues, we can apply the mirror of recurring human experience to gaze around the corner of current trends and say something instructive about the decades to come
- The lifecycle experience of ancestral generations tells us, in particular, that the peer personality of each generation may express itself very differently from one phase of life to the next

### Examples of Generational Lifecycle Differences

- **Idealist generations** (like Samuel Adams's) typically come of age attacking elder-built institutions before retreating into elder-absorbed remission, but their mature age uncompromising "Gray Champion" moralists
- **Reactive generations** (like George Washington's) bubble over with unfettered risk-taking in their twenties, but age into mellow pragmatists by their sixties
- **Civic generations** (like Cotton Mather's) are aggressive institution-founders when young, but solid institution-defenders when old
- **Adaptive generations** (like Theodore Roosevelt's) are elder-focused conformists early in life, but junior-focused pluralists later on

### Drawing on Rich Source Book of History

- With fourteen generational lifecycles already completed, we can draw on a rich source book of history to help us understand how the peer personalities of today's four youngest generations—Silent, Boom, 13th, Millennial—are likely to express themselves as they age in place
- Looking back over four full generational cycles, we can also project how the national mood will evolve over the next half century as the generational constellation clicks up once, two, and three notches

### Generations and National Progress

- History does not guarantee good endings
- The American saga is replete with good and bad acts committed by generations no less than by individuals
- Our national liturgy reminds us how ancestral generations provided helpful *élan-mens* that made progress possible, from the clearing of land to the building of great architecture, from the waging of wars to the writing of great literature
- **Yet ancestral generations have also, at times, inflicted terrible harms on their heirs**: From instituting slavery to exterminating Indian tribes, from exploiting child labor to accumulating massive public debts

> "A lesson of the cycle is that each generational type specializes in its own unique brand of positive and negative endowments. Each of today's adult generations—G.I., Silent, Boom, and 13th—has its own special way of helping or hurting the future. Each, collectively, has choices to make that will determine what sort of world its heirs"

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

## Chapter 2: Life Along the Generational Diagonal

### The Cohort-Group Biography

- **Gail Sheehy's** *Passages* (1976) pioneered **cohort-group biography**: rare and compelling example of human history told from the inside out, as peers experienced it
- Cohort-group biographies reveal how friendships, anxieties, sororities, and fraternities "have grown up and matured in ways that are, in some sense, special"
- Traditional history books fragment life into disconnected age brackets (childhood chapter, adolescence chapter, midlife chapter, old age chapter)—missing the integrated experience
- **Sociologist Matthew White Riley** calls this the "life-course fallacy": mistake of describing a lifecycle simply by stitching together all different age brackets alive at the same time
- No single lifecycle snapshot is genuine—1990 shows adored babies, cynical college kids, self-inflamed yuppies, ambivalent midlifers, and busy senior citizens, but no one lived that path

### Historical Shifts in American Lifecycles

American lifecycle has encountered frequent, major shifts over four centuries:

- **1630s New Englanders**: collective personality emphasized patriarchal elders; youths utterly alien
- **1680s**: youths preferred teamwork over spiritual conversion; their sons reversed this
- **1770s**: twentyish soldiers of French and Indian War grew up distrusting authority; 1830s young adults tried to fire passions of the old
- **Post-WWI**: midlifers extended very different welcomes to homecoming young soldiers after WWI vs. WWII

> "The human lifecycle has many timeless denominators... but within this general and slowly changing matrix, human behavior can be quite abruptly and sharply variant from one era to the next."

### The Generational Diagonal

**The generational diagonal** emerges when college alumni recall unusual cohort-groups coming of age:

- **Early 1920s**: upbeat, collectivist batch replaced cynics and war heroes
- **Mid-1960s**: fiery batch replaced adult emulators
- **Around 1980**: smooth batch replaced complainers

Changes visible in: rising drug use among successive college freshmen (late 1960s-early 1970s), growing popularity of military/entrepreneurial careers (early 1980s campuses)

**Cohort-group membership is involuntary, permanent, applies to everyone**—unlike neighborhood or career. Fixed in history, must eventually disappear. What makes it unique: all members encounter same national events, moods, and trends at similar ages throughout their lives.

> "Since history affects people differently depending on their age at the time, a common age location is what gives each cohort-group a distinct biography and a distinct lifecycle."

### Age Location Shapes Collective Personality

Historical events affect people vastly differently based on age:

- 10-year-old finds terrifying what 30-year-old finds empowering
- 50-year-old calms, 70-year-old inspires
- **35-ish Boomers** came of age with Vietnam, Watergate, "Consciousness III" euphoria—retain taste for introspection
- **75-year-olds** had no Woodstock, no D-Day—nothing like bustling senior citizens never had
- **D-Day** empowered young-adult G.I.s but intimidated Silent children; **Woodstock** brought inner rapture to 25-year-old Boomers, made 5-year-old 13ers feel the adult world was turning hysterical

Age location shapes cohort-groups through historical shifts in attitudes toward families, schooling, sex roles, religion, crime, careers, personal risk.

### Social Institutions Accentuate Age Location

America's institutions reinforce cohort identity:

- Kindergarten through high school: all pupils in any classroom belong to same birthyear
- College-age students date, study, compete within cohort-groups or two-to-three-year zones
- As adults age into midlife, friendships widen but cohort bonds remain strong
- High school/college reunions remind alumni of their cohort bonds
- Cohorts retire together in early-to-mid-sixties

### Quantitative Research on Cohorts

**Émile Littré** coined "birth cohort" (1863); serious research emerged mid-1960s—intrigued by lifecycle shifts. Social scientists began studying modern behavioral data from birthyear perspective.

**Survey analysis of voting behavior** (classic case):

- **Early 1960s**: researchers discovered Americans age 65-80 voted heavily Republican; younger Americans Democratic
- Two explanations seemed plausible: (1) age effect—people vote Republican when old, or (2) cohort effect—Republicans leading during period (1890s-1920s)
- Most experts chose the first—**aging produces conservatism**
- Study in 1962: "The pattern appears to be linear." **Wrong.**
- Two decades later: post-1970 arrival of increasingly Democratic batch of 65-to-80-year-olds made cohorts the only explanation
- New and increasingly Republican batch of young voters arrived a decade later

### Intelligence and Educational Aptitude Tests

**Psychologist K. Warner Schaie** measured "psychometric intelligence" of cohort-groups born 1886-1962 in Seattle:

- Measured intelligence rises most steeply in twenties, levels off in thirties, enters gradual decline around middle fifties
- Schaie found powerful correlation between aptitude scores and specific cohort-groups
- Cohort effect stronger even after controlling for age and historical changes like better schooling
- **Most measures of aptitude vary far more across cohort lines than across age brackets**

**Key findings:**

- **1886-1892 cohort-group**: highest of all groups in "word fluency" (vocabulary), lowest in everything else
- **1907-1927 cohort-groups**: done very well in overall "intellectual ability," outperformed all other groups in "numbers skills"—the last of these three groups (1921-1927) appears to be the highest-scoring group thus far tested
- **1935-1941 cohort-group**: scored highest in "space" (geometry) reasoning, second in "reasoning" (logic), last in "word fluency"
- **1942-1948 cohort-group**: beaten all others in "verbal meaning" but done little better than average in "numbers skills" and "space" reasoning
- **More recent cohort-groups (born 1949-1962)**: shown progressively declining scores across the board

### The SAT Score Decline (1964-1980)

**Seventeen straight years** (1964-1980): average SAT score declined among U.S. high school seniors.

- **1976**: federal Wirtz Commission attributed roughly half the fall to growing share of all high school seniors who chose to take the test (permissiveness, less homework)
- **1988**: Congressional Budget Office (CBO) researchers discovered a very close **diagonal match**—at all grades, scores went down for each cohort
- **SAT trend could have been predicted by looking at lower-grade test scores in earlier years**:
  - Even as Wirtz Commission agonized over SAT decline (1976), 12-year-olds already scoring higher than next-elders
  - Five years in future (third grade: mid-1970s; sixth grade: mid-1970s; junior high: late 1970s), same kids (1964 and 1965 cohorts) reached twelfth grade in early 1980s—SAT scores began rising again

### The Cohort Diagonal in Crime and Social Pathology

**Figure 2-1** summarizes data on average grade-school test scores (ages 8-17); per capita alcohol consumption (17- and 18-year-old students only) and marijuana (17-year-old students only); per capita arrest rates for arson, robbery, assault (ages 15-24); and per capita arrest rates for drunk driving (ages 15-24).

**Portrait of the 1961-1964 cohort-group** (vivid and unflattering):

- Generated all of America's lowest aptitude-test scores
- Highest high school senior drug and alcohol abuse
- All but one of America's highest drunk-driving rates
- Most of America's highest arrest rates for three violent crimes

Very likely (though detailed age-bracketed data unavailable), this cohort also generated record rates for many other social pathologies. Since most of the high-crime years cluster around late 1970s and early 1980s, at first glance we might suspect historical trend affecting all age groups. **Yet behavior of older age brackets shows this is not the case**—while rates for drunk driving, suicide, most violent crimes accelerated for 15-to-24-year-olds, they were stabilizing or falling for all age brackets over age 35.

> "By 1991, the men and women born from 1961 through 1964 have reached their late twenties. They are no longer taking aptitude tests and have left their high-crime and high-drinking ages behind them."

**Context for the 1961-1964 cohort**: Individuals born 1962 were year-old infants during **Jack Kennedy's assassination**; age 7 at time of anti-Vietnam marches, moon landing, Chappaquiddick, sudden leap in divorce rates; age 13 when Watergate trials ended and poverty rate for youths rose steeply; age 17 when Americans parked in gas lines and saw angry Iranian mobs on TV.

### From Cohorts to Generations

**Generational diagonal** reveals countless unanswered questions about cohort-groups from past four centuries. Examples:

- **1633-1647**: born the most berated and abused children in colonial history, most notorious seventeenth-century pirates and rebels, about half executed for witchcraft in New England
- **1721-1723**: born all Americans age 18 at height of colonial "Great Awakening"; most energetic evangelicals and antislavery activists of entire eighteenth century—half of all delegates over age 30 at First Continental Congress (1774)
- **1767-1775**: born all Americans who watched Revolutionary War only as children; all 44 methodical, well-behaved members of Lewis and Clark expedition; three members of antebellum "Great Triumvirate" (Clay, Webster, Calhoun); known in midlife for hair-splitting oratory, procedural compromises over slavery, twelve failed attempts to run for Presidency
- **1809-1821**: born vast majority of best-known reformers, abolitionists, feminists, self-proclaimed prophets, commune founders of nineteenth century—nearly two-thirds of Congress in session at outbreak of Civil War
- **1822-1829**: born most of Gold Rush '49ers, most colorful and effective Civil War generals, leading postwar "scalawag" southern governors, most notorious machine bosses of Gilded Age, every American age 64-71 during Crash of '93 (first recession forcing categorical retirement of elder workers)
- **1869-1880**: born nearly all fiery young journalists whom **Theodore Roosevelt** called "muckrakers," nearly half the Congress that approved Prohibition in 1919, leading public figures (Herbert Hoover, Douglas MacArthur, George Marshall, Bernard Baruch, Herbert Lehman) who established America's global reputation as crusading defender of civilized morality by midcentury
- **1911-1921**: born nearly all Depression-era high school graduates whose first job was in New Deal relief program, all but one of President Kennedy's leading "best and brightest" advisers, two-thirds of all Americans ever awarded Nobel Prize for economics, most aggressive and effective lobbyists for public retirement benefits in American history
- **1925-1932**: born most of "Li'l Rascals," kids of Great Depression, "beatniks" of late 1940s, vast majority of most popular social and political satirists during entire postwar era (1950s to present day)
- **1941-1942**: born children of *Brown v. Board of Education* school desegregation case (1954), majority of Greensboro lunch-counter sit-in protesters (1961), best-known "black power" advocates of late 1960s and early 1970s, Jesse Jackson
- **1943**: born WWII's home-leave "goodbye babies"—vastly disproportionate number of most inner-driven and judgmental figures of last several decades, including: Bob Woodward, Gracie Slick, Jim Morrison, Bobby Fischer, Robert Crumb, Randy Newman, Mitch Snyder, Oliver North, Newt Gingrich, William Bennett, Richard Darman, Geraldo Rivera
- **1967-1970**: born all children conceived during flower-child summers of "love" and antiwar protest, nearly everyone who first heard about space shuttle *Challenger* disaster while sitting in high school classroom, two-thirds of all U.S. soldiers killed during American invasion of Panama in December 1989

### The American Lifecycle in the Twentieth Century

**Figure 2-2** shows lifecycle framework out of four life phases of equal twenty-two-year lengths:

- **Youth** (ages 0-21)
- **Rising adulthood** (ages 22-43)
- **Midlife** (ages 44-65)
- **Elderhood** (ages 66-87)

Chart shows lifecycle on vertical axis, calendar years on horizontal axis at twenty-two-year intervals. Americans located in any one life phase (such as "youth") in one marked year fall in the next life phase ("rising adulthood") in the next marked year.

At each intersecting point, an adjective reflects how contemporaries regarded the personality of Americans in that phase of life at that year:

- **1920 midlife**: moralistic
- **1942 midlife**: pragmatic
- **1964 midlife**: powerful
- **1986 midlife**: indecisive

**Figure 2-3: The Generational Diagonal in the Twentieth Century**

Third approach: **read history along the generational diagonal**—deal with SAT scores (diagonal read).

Starting at bottom of 1942 column, move diagonally up and to the right:

- "Suffocated" youths → "conformist" rising adults → "indecisive" midlifers (Gail Sheehy in *Passages*)
- Next diagonal to right: Cheryl Merser's path
- Switching in the other direction: "protected" → "heroic" → "powerful" → "busy" diagonal of Erik Erikson (and John Kennedy) peers

By tracing along these diagonals in sequence, we avoid the fallacy of cohort-centrism and monitor how each set of peers has traveled a separate path through life, from youth to elderhood. We can appreciate how each era looked and felt to the people who lived different lifecycles.

Each diagonal represents more than just a randomly selected cohort. Each diagonal **represents a generation** possessing its own distinct age location and peer personality. Only **generational** cohort-groups encompass all individual cohorts and organize them by peer personality into basic building blocks of social change.

> "By inquiring into generations—what creates them, how long they are, how their boundaries can be identified, and how they align in constellations—we can begin to understand their powerful relationship with history over the centuries."

## Preface

### The Disconnection from History

- College graduates now list history as the academic subject of **least use** in daily affairs—reflects today's pragmatism and disconnection from the past
- People across all ages feel history is irrelevant to present lives, "all about Presidents and wars, depressions and scandals"
- **"Today fixation"** has rumbled through American society in the 1970s-1990s: preference for consumption over savings, debt over taxes, needs of elders over children
- Same attitudes reflected in first-family choices, adult-only condos, Wall Street buy-outs, inner-city drug dealers
- Authors aim to provide a perspective on human affairs unlike anything in standard history and social science texts

### The Core Thesis: Generational Cycles

- American history shows a **recurring dynamic of generational behavior** that determines how and when we participate as individuals in society
- If the future replays the past, then **the past must anticipate the future**
- The book presents the **"history of the future"** by narrating recurring generational patterns from the **Puritans forward** (1584-2069)
- Introduces the **"generational diagonal"**—the lifecycle course lived by discrete birthyear groups called **"generations"**
- Identifies **eighteen such generations** through four centuries of American history dating back to first New World colonists

### The Four Generational Types

Among these eighteen generations, four distinct personality patterns—**four types of "peer personalities"**—follow each other in fixed order:

1. **"G.I."** elders, born 1901-1924, age 66 to 89 as of 1991
2. **"SILENT"** midlifers, born 1925-1942, age 48 to 65
3. **"BOOMER"** rising adults, born 1943-1960, age 30 to 47
4. **"13ER"** youths, born 1961-1981, age 9 to 29

- Each generation's collective mind-set influences individuals whether they agree or spend lifetime fighting against it
- Every generation includes all kinds of people, but shares the same **"age location"** in history
- The **"generational cycle"** lies at the heart of the story and offers explanation for why America unfolds as it does

### The G.I. Generation

- Collegial identity has left colossal lifelong imprint on America's political, social, and economic institutions
- See older and younger generations as ineffectual facsimiles of their own
- Your **"Civic" type** is probably the most crisply defined; clearest boundaries separating G.I.s from Lost and Silent
- Among basic peer personalities in American history: **believers in public harmony and cooperative social discipline**
- Accustomed to being looked upon (and rewarded) as good, constructive, and deserving
- You expected to be viewed and treated differently later in life, understanding how others might view themselves
- All aging Civic generations have had this trouble, including peers of **Cotton Mather** and **James Blair** in the 1690s, **Thomas Jefferson** and **James Madison** in early 1820s

### The Silent Generation

- **Rationalist generation** in tradition of eighteenth-century patriot-scientist **Benjamin Rush**
- Believe age and stage of generational saga move in orderly straight lines
- Attitude brought hope, old age, and Puritan piety in mostly-despised 20s
- Over last two decades, recognized younger generations don't display friendliness, optimism, community spirit of your own peers at like age
- Younger generations preparing to leave behind endowments of less visible and secular nature, difficult to appreciate
- As generation loses energy, may fear unique virtue will fade
- **Cycle suggests**: special strengths will rekindle, thanks to values-laden nurturing style you dislike (and what elder **Mather** and **Jefferson** similarly disliked) in younger parents and leaders
- Resisting measuring others against your standard may reveal **"generational diagonal"** and nonlinear cycle as comforting ideas
- Cycle may revive interest in nurture of today's preschoolers—their early childhood resembles what you remember from 70-80 years ago

### The Adaptive Type (Silent Characteristics)

- **Other-directed generation** that comes easily to appreciation of elites, mind-sets, virtues
- Need less persuasion than others to accept **apology of generations**, theory of historic oscillation, need for balance and diversity
- Since coming of age again, tend to respond ambivalently to anything confronted
- May quarrel with general conclusions and inquire into **Teddy Roosevelt's "melting pot"** or majoritarian elements of theory
- Doubts whether any diverse group numbering tens of millions can fit single peer personality or single generation
- Like **Henry Clay** once did with slave emancipation, might try melding theory together with other peer-elected theories to yield consensus or "compromise" perspective
- In manner of **Woodrow Wilson** at Versailles, might remain undecided until hearing what experts have to say
- In spirit of aging **William Ellery Channing** or **John Dewey**, might search for evidence that civilized world will produce endings as long as everyone remains open to new ideas
- Puzzle over what it means to be "Adaptive"—debating where authors set generational boundaries
- May at times sound or feel like a G.I. or a Boomer, reaching cusp of elderhood having shared neither outer triumph nor inner rootedness of next-juniors
- Sixty-five years after first birthyear, no generation election has been elected President
- Bothers you—though would be the first to admit that an instinct for leadership may not be generation's strong suit
- Like midlife peers of **William Byrd** and **Alexander Spotswood** in early 1700s, or **William-drawing rooms**
- Generation has highly refined taste for process and expertise that ties other people in knots
- Yet in your own humility, even in creative tension from elusive hunt for catharsis, generation has done more than any since **Louis Brandeis** to bring sense of nonjudgmental fairness and open-mindedness to American society
- Pluralist antennae, so generously directed everywhere else, have yet to focus on own offspring, who have so far been mostly a source of disappointment and worry—much as Trumansesque children were to Wilsonesque parents
- Had hoped 13er children would grow up kind and socially sensitive; instead their generation is turning out too hardened for your taste
- You suspect maybe you did something bad as parents, but you're not about to give up searching for ways to make amends

### The Boomer Generation

- **Know yours is, beyond doubt, an authentic generation**
- Will recognize generational boundaries separating you from others (born 1943-1945 are probably delighted someone finally placed you correctly)
- Have no trouble recognizing how other generations have personalities different from your own
- Unlike Silent, you have never imagined being anything other than what you are
- Great comfort derives from identity—precisely what makes you troubling to eyes of others
- Like peers of **John Winthrop** or **Ralph Waldo Emerson**, perceive that within your circle lies unique vision, transcendent principle, moral entity more wondrous than anything ever sensed in history of mankind
- Like **Herman Melville** or **H. L. Mencken**, often loathe narcissism and self-satisfaction of peers, but too important a trait of your **"Idealist"** generational type
- Possessing unyielding opinions about all issues, judge own peers no less harshly than elders and juniors
- Either way, well appreciate that time has come to move Boomer discussion beyond hippie-turned-yuppie theme
- **Boomer-as-hypocrite theme** stripped to its fundamentals, generation of Transcendentalists is no more hypocritical than **Thoreau** at Walden Pond or **Jefferson Davis** during seven-year retreat into Mississippi woods

### Idealist Disappointments and Strengths

- May feel disappointment in **Dan Quayles** and **Donald Trumps** among first agemates to climb life's pyramid, along with danger in prospect of Boomer Presidents and Boomer-led Congresses farther down road
- Watching **Franklin Pierce** and **Stephen Douglas**, peers of Lincoln and Lee felt same trepidation about their generation—with reason
- History soon demonstrated yet may see peers rise to capacity for great wisdom, terrible tragedy, or just insufferable pomposity
- Over centuries, **Idealist generations** like yours have produced more than fair share of all three
- Having lived just half a lifecycle, probably find it hard to imagine generation may someday produce strong-willed leaders on par with **Sam Adams** or **Benjamin Franklin**, **Douglas MacArthur** or **Franklin Roosevelt**
- Not surprising—Idealist generations quite the reverse of Civic generations, typically reach decisive phase on history late in life
- To understand how this happens, need to step outside inner-absorption, take look at like-minded ancestors, understand fateful connection between Idealist lifecycle and larger march of events
- Already sense Boomer peers, for all narcissism and parallel play, will someday leave decisive mark on civilization quite unlike anything they've done up to now
- **Intuition is correct. History suggests they will.**

### The 13er Generation

- Authors imagine cautious reception from generation you don't especially like
- Laying bare generation's problems and affixing label with ominous ring (like **Gertrude Stein** in mid-forties did to thirtyish juniors)
- Name chosen (**"Lost Generation"**) was perverse enough to catch on with rising cultural elite
- May not like being lumped with mall rats, drug gangs, collegians who can't find Chicago on map—but will grudgingly admit that's how others often see you
- Already noticed recent barrage of experts and articles declaring your generation dumb, greedy, soulless
- May find solace learning several earlier American generations have also been perceived this way at your age of birth—peers of **George Washington**, **John Hancock**, **Patrick Henry**
- Along with **Ulysses Grant** or **George Patton**, might not mind striking others as "bad," knowing full well expectations as game you'll play to advantage
- Know the odds: maybe like **John D. Rockefeller**, you will hit jackpot—or else, **Cloid Barker**, win or lose, not looking for testimonials or grand collective mission
- Notice we've made your generation equal partner to all others in our saga—half intrigued, half alarmed
- **To be equal partner means history might be counting on you, and you're not quite ready for that**

### 13er Context: "Ill-Timed Lifecycle"

- 13er reader knows perfectly well what elders seldom admit: **yours is an ill-timed lifecycle**
- Experienced **"Consciousness Revolution"** of late 1960s and 1970s from child's perspective—**Louisa May Alcott** had to grow up fast to survive in world of parental self-immersion or even neglect
- Tired of gauzy talk about yuppies, born-agains, hippies, TV shows full of Boomers too busy whining about problems to solve them
- Generational consciousness is on rise: you already sense it's just matter of time before you and peers snap into cultural focus
- Like **Sinclair Lewis** did with snooty "Babbitts," start trimming sails of smug next-elders with justifiable pride in your pragmatism, but watch out: **it has its limits**
- Popular 13er putdown: "That's history," translated to mean "That's irrelevant," "Wrong"
- We look on eyeball with other **"Reactive" types**—especially generations like **Captain Kidd's**, **Benedict Arnold's**, **William Quantrill's**, **Al Capone's**
- Their lifecycle spent dodging criticism and mistrust of others
- Produced many of America's toughest leaders, most effective warriors, most scathingly perceptive artists, (of course) most successful entrepreneurs
- But so too did many of members burn out young, turn traitor, endure heaps of blame, suffer difficult old age

### Cross-Generational Perspectives

- Regardless of generation or current phase of life, chances are you share commonly held view that your own peers' recent lifecycle experiences are the norm
- In each case, may believe other generations could or should think and behave like you at whatever phase of life you have recently completed
- If G.I., probably regard retirement as natural opportunity to stay active within own community and reap economic rewards of lifetime of purposeful labor
- If Silent, may believe reaching age forty or fifty inevitably triggers midlife "passage," abrupt and liberating personality shift
- If Boomer, may see spiritual self-discovery as very essence of being 25-year-old
- If 13er, may find hard to imagine how any teenager would not instinctively reduce such issues as courtship, schooling, career choice to practical, matter-of-fact essentials

> "Americans have felt much the same sense of generational warp for centuries. By nature, we all want to believe in an unvarying lifecycle; this makes life more predictable and hence more manageable." (Authors)

### The Reality of Generational Cycles

- That is not, however, how generations work
- It isn't true in early 1990s, wasn't true during circa-1970 "generation gap," wasn't true in 1950 or 1930, or for that matter, in 1830, 1730, or 1630
- Much stress in cross-generational relationships arises when people of different ages expect others to behave in ways their own personalities won't allow
- Plainly, this happened between G.I.s and Boomers in late 1960s
- Recently started happening again, albeit with less noise and fanfare, this time between Boomers and 13ers
- Poll today's collegians: which generation they like least, then ask fortyish professionals which generation they think offers least to offer
- Answer, in each case: the other
- Boomers and 13ers coming to recognize how unlike each other they are; as yet, neither side realizes that this personality clash will endure, **almost continuously**, over next decade
- **This is nothing new**

### Historical Pattern of Generational Conflict

- For centuries, **"Idealist" generations** have invariably come of age mounting highly symbolic attack against their aging **"Civic" elders**—and have later entered midlife engaging in bitter conflict with their **"Reactive" next-juniors**
- No other generational type shares this lifecycle pattern of conflict
- **"Crysis"** (or instance) have typically held in-life battles with twentyish children so difficult because they could recall nothing like it from own youth
- While **"Adaptives"** have been spared from overt generational conflict throughout their lives—often to their great frustration

### Purpose and Scope of the Book

- One purpose: **to dispel illusion of generational sameness**
- In doing so, hope to promote more reciprocal understanding and mutual respect among very unlike generations alive today
- Timing and authorship may reflect workings of cycle we describe
- Many have felt this book is this book has long needed to be worked on by Boomers (which indeed your authors are from 1947 and 1951 cohorts)
- Some finest generational biographies ever published—including *Passages* and *Private Lives*—have been written by Silent authors
- Yet Boomers remain twentieth century's most generation-conscious peer group, one that has overwhelmed all thinking about subject over past few decades
- As Boomers come to dominate media, word **"generation"** heard more often in news, entertainment, advertising since late 1960s
- Attribute this, in part, to renewed stirrings of Boomer spiritualism in public life—and to present location of Boomers at center of multigenerational family trees

### Authors' Personal Context

- Authors know feeling quite well
- At one end of own families, see surviving parents and stepparents, all G.I.s, all faring very well in comparison with what remember of elders of our youth—and all looking upon current drift of America with mixture of public concern and private detachment
- At other end: children, born in mid-1980s, about whose future adult Americans of all ages beginning to worry
- Between us, have four children: two 13ers, two Millennials, perhaps more to come
- Like many of peers, recognize instinct for teamwork and cooperation—something G.I.s have always had and Boomers came of age rejecting—will make sense for these Millennials just now coming onstage

### The Generational Diagonal Discovery

- Both of us have separately written on generational topics for many years
- In quite different ways, each came across what we call **"generational diagonal"**
- Earlier books focused mainly on Boomers and G.I.s—**Strauss'** on Vietnam War, **Howe's** on federal entitlements programs
- Wondered why these two generations developed such entirely different ways of looking at world—G.I.s seeing themselves (even in old age) as uniquely productive, Boomers seeing themselves (even in youth) as uniquely sagacious
- Fascinated by curious 1970s-era resolution of generation gap between them—an unspoken deal in which G.I.s achieved social and economic independence (and entered post-Vietnam fiscal "peace dividend" almost entirely on themselves) while Boomers asserted their social independence
- In each case, came as great surprise: aging G.I.s gave up cultural and spiritual authority, and Boomers abandoned any realistic prospect of matching elders' late-in-life economic rewards
- Wondered what it was about very different growing-up experiences of G.I.s and Boomers that prompted such behavior, and whether any earlier American generations had ever acted along same lines

### Discovery of Historical Cycles

- As stretched search for analogues back through centuries, panoramic outline of generational saga began emerging
- Again and again, this lifecycle approach to history revealed **similar and recurring pattern**—one that coincided with many of rhythms scholars see running through American history
- Found ourselves with new answers to old riddles that have puzzled historians
- Why, for example, great public emergencies in America seem to arrive every eighty or ninety years—and why great spiritual upheavals arrive roughly halfway in between
- **If we had in fact discovered a cycle, we knew proof had to lie in its predictive possibilities**
- Decided then and there to write last chapter on future
- Not many academic theories of history, without predictions (what **Karl Popper** once called **"falsifiability"**) any road map of history ends just where reader begins to find it interesting

### Predictions and the Crisis of 2020

- In advancing own cycle theory about alternating eras of liberal activity and conservative quiescence, **Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.** has made very date-specific predictions
- For example, that America now poised for sharp pivot back toward 1960s-style activism
- Authors harbor doubts about that prognosis (for reasons explained in Chapter 6)
- Give Schlesinger credit for pioneering his cycle and giving reader measure by which theory can be tested
- Same is true for **Kondratief** and **Schumpeter**: time will tell if events of next few years explain much
- Ten years will reveal something, twenty years quite a bit, forty years will close case one way or other

> "Anyone who claims to possess a vision of the future must present it with due modesty, since no mortal can possibly foresee how fate may twist and turn." (Authors)

- Readers who encounter this book fifty years from now will no doubt find Chapter 13 odd in much of its detail
- But it is not purpose to predict specific events
- Rather, purpose is to explain underlying dynamic of generational change will determine which sorts of events are most likely
- No one can predict specific emergencies that will confront America during what we call **"Crisis of 2020"**—nor, of course, exact year in which crisis will find epicenter
- What we claim cycle can predict: during late 2010s and early 2020s, American generations will pass deep into **"Crisis Era"** constellation and mood—and that, as consequence, nation's public life will undergo swift and possibly revolutionary transformation

### Scope and Ambition

- Sum total of predictions does not present idealized portrait of America's future, but rather honest depiction of where generational cycle says nation is headed
- Reading Chapter 13, most readers will feel mixed emotions about what authors foresee happening over next several decades
- Whatever values or politics one may hold, there are subjects that surely divide those who do and others who do not
- May also be surprised to find only passing mention of many subjects—from space-age technology to shifting fortunes of political parties—that weigh so large in most speculations about future
- In view, timeless dynamic of human relationships comes first and matters most
- While others may describe technological marvels will greet manned spacecraft to planet Mars, tell something else: when America's leaders and voters will want this flight to happen; why; which generation will fly it; how nation will feel about it at time; and afterward
- Acknowledge this to be ambitious book, with wholly new interpretations of important moments in American history—from persecution of Salem witches to rise of Wall Street yuppies
- Admit, of course, that generational cycle cannot explain everything
- Were history so easily compartmentalized, it would lose not just its mystery, but also much of its hope, passion, triumph
- **What we do insist: that generations offer important perspective on human events, from great deeds of public leaders to day-to-day lives of ordinary people**
- Urge those who believe in other theories of history (or in no theory at all) to consider how ours can at times help explain otherwise unexplainable

### Skepticism and the Lifecycle Perspective

- Many readers may well remain unpersuaded about cycle, at least until more time passes
- To skeptical historians in particular, suggest suspending disbelief long enough to take hard look at generational diagonal
- Historians seldom write biographies—and, all too often, recount events without lifecycle perspective of what we call **"people moving through time"**
- Generations and history share two-way relationship—not just in America, and not just in modern era

### Approach and Terminology

- Ask reader to approach book in same manner authors came to subject—**inductively**, as gradual discovery of something very new
- Sometimes use terms you may find unfamiliar at first, like **"cohorts"** and **"spiritual awakenings"**
- When necessary, even invent own terms, including typology of generations and of **"constellational" eras**
- Define all these terms for easy reference
- Urge reader to enliven concepts with your own experience and imagination
- Whether or not you agree with vision of America's future, hope you will find approach useful in clarifying your own view of next decade and century

### Messages for Each Generation

- Whatever your generation—G.I., Silent, Boom, 13th—will learn, as we have, how every generation has its own strengths and weaknesses, is own opportunities for triumph and tragedy
- Yes, there are implicit messages here—for example, about how each generation should apply its unique gifts for benefit of its heirs
- But object here is less to judge than to understand

> "Before God all the generations of humanity appear equally justified. In 'any generation,' he concluded, 'real moral greatness is the same as in any other.'" — **Leopold von Ranke**

## Acknowledgments

### Key Influences

> "Historical generations are not born. They are made." — **Robert Wohl**

- Authors consider this book to be interpretive gathering of many disciplines, each reflecting important achievements of number of scholars, journalists, pollsters, and friends—several of whom deserve mention
- On concept of generation itself, aided immeasurably by work of **Julián Marías**, himself disciple of **José Ortega y Gasset**
- Must credit **Anthony Esler**, who kept "generations approach" alive in American academic circles over decades
- Acknowledge pioneering work of two **Arthur Schlesingers**, demonstrated that oscillating political and social mood can coincide with American-style progress
- Thank **William McLoughlin** and **David Hackett Fischer** for illumination of parallels between periodic "awakenings" and **Samuel Huntington** for being first to see relationship between awakenings and what we call secular crises

### Historical Research

- In depiction of historical cycles through nineteenth century, indebted to modern social historians who uncovered important clues about cohort and age-bracket behavior of children
- Especially thank **Oscar Handlin**, **Mary Cable**, **Ray Hiner**, **Joseph Hawes**, **Peter Gregg Slater**, **Robert Bremner**, **David Nasaw** (on childhood)
- **Emmý Bailyn**, **Frederick Rudolph**, **Carl Kaestle**, **Lawrence Cremin** (for adolescence)
- Work of **Joseph Kett** stands out; and for old age, **David Hackett Fischer**

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Chapter 3 (continued): Belonging to a "Generation"

### The Length of a Generation

- Generation defined by **peer personality** more than chronological age
- Authors reject traditional 30-year genealogical spans (parent-to-child)
- Instead: generation = **phase of life** (~22 years), defined by social roles

**Four life phases with central roles:**
- **ELDERHOOD** (66-87): stewardship, mentoring, passing values
- **MIDLIFE** (44-65): leadership, parenting, directing institutions
- **RISING ADULTHOOD** (22-43): activity, working, starting families, testing values
- **YOUTH** (0-21): dependence, learning, acquiring values

- Coming-of-age timing varies by era (1960s-70s drifted upward, 1930s-40s downward)
- Most societies recognize **rites of passage** separating youth from adulthood
- American legal markers cluster around specific ages: 18 (legal majority), 21 (end of apprenticeship), 35 (youngest Presidential candidate), 65-66 (retirement)

**Decisive events reshape generations:**
- Major wars/revolutions hit each life phase differently
- Youth encouraged to keep out of danger (dependence)
- Rising adults fight the enemy (activity)
- Midlifers organize home front (leadership)
- Elders offer wisdom and perspective (stewardship)
- Result: four distinct cohort-groups with **unique peer personalities** lasting a lifetime

### Family Generational Patterns

**Three rules of generational family dynamics:**

1. **Parents distributed across two preceding generations** — mothers/fathers typically 20-45 years old
2. **First-wave cohorts have earlier parent generation** than last-wave cohorts
   - Boomers example: first wave (mid-1940s) mostly had Silent parents, last wave (late 1950s) mostly had G.I. parents
3. **Especially strong nurturing influence on second succeeding generation**
   - By 1960, fortyish/fiftyish G.I.s had greater influence on childhood than twentyish/thirtyish Silent
   - 1970s: Silent and Boom parents raised 13ers, but Silent set tone (from *Sesame Street* to rising divorce rates)
   - 1990s: Boomers (not 13ers) asserting control over Millennial children

> "Between any two parenting generations, the one in midlife naturally exercises a greater cultural and institutional influence than the one in rising adulthood."

### Peer Personality

**Peer personality** = caricature of prototypical member's attributes:
- Collective attitudes about family, sex roles, institutions, politics, religion, lifestyle, culture
- Can be outer-driven or inner-driven, generous or selfish, spiritual or secular
- Safer basis for generalization than sex, race, region, or age brackets

**Why generations work better than other categories:**
- A generation "is born, lives, and dies" — experiences historical urgency
- Unlike sex/age/race, understands work left undone may never be completed
- Feminist vs. traditional women differ more by generation than by ideology
- Attitudes of women/mothers toward work and family are central to peer personality

**Elite vs. non-elite:**
- **i capi della società** = "heads of society, kings of thought, lords of generation"
- Elite commonly express generational tone, but personality often established by non-elites
- Groups at social periphery (immigrants, blacks, fundamentalists) play major role

### Three-Part Test for Peer Personality

**A PEER PERSONALITY is recognized by:**
1. **Common age location** — chronology relative to historic trends/events
2. **Common beliefs and behavior** — objective data on marriage, crime, fertility, education, voting, attitudes
3. **Perceived membership** — society recognizes who belongs and who doesn't

### Chronology: Common Age Location in History

- Members "came along at the same time" through key life phases
- German sociologist **Karl Mannheim** coined **Generationslagerung** ("generational setting")
  - "Community of date and space"
  - "Common location in historical dimension of social process"
- Spanish peer **José Ortega y Gasset**: "coexistence" of cohorts makes them "the same age vitally and historically"

**Social community creates peer personality:**
- Expectations of elders create "something akin to gravity" pulling cohorts together
- Major events touch youngest/oldest members differently, even within same phase
- WWII combat cohorts (1915-1924) pulled on older cohorts with same dangers/rewards
- Vietnam draft cohorts (1943-1949) identified with their experiences

**Generational boundaries arise from two moments:**
1. **Birth cohorts** — some boundaries more decisive than others
2. **Coming-of-age shifts** — when older generations change nurturing attitudes

Examples of boundary shifts:
- Spiritual fervor eras: 1741-42, 1842-43, 1981-82 **Awakenings**
- Major crises: 1723-24, 1842-43, 1942-43 wars
- 1839-1860, 1942-1943 life crises close doors between adjacent cohorts

> "There is no single rule for locating a decisive shift in age location that divides adjacent generations."

### Attributes: Common Beliefs and Behavior

- Inner beliefs retain consistency over lifecycle (like individual personality aging)
- 19th century **Auguste Comte**: how one generation develops "unanimous adherence to certain fundamental notions"
- **Wilhelm Dilthey**: generational *Weltanschauung* = web of beliefs/ultimate questions carried from rising adulthood through old age

**Behavioral data across cohorts:**
- Marriage, crime, fertility, suicide, education, accidents, drug consumption, alcoholism, voting, work habits, ambition
- Example: 1723-1724 vs. 1821-1822 or 1859-1860 vs. 1924-1925 personages show telling contrasts

**"Dynamic compromise" between mass and individual:**
- Even those differing from peer norm are **aware** of their nonconformity
- **"Directive"** personalities help legitimize peer mind-set
- **"Suppressed"** personalities withdraw or struggle against their generation
- G.I. examples: Walt Disney (directive), Jack Kerouac (suppressed)
- Presidential examples: Truman/Johnson/Reagan (directive), Nixon/Ford/Bush (directive), Carter (suppressed)

**Contemporary example:**
- UCLA survey (late 1960s to late 1980s): college freshmen prioritizing "developing a philosophy of life" fell from 80% to 40%
- Prioritizing "being very well off financially" rose commensurately
- Both eras had people in both camps, but minority aware they're running against peer consensus

**Caution on interpreting data:**
- Statistics must be contextualized historically
- 1890s drug/alcohol consumption data ≠ 1960s-70s meaning
- Marriage age shifts depend on social conventions (1700s conformity vs. 1950s acceleration)

### Awareness: Perceived Membership in a Common Generation

> "Each of us moves with the men of our generation," — **Julián Marías**

- People intuitively feel generational membership of elders and juniors
- **Pinder's "entelechy"**: even boundary cohorts reveal objective clues about where they subjectively belong

**Media examples of generational awareness:**
- 1943 cohort: first toddlers labeled "Dr. Spock" children, first "extremists" in college (1965), "Americans Under 25" (*Time* 1967), "under-30 generation" phrase before disappearing (1972)
- Ask someone born 1943 vs. 1942 whether they identify with 1940s or 1950s — answer likely opposite

> **Ortega**: generational awareness makes a cohort "a species of biological missile hurled into space at a given instant, with a certain velocity and direction, a predetermined vital trajectory."

> **Mannheim**: generation's "essential destiny" — for some, reflects keen consensus about world they wanted to build

**Post-WWII examples:**
- 1961 John Kennedy's peers as "torchbearers" of power
- Postwar G.I.s shared strong sense of Mannheim's "essential destiny"
- 1960s: Jefferson/Cotton Mather elders reinforced expectations of greatness
- 1990s Boomers (not 13ers) asserting control of Millennials

> "Generation, like an individual, merges many different qualities, no one of which is definitive standing alone."

- Identifying eighteen generations requires assembling all evidence
- Challenge: identify **recurring elements** suggesting relationship between generational sequence and larger historical pattern

## Chapter 4: The Four-Part Cycle

### Generational Memory and Social Moments

**Pearl Harbor Sunday (Dec 7, 1941)** — defining generational moment:
- Missionaries as elders (stewardship), midlife Lost (pragmatic), rising adult G.I.s (soldiers/workers), Silent children (stay-out-of-way dependents)
- Half century later: G.I.s fought it, Silent saw it as children, Boomers nurtured by its aftermath, 13ers know it only as "history"

**Summer 1969** — Apollo moon landing, Chappaquiddick, Woodstock:
- Maximum convulsion, not maximum cooperation
- Silent began breaking from G.I. conformism, finding fault with G.I. constructions
- Coming-of-age Boomers established counter-community "as defiantly anti-G.I. as anything they could possibly have concocted"
- Late 1960s child 13ers found themselves in a world that told kids to "grow up fast"
- Next decade: social upheaval would redefine every phase of life

**Two events shaped lasting impressions:**
- WWII empowered G.I.s as rational civic doers — encouraged overreach into hubristic Apollo missions
- Silent aware of G.I. catharsis, came of age emulating war-hero elders, then began compensating with high-risk personal behavior
- G.I. dogma of science/optimism planted seeds of spiritual rebellion (younger 13ers)
- 13ers disconnected from focal event, passed through "generational childhood" without adult-perceived mission

**By 1969, span of roughly one generation had passed:**
- Everyone moved up one lifecycle notch
- Millennials now replacing 13ers in youth
- Memories of WWII and late 1960s still define generational mind-sets

**Reagan's 1989 farewell speech:**
- Baby born Reagan's speech day had more personal distance from Pearl Harbor Sunday (47+ years) than 40+ year distance Reagan had from Lee's Civil War surrender or Grant at Appomattox
- Echoes of 1960s in campaigns of "Drug Czar" William Bennett, "Dole-Czar" Bob Dole, Senator Al Gore's environmental focus
- 5-year-old Boomers grew up amid giddy optimism; 5-year-old Millennials nurtured in sober aftermath of spiritual discovery

### Social Moments

**A SOCIAL MOMENT** = era (~decade) when people perceive historic events radically altering social environment

- Everyone senses history moving swiftly, familiar world disappearing, new world emerging
- **Franklin Roosevelt's 1932 election** launched 13-year period rearranging American social landscape through WWII
- **Consciousness Revolution** (late 1960s-1970s): radical changes in family, language, dress, duty, community, Dick-and-Jane artifacts

**Two types of social moments:**

1. **SECULAR CRISES** — reordering outer world of institutions and public behavior
2. **SPIRITUAL AWAKENINGS** — changing inner world of values and private behavior

- Do not arrive at random
- Secular crisis and spiritual awakening never occur back-to-back
- **Social moments normally arrive in time intervals roughly separated by two phases of life** (~40-45 years)
- They **alternate in type** between secular crises and spiritual awakenings

### The Generational Diagonal

**Figure 4-1 schematic:**
- Vertical axis: phases of life (Elder, Midlife, Rising, Youth)
- Horizontal axis: calendar years (22-year intervals)
- Social moments culminate when generation fully enters phase
- Shows dominant and recessive generations passing through at alternating life phases

**Pattern:**
- **DOMINANT generations** entering rising adulthood and elderhood during social moments
- **RECESSIVE generations** entering youth and midlife during social moments

**Age location relative to social moments:**
- One type enters rising adulthood during crisis, enters elderhood during awakening
- Opposite type enters youth during crisis, enters midlife during awakening
- Every generation has unique phase-of-life position before/after each social moment type

### Four Generational Types (Figure 4-2)

**1. IDEALIST GENERATION** (dominant, inner-fixated):
- Grows up indulged after secular crisis
- Comes of age inspiring spiritual awakening
- Fragments into narcissistic rising adults
- Cultivates principle as moralistic midlifers
- Becomes visionary elders guiding next secular crisis

**2. REACTIVE GENERATION** (recessive):
- Grows up underprotected/criticized during spiritual awakening
- Matures into risk-taking, alienated rising adults
- Mellows into pragmatic midlife leaders during secular crisis
- Maintains respect but less influence as reclusive elders

**3. CIVIC GENERATION** (dominant, outer-fixated):
- Grows up increasingly protected after spiritual awakening
- Comes of age overcoming secular crisis
- Unites into heroic/achieving rising adults
- Sustains institutions as powerful midlifers
- Becomes busy elders attacked by next spiritual awakening

**4. ADAPTIVE GENERATION** (recessive):
- Grows up overprotected/suffocated during secular crisis
- Matures into risk-averse, conformist rising adults
- Produces indecisive midlife arbitrator-leaders during spiritual awakening
- Maintains influence but less respect as sensitive elders

### Lifecycle Paradigms

- **Idealists**: *prophetic* lifecycle of vision and values
- **Reactives**: *picaresque* lifecycle of survival and adventure
- **Civics**: *heroic* lifecycle of secular achievement and reward
- **Adaptives**: *genteel* lifecycle of expertise and amelioration

**Critical condition for fixed order:**
- Society must resolve each secular crisis with reasonable success
- When condition fails, cycle experiences interruption — skipping a beat

### Four Constellational Eras and Moods

**Chronological end of each era** = "aligned" constellation (last cohort of new generation born, older generations enter new phases):

1. **AWAKENING ERA** (Idealists coming of age) — cultural creativity, new ideals emerge, institutions challenged by spiritual awakening

2. **INNER-DRIVEN ERA** (Reactives coming of age) — individualism flourishes, new ideals cultivated separately, confidence in institutions declines, secular problems deferred

3. **CRISIS ERA** (Civics coming of age) — collective unity against perceived peril, secular crisis culminates, danger overcome, one set of new ideals triumphs

4. **OUTER-DRIVEN ERA** (Adaptives coming of age) — conformity and stability, triumphant ideals secularized, spiritual discontent deferred

**Aligned constellations** occur when last cohort enters new phase (years 0, 22, 44, 66 in Figure 4-2):
- Awakening era ends when last Reactive cohort born (coincides with last Idealist entering rising adulthood)
- Cycle reaches aligned Awakening constellation when Adaptive/Civic fully moved into midlife/elderhood

**History shapes generations, generations shape history:**
- During social moments, dominant types (Idealist/Civic) entering rising adulthood set "active" agenda (secular to spiritual or vice versa)
- Boomers during 1960s-70s: entering midlife with recessive generations behind, continued setting social agenda until next moment
- Thus social moments and constellational eras both matter

### Can the Cycle Exist in a Complicated World?

**Historical contingency vs. cycle:**
- History has good/bad surprises, accidents, rise of perestroika/Churchill or Saddam Hussein
- But prejudice focuses too closely on events without attention to **response those events generate**

**Response determines social moment:**
- Compare American response to WWI vs. WWII
- Both preceded by foreign acts (sinking *Lusitania* vs. Pearl Harbor)
- WWI: Congress waited 2 years to declare war, declared war only after divisive Prohibition movements
- WWII: nation mobilized as single organism
- WWI soldiers came home to moral nagging/whippet ticker-tape; WWII soldiers came home to moral nagging/whippet parades in different sense

**Why response matters more than events:**
- When society in midst of Crisis era (America 1941), generational forces cooperate, secular crisis exogenous events arise
- Had world not drifted into depression/war, some other historic emergency would have emerged
- Age location of peer personalities: inner-fixated Missionaries (sixties), plucky Lost (forties), outer-fixated G.I. (twenties), underprotected Silent (childhood)
- America poised for decisive effective action

**Compare 1941 with 1967** (Tonkin Gulf Incident):
- At peak of Awakening era — doers reaching elderhood, new prophets reaching combat age
- Both filled war-waging roles awkwardly, displeased each other
- Generational cycle significantly influenced American action during/after every major war

**Major war examples from cycle moods:**
- Revolution/WWII (Crisis era)
- War of 1812/Korea (Outer-Driven era)
- French and Indian/WWI (Inner-Driven era)
- Spanish-American/Vietnam (Awakening era)

> "They suggest how fortunate America may have been that the world's hour of fascist peril came when it did, and not a quarter century earlier or later."

**Spiritual awakenings less dependent on outside events:**
- Triggered from within, less dependent on outside events
- Specific emergence year may hinge on political/economic conditions (1886), war (1967), overdose of heroic fathers (1734, 1822)
- Awakenings in 1730s-40s and 1820s show how awakenings arise even without specific historical sparks
- Can reasonably conclude Puritans would have erupted without ostracism (though not necessarily sending offshoots to America)
- Transcendentals without abolitionism, Missionaries without Haymarket/agrarian revolt

**Idealist generations nurtured to burst forth spiritually:**
- When they do, awaken other generations along with them
- Generational cycle is deterministic in its broad outlines, but does not guarantee good/bad outcomes
- Each generation has flaws, each constellational mood comes with dangers
- Missionary generation produced zealot President (Mitchell Palmer), also principled Herbert Hoover/FDR
- Civil War offers normative lesson for all generations alive today
- Cycle provides each generation with location in history, peer personality, set of possible scripts
- **Each generation free to choose script that posterity may later read with gratitude or sorrow**

### The Twentieth Century Pattern (Figure 4-3)

**Four constellational eras shown:**

**INNER-DRIVEN ERA (1901-24)** — Crisis ends 1924:
- ELDERHOOD: PROGRESSIVE-MISSIONARY (Adaptive-Idealist) sensitive-visionary
- MIDLIFE: MISSIONARY (Idealist) moralistic
- RISING ADULTHOOD: LOST (Reactive) alienated
- YOUTH: G.I. (Civic) protected

**CRISIS ERA (1925-42)** — Outer-Driven begins 1942:
- ELDERHOOD: MISSIONARY (Idealist)
- MIDLIFE: LOST (Reactive) pragmatic
- RISING ADULTHOOD: G.I. (Civic) heroic
- YOUTH: SILENT (Adaptive) safcoated

**OUTER-DRIVEN ERA (1943-60)** — Awakening begins 1960:
- ELDERHOOD: LOST (Reactive) reclusive
- MIDLIFE: G.I. (Civic) powerful
- RISING ADULTHOOD: SILENT (Adaptive) conformist
- YOUTH: BOOM (Idealist) indulged

**AWAKENING ERA (1961-81)** — Inner-Driven would follow:
- ELDERHOOD: G.I. (Civic) busy
- MIDLIFE: SILENT (Adaptive) indecisive
- RISING ADULTHOOD: BOOM (Idealist) narcissistic
- YOUTH: THIRTEENTH (Reactive) criticized

**Aligned dates:** 1924, 1942, 1960, 1981 (each exactly 22-44 years from next)
- Note: aligned dates don't coincide perfectly with actual generational boundaries
- Actual boundaries occur during 2-year transition windows
- Generational constellation is always precisely 22 years long

**First eight decades of twentieth century show:**
- Crisis and Awakening constellations from diagonal (lower left to upper right)
- Pattern held in all but Civil War Cycle
- Shall find pattern held in five cycles with eighteen generations

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Chapter 5: The Cycle in America

### The Gray Champion Archetype

- Opening anecdote from **Hawthorne's _Twice-Told Tales_**: April 1689, King James II threatens American colonies with slavery
- Mysterious **"Gray Champion"** appears—an ancient man with commanding presence, stops British soldiers with a single gesture
- Revealed as **Simon Bradstreet**, one of original fire-hearted Puritans who first settled New England
- **Hawthorne's prophecy**: "whenever the descendants of the Puritans are to show the spirit of their sires, the old man appears again"
- Pattern confirmed in Revolutionary summer 1775, Civil War 1861, and each American crisis thereafter
- **Gray Champion** = aging, principled generation returning to leadership during secular crisis
- These elders had been young idealists during prior spiritual awakening, now face "darkness, adversity, and peril" in old age

### Eighteen American Generations Overview

**Population by Cycle:**
- Colonial Cycle: 600,000 people
- Revolutionary Cycle: 8,000,000 people
- Civil War Cycle: 50,000,000 people
- Great Power Cycle: 200,000,000 people
- Millennial Cycle: 180,000,000 (340M projected by 2025)

**The Pattern Confirmed (Figure 5-1):**
- **Puritan Generation** (1584-1614): Idealist/Reactive types, birthyears 1584-1614
- All 18 generations fit into five cycles spanning 1580s-1980s
- From first New World colonies to present, American history pulses to generational rhythm
- **Only one interruption**: Civil War Cycle lacks a Civic-type generation

### Core Generational Patterns

**Generational Boundaries:**
- First cohort of each Idealist generation born during/immediately after secular crisis
- **Puritans**: 4 years prior to culminating English victory over Spanish Armada
- **Awakeners**: 12 years after Glorious Revolution
- **Transcendentals**: 3 years after U.S. Constitution ratification
- **Missionaries**: 1 year before Civil War start
- **Boomers**: just after WWII turning point

**Generation Length:**
- All 17 completed generations range from 17-33 years, average **23.4 years**
- First two Colonial Cycle generations were 31 and 33 years (irregular immigration bursts)
- After Colonial period: only one generation longer than 26 years
- Average roughly matches **22-year span** postulated in Chapter 3 between birth and coming-of-age

**The Two-Stroke Rhythm:**
- All generations appear in **alternating sequence** of dominant (Idealist or Civic) and recessive (Reactive or Adaptive) lifecycles
- **Single exception**: two back-to-back recessives (Gilded and Progressive) during Civil War Cycle

**The Four-Type Cycle:**
- Four generational types appear in **fixed sequence**: Idealist → Reactive → Civic → Adaptive
- **Exception**: Civil War Cycle missing Civic type

**Cycles and History:**
- Timed to alternating rhythm of awakenings and crises
- Each cycle matches discrete historical epoch with crisis at approximate midpoint
- Three completed phase-of-life cycles: Colonial (1621-1733), Revolutionary (1734-1821), Civil War (1822-1885)
- Ongoing cycles: Great Power (1886-1966), Millennial (began 1967, still extending)
- Average cycle length: **89 years**; Civil War cycle only 64 years (considerably shorter)

### First to Define the Sequence

- Authors claim to be **first to define, locate, and name** the entire sequence of American generations
- Beginning with the Lost, reader may recognize several consensus names
- **Baby Boom exception**: demographers define as high-fertility years 1946-1964
- Authors fix boundaries a few years earlier to fit peer personality criteria (not parents' fecundity)
- "Baby" is **inappropriate name** for generation now entering midlife

### Scholarly Convergence

**Four scholars have suggested generational divisions closely matching authors' boundary lines:**
- **1925**: Historian Arthur Schlesinger described eight generations Liberty to Missionary (7 found)
- **1976**: Daniel Elazar found eleven generations in 13-generation span
- **1976**: Brandeis historian Morton Keller identified eleven generations from Liberty through Boom
- **1978**: Harvard professor Samuel Huntington listed eight generations roughly matching authors' eight from Republican through G.I.s

**Key Difference from Other Scholars:**
- Most scholars define generations by **public activity** during rising adulthood and midlife
- Authors examine **entire lifecycles**, evaluate peer personality during each phase of life, including private behavior

### Social Moments Defined

**Chapter 4 showed**: social moments—secular crises and spiritual awakenings—lie at core of generational cycle

**Figure 5-2 shows intervals** between social moments for past five centuries:
- First two social moments (Reformation Awakening, English Armada Crisis) shaped peer personalities of immediate English-born ancestors of Puritan Generation
- Next nine social moments occurred during lifecycles of eighteen American generations

**Social Moment Timing:**
- Can run from about **one to two decades** in length
- Toward end of each, typically occurs a climactic event marking maximum emotional impact
- **Secular crises**: Pearl Harbor Sunday 1941, colonial Glorious Revolution 1689, Gettysburg 1863
- **Awakenings**: ratification of U.S. Constitution 1789, election of Ronald Reagan 1980
- Peak events suddenly shape cohort-groups into well-defined generations according to respective phases of life

**Influence on Generation Formation:**
- Entire generation can carry deep impression if social moment makes deep impression on youths in late teens/mid-twenties
- Can shape entire generation as it comes of age

### Intervals Between Social Moments

**Figure 5-2 shows**:
- Intervals are **not identical**, partly because generational process can widen or narrow actual length
- Powerful influence of last-wave G.I.s (earlier-born peers) and first-wave Boomers (later-born peers) helped narrow interval between WWII-era crisis and Boom Awakening
- Average interval: **44 years**, matching 44-year span for two phases of life
- Somewhat longer generations produce somewhat longer intervals; some cycles where we observe shorter ones
- **Single telling exception**: 28-year interval before Civil War Crisis, precisely where we observe a truncated, three-generation cycle

### Secular Crises: The Five Events

**Important coincidence**: timespans separating four pivotal events of American history almost exactly match

**Exactly 85 years passed** between first Confederate shot on Fort Sumter and Pearl Harbor Day

**85 years also passed** between Fort Sumter and Declaration of Independence (with President Lincoln noting "Four score and seven years" separate Fourth of July from Gettysburg)

**Similarity: 87 years** separate First Fourth of July from Battle of Gettysburg

**Another 87 years** between Anglo-American "Glorious Revolution" of 1689 and Independence Day

**99 years** preceded Glorious Revolution by slightly longer period—epocal victory of English navy over Spanish Armada

**All five events marked culmination** of swift and sweeping change in secular world:
- Each surrounded witnesses with palpable fear for social survival, collective unity in face of peril, sudden institutional change/innovation
- Apprehensive about future reached climax
- Followed (in all but fourth case) by sense of optimism and dawning of bright new era

### The Five Secular Crises Listed

**The Armada Crisis (1580-1588)** in England:
- Extended from first overt hostilities between England and Spain through Drake's epic voyage in _Golden Hind_
- Ended with English destruction of Spanish Armada
- Sample rising-adult leaders: Sir Walter Raleigh, Francis Bacon, Sir Philip Sidney

**The Glorious Revolution Crisis (1675-1692)** in American colonies:
- Extended from King Philip's War and Bacon's Rebellion through American rebellions against James II
- Ended about time of Salem witch trials
- Sample rising-adult leaders: Cotton Mather, John Wise, Peter Schuyler

**The American Revolution Crisis (1773-1789)** in American colonies and states:
- Extended from Boston Tea Party through Declaration of Independence
- Ended with ratification of Constitution and inauguration of President Washington
- Sample rising-adult leaders: Thomas Jefferson, James Madison, John Marshall

**The Civil War Crisis (1857-1865)** in United States:
- Extended from Dred Scott decision, great Kansas debates, fragmentation of Democratic Party
- Ended with Lee's surrender and Lincoln's assassination
- Sample rising-adult leaders: Ulysses Grant, Stonewall Jackson, Andrew Carnegie

**The Great Depression-World War II Crisis (1932-1945)** in United States:
- Extended from bleakest depression year and FDR's election
- Ended with VJ-Day
- Sample rising-adult leaders: John Kennedy, Robert Oppenheimer, Walt Disney

### Crisis Constellations (Figure 5-3)

**Optimal generational lineup** for overcoming social emergencies appears in every secular crisis except Civil War:

**Elder phase (old Idealists):**
- Providing principle and vision
- Glorious Revolution: **Puritan** (Simon Bradstreet)
- American Revolution: **Awakening** (Samuel Adams)
- Civil War: **Compromise/Adaptive** (James Buchanan)
- Great Depression/WWII: **Missionary** (Franklin Roosevelt)

**Midlife phase (Reactive midlifers):**
- Understanding how real world functions, leading accordingly
- Glorious Revolution: **Cavalier** (Increase Mather)
- American Revolution: **Liberty** (George Washington)
- Civil War: **Transcendental** (Abraham Lincoln)
- Great Depression/WWII: **Lost** (Dwight Eisenhower)

**Rising adult phase (smart, organized Civics):**
- Doing their duty
- Glorious Revolution: **Glorious** (Cotton Mather)
- American Revolution: **Republican** (Thomas Jefferson)
- Civil War: **Gilded/Reactive** (Ulysses Grant)
- Great Depression/WWII: **G.I.** (John Kennedy)

**Youth phase (Adaptive youths):**
- Emulating adults, making relatively few demands
- Glorious Revolution: **Enlightenment** (Elisha Cooke Jr.)
- American Revolution: **Compromise** (Dolley Madison)
- Civil War: **Progressive** (Bookey T. Washington)
- Great Depression/WWII: **Silent** (Sandra Day O'Connor)

**Key insight**: This is constellation of action, not reflection. People become pragmatic, community-oriented, more risk-averse in public and private life. Distinctions between sex roles widen, all prerogatives of seniority grow to maximum intensity.

**Crisis leaves heavy footprint** on remaining lifecycle of every generation then living—especially Civics, who thereafter assume a hubris born of triumph, confidence in own achievements that elders and juniors can never match.

> "To propel the generational cycle in this direction, a _secular crisis_ ended _with triumph_."

Happened in every cycle but one: **Civil War**. This anomaly offers important lessons about how generational history can turn out well—or badly.

### The Civil War Anomaly

**Civil War Cycle lacks Civic-type generation**—at 64 years, fully 17 years shorter than any other cycle

**Twenty-eight years separate** end of Civil War Crisis from end of preceding Transcendental awakening

**What happened?**

**First, the crisis came early:**
- Initial year of crisis came **51 years** after middle birth cohort of Transcendental (Idealist) generation
- Other crisis periods begin 72, 62, and 61 years after middle Idealist birthyear
- **Ten-to-fifteen-year difference** (equivalent of half a phase of life) is quite significant
- By 1920s/1930s when Franklin Roosevelt's midlife Missionary Generation still crusading for Prohibition "experiment" and rising-adult Lost had yet to emerge from alienation and pleasure-seeking
- Suppose combination of domestic fascism and global fascism had hit then
- Very likely national mood would have been more fragmented, public action less confident
- American Revolution might have taken less radical turn if occurred before Stamp Act riots of 1765
- What sort of Constitution might have been written by midlife Awakeners or hard-luck Liberty rising adults, rather than confident public-minded Republicans?
- **These odd hypotheticals point to what happened in Civil War**
- Civil War waged **15 years later**—with Transcendentals more self-controlled as elder stewards, Gilded less daring as midlife leaders, Progressives more obedient as rising-adult order-takers

**Second, three adult generations allowed more dangerous peer instincts to prevail:**
- Following failed efforts of Henry Clay, Daniel Webster, John Calhoun to avert war, **elderly Compromisers of Buchanan** were unable to rise above empty process and moral confusion
- **Transcendental Generation** split not just along competing but two entirely contained, mutually exclusive societies
- Transcendental leaders—**Abraham Lincoln, William Sherman, Thaddeus Stevens, Jefferson Davis, Julia Ward Howe**—were, as youths, unable to resist waging war (and peace) with ruthless, apocalyptic finality
- Younger **Gilded** never outgrew an adventurer's lust for battle or gambler's hankering for personal honor
- Until war was over, three adult generations steered very dangerous constellation
- Together produced **nearest approximation of holocaust** America has ever experienced
- Place Civil War Cycle alongside two neighboring cycles—Revolutionary and Great Power
- Notice how Civil War roughly a decade after French and Indian War and WWI, decade before Revolution and WWII
- Combined worst features of both: colossal scale of former with lasting bitterness of latter

**Third, the crisis came to an untriumphant end:**
- Was Civil War a failure?
- Need not answer question directly, but simply observe: for each of other secular crises, difficult to imagine more uplifting finale than what actually occurred
- For Civil War, can easily imagine better outcome
- Yes, Union preserved, slaves emancipated, industrial revolution fully unleashed
- But consider enormous cost: deep-rooted sectional hatred, impoverishment and political exile of South, collapse of Reconstruction into era of lynchings and Jim Crow, long delay that postwar exhaustion later imposed on most other social agendas
- Everything from antitrust policy to labor grievances to temperance to woman's suffrage rights

**Political reaction** of those alive at time indicates many Americans did indeed attribute harmful finale of these crises to calamitous miscommunication between young and old:
- Civil War followed by **largest generational landslide** in American history
- In 1868, rising-adult Civics tossed out aging Transcendental zealots for fortyish Gilded
- Afterward, no rising generation emerged to fulfill Civic role of initiating public institutions to realize Transcendentals' visions
- Instead, Gilded aged in midlife, presided over period of unusual cultural and spiritual staleness
- Likewise, though Progressives been much raised with protective prewar nurture that prepared them to come of age as Civic generation, they emerged from Civil War rather with emotional baggage
- Acquiring little collective confidence as young adults, left their future in hands of Gilded, developed distinctly Adaptive peer personality

### Spiritual Awakenings

**America encounters secular crisis roughly every 90 years**, now turn to other kind of social moment arriving roughly halfway in between: **spiritual awakening**

**Stepping ahead 40-odd years** from Armada victory of 1588 brings us to 1630, year of popular religious enthusiasm in England when **John Winthrop** and fellow zealots set sail to found a New Jerusalem in America

**Moving 40-odd years** from colonial Glorious Revolution of 1689 takes us to 1734—year **Jonathan Edwards** touched off Great Awakening

**Connecticut Valley** fire intervals separate each of remaining three secular crises from later episodes of widespread and tumultuous spiritual fervor

**Past two decades**, several social and religious historians explored importance of these episodes:
- **William McLoughlin's 1978 book _Revivals, Awakenings, and Reform_** identifies five American "awakenings" roughly conforming to intervals our cycle would suggest
- McLoughlin defines awakenings as "periods of culture revitalization that begin in general crisis of beliefs and values and extend over period of generation or so, during which time profound reorientation in beliefs and values takes place"
- Building from anthropologist **Anthony Wallace's** theory of "revitalization movements"
- McLoughlin describes how, in modern society, spiritual awakening can "alter world view of whole people or culture"
- Over intervening span of 6-11 decades, "times change; world changes; people change; and therefore institutions, world views, and cultural systems must change"
- Notes each awakening episode was, in its own time, center of "individualistic, pietistic, perfectionist, millennarian ideology" which "has from time to time been variously defined and explained to meet changing experiences and contingencies in our history"

**Unlike episode of secular crisis** (real-world threat triggers disciplined collective action and sudden institutional change):
- **Awakening is driven** by sudden value changes and society-wide effort to recapture feeling of spiritual authenticity
- Focus not on institutions, but on individual
- **Awakening moment is not essentially public or collective** (though may spark crowds, hysteria, violence), but personal and individual
- Awakening brings to rising-adult Idealists what **Robert Bellah** has called "a common set of moral understandings about good and bad, right and wrong, in realm of individual and social action"
- During Awakening, these new "understandings" arose almost entirely in terms of **religious dogma**
- Ever since, focus has shifted by degrees toward radical "-isms" of modern age

**Underlying psychology of awakening conversion** remained much the same through subsequent centuries

**Like crisis**, awakening leaves **indelible impression** on remaining lifecycle of every generation then alive:
- Shapes rising-adult generation with special force
- Whereas crisis empowers rising-adult generation, awakening endows it with perpetual or ideological mission that stays with life members
- Among vanguard of awakening, always notice **isolated or ambivalent midlife** (Desiderius Erasmus, William Brewster, Thomas Foxcroft, William Ellery Channing, John Dewey, Charles Reich) quite aware movement's center of gravity is located in **younger generation**
- Yet best-known leaders are typically **first-wave Idealists**, preaching to younger Idealists just coming of age—peer leaders like **Martin Luther, John Winthrop, Jonathan Edwards, Ralph Waldo Emerson, William Jennings Bryan, Angela Davis**

### The Five American Awakenings Listed

**McLoughlin's five American "awakenings"** correspond closely to five "spiritual awakenings" as we define them:
- Other historians have located and named eras of historic spiritual upheaval at similar dates
- Starting with **surge of Reformation enthusiasm** in precolonial period, list them as follows, naming each after **Idealist Generation** whose coming-of-age youths were largely responsible for pushing it forward:

**The Reformation Awakening (1517-1539)** in Europe:
- Universally known as "Reformation"
- Best known of all awakenings in western history
- Sample rising-adult leaders: **Martin Luther, John Calvin, John Knox**

**The Puritan Awakening (1621-1640)** in England, Scotland, and America:
- Often called "Puritan Awakening"
- Also known as era of "Puritan Enthusiasm" or "Revolutionary Puritanism"
- Sample rising-adult leaders who came to America: **John Winthrop, John Cotton, Anne Hutchinson**

**The Great Awakening (1734-1743)** in American colonies:
- Known at time as "the Great and General Awakening"
- Referred to ever since as "Great Awakening"
- Sample rising-adult leaders: **Jonathan Edwards, George Whitefield, William Tennent**

**The Transcendental Awakening (1822-1837)** in United States:
- Loosely dated period known to most historians (and Idealists) as the "Second Great Awakening"
- Also called era of "Romantic Evangelicalism" and "Transcendental Idealism"
- Sample rising-adult leaders: **Ralph Waldo Emerson, Nat Turner, Charles Finney**

**The Missionary Awakening (1886-1903)** in United States:
- Called "Third Great Awakening" by McLoughlin and few others
- Also known as age of "Reform," "Victorianism," and "Labor Radicalism"
- Sample rising-adult leaders: **William Jennings Bryan, Jane Addams, W.E.B. DuBois**

**The Boom Awakening (1967-1980)** in United States:
- Called "Fourth Great Awakening" by McLoughlin
- At times termed "New Transcendentalism"
- Now generally referred to as recent "Sixties," "Counterculture," or (especially) "Consciousness Revolution"
- Sample rising-adult leaders: **Arlo Guthrie, Mark Rudd, Rap Brown**

### Awakening Constellations (Figure 5-4)

**Figure 5-4 identifies generational constellations** of each Awakening era, excluding precolonial Reformation Awakening

**Once again**, see repeating constellational pattern in all but Great Power Cycle (which followed Civic-less Civil War Cycle):
- Pattern consisting of **old Civics, midlife Adaptives, rising-adult Idealists, and young Reactives**
- Picture peer personalities of each generational type at respective phase of life:

**Civic elders:**
- Confidently running or overseeing institutions they once built around earlier set of values

**Adaptive midlifers:**
- Feeling pulled in competing directions by more powerful generations on either side

**Idealist rising adults:**
- Experiencing spiritual conversion near coming-of-age moment and cultivating implacable moral conviction

**Reactive youths:**
- Too young to participate, left alone, urged to grow up quickly, criticized as "bad"

**This lineup of elder doers and rising-adult thinkers**—very different from Crisis constellation—rarely does well at large public undertakings:
- Trained order-takers are old
- Instinctive order-givers are young
- Any collective effort (such as major war) faces strong social obstacles
- During height of this constellation can generate **great spiritual energy and unusual creativity** in philosophy, letters, and arts
- During later Idealist maturity, see **more mounting frustration** with public institutions, fragmenting families and communities, rising alcohol and drug abuse, growing tendency to take risks in most spheres of life
- Sex-role distinctions decline, protected-accredited children reaches low ebb
- Afterward, maturing Idealists retain inner convictions borne of awakening experience and (after period of political exploration) attempt to project and enforce principles on world around them

**Where post-crisis rising-adult Civics exude confident optimism and rationality** as move into midlife:
- **Post-awakening Idealists steer national mood** toward pessimistic and portentous spiritualism

**To comprehend generational cycle** is to foresee where cycle will turn as future unfolds:
- To anticipate who next "Gray Champion" will be—and when his next "hour of darkness, and adversity, and peril" will arrive
- **"Long, long may it be ere he comes again!"** wrote Hawthorne

**One purpose of this book**: to help reader **foresee _how long_**—and understand why

## Chapter 6: From Puritans to Millennials and Beyond

### Childhood Images in Film (1960s-1970s)

**1968 was not exactly Year of the Baby**, but amid assassinations, riots, student strikes, Vietnam buildup, highest-grossing movies featured babies:
- **_Rosemary's Baby_**: watching Daddy sell soon-to-born child to witch's coven, audience had to think "Please don't have this baby, abort it!"

**Over next ten years**, child demons proliferated across American movie screens:
- _The Exorcist, Exorcist II, Damien, Omen II, Omen III, It's Alive! It Lives Again, Demon Seed_

**Even when film children of 1970s** weren't slashing and biting parents:
- They were: precocious proddies (_Taxi Driver_), molls and racketeers (_Bugsy Malone_), arsonists (_Carrie_), spoiled brats (_Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory_), abandoned articles (_Kramer vs. Kramer_)

**Never in age of cinema** had producers and audiences obsessed over such thoroughly distressing image of childhood

**Compare with children** featured in Disney's _Shaggy Dog_ films of 1950s: bright, well-meaning kids whom adults respected, kids any filmgoer knew would grow up to be interesting people

**Compare those 1970s-era child images** with cuddly-baby antidotes that began to appear mid-1980s:
- _Raising Arizona, Three Men and a Baby, Baby Boom, Parenthood_—all featuring lots of audiences felt like bundling in their arms and protecting

**Who occupied early-childhood age bracket** when these films being made and viewed?
- **Boomers** during smart-kid movie era of 1950s
- **13ers** during demon-seed era of 1970s

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Chapter 3 (continued): Belonging to a "Generation"

### The Length of a Generation

- **Generation length** defined by phases of life, not fixed arithmetic averages
- Social philosophers traditionally used cohort-groups or average age of parenthood (~33 years), but this misses key dynamics
- Authors choose **phase of life** approach: generation length = span of one life phase (~22 years)
- Four life phases with distinct central roles:
  - **ELDERHOOD** (66-87): *stewardship* (supervising, mentoring, passing values)
  - **MIDLIFE** (44-65): *leadership* (parenting, teaching, directing institutions)
  - **RISING ADULTHOOD** (22-43): *activity* (working, starting families, testing values)
  - **YOUTH** (0-21): *dependence* (learning, accepting nurture, acquiring values)

- **Coming-of-age moment** ("rite of passage") critical for generational identity—sharp contrast between youth dependence and adult independence creates lasting peer personality differences
- American 22-year intervals: end of apprenticeship, college, peacetime draft, homeownership access, first suffrage (historically), youngest Presidential candidate age (~43-44), typical retirement (~65-66)

### Decisive Events Shape Generations

- Major wars or revolutions suddenly realign society—each age group responds differently according to its central role
- Example: major war places youths in dependence, rising adults at the front, midlifers leading home front, elders offering wisdom
- **Decisive events** permanently reshape cohort-groups, reinforcing separate identities and creating distinct generational personalities lasting into old age
- Result: series of distinct cohort-groups with unique **peer personality**

### Generation Boundaries Shift with Historical Context

- Generation length not always precisely 22 years—varies with historical rhythms
- 1960s-70s: coming-of-age drifted upward (youth extended); 1930s-40s: drifted downward (early adulthood)
- Large sudden changes rare; most Americans come of age gradually over many years
- Historical context matters: marriage age, risk appetite, institutional norms all shift decade by decade

### Family-Based Generational Patterns

- **Parents distributed over two preceding generations** (mothers/fathers typically ages 20-45)
- **First-wave vs. last-wave cohorts** within a generation receive different nurture
  - Example: confident G.I.s (born mid-1940s) = first wave, from young parents born 1925-1942
  - More ambivalent Silent (born late 1950s) = last wave, from older parents
- **Second-succeeding generation** has especially strong nurturing influence
  - 1960: G.I. parents roughly equal Boomer children by number
  - 1970s: fortysish/fiftyish G.I.s (Dr. Spock, Walt Disney, school principals) had greater influence on Boomer childhood than twentyish/thirtyish Silent
  - 1990s: Silent and Boomer parents together raising 13ers, but midlife parent naturally exercises greater institutional influence than rising-adult parent

### Peer Personality

- **Peer personality** = caricature of prototypical member; cohesive cohort-group with unique biography
- Defined by: (1) common age location, (2) common beliefs and behavior, (3) perceived membership
- Safer basis for personality generalization than sex, race, region, or age
- Consensus personality easier to establish for Lost, Boomers than for women, Hispanics, Californians, or 30-year-olds
- Generation "is born, lives, and dies"—feels historical urgency and finality, conscious of unrepeatable opportunities
- Work left undone at each phase may never be done by others the way an aging generation wishes

### Elite vs. Non-Elite Personalities

- Peer personality gives heavy focus to **generational elite**—*i capi della società* ("heads of society")
- Elite commonly expresses tone of generation's peer personality, but personality itself often established by **non-elites**
- Women, mothers, family roles, and social periphery groups (immigrants, blacks, fundamentalists) play major role in revealing peer personality

### Three-Part Test for Peer Personality

**A PEER PERSONALITY is a generational persona recognized and determined by:**
1. **Common age location** (chronology against historical backdrop)
2. **Common beliefs and behavior** (objective measures, trends, attributes)
3. **Perceived membership** in a common generation (who is considered a member and who is not)

## Chapter 3 (continued): Chronology: Common Age Location in History

### Karl Mannheim's Generationslagerung

- **Karl Mannheim** invented term *Generationslagerung* ("generational setting")—"a community of date and space" and "common location in the historical dimension of the social process"
- **José Ortega y Gasset**: "coetaneous" cohorts share "the same concrete circumstances which make them 'the same age vitally and historically'"
- Sense of social community reinforced by elders creates "something akin to gravity" pulling outlying cohorts into common peer personality

### Age Location and Major Events

- Generation of average length can stretch from newborn babies to 40-year-olds—any major event touches youngest and oldest differently
- Even within same phase of life, few important cohorts strongly influence reflections of larger cohort-group
- Example: **WWII combat cohorts** (born 1915-1924)—pulled on older cohorts, saw themselves taking same risks, earning same rewards
- Example: **Vietnam-era cohorts** (born 1943-1949)—pulled on younger cohorts, identified with their experiences

### Generational Boundaries: Birth and Nurture Shifts

- Boundaries arise at two moments: birth year clustering AND nurture shifts
- Boundaries typically occur:
  - During or just after eras of **exceptional spiritual fervor** (1741-1742, 1842-1843, 1981-1982 shifts)
  - During or just after **major crises in public life** (1859-1860, 1942-1943 shifts)
- Public crises close door of communication between coming-of-age youngsters (1723-1724, 1882-1883, 1960-1961 boundaries)

- No single rule for locating decisive shifts—usually many historical trends point to same boundary

### Attributes: Common Beliefs and Behavior

- As generation ages, inner beliefs retain consistency over lifecycle (like individual personality)
- **Auguste Comte**: "each generation develops 'unanimous adherence to certain fundamental notions'"
- **Wilhelm Dilthey**: *Weltanschauung* = web of beliefs and ultimate questions each generation carries from rising adulthood through old age
- Important behavioral traits offer clues about boundaries: marriage, crime, fertility, suicide, education, voting, work habits, ambition

### Telling Contrasts Across Adjacent Cohorts

- Famous personages born across 1723-1724, 1821-1822, 1859-1860, 1924-1925 show sharp contrasts
- Beliefs and behavior never show up uniformly across all members—"dynamic compromise between mass and individual"
- Even those who differ from peer norm are **aware** of their nonconformity

### "Directive," "Directed," and "Suppressed" Personalities

- **Julius Peterson** typology legitimizes peers' mind-set:
  - **"Directive"** individual helps overall tone; "directed" follows and legitimizes; "suppressed" withdraws or struggles against
  - Example G.I.s: **Walt Disney** = directive; **Cronkite** = directed; **Jack Kerouac** = suppressed rebel
  - Example G.I. Presidents: **Eisenhower, Johnson, Reagan** = directive; **Nixon, Ford, Bush** = directed; **Carter** = suppressed

### UCLA Survey Example: Philosophy of Life Shifts

- Annual UCLA survey of college freshmen (late 1960s to late 1980s):
  - "Developing a philosophy of life" priority: fell from 80% to 40%
  - "Being very well off financially" priority: rose commensurately
- Both eras had young people in both camps—but minority acutely aware they were running against peer tide

### Historical Context Required

- No reductive rules for comparing beliefs/behavior across cohorts
- Social science data must be interpreted in proper historical context
- Trends in inner/outer life, risk-taking, self-esteem reflect age-specific personality traits over centuries
- High rates of youthful substance abuse have *always* indicated attraction to risk; rise during 1960s-70s says about generations alive *today*
- Average marriage age must be interpreted differently from decade to decade: 1700s early conformity, 1950s accelerating marriage/moving out early

## Chapter 3 (continued): Awareness: Perceived Membership in a Common Generation

### Generational Self-Awareness

> "Each of us moves with the men of our generation," Julián Marías observed two decades ago

- Most people know intuitively to which generation they belong—good feeling for membership of elders and juniors
- Awareness of generational membership helps most with boundary cohorts possessing **Pinder's "entelechy"**
- Even when cohorts reveal few *objective* clues about where they belong, they often have strong *subjective* perceptions

### Media Examples of Generational Identity

- **Lost novelists** born 1898-1899 (Fitzgerald, Hemingway) made clear they felt hugely different from "bright and alien" youngsters (Lindbergh, Disney) born 1901-1902
- **1943 cohort** media ripple: first toddlers labeled "Dr. Spock" children, first high school "extremists," first college class (1965) to be called "radical," youngest "Americans Under 25" (*Time* 1967 Man of Year), last 29-year-olds (1972) to hear "under-30 generation" phrase before it suddenly disappeared

### Generational Awareness and Trajectory

- Awareness applies to where generation is now, but also **where it is expected to go tomorrow**
- **José Ortega y Gasset**: generation like "species of biological missile hurled into space at a given instant, with certain velocity and direction"—predetermined vital trajectory
- **Mannheim**: generation's "essential destiny"

### Examples of Expected Destiny

- Cohesion of postwar G.I.s reflected keen generational consensus about world they wanted to build—adding to sense of collective mission when **JFK** brought peers to power in 1961
- Earlier American generations shared strong sense of essential destiny:
  - Reconstructing outer world (Jefferson and peers of **Cotton Mather**)
  - Expected greatness reinforced by elders/juniors at time

### Generational Identity: Persuasive but Not Definitive

- Like individual personality, generational identity merges many different qualities—no single quality definitive standing alone
- Once all evidence assembled, can build persuasive case for identifying eighteen generations over American history
- All Americans born over past four centuries belonged to one or another of these generations

### Next Challenge: Recurring Elements and Historical Cycles

- Authors' deeper challenge: identify recurring elements in peer personalities suggesting relationship between sequence of generations and larger pattern of history
- Now turn to **the cycle**

---

## Social Moments in American History

### Secular Crises

**Definition**: Moments when public institutions suddenly strengthen as people of all ages unite to protect their community
- Peak events occur every ~90 years
- History turns **decisively** during these moments

**Five American Secular Crises:**

1. **The Armada Crisis (1580-1588)**: England vs. Spain hostilities through Drake's *Golden Hind* voyage to Spanish Armada destruction
   - Rising-adult leaders: **Sir Walter Raleigh, Francis Bacon, Philip Sidney**

2. **The Glorious Revolution Crisis (1675-1692)**: King Philip's War through Bacon's Rebellion to American rebellions against James II, ending with Salem witch trials
   - Rising-adult leaders: **Cotton Mather, John Wise, Peter Schuyler**

3. **The American Revolution Crisis (1773-1789)**: Boston Tea Party through Declaration of Independence to Constitution ratification and Washington's inauguration
   - Rising-adult leaders: **Thomas Jefferson, James Madison, John Marshall**

4. **The Civil War Crisis (1857-1865)**: *Dred Scott* decision through Kansas debates and Democratic Party fragmentation to Lee's surrender and Lincoln's assassination
   - Rising-adult leaders: **Ulysses Grant, Stonewall Jackson, Andrew Carnegie**

5. **The Great Depression-World War II Crisis (1932-1945)**: From bleakest depression year through New Deal election to VJ-Day
   - Rising-adult leaders: **John Kennedy, Robert Oppenheimer, Walt Disney**

**Historical Timing:**
- **Exactly 85 years** passed between first Confederate shot at Fort Sumter (1861) and Pearl Harbor (1946)
- **85 years also** between Fort Sumter and Declaration of Independence signing
- **"Four score and seven years"** separates Fourth of July from Gettysburg
- **Another 85-87 years** between Anglo-American "Glorious Revolution" (1689) and Independence Day
- **99 years** preceded Glorious Revolution by English navy victory over Spanish Armada

All five crises marked sudden, sweeping change in secular world: widespread fear for survival, collective unity, institutional change/innovation, climax followed by sense of bright new era dawning

### The Constellational Pattern During Crises

**Optimal Crisis Lineup** (except Civil War):
- **Idealist elders**: old, providing principle and vision
- **Reactive midlifers**: understanding real-world function, leading accordingly
- **Civic rising adults**: smart, organized, doing their duty
- **Adaptive youths**: emulating adults, making few demands

This constellation enables decisive action: elders bring wisdom, midlifers savvy, rising adults cooperation, children silence. Result: order-givers are old, order-takers young—actionable, community-oriented, risk-averse. Sex role distinctions and generational hierarchy grow to maximum intensity.

> "The crisis leaves a heavy footprint on the remaining lifecycle of every generation then living—especially the Civic, who thereafter assume a hubris born of triumph, a belief in community over self, and a collective confidence in their own achievements that their elders and juniors can never match."

The generational cycle in crisis moments is a **secular crisis myth ended with triumph**—occurred in every cycle but Civil War. This anomaly offers important lessons about how generational history can turn out well—or badly.

---

## The Civil War Anomaly

### Why the Civil War Cycle Was Different

**Key Issue**: Civil War Cycle lacks a Civic-type generation—fully **17 years shorter** than any other cycle (only 64 years vs. typical 81+ years)

### Three Factors Explaining the Anomaly

**1. The Crisis Came Early**
- Crisis began 51 years after middle birth cohort of **Transcendental (Idealist) generation**
- Other crisis periods began 62-72 years after the middle Idealist birthyear
- **10-15 year difference** = roughly half a phase of life
- In 1920s equivalent: FDR's midlife Missionary Generation still crusading for Prohibition while rising-adult Lost had yet to emerge from pleasure-seeking alienation
- Very likely national mood would have been more fragmented, public action less confident
- Suppose global fascism had hit then—American Revolution might have resembled Stamp Act riots (1765) rather than successful revolution
- **Effect**: Crisis happened 15 years later with Transcendentals more self-controlled as elder stewards, Gilded less daring, and Progressives more effective as rising-adult order-takers

**2. Three Adult Generations Allowed More Dangerous Peer Instincts to Prevail**
- Following failed efforts of **Henry Clay, Daniel Webster, John C. Calhoun** to avert war, elderly Compromise Generation of Buchanan were unable to rise above empty process and moral confusion
- Transcendental Generation split into mutually exclusive societies unable to compromise
- Leaders like **Abraham Lincoln, William Sherman, Thaddeus Stevens, Jefferson Davis, Julia Ward Howe**: full of apocalyptic finality, ruthless in waging war (and peace)
- Younger Gilded never outgrew an adventurer's lust for battle or displayed personal honor—until war was over
- **Three adult generations** steered a very dangerous constellation—together produced the nearest approximation of holocaust America has ever experienced
- Place the Civil War Cycle alongside Revolution and WWII: **combined worst features of both**—colossal scale of former with lasting bitterness of latter

**3. The Crisis Came to an Untriumphant End**
- Was the Civil War a failure? No simple answer, but compared to other secular crises, difficult to imagine more uplifting finale
- Union preserved, slaves emancipated, industrial revolution unleashed—BUT enormous cost:
  - Deep-rooted sectional hatred
  - Impoverishment and political exile of the South
  - Collapse of Reconstruction into era of lynchings and Jim Crow
  - Long delay imposing postwar exhaustion on most social agendas (from antitrust policy to labor reservoirs to temperance)
- Political reaction indicated many Americans attributed painful finale to **calamitous miscommunication between young and old**
- Civil War followed by largest generational landslide in American history
- In 1868: aging Transcendental zealots tossed out for fortyish Gilded
- No rising generation emerged to fulfill Civic role of building public institutions or realize Transcendentals' visions
- Instead: Gilded aged into unique Reactive-Civic hybrid, presiding over period of unusual cultural/spiritual staleness
- Likewise: Progressives had been raised with protective prewar nurture, prepared to come of age as Civic generation
- But they emerged after Civil War rather than **during** it, left their future in hands of Gilded
- Developed distinctly **Adaptive peer personality**
- Acquired little collective confidence as young adults

---

## Spiritual Awakenings

### The Pattern of Awakenings

America encounters a spiritual awakening roughly every **90 years**, arriving about halfway between secular crises. Stepping ahead 42-49 years from Armada victory (1588) brings us to **1630**: year of Puritan enthusiasm in England when **John Winthrop** and fellow zealots set sail to found a New Jerusalem in America.

Moving 43 years past colonial Glorious Revolution (1689) takes us to **1734**—year **Jonathan Edwards** touched off Great Awakening in Connecticut Valley. Four intervals separate remaining three secular crises from later episodes of widespread, tumultuous spiritual fervor.

### Five American Spiritual Awakenings

**Defining Awakenings** (per **William McLoughlin**, *Revivals, Awakenings, and Reform*, 1978):
> "periods of culture revitalization that begin in a general crisis of beliefs and values and extend over a period of a generation or so, during which time a profound reorientation in beliefs and values takes place"

Building from anthropologist **Anthony Wallace's** theory of "revitalization movements," McLoughlin describes how a spiritual awakening can "alter the world view of a whole people or culture" over 6-11 decades:
> "times change; the world changes; people change; and therefore institutions, world views, and cultural systems must change"

Notes each awakening episode was "in its own time, the center of the 'individualistic, pietistic, perfectionist, millenniarian ideology'" which "has from time to time been variously defined and explained to meet the changing exigencies and contingencies in our history"

**Key Distinction from Secular Crisis:**
- Crisis = real-world threat triggers disciplined collective action and sudden institutional change
- Awakening = sudden value changes and society-wide effort to recapture feeling of spiritual authenticity
- Awakening focus: not public institutions but **the self**—rising-adult Idealists discovering what **Robert Bellah** calls "a common set of moral understandings about good and bad, right and wrong, in the realm of individual and social action"
- Since Puritan Awakening, focus shifted toward radical "isms" of modern age
- Underlying psychology remained much the same through subsequent centuries

**Crisis vs. Awakening Effects:**
- **Crisis**: empowers rising-adult generation, endows with spiritual or ideological mission that stays with members for life
- **Awakening**: leaves deep, permanent impression on remaining lifecycle of every generation then alive—shapes rising-adult generation with special force
- Vanguard of awakening: always ambivalent midlife Adaptives (Dissenters, Dreams, William Ellery Channing, John Dewey, Charles Reich)
- Best-known leaders: typically first-wave Idealists just coming of age—peer leaders like **Martin Luther, John Winthrop, Jonathan Edwards, Ralph Waldo Emerson, William Jennings Bryan, Angela Davis**

### The Five American Awakenings

1. **The Reformation Awakening (1517-1539)**: Europe-wide surge of Reform enthusiasm in precolonial period
   - Rising-adult leaders: **Martin Luther, John Calvin, John Knox**

2. **The Puritan Awakening (1621-1640)**: England, Scotland, America—era of "Puritan Enthusiasm" or "Revolutionary Puritanism"
   - Rising-adult American leaders: **John Winthrop, John Cotton, Anne Hutchinson**

3. **The Great Awakening (1734-1743)**: American colonies, known as "the Great and General Awakening," referred to ever since as "the Great Awakening"
   - Rising-adult leaders: **Jonathan Edwards, George Whitefield, William Tennent**

4. **The Transcendental Awakening (1822-1837)**: United States, loosely dated period known to historians (and Idealists) as "the Second Great Awakening," also called era of "Romantic Evangelicalism" and "Transcendental Idealism"
   - Rising-adult leaders: **Ralph Waldo Emerson, Nat Turner, Charles Finney**

5. **The Missionary Awakening (1886-1903)**: United States, called "Third Great Awakening" by McLoughlin, also known as age of "Reform," "Victorianism," and "Labor Radicalism"
   - Rising-adult leaders: **William Jennings Bryan, Jane Addams, W.E.B. DuBois**

6. **The Boom Awakening (1967-1980)**: United States, called "Fourth Great Awakening" by McLoughlin, termed "New Transcendentalism," now generally referred to as recent "Sixties," "Counterculture," or (especially) "Consciousness Revolution"
   - Rising-adult leaders: **Arlo Guthrie, Mark Rudd, Rap Brown**

### The Constellational Pattern During Awakenings

**Typical Awakening Lineup** (except Great Power Cycle):
- **Civic elders**: confidently running or overseeing institutions they once built around earlier values
- **Adaptive midlifers**: feeling pulled in competing directions by more powerful generations on either side
- **Idealist rising adults**: experiencing spiritual conversion near coming-of-age moment, cultivating implacable moral conviction
- **Reactive youths**: too young to participate, left alone, urged to grow up quickly, criticized as "bad"

This constellation rarely does well at large public undertakings. Trained order-takers are old, instinctive order-givers young. Collective effort (major war) faces strong social obstacles.

During/after Awakening: fragmenting families and communities, rising alcohol/drug abuse, growing tendency to take risks in most spheres of life. Sex-role distinctions decline, protective accorded children reaches low ebb.

**Aftermath**: Maturing Idealists retain inner convictions of awakening experience—after a period of political withdrawal—attempt to project and enforce principles on world around them. Post-crisis rising-adult Civics exude confident optimism and rationality as they move into midlife; post-awakening Idealists steer national mood toward irrational, portentous spiritualism.

---

### Conclusion: Forecasting the Future

To comprehend the generational cycle is to **foresee where the cycle will turn** as future unfolds. The cycle helps anticipate who the next "Gray Champion" will be—and when the next "hour of darkness, and adversity, and peril" will arrive.

> "Long, long may it be ere he comes again!" wrote Hawthorne.

One purpose of this book: help the reader **foresee how long**—and understand why.

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 3: From Puritans to Millennials and Beyond (continued)

### Phase-of-Life Dynamics and Generational Nurture

- **Childhood nurture shapes peer personality**: Peer groups create attitudes and expectations that manifest later in adulthood
- Young **Idealists** (rising adults) show strongest attachment to mothers; young **Civics** show strongest conflict with fathers
- **Oedipal dynamics**: Martin Luther King, Abraham Lincoln, Franklin Roosevelt, and "young radicals" studied by **Kenneth Keniston** and **Lewis Feuer** (1960s) all exhibited mother-attachment patterns
- Puritans to Boomers: rising Idealists gave spiritual awakenings an "anti-masculine flavor," commonly ascribing greater influence to mothers
- Rising **Civics** produced sharpest attacks on elder mother figures: **James I**, **Cotton Mather** to **Philip Wylie's** "momism" critique and **she-popery** attacks

### Phase-of-Life Oscillations by Generational Type

**Coming of age:**
- Idealists: most attracted to spiritual self-discovery and teamwork
- Civics: least attracted; display strongest desire for early independence and adventure
- Adaptives: weakest
- Reactives: display easiest

**Rising adulthood:**
- Idealists: narrow distinction between acceptable sex roles
- Civics: widen them
- Reactives: most risk-prone
- Adaptives: most risk-averse

**Midlife:**
- Idealists: growing pessimism about worldly affairs
- Civics: growing optimism
- Reactives: tire from earlier bingeing, slow down
- Adaptives: break free from earlier conformity, speed up

**Elderhood:**
- Idealists: preoccupied with moral judgment and secular achievement
- Reactives: live least comfortably relative to younger generations
- Adaptives: most comfortably

### Cycle Theories of American History

**Prior cycle theorists** (few explicitly connected cycles to generational rhythm):
- **Frank Klingberg**: Two-stroke pendular movement between "extroversion" (interventionism) and "introversion" (isolationism) in foreign policy since 1776
  - Each period lasts ~23 years (timing of foreign policy cycle matches timing of generational cycle)
  - Klingberg's cycle registers two oscillations; four-part cycle registers only one
  - Example: 1940-1965 ("Era Americanus") = spiritual awakening + secular crisis as *periods of activity*
  - Does not differentiate between them as generational constellations

**Arthur Schlesinger** (elder): *Paths to the Present* (1949)
- Pendular movement between "public activity" and "private interest" (or "conservative retrenchment")
- Each period lasts ~16 years; wide variations before 1901
- Successfully predicted mid-1940s surge toward conservatism, late-1950s tilt toward liberalism, re-emergence of Reagan-style conservatism mid-1970s

**Arthur Schlesinger Jr.**: "Wake Up, Liberals, Your Time Has Come" (spring 1988)
- Predicted resurgence of sixties-style liberalism
- Problem: in hindsight, flat six-year pendulum too exact
- Unlike Klingberg's 23-year pendulum, speeds the clock too fast

**Limitations of two-stroke cycles:**
- Imply generations two apart engage in very similar public behavior
- Cannot find matching midlife-youth peer personalities (Missionaries and G.I.s, or G.I.s and Boomers)
- Cannot find matching Silent and Lost, or Silent and 13ers
- Focus exclusively on "political generations" (like **Thomas Jefferson** and **Karl Mannheim**'s frameworks)
- Do not incorporate entire lifespan into theories

**Four-part generational cycle lineage:**
- Many theorists have noted cycles before—origins date to **Homer** and **Ibn Khaldun**
- **Eminent social philosophers**: **Auguste Comte**, **John Stuart Mill**, **José Ortega y Gasset**, **Karl Mannheim**
- **19th-century European writers**: **Émile Littré**, **Giuseppe Ferrari** identified cycles in modern European history
- **20th-century theorists**: Spanish sociologist **Julián Marías**, American historian **Samuel Huntington**

**Samuel Huntington's theory**:
- Especially important antecedent to authors' cycle
- **"Institutions versus Ideals" cycle**: lines up social moments exactly as authors do
- Alternates between "creedal passion" (new ideals emerge) and "creedal action" (ideals institutionalized in public life)
- Within 60-90 year cycle: sees "idealistic," "cynical," "complacent," "hypocritical" attitudes—social periods roughly describe four constellational eras and reflect coming-of-age personalities

**Authors' advantages over prior theorists:**
- Beyond general references to rejuvenation nature of social change, prior theorists said little about *why* cycles occur
- Klingberg and Schlesingers limited discussion to political generations, focused on just two generations at a time
- Authors' theory pays more attention to importance of generation's nurturing and coming-of-age experiences, behavior in midlife and old age
- Describes what the cycle *is* more than explaining connection with larger currents of social history

### The Predictive Record of the Generational Cycle

**Ancient Chinese legend**: Astronomers **Hi** and **Ho** predicted eclipse for emperor; 1989 California earthquake caught **Joan Quigley**, **Nancy Reagan's astrologer**, by surprise—oversight led to sarcastic columnist attacks

**Cycle theory limitations:**
- Cannot predict which party wins elections or whether stock crash/war will occur in specific year
- Cycles aiming at such accuracy never work over time
- Historical observer obsessed with accuracy typically refuses to examine underlying (imprecise) dynamics of social causation

**Tidal analogy:**
- Person tracking high/low tides gets nowhere predicting exactly when each wave breaks
- Person thinking about high and low tides might develop theory of considerable predictive power
- Authors liken their theory more to tide analogy

**Timing precision:**
- Phrase conclusions in terms of constellational eras and generational phases of life, not specific years
- Cycle reveals four-century record of strikingly consistent timing (Figure 6-3)
- Every social moment has begun shortly after birthyear of recessive-type generation (Reactive or Adaptive)
- Every social moment has coincided near first birthyear of dominant-type generation (Idealist or Civic)

**Social moment timing patterns:**
- Nine social moments started 0-14 years after first recessive birth cohort (Reactive/Adaptive), average 6 years
- Social moments ended 9 years before to 5 years after first birthyear of dominant (Idealist/Civic) cohort, average margin 4.1 years after, average margin of error 4.1 years
- Remarkable timing: each social moment (and first birthyear of each generational type) occurs only once every 89 years

**Birth cohort timing and dominant generations:**
- Timing of social moments linked with arrival of first recessive birth cohort
- Linked with aging of dominant generations that propel and preside
- Plotting midpoint of Idealist and Civic generation birthyears against arrival at social moment start reveals consistent pattern

**Two-stroke dynamic underlying rhythms:**
- Both pathway into rising adulthood still "coming-of-age" at passage
- Other pathway into elderhood still exercising final leadership role before ebb of old age
- Social moments begin 18 years (end 2 years) after mid-cohort birthyear of younger dominant generation, average margin of error 2.8 years
- Begin 64 years (end 77 years) after mid-cohort birthyear of elder dominant generation, average margin of error 7.7 years
- Two types of dominant generations (Idealist and Civic) have exactly opposite phase-of-life relationships with two types of social moments

**Future projections:**
- Can foresee future historians filling in Millennial Cycle blanks in Figure 6-4 with numbers roughly comparable to above
- Projecting future range does not allow prediction of social moments with to-the-year accuracy
- Since cohort-group boundaries remain imprecise while peer personality still young, cannot estimate about future as precisely as past
- Generational cycle shows powerful recurring rhythm—and powerful two-way relationship with history

### Figure 6-4: Age of Dominant Generations at Start of Social Moments

**Timing averages (excluding Civil War Cycle):**
- Mid-Idealist births to Awakening: 18 years average
- Mid-Civic births to Awakening: 65 years average
- Mid-Civic births to Crisis: 18 years average
- Mid-Idealist births to Crisis: 66 years average

### Looking for Analogues

**Common generational analogies:**
- JFK's rise (early 1960s) heralded as "dawn of a new Augustan Age"
- 1960s college-age utopians labeled "New Transcendentals"
- Values-obsessed 40-year-olds often called "New Puritans"
- Fiftyish liberals labeling themselves "Progressives"
- Thirteeners sometimes described as "Lost" or "New Lost" generation
- Most common decade pairings coincide with constellations: 1960s with 1890s or 1830s

**Value of analogues:**
- Recognizing which ones apply and understanding why makes history enjoyable and important
- Readers often want to ask: How does *that* character or situation compare to any I have come across?

**Part II structure (capsule biographies for 18 generations):**
- One chapter per cycle
- Each chapter begins showing how six social moments of given cycle helped define generational drama
- Illustrates age location of each generation with series of "diagonals"
- Geometry brings to mind how sociologist **François Mentré** likened generations to "tiles on a roof"
- Diagrams: generational history three-dimensional—chronological date is one point, but interests evolving at different phases of life
- Single event in time (like **Wilhelm Pinder's** "depth perspective") writes historian differently at age 10, 30, 50, or 70

**Chapter content:**
- Capsule biographies of four generations themselves
- Equal weight to each phase of life plus coming-of-age experience through old age
- Biographies are suggestive sketches, not histories
- Clarify cohort boundaries, peer personality, age location, lifecycle trajectory of each generation

**Part III return:**
- After traversing 18 generations, return to patterns of cycle
- Expect reader will have developed intuitive feel for what it means to belong to "Adaptive" or "Idealist" generation
- Or to live in "Outer-Driven" or "Crisis" era

**Chapter 12**: construct analogues for constellational moods, generational types, endowment behavior

**Chapter 13**: project analogues into future
- Explain what four centuries of generational cycles suggest about how national mood will evolve in decades to come
- How each of today's living generations will mature through later phases of life
- What kinds of endowments each can expect to leave for heirs

**Stimulating thinking about analogues:**
- Sort generations by type in Figure 6-5

### Analogical questions to explore:

**Questions posed:**
- What do legacies of Glorious and Republican G.I.s tell about how they will be remembered—and what sense of community today's Millennial infants likely to feel upon coming of age?
- What do old-age experiences of Enlighteners, Compromisers, and Progressives tell Silent about sense of connection with history at end of lives?
- What do completed lifecycles of Puritans, Awakeners, Transcendentals, and Missionaries tell "trait-negating" Boomers about "healing" (and why they may send younger generations into battle)?
- What do stories of America's "bad child" Reactive generations—Cavaliers, Liberty, Gilded, and Lost—tell 13ers about what to expect from mistimed lifecycle?
- How does endowment behavior of other Awakening eras compare with narcissism associated with recent Boom Awakening?
- What can constellational moods of other Inner-Driven eras tell us about whether consensus vision of future will brighten or darken as America approaches year 2000?

**Historian Anthony Esler** commented: "the generational approach may provide one of the royal roads to total history"

**Book roadmap reference:**
- Take a look at fold-out chart preceding this chapter
- Complete road map of journey about to take—journey through American history along generational diagonal, from Puritans to Millennials and beyond

