## Part II: THE GENERATIONS

## Chapter 7: THE COLONIAL CYCLE

### Opening: The Puritan Generation

**William Shakespeare** (b. 1564) epitomizes first generation of Americans:
- Creative life (first child 1583 to death 1616) almost perfectly matches birthyears of **Puritans**
- Along with Shakespeare: **Francis Bacon**, **Walter Raleigh**, **Robert Cecil**, **Philip Sydney**, **Christopher Marlowe**—pantheon of midlife Elizabethans who raised Puritans as children
- Celebrated order, rationality, optimism, and expansion
- As young soldiers, fathers triumphed over Spanish Hapsburgs
- Elizabethans transformed England into global power in war and commerce
- Brought glory of Renaissance north to "Sceptr'ed Isle"

**Puritan inheritance:**
- World of fathers not only generational layer young Puritans inherited
- Could also look up at less stolid, more picaresque world of grandparents: **Francis Drake**, **John Hawkins**, wily **Queen Elizabeth** and master sleuth **Francis Walsingham**
- Children's great-grandparents: **Shakespearean** men may have lost something by comparison
- Many Puritans recognized great-grandparents who came of age alongside **Martin Luther** and **John Calvin**, burned at stake as Protestant heretics

**Nurture and worldview:**
- Young Puritans heard stories by word of mouth or read in **John Foxe's** *Book of Martyrs* (best-seller for children, early 17th century)
- Fathers suffered by comparison: saw fathers as worldly burghers and optimistic materialists comfortably into their fifties
- King James I: might prefer elder ancestors' hundreds of world-rejecting prophets, refusing to recant as smoke wafted into eyes
- Puritans matured: might feel elder ancestors were holier than own parents
- Far more in common with ancestors than with own parents

**Nurture style impact:**
- Style producing Puritans and mood of world in which they came of age substantially determined by generational constellation into which born
- Constellation shaped by social moments preceding: Massacre of St. Bartholomew's Day, English sea victory over Hapsburg Armada
- Participating events were individuals who, collectively, reflect four peer personalities of precolonial "Reformation Cycle" of generations

### Preparing for the Puritans: The Reformation Cycle

**Reformation generation (Idealist-like rising adults):**
- Nearly all born 1483-1509
- Including: **Martin Luther**, **John Calvin**, **Ulrich Zwingli**, **Ignatius Loyola**, **John Rogers**, **Nicholas Ridley**, **Thomas Cranmer**, **John Knox**
- Next came Regicide generation of **Queens Elizabeth** and **Mary** (born 1510-1541)
- Late wave reached midlife during Armada Crisis

**Historian Anthony Esler** on generational contrast:
- Describes contrast between second and third English peer groups
- **Anthony Esler**: calls **Drake** and **Elizabeth** "burned-out generation" of risk-takers who "grew up in age of ideological ferment," later aged into "cool, cautious, and *politique* elders"
- By contrast, younger peers of **Shakespeare** and **Raleigh** "born at uniquely favorable time," undertook "ambitious projects of world-building scope and grandeur," ultimately aged into "generation of overreachers"
- Esler named them **"Generation of 1560"**—followed by fourth, Adaptive-like generation born 1566-1583
- Anxious, sentimental (and upwardly mobile) peers of **John Donne**, **Ben Jonson**, and **Sir John Davies**

### The Reformation Cycle's Two Social Moments

**The Reformation Awakening (1517-1539):**
- Often regarded as final curtain on European Middle Ages
- Began 1517 when **Martin Luther** tacked on church door at Wittenberg famous protest against Papal doctrine
- Two decades of religious and social upheaval: peasant uprisings, fanatical Anabaptist heresies, sack of Rome, Protestant conversion of many German and Scandinavian princes
- Uproar culminated with anarchist Münster in 1534-1536 and **John Calvin's** arrival in Geneva, next year (after feeling "sudden conversion" at age 24)
- In England: enthusiasm peaked about same time
- **King Henry VIII** broke with Papacy in 1534, "Reformation Parliament" confiscated vast Catholic estates through late 1530s
- Terror ebbed after 1539, though dynastic wars and unrest continued throughout Europe
- Many rising-adult leaders of English Reformation: after maturing into midlife as dour and uncompromising prophets, later executed by **Henry VIII** in 1540s
- **Cavalier** in 1540s, **Queen Mary** in 1550s

**The Armada Crisis (1580-1588):**
- Marked climax of long rivalry between Spanish Hapsburg emperor **Philip II** and Protestant queen of **England Elizabeth**
- Crisis began 1580, with England in alliance with Netherlands
- Philip's acquisition of Portugal, Drake's return from daring 3-year voyage around world
- 1588: loaded with Spanish treasure
- Led by fiftyish **Drake** and **Hawkins**, English fleet destroyed Philip's invasion "Armada" and established England as growing naval and colonial power
- Following: explosion of security and optimism
- Those who celebrated heroic victory as coming-of-age soldiers—younger courtiers, poets, merchants, scientists, explorers serving elder queen
- Ushered in Elizabethan Renaissance (today remembered as "Age of Shakespeare")
- By midlife: set prosperous stage for "chosen" generation of disaffected children—some of whom would seek spiritual exile in New World

**Timing:**
- Puritan Awakening in England began 87 years after Reformation's peak year of 1534
- 41 years after **Queen Elizabeth** decided to test Spain's naval power in 1580

### The Colonial Cycle

**Setting: Gallows Hill, Salem, Massachusetts, September 22, 1692**
- Eight middle-aged New Englanders, seven women and one man, standing on scaffold with nooses around necks
- Crime: witchcraft
- Near foot of scaffold: crowd of all ages
- Ranged from 89-year-old **Simon Bradstreet** (recent governor) to 6-year-old **William Stoughton** (presiding judge at witch trials) to 29-year-old **Cotton Mather** (brilliant and energetic clergyman) to "possessed" children in early teens
- Jerking and shrieking reminded everyone why witches had to die
- No one in crowd surprised by horrible spectacle

**Historical context:**
- Over prior decade: New Englanders lived through revolution, anarchy, war, pestilence
- Signs their chosen community broken sacred "Covenant with God"
- Ministers sermonized: darker times would come next
- Now four generations of COLONIAL CYCLE could witness fulfillment of prophecy

### The Four Generations of the Colonial Cycle

**Bradstreet's patriarchal PURITAN GENERATION (Idealist, age 78 and over):**
- Scene on Gallows Hill represented God's culminating judgment on His "Chosen Remnant"—and on Puritans' own life mission
- Half century earlier, workers like **John Winthrop** and **John Cotton**: Bradstreet and peers forsaken Elizabethan fathers, left England, founded holy community of love and reform in New World
- More recently: tribal hatte penned petition for wayward offspring
- Purging witches: handful of Puritans still alive hoped God would finally turn aid these colonizations, raise up younger generation to greatness and glory
- Hangings that day turned out to be last judicial executions for witchcraft in America
- By end of century: had returned to colonies
- Ancient tail of Puritan Generation passed on in peace
- **Simon Bradstreet** died 1697—aged 94, American Nestor, 6-7 years after outliving friend **Winthrop** by 48 years, his poetess wife **Anne** by 25 years
- With him expired a legend

**Stoughton's CAVALIER GENERATION (Reactive, age 45 to 77):**
- Having no such memories or hopes, watched with resignation
- Witches about to die were their own age
- Leading magistrates who condemned them
- In hearts: **Cavaliers** knew they all shared guilt
- Since childhood: always been told they were "lost generation," that spirit "corrupt" and "unconverted"
- Only escape was stick


<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## PURITAN GENERATION (Born 1584-1614)

**Type:** Idealist

### Age Location
- **Puritan Awakening** in rising adulthood
- **Glorious Revolution Crisis** in elderhood

### Founding Vision

**John Winthrop's** sermon aboard *Arabella* (1630): "We shall be as a city upon a Hill" — a call to build a religious utopia in Massachusetts

- Young Puritans included **John Endicott** (age 14), **Anne Hutchinson** (age 12), **Richard Mather** (age 7), **Oliver Cromwell** (age 9), **Roger Williams** and **Simon Bradstreet** (both infancy)
- This peer group would become a **transatlantic vanguard** reshaping both Old World and New World
- Founded **religious utopia** in New World and compressed first European colonies on Atlantic seaboard

### Character and Ambition

- Belonged to English-born generation of **boundless spiritual ambition**
- Children: overaged and lifeless culture under Elizabethan fathers
- Coming of age: "ravished by beauty of the Earth" in age of exploration
- Experienced novel lifestyles combining education, piety, commerce, founding, and agitation
- Moved into midlife gravitating toward **decisive action** — laboring to reshape the world as God had reshaped their souls
- Never left England in majority, but those who did joined activists like **Cromwell** launching Puritan Revolution against King Charles I, or preachers like **Fifth Monarchists** advocating dictatorship of God on earth, or poets like **John Milton** recreating universe where each soul struggles personally toward grace

### Migration to New England

Only a few "Puritans" chose to leave home and found **New Jerusalem**:

- **12,000** of Winthrop's peers emigrated to Massachusetts during 1630s
- After first year, outnumbered all adult colonists who had settled in New England (including *Mayflower* pilgrims ten years earlier)
- By end of decade, outnumbered combined adult population of all other English colonies in America, including 35-year-old Virginia colony

### Midlife Transformation

When English-born generation reached midlife, Puritans knew they had changed history — but in Old World, changes were mixed:

- Stay-at-home Puritans never budged England from corrupting influence of world affairs
- New England Puritans stopped at nothing short of perfection
- Disappointed by Restoration of Stuart throne (1660)
- Rather than be corrupted by world, **revised every corner of their society** into ideal temple
- By midlife, closed ranks around theocracy by **punishing** younger Cavaliers (regarded as shallow, wasted)
- Prayed younger generation of Glorious might save holy experiment after all

### Puritan Birthyear Waves

Birthyears reflected events shaping lifecycle:

- **First wave** (John Cotton, Myles Standish): came of age as Queen Elizabeth dying and handful of elders resisting ecclesiastical reform
- **Last wave** (Anne Bradstreet, Henry Dunster): came of age during late-1630s tyranny of Charles I, when twentyish men and women could hone fighting idealism in years of suppressed expectation

### Success Formula

Last-wave Puritans were youngest adults to join Great Migration to New England:

- Experienced near-total idealism of the Golden Age (1630s)
- Success grew with advancing age — peer personality: **immature and narcissistic** through long adolescence, but **implacably strong-willed and morally committed** when older
- 12,000 Puritan settlers in 1630s were mostly married adults in their late twenties — at least three out of four survived
- At least as many went to colonies south of New England, but most were **single males in late teens**, survival rate abysmal as youth encountered Indians, starvation, malaria

> "The few southern Puritans who survived to become leaders of lasting importance, such as Governor **William Berkeley** in Virginia and Governor **Leonard Calvert** in Maryland, followed their generation's formula for success."

### Puritan Facts

- **Educational elite:** Puritan emigrants to New England included roughly one university alumnus (Cambridge or Oxford) for every forty families — educational level towering above England's at the time and not reached by any later American generation until late 19th century
- **Radicalism:** English-born Puritan elite earned reputation for radicalism when students/teachers — **Thomas Hobbes** noted they were more likely than next-juniors to advocate revolution
- In 1642, **Roundheads** outnumbered Royalists two-to-one among all Members of Parliament in their fifties (Puritan cohorts), while opposite ratio prevailed among M.P.s in twenties (Cavalier cohorts)
- By 1650s, some Puritans from London having returned from America dominated most violent religious sects; several were executed when throne restored to Charles II in 1660

### Reformed Communities and Female Leadership

Wherever radicals of this English-born generation set up "reformed" communities — Amsterdam, Geneva, America, or London — **women assumed roles of conspicuous activism and leadership**:

- In 1630s, several New England women became popular lay preachers
- **Anne Hutchinson** gathered such powerful Boston constituency she nearly toppled Winthrop's leadership
- **Anne Bradstreet** today remains most celebrated American authoress born before Transcendentalists

### Political Longevity

- Puritans held governorship of **Massachusetts for 53 years** — longest single-generation control of major political entity in American history
- Last Puritan governors stepped down from office in Virginia (1677), Connecticut (1683), and Rhode Island (1686) at average age of 77

### Life Expectancy

Town records indicate New England Puritans lived on average into **late sixties** — making this (excluding southern settlers) longest-lived American generation born before 20th century:

- Of 35 New England Puritan ministers whose birthplaces were known, all but two preached until death at median age of 68; only three retired at median age of 73
- Longevity attributed to: good nutrition; scattered settlements retarding disease spread; little crime or substance abuse; regular pattern of work and leisure thanks to strictly enforced Sabbath

---

## The Puritan Lifecycle

### YOUTH: Brightening Aftermath of Triumph

First-wavers hardly been born by **Armada year of 1588**, still in teens when James I succeeded Queen Elizabeth

- England was confident, optimistic world — booming with colonies, teeming with art and construction, well protected by fathers' mighty fleet
- Parents told every person and planet "knew" its rank
- Puritan children — indulged, secure, showered with new schools — should have settled happily into friendly future

**But they didn't.** Instead, they:

- Grew into adolescence and became **introspective and morally demanding**
- Saw moral chaos and spiritual drift, lapsing from **Sodom and Gomorrah**
- Became obsessed with **sinfulness of man** apart from God
- Questioned man's potential for godliness on earth
- In "Doomsday," young **Herbert** prayed: "Come away, / Help our Decay. / Man is out of order hurled, / Parcell'd out to all the world"

> "Elders ridiculed these touchy young souls by popularizing the very word 'Puritan' to describe them — while also puzzling over 'whose child he is... for willingly his faith allows no father.'"

According to historian **David Leverenz**, the Puritan Generation expressed extreme **"ambivalence about the father's role"** — "mixture of relatively good mothering and relatively anxious, distant, weak, or repressive fathers"

### COMING OF AGE: The Conversion Experience

Near end of adolescence arrived the **threshold event of the Puritan lifecycle: the conversion experience** — moment when God "ravished" them:

- Tentative prayers became rushes of enthusiasm
- Moral qualms became fervent principles
- After conversion, Puritans struggled to master inner ecstasy by inventing regimes of: personal piety, what historians call "precisionism" — prayer, work, reading, spiritual diaries, sporadic bursts of abstinence and political activism

> **Winthrop** wrote to God in his diary: "make us sick with thy love: let us sleep in thine arms, and awake in thy kingdom."

To chagrin of their fathers, young men insisted on **"faith" over "works"** and celebrated dependent, feminine relationship to God as **"brides of Christ"**

By 1620s, conversion drew strident opposition to elder authority, apocalyptic strain began appearing in their writings:

- Reviling "prodigious lusts" and "impudent sinning"
- **Herbert** wrote: "Religion stands on tip-toe in our land, / Ready to pass to the American strand"
- Pointing to "these so evil and declining times," Winthrop called upon peers to **leave "home and comforts" in America as government of Christ in exile**

Thus began **Great Migration to New England**

### RISING ADULTHOOD: Founding a God-Focused Civilization

During single decade (1630s), young Puritan voyagers to New England founded nearly everything for which future Americans would remember them:

- Port of Boston, church-centered towns stretching from Connecticut to Maine
- **Harvard University**, printing press, schools for Indians, representative assembly
- Their own navy

Rising adults hardly heard wolves still howling near their cabins as they labored — **with minds as much as bodies** — to create entirely **God-focused civilization**:

> "To account for their creative energy, Winthrop, Cotton, and Shepard spoke incessantly of 'love.' Church members laid 'loving hands' on ministers. New towns held 'loving conversations' agreed on unanimously. Covenants had 'ever-lasting love,' and kept a 'loving eye' on neighbors."

There was nothing liberal about their utopian communities:

- To Puritans, all society had to be **church** and all behavior had to reflect **perfect fellow feeling**
- Cotton proudly declared "we are professed enemies"

> "When two group leaders disagreed over God's truth, compromise was unthinkable. Ego clashes typically ended in banishment — the fate of **Anne Hutchinson** (who conversed personally with God), **Roger Williams** (who deemed no one holy enough to take communion with him), and **Samuel Gorton** (whose "Family of Love" worshiped him as Jesus Christ)."

Group intolerance, not frontier spirit, propelled wide geographic scattering of Puritan towns during 1630s — **a single settlement just couldn't accommodate so many infallible prophets**, each playing "spiritual chemist" in search of perfect life

### MIDLIFE: Turning Point from Reform to Law

Outbreak of **English Civil War in 1641** put sudden stop to new voyages and thrust American colonies into temporary isolation

- Marked midlife turning point in Puritan lifecycle — from ferment of youthful enthusiasm to outward righteousness
- During 1640s and 1650s, Puritans abandoned fanciful dreams of world reform and labored to achieve more realistic ideal: **enforceable moral order at home**

As geographic mobility ebbed and customs congealed around seasonal rhythms of agriculture, Puritans steered their institutions toward **formalism**:

- They **"closeted covenants"** with written compacts
- Enacted **draconian punishments** for religious apostasy
- Insisted all new church members offer public proof of their conversions

Puritan parents and leaders raged over apathy of younger Cavaliers who seemed perversely reluctant to join their churches:

> "This was an alarming situation for a community which, as it was founded for religious purposes, 'ob-serves historian **Edmund Morgan,** 'It was one thing to create a church of saints; it was another to let those saints carry the church out of the world with them entirely when they died.'"

But that later radical poet-sage brought back in (age 34), **John Endicott** (who hanged younger Cavalier Quakers who mocked Puritan creed) completed this generation's midlife transition from law of love to **love of law**

### ELDERHOOD: Crisis and Unyielding Example

Entered old age knowing their world was heading for crisis:

- Half New England Puritans lived to learn of restoration of throne to Charles II in 1660
- Colonies moved back into Cavalier orbit of heel of Stuart "tyranny"
- Quarter lived to witness their grandchildren go off to fight (many to die) in gruesome war against King Philip's Indians in 1675
- Handful, like **Bradstreet**, still presided in high public office as late as 1689, when colonies joined England in **Glorious Revolution** against James II

Most of these ancients, looking down on troubled souls of their grown children, feared young would **trade ideals for security** and thereby **destroy everything that mattered**

Their last act was to **set an unyielding example**:

- Diehards included patriarchs like **Massachusetts Governor Richard Bellingham** (at age 75) scornfully burned letters from English crown
- **John Davenport** (at age 70) left his Mosaic "Bible State" in New Haven for ultimate in Boston against youth who "polluted" the church
- **Indian apostle John Eliot** (at age 72) protested seeing his life's work torn apart by younger soldiers more interested in killing Indians than saving souls
- **Virginia Governor Berkeley** (at age 71) hanged twenty-three younger leaders of Bacon's Rebellion

> Confident that principle would triumph, most Puritans **faced death with what historian Perry Miller has described as "ponderous optimism."** Said a witness at **John Eliot's** deathbed: "His last breath smelt strong of Heaven."

Often Puritans expected Christ's Second Coming, death finally came, they met it with **composure** — like travelers returning home after pilgrimage

### Spiritual Self-Absorption: Strength and Weakness

**Spiritual self-absorption** was both strength and weakness of this generation:

- Gave Puritans confidence to plant first successful colonies in American wilderness
- Yet it did so by midlife, **making them intolerant**, locking them into rigid theocracy
- Building only perfect society since Adam's Fall — **New Jerusalem was a project the next generation would not understand** and would sourly resent

As Puritans grew older, they found they could not experience fulfillment:

- Their punishment was to see, among devils attacking Eden, faces of their firstborn — their own Cavalier children
- Their expiation was to pass away showing Glorious what it meant to believe an idea

> "Insensible to the Puritans' inner fire, the Glorious later revered them as black-clothed statues of unfeeling rectitude. We can only guess how this image would have struck the Puritans themselves — a generation that had once forsaken all earthly dross to create the perfect society, a community of love."

**Thomas Shepard** as young minister described faith motivating his coming-of-age peers:

> "As 'tis with woman when the fulness of the husband's love is seen, it knits the heart invincibly to him, and makes her do anything for him; so here."

Later generations would rediscover this feeling — but Puritans' own offspring **could not possibly understand**. They had not been there — at that moment of history and at that phase of life.

---

## CAVALIER GENERATION (Born 1615-1647)

**Type:** Reactive

### Age Location
- **Puritan Awakening** in youth
- **Glorious Revolution Crisis** in midlife

### Character: "A wicked and perverse generation"

Young Quaker **Josiah Coale** called his peers as he toured American colonies at midcentury:

> "We might well have called them the **CAVALIER GENERATION**, a peer group of pluck, materialism, and self-doubt."

Cavaliers followed Puritans the way many **belief scatters after crashing of storm wave**:

- **Skepticism** following belief
- **Egotism** following community
- **Devils** following saints

At their worst, Cavaliers were **unlettered generation of little faith, crude ambition** — so foul and so many believed and behaved:

- Their roster includes more than usual number of rogues: **adventurers, witches, pirates, and Indian-haters, and traitors**

Yet at their best, Cavaliers were a generation whose **perverse defiance of moral authority** gave America its **first instinct for individual autonomy**, for "rights" of property and liberty — concepts utterly foreign to their Puritan elders

Leaders of offenders and independence: **William Penn** (apostle of religious toleration), as were **unattractive and offenders of Quakers**: **Increase Mather, Elisha Cooke, and Jacob Leisler**

### Varied Life Experience by Geography

Typical life experience of 100,000-member Cavalier generation varied dramatically according to geography:

- Of 40,000 in New England, nearly all were either **born in America** or **brought over as children by their parents**
- Grew up in large families among churchless and long-lived Puritan elders
- Of 60,000 or so farther south, especially in Chesapeake colonies of Virginia and Maryland, most were **immigrants** — perhaps two-thirds coming over as young, footloose, and indentured servants

Chesapeake Cavaliers rarely saw complete family:

- Most arrived unattached and perished before marrying
- Throughout seventeenth century, theirs was **frontier society of extreme youth and routine violence** — "a people," scowled old Puritan Governor Berkeley, "where six parts of seven at least are poor, indebted, discontented, and armed"

> "Yet whatever the colony, Cavaliers every-where met life on similar terms: discarded in a childhood without structure, shamed while coming of age, and pushed into adulthood with few hopes other than climbing fast and avoiding judgment."

Later on, during years of war and rebellion, midlife Cavaliers managed to salvage their reputation for posterity — **not by suddenly turning virtuous, but by fighting gamely according to their own rules**

### Cavalier Character in Old World

First took shape in Old World around mid-seventeenth century:

- New generation came of age — **profoundly disillusioned** by chaos left behind by their saintly next-elders
- Continent's three decades of holy war had succumbed to **realpolitik of hungry new superpowers**: France, Sweden, and Holland
- In England, religious revolution had given way to **brutality of Cromwell**, decadence of Restoration, duplicity of Cavalier-age kings Charles II and James II

For this new generation, it was **time to repudiate failed dreams**, to learn that **interest is secret of happiness** and that **power is source of glory**

Tired of bookish principle, Cavaliers avoided Puritan idealism, prompting English historian **Lawrence Stone** to note that:

> "the old were more radical than the young in the 1640s. They grasped instead for what was tangible and grandiose — the fabled jewels of Aurangzeb, the Versailles splendor of Louis XIV, the sensuous curves of baroque art."

**Initial Cavalier birthyear, 1615**, marks first English-born cohort whose childhood environment began to disintegrate from stable Elizabethan order known by Puritans at like age:

- A fifty-year time draws rough dividing line between **Great Migration to New England** (ending in 1640 for adults in their late 20s) and first great English wave draws to Virginia (beginning about 1635 for servants in their late teens)

### Etymology of "Cavalier"

English word "Cavalier" comes from mixture of Romance words for "horse," "hair," and "knight" (in French: *chevalier*, and *cheveler*):

- Fitting images of showy, arrogant, and predatory values this generation took to heart
- Many historians, most recently **David Hackett Fischer**, have called this the **"Cavalier wave" of American immigration**

To be sure, only few adorned themselves like **Prince Rupert** and fully *dressed* the part:

- But what matters is how many *played* the part — and only in royalist Virginia
- **Fitz-John Winthrop** concludes their biographer, "grew up a couple of Cavaliers in Israel": **"half-indolorous, uncertain of their values, and always chiefly absorbed with fashion, status, and accumulation of real estate"**

> **Bernard Bailyn** about New England, "the character of the rising generation was discernible, and to the entrenched oligarchy it seemed pitifully weak. The children of the Founders... knew nothing of the fire that had steeled the hearts of their fathers. They aspired to their elders, frivolous, given to excess in dress and manners, lacking the necessary fierceness of belief."

What they did not lack, these children would someday show their elders, was **necessary fierceness of action**

---

## Cavalier Facts

- Young male servant coming to Maryland in 1640s stood only **two-thirds chance of surviving the voyage**. If made it ashore, faced: **57% chance of living out his indenture term**, **29% chance of ever owning enough land to support himself**, **6% chance of dying with an estate worth more than 1,000 pounds**, and **less than 1% chance of ending up as a respected "planter-merchant"**

- While Puritan voyagers to Massachusetts came mainly from **east of England (Roundheads and short vowels)**, Cavalier voyagers to Chesapeake came mainly from **southwest of England (Royalists and wide vowels)** — these regional differences in England accentuated contrast between two peer personalities and gave rise to **regional differences in America that have persisted to this day**

- Throughout colonies, Cavaliers probably represent **largest one-generation decline in educational achievement** from their next-elders in American history. In Massachusetts, **no Harvard-trained Puritan minister was ever regarded as the intellectual equal of the leading Puritans**. In Chesapeake, **60% of young immigrants could not sign a name to their indenture contracts**

- From 1640s through 1660s, **majority of first graduates of Harvard College left for England** seeking escape or adventure — usually returning again to their native New England by midlife

- Striking number of best-known Cavaliers **died a violent death**: **Mary Dyer** (hanged in Boston, 1660); twenty-three captured leaders of **Bacon's Rebellion** (hanged in Virginia, 1677); **Metacomet** the Indian leader "King Philip" (shot in back in rural New England, 1676); **Jacob Leisler** and **Jacob Milbourne** (drawn and quartered in New York City, 1691); most of thirty-one convicted **Salem witches** (hanged in Salem, 1692); **Thomas Tew** (blown in half by Muslim merchants, 1695); and **William Kidd** (hanged in London, 1701)

- Among thousands of young, poor, and solitary Cavaliers who emigrated from England to Chesapeake, four — **John Washington, Thomas Jefferson, James Maddison, and Andrew Munro** — were great-grandfathers to four of first five U.S. Presidents

---

## The Cavalier Lifecycle

### YOUTH: Messiani Visions and Harsh Realities

During 1630s through 1650s, as adults grappled with messianic visions, children understood that **no one cared much about their welfare**:

- In England, revolution and war sent tens of thousands of these afterthought kids — **orphaned and abandoned** — scurrying toward cities like London and Bristol
- Infested bailiffs scrambled for a living until swept into **"kidnapping"** (word first coined at midcentury) consigned them to disease-ridden ships bound for Virginia and Maryland

Unschooled and worldly-wise youthful Cavalier servants fought bad odds and self-hatred to survive grueling **seven-year slavelike indentures in tobacco fields**:

> Teenage **James Revel** in Winthrop's "New Jerusalem": "To wickedness I quickly was inclined... my mind was soon tainted any youthful mind."

Childhood among isolated and fanatical towns of Winthrop's "New Jerusalem" was safer, but hardly more conducive to self-esteem:

- Puritan parents frequently castigated youngsters for their palpable unsaintliness
- Elder assemblies in Boston soon declared **child misbehavior a capital crime**

Perhaps more than 60% of **stressed Puritans' New England kids** did what youngsters often do when they don't fit in society: **to discover New England for themselves among the forests and Indians**

> "I have no confidence in my doings, O wretched I am," wrote young **Michael Wigglesworth** in his Massachusetts diary. "What will become of this generation?"

Remarked **Eleazar Mather** several years later: **"Are they not in danger to sink and perish in the waters?"**

### COMING OF AGE: Corrupt and Degenerate

**"Early in the 1640s,"** notes historian **Perry Miller**:

> "ministers began to complain that sons and daughters were not exhibiting zeal."

By midcentury, midlife New Englanders spoke routinely of **"corrupt and degenerate rising generation"** — as Puritan **Richard Mather** wrote, **"the sad face of the rising generation"**

Unimpressed by these "heathenish" and "hard-hearted" 20-year-olds, Puritans accused them of:

> "cruelty" and "covetousness," of living by "external considerations only, by a kind of outward force without any spiritual life or vigor or delight in them."

In England, mayor of Bristol echoed similar disgust at **"lewd, idle, and debauched"** flowing through his port to Chesapeake:

- When they arrived in Virginia, Puritan Governor Berkeley picked up where others left off: **"The wild beast multitude,"** Berkeley called them — **"rude, dissolute, and tumultuous"** youths who valued **"pelts"** over their lives

> Young **William Stoughton** lamented: "It is a sad name to be styled 'Children that are Corrupters.'"

Yet beyond blaming themselves, Cavaliers grew to resent the lies they were inheriting:

- Their Puritan elders had promised them a **"New Jerusalem"** (in Massachusetts) and a royalist **"land of plenty"** (in Virginia)
- But all they saw around them were **miserable exiles** and **a howling wilderness**

> **Oscar Handlin** concludes: "In the eyes of the immigrants, the second generation seemed a ruder, less cultivated, and wilder people." But in eyes of Cavaliers, "it was intensely sad and wilder was the New World to which their elders had taken them."

### RISING ADULTHOOD: Striking Out Alone

Alienated by elder criticism, **thirtyish Cavaliers struck out alone**, trying (explained officer **Fitz-John Winthrop**, then young expatriate in London) to stay away from:

> "a city or place where I am known, and where every judgment will pass their verdict on me."

They also hustled desperately to win wealth and respect:

- In **Chesapeake** world of isolated planters and contracted labor, rising planters like **John Carter** competed fiercely for what they called **"the main chance,"** that one swift stroke of **enormous profit** that would catapult them to top
- In **New England**, apprentices like **John Hull** became silversmiths and world traders, fur trappers like **Benjamin Church** wandered to frontier, and aspiring elite sought degrees back in England

Of all ways to top, **land became a Cavalier obsession**:

> "Land! Land! hath been the Idol of many in New England," thundered Increase Mather in old age

Odds were slim that ex-servant could acquire enough land to merit titled name ("mister" or "esquire"), but Cavaliers took their chances willingly:

- Besides, by bending few rules — **smuggling, bribing, taking "headright" documents** — they could always get an edge
- Truly bold joined **Thomas Tew** and **William Kidd** in ultimate gamble and purest form of lifesty "**buccaneering**," a rising plague along Atlantic coast from 1650s forward

Why not go for it? Everyone kept telling the Cavalier he was **loser anyway**:

> "A dead loser, he would no longer have to listen. A rich loser, no one would dare tell him of his presence."

### MIDLIFE: Crisis of 1675 and Suicidal Rebellions

**Crisis year of 1675** marked Cavaliers' passage into midlife and inaugurated **darkest two decades in American history** until nearly another century afterward:

- In **New England**, the bloody **Indian rebellion** known as **King Philip's War** killed more inhabitants per capita than any subsequent war in American history
- In **Virginia**, **Bacon's Rebellion** (a brief war) began as war against Indians, but soon expanded into vicious civil war between Puritan governor (**Sir William Berkeley**) and Cavalier rebel (**Nathaniel Bacon**)

More adversity soon followed: **epidemics, harsh winters, the colonial Glorious Revolution, and global war against France**

All eyes turned to Cavaliers for leadership — **could this wild and pragmatic generation handle such adversity?**

- Doubtful Puritan elders, still retaining symbolic authority into extreme old age, shook their heads
- But **Cavalier leadership prevailed**

Cavaliers handled such adversity in way their elders never possessed:

- **Realistic diplomacy** (Increase Mather)
- **Cunning generalship** (Benjamin Church)
- **Reckless courage** (Jacob Leisler)

**Outshining Puritans** in elemental altruism, midlife Cavaliers staged **suicidal rebellions** and bore crushing war-era taxation on behalf of their families **without complaint or condescension**

They treated younger Glorious, moreover, with **gentleness they had been denied at like age**

Exhausted and politically tamed once crisis had passed, they hardly protested numerous **witchcraft hysteria** (such as deadly witch trials of 1692) that **targeted their own peers**

### ELDERHOOD: Worst Was Over

At turn of century, Cavaliers sank into old age marveling that perhaps **worst was over**:

- They had survived Indians, Restoration, Dutch, rebellions, and (for time being) French
- Colonies were again growing rapidly, thanks mainly to younger and more industrious Glorious

Reminiscing over their travails, aging Cavaliers often attributed their success to **dumb luck**, only sort of grace that most of them had ever prayed for:

- Even as elders, they never tried to hide their generation's failings, especially their **vulgarity and irreligion**

> **Increase Mather** in verse: "This scale me, the Age of Iron"
> **Henricus Selyns** (New Yorker) described them in 1690s: "living here as many wild beasts and vultures do, to be plucked"

> "Not of Cavaliers step blaming themselves for not measuring up to their elders. If the body of the present generation be compared with what was here forty years ago," boomed Increase Mather, "what a sad degeneracy is evident in the view of every man."

**Benjamin Tompson** looked back in verse:

> "These golden times (too fortunate to hold) / Were quickly sin'd away for love of gold!"

But Cavalier 'gold' only landed on a handful: the few former apprentices who now owned Boston mansions or shares in a New York trade ship, or the few former servants who now owned Tidewater estates with private stocks and docks

Yet even so, **most Cavaliers died before age 45**; rest entered old age **without wealth or pretense** — crusty, used up, and unaware of what they had given:

- In late seventies, Boston merchant **Joshua Scottow** wrote book entitled *Old Men's Tears for Their Own Declensions*
- Eightyish **Jonathan Burt** agreed that **"the Lord is bearing with the Rod to visit us"** when Old

### Legacy: Self-Deprecating Realism

**Self-deprecating realism** gave Cavaliers special strengths:

- Ability to **outwit evil**, to **survive in ugly, no-second-chance world** and later joke about their escapades in America's first adventure tales and travelogues
- Unlike Puritans (who could just as well have emigrated to moon), Cavaliers felt **visceral affinity for the American wilderness** — lonely and uncouth, like their own generation

> **"Dear New England, Dearest land to me!"** wrote **Michael Wigglesworth**, painfully aware how many mountains and forests distanced him from civilization

Yet if Cavaliers excelled in **outgaming Satan** — perhaps because they were "devils" themselves, as older Berkeley and younger Cotton Mather told Salem witches — they **remained helpless against judgment of God and community**

**Early in seventeenth century**, Cavaliers grew up in world that faulted children and hardly bothered to punish kidnappers (official fine was **one shilling**) who "spirited" London waifs to New World as quasi-slaves

Near end of century, they grew old in world that **faulted the elderly**, that sermonized on old age with what historian **John Demos** calls:

> "a note of distaste... almost of repulsion"

Very sacrifices they made as mature adults to protect their families helped, sadly, to **keep themselves a target of blame** throughout their lifecycle

---

## GLORIOUS GENERATION (Born 1648-1673)

**Type:** Civic

### Age Location
- **Glorious Revolution Crisis** in rising adulthood
- **Great Awakening** in elderhood

### Collective Purpose and Activity

**Benjamin Colman** preached in his thirties:

> "Be up and doing. Activity. Activity. This will be most likely followed and rewarded, with triumphant satisfaction."

Colman's message energized his young audience — and sums up the story of the **GLORIOUS GENERATION**, the band of American heroes who came of age during last quarter of seventeenth century

**Their dutiful valor:**
- Won the Indian wars
- Repelled the French
- Overthrew Stuart tyranny and quelled social disorder
- Planned harbors, charted the planets, and organized African slaves

In **1689**, the colonial Glorious Revolution told the world, at age 16 to 41, through a rite of passage — **stamping them for life as public persons, institution-founders, collective builders, and secular dreamers**

Ever afterward, their diaries buzzed with nonstop activity: families, elections, trade, profits, roads, cultivation — all accomplished with only the rarest idle feeling

To **Cotton Mather** in Boston, who wrote over 450 volumes over lifetime; or to **Robert Beverley** in Virginia, "laziness" the only sin. Not just any activity would do. It had to be **"social," "useful," "serve the public"** or **"enrich the common-wealth"**

### Youth: Programmed for Achievement

**Growing up in an increasingly protective adult world**, coming of age at a moment of triumph, and entering adulthood programmed for achievement, the Glorious **mapped out a lifecycle of enormous collective confidence**

Those born before 1648 arrived too soon to experience what Cavalier **Thomas Shepard, Jr.**, called the **"more thorough, conscientious, religious, effectual care for the rising generation"**

Those born after 1673 came of age too late to participate in victory

As the Puritans' favored heirs, the Glorious revered their "upright" colonial vision of elder patriarchs and **never imagined improving it**. Instead, from childhood on, they understood that their group mission was to **champion that vision** against growing worldly threats — to make it stable and orderly, to give it permanence and power and grandeur

After helping to topple the Cavalier-age Stuart **James II** from the throne of England, the Glorious cherished their "rightful" colonial liberties from later crown-appointed governors

Yet they also came to admire their like-minded peers in England and tried to bathe in the reflected glory
<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Glorious Generation (Born 1648-1673) - Elderhood and Legacy

### Elderhood Characteristics
- Old age brought mixed blessings; aging Glorious could look back with pride at transforming colonies from savage outpost of 100,000 into wealthy "jewel" with 600,000+ population
- Earned and saved far more than Puritans or Cavaliers; rising land prices gave commanding bargaining power over land-poor children
- Yet complained of physical decline and regretted secularized religion offered little solace
- Staged gaudy last rites that led Massachusetts to enact laws "to restrain the extraordinary expense at funerals" (1720s)
- Wondered why young didn't show same warmth they remembered for their own fathers
- Withdrew from hostile, value-laden culture of young Awakeners
- **Cotton Mather** (mid-60s): criticized spiritual rebinding popularity by insisting "going to heaven in the way of repentance is much safer and surer than going in the way of ecstasy"
- Warned aging peers: "Our patience must be tried by the contempt... among those who see we are going out"

### Legacy Assessment
- Overcame every major challenge faced coming of age: took America politically from chaos to affluence; materially from penury to science
- From youth through old age, knew they were gifted achievers
- **Dark side**: lay not in deeds left undone, but in too many deeds done too well—sheer energy eclipsed reflection
- **Cotton Mather**: tireless, never stopped marking "GDs" (Good Deeds) in diary margins
- Generational instinct for social discipline limited room for spiritual/philosophical metaphors
- **Benjamin Colman**: "All nature is industrious and every creature about us diligent in their proper work. Diligence is the universal example. Look through the whole creation, and every part it has a work and service assigned to it"
- By old age, hoped two new colleges (Yale, William and Mary) might inspire children to something higher than "diligence"
- **"King" Carter**: "Pray God, send the next generation that it may flourish under a set of better polished patriots"
- The colonies did get "polish"—and much else besides

---

## Enlightenment Generation (Born 1674-1700)

### Type and Demographics
- **Type**: Adaptive
- **Total number**: 340,000 (34% immigrant, 17% slave)
- **Age Location**: Glorious Revolution Crisis in youth, Great Awakening in midlife
- **Sample members**: William Byrd II (1744), James Logan (1751), Alexander Spotswood (1740), Elisha Cooke Jr. (1737), Zabdiel Boylston (1766), Daniel Dulany (1753), Andrew Bradford (1742), Cadwallader Colden (1776), Thomas Lee (1750), Johann Conrad Beissel (1768), Mann Page (1730), Nathaniel Appleton (1784), William Shirley (1771), Samuel Johnson (1772), Sir William Pepperrell (1759), Ebenezer Gay (1787), Thomas Foxcroft (1769), James Franklin (1735), John Peter Zenger (1746), John Bartram (1777)

### Defining Generational Character
- Came of age eager to mature into "better-polished generation" Glorious hoped for
- Growing up during crisis, witnessed bloodshed by elders on their behalf
- Entering adulthood at peace and prosperity, dared risk upsetting status quo
- Yet behind nice ornaments (minuets, carriages, libraries, lawsuits, vote counting, purchased pews) lay inner life of gnawing anxiety
- Never stopped worrying refinement and sensitivity betrayed absence of generational power and vision
- Leaders tended to defer rather than solve problems

### The Two Chasms That Defined Them
- **Lifecycle best defined by two chasms they just missed coming of age**:
  1. **Glorious Revolution**: First-wavers arrived too early (ages 15-16) to take part
  2. **Great Awakening**: Late-wavers arrived too late (mid-30s) to take part in spiritual revival
- Absence of visceral peer bond made them better **mediators for other generations** than confident leaders of their own
- Impelled them to hunker down early—caution they paid for by missing (though often seeking) release later
- Reaching midlife after finally outgrowing elder shadow, took risks in society entering enterprise, fashion, art, wit, social mobility, rising immigration
- Yet barely began enjoying freshness when younger moralists condemned them for moving in wrong direction
- **Generational whipsaw**: Those who once defended civic muscle to elders spent later years defending moral purity to juniors
- For few who survived until American Revolution, proving themselves to young was rearguard battle rarely won but never gave up

### Enlightener Facts
- **First large African-American population**: Over 50,000, triple total of all previous generations combined—primarily young slaves purchased by elder Glorious planters; first of four generations extending through Republicans transported on slave ships
- **Least geographically mobile generation** in American history: among native-born New Englanders, only 23% died more than 16 miles from birthplace (less than half the share of any generation before or after)
- In southern colonies: first landed planters whose marriages/inheritances dynastically arranged by (mostly Glorious) parents
- Ran America's first bar and clerical associations, electoral machines (Boston, Philadelphia)
- Included first significant number of doctors/scientists with European credentials
- Gained more memberships in prestigious London Royal Society than any other colonial generation
- **Most humanitarian**: Founders of many church- and town-based charities
- In early 1730s, **James Oglethorpe** colonized Georgia as haven for imprisoned debtors, financed entirely through charitable donations
- As Anglophile rising adults, brought **Queen Anne style**: dainty china, walnut cabinets, parquet floors, "comfortable" furniture
- Also adopted new vices (gin, tea drinking), never imagining children/grandchildren would someday dump stuff into Boston harbor

### The Enlightener Lifecycle

#### Youth: Split Universe
- Growing up amid rebellion and war, learned to split universe into two halves:
  - **Dark side**: **Samuel Johnson** recalled forests filled with Indians, armies, infant-hungry devils
  - **Safe side**: Family safety, smothering embrace of midlife Cavaliers like **Samuel Willard** ("If others in a family suffer want, yet the children shall certainly be taken care for") and confident energy of rising-adult Glorious like **Cotton Mather** ("restrain your children from bad company... You can't be too careful in these matters")
- In New England: towns appointed tithingmen "to attend to disorders of every kind in the families under their charge," sent children to "dame schools" in nearby households rather than risk daily walks outdoors
- In South: vast influx of bonded young Africans traumatized youths of both sexes
- With first glimmers of peace in late century, adults encouraged children to emulate emerging sex-role divisions
- Girls privileged to become "virtuous mothers" tutored in religion, music, embroidery; learned to wear towering "fontanelle" hairstyles
- Boys attended Wigs-sent to writing schools or new colleges
- **Yale** assured parents souls of children were in safe-keeping; **William and Mary** charter promised young gentlemen would be "piously educated in good letters and manners"

#### Coming of Age: Compliance and Tepid Rebellion
- Haunted through youth by fears of "disorder," matured into compliant, immobile, parent-respecting young adults
- Seeking approval, peer elite mastered structured, value-neutral subjects: botany (**John Bartram**), mapmaking (**Lewis Evans**), bookmaking (**Zabdiel Boylston**), and especially law (**Jeremiah Dummer**, **Daniel Dulany**, **Thomas Lee**)
- Such achievements earned respect more than admiration
- By late 1690s, Glorious began complaining youthful Enlightener failed to live up to their own super-straight standard at like age
- Elders chafed at snooty English mannerisms (coffeehouse etiquette to plaid jackets), expected cowardice during Queen Anne's War (ended 1711 stalemate)
- Fretted over young generation's cardplaying, swearing, tavern-going, premarital pregnancy—petty vices indicating post-adolescent tension release
- Yet if Cavaliers and Glorious considered them effete, coming-of-age Enlighteners felt perfectly justified bringing touch of wit and class to dull conformity of post-crisis America
- **Handful stood ground**: In 1721, **James Franklin** set up Boston newspaper, lampooned fiftyish **Cotton Mather** (who, notes historian **Perry Miller**, "appeared, for the first time, silly")
- In 1723, Yale graduate **Samuel Johnson** shocked New England by announcing conversion to Anglican Church
- Such tepid, isolated gestures closest Enlighteners ever came to generational rebellion

#### Rising Adulthood: "The Golden Age"
- **"The Golden Age succeeds the Iron,"** announced *Rhode Island Gazette* (1732), celebrating "erudition and politeness" Enlighteners bringing to colonial "civilization"
- Outwardly: rising adults lucky, setting pace in era of peace and prosperity
- Seemingly without effort, well-groomed elite could inherit/marry into upwardly mobile lifestyles: as town leaders (now versed in law), genteel planters (building Williamsburg-style mansions), colonial agents (riding in coaches), managers of trading empires (familiar with luxuries)
- Inwardly: compensated for denied catharsis by obsessing guiltily over rococo interior of lives
- **"The Grandeur (ah, empty grandeur!) of New England,"** worried 26-year-old **Thomas Paine**: "Our age... how fine and rich! Our furniture and tables, how costly, sumptuous, and dainty!"
- **William Byrd II**: studied *Complete Gentleman* to improve family name of Glorious father while hiding sexual and poetic fantasies in secret coded diary
- Attracted to emotional privacy while inheriting deep trust in institutions
- Gathered in "philosophical" associations, "virtue" societies, humanitarian charities
- Embraced new ethos of professionalism, dominated explosive 1720 growth in colonial office-holding (1720s-1730s)
- Became what historian **Jack Greene** labeled **"the new political professionals"**—parliamentary bickering marks dullest pages in colonial history
- Compared to like-aged Glorious: rising-adult Enlighteners more apt to sue than vote, lobby than build, advocate private process rather than decisive action

#### Midlife: Subversive Pleasure and the Awakening Shock
- Took subversive pleasure in looser, freer tone of colonial society (1730s-1740s)
- Past age 40, many took big risks for first time: speculating in land, launching businesses, womanizing, petitioning
- Few dabbled in skeptical philosophy (**Berkeley**) and dueling clubs or mystical religion (**Zinzendorf's Moravian Church**)
- All nervous joviality came to sudden end around 1740, thanks to youth-propelled **Great Awakening**
- Mid-Enlighteners had sensed it coming; indeed, their craving for "refreshed" emotion in church
- Yet face to face with unbridled passion, quickly realized how little regard Awakening showed for Enlighteners' own strengths—credentials, politeness, pluralism, deference
- **Condemned by Awakener Jonathan Edwards** as "moral neuters," many sank into guilt
- **"I have studied to preserve a due moderation,"** admitted **Edward Wigglesworth**, "and if any expressions have happened to slip from me, that may seem a little too warm or harsh, I shall be sorry for it"
- While **Samuel Niles** feared "strife and contention" and **Benjamin Doolittle** warned of "too much boldness"
- Most Enlighteners responded to next-juniors with sympathy, even envy revealing own inner doubts
- **Nathaniel Appleton**: became "more close and affecting in preaching" after hearing younger enthusiasts
- Admiring passion of younger **George Whitefield**, clergyman **Samuel Dexter** confessed: "ten thousand worlds would I give... to feel and experience what I believe that man does"

#### Elderhood: Accommodating Pluralism
- **"I don't think I know anything,"** said aging **Nathaniel Chauncy** (1756) after reading popular book on religion: "Forty years have I been studying, and this book has told me more than I have ever known"
- Most Enlighteners entered old age with remarkable capacity to rethink narrow childhood prejudices, admit failure, try again
- **"The greatest and worst sorts of trouble and uneasiness,"** lamented **Samuel Johnson** shortly before 1772 death: "are endless doubts, scruples, uncertainties, and perplexities of mind"
- Superseded as leaders by moralistic midlife Awakeners, many tried like Johnson to be "yet further useful" as elders
- When stakes seemed limited, behaved with immature swagger—like **William Shirley** and **William Pepperrell**, gung-ho leaders of colonial crusade against French (1740s-1750s)
- But as stakes grew larger, usually argued for compromise
- **Daniel Dulany** and **Thomas Lee** supported "polite" and "friendly intercourse" with English
- **Ebenezer Gay** (in words of one admirer) tried "to point out that there were always two sides to every question"
- The handful who lived to see Revolution outbreak typically hoped, like **Daniel Perkins**, for "that calmness, dispassionateness, and prudence that may prevent rage and acts of violence"
- Ultimately, 79-year-old **Perkins** forced by juniors to sign statement endorsing American Revolution
- **Cadwallader Colden**, New York governor and *philosophe*, struggled in vain throughout 1776
- Watching every symbol of beloved mother country smashed in fury, he did that same year, at age 88, not knowing how crisis would be resolved

### Legacy Summary
- **Most decent, accommodating, and pluralist**—if also most colorless—of colonial generations
- Collective legacy inferred from eulogies, typically reflecting painful struggle for equilibrium
- Clergyman **Thomas Foxcroft** remembered peer **Thomas Prince** as having "interfered... grave, but not morose"; **Nathaniel Appleton** as "impartial yet pacific, firm yet conciliatory"; **William Byrd II** as "eminently fitted for the service and ornament of his country," yet "in all this were added a great elegance of taste and life"
- As mediators between civic hubris of elders and inner fire of juniors, Enlighteners averted what could have been serious social conflict twisting far in either direction
- Pioneered "freedom of the press," used relative affluence to adorn colonial culture, cultivated respect for "due process" that grandchildren later incorporated into a Constitution
- Yet for all balance brought to public life, **own personal lives took them on zigzag path of overcompensation**:
  - As rising adults: knuckled under too easily to rebuke conformity
  - In midlife: dazzled by younger Awakeners, left with anxious memories of own smothered youth, veered so far toward personal adventure and hands-off parenting that failed to protect emerging crop of Liberty children
- **No one called Enlighteners a great generation**, but they did not try to be
- Sought approval from others, tried to be helpful in great struggles that—often to their secret frustration—never seemed to hit them full force

---

## Chapter 8: The Revolutionary Cycle

### Battle of Bunker Hill (June 17, 1775)
- **Samuel Langdon**, gray-haired Harvard president, led 1,200 soldiers in twilight prayer on Cambridge Common
- Early next morning, **Israel Prescott** (veteran) mustered Patriot troops to rise near Bunker Hill overlooking British army occupying Boston
- Prescott: gritty Indian-war veteran in forties, had little of Langdon's flair for elevated words
- **"Don't fire until you see the whites of their eyes,"** he advised, then added with smile: **"Then aim at their waistbands, and be sure to pick off the commanders, known by their handsome coats"**
- Twentyish soldiers confidently did as ordered; seeing ridiculous red in piles before them, knew they had won not just battle but glory in eyes of all posterity
- Meanwhile, young mother led 8-year-old child "Mr. Johnny" (**John Quincy Adams**) to nearby hill where he could watch cannons thunder at safe distance
- **Stage was set**: All four generations of REVOLUTIONARY CYCLE present, signaled birth of new nation

### Four Generations at Bunker Hill

#### 1. Awakening Generation (Idealist, age 52-74)
- For **Langdon's AWAKENING GENERATION**, Battle of Bunker Hill tested vision that first inspired them decades ago as coming-of-age youngsters
- Back then, upwelling of godly euphoria incited them to rage against fathers
- **"Many such instances there were of children condemning their parents"** and calling them "old hypocrites"—young **Charles Chauncy** had written of fledgling peers (1743)
- Much later, by Revolution, that ideal matured into stern principles of civic virtue which leading Awakeners—**John Adams** and **Benjamin Franklin**—preached entirely to juniors
- "It was time for the old to think and the young to act"
- **"Love itself is a consuming fire with respect to sin,"** **Joseph Bellamy** told Connecticut volunteers coming to Boston
- **Joseph Hawley** likewise inspired Minutemen under Prescott by reminding them of tiny Lexington attendance: **"You will show by your future conduct whether you are worthy to be called offspring of such men"**
- Elder Awakeners raised these "republican" youth for worldly valor—praised them when they later displayed it against **Samuel Howe**

#### 2. Liberty Generation (Reactive, age 34-51)
- **Prescott's LIBERTY GENERATION** shrugged off dialogue between next-elders and next-juniors
- "The Awakening's inner fire was something they had learned to avoid, something that had scorched them once as berated children and again, during 1750s, as despised foot soldiers in murderous crusade against French"
- **Colonel Prescott** not alone in wry wit
- From **George Washington** to **Daniel Boone**, from **Francis Marion** to **Benedict Arnold**, French and Indian War had left mark of devilry and cynicism on entire generation
- **"Rifleman" Daniel Morgan** even had scars of 499 lashes for talking back to officer (His punishment called for 500, but when quartermaster miscounted, Morgan joked, **"I got away with one"**)
- As for younger soldiers on Bunker Hill, Prescott and peers knew what they could and could not expect of themselves
- No matter which side they chose or which side won, these hardbitten peers of **John Adams**—a generation whom historian **Cecelia Kenyon** called **"men of little faith"**—fully expected to be blamed
- Most would indeed reach elderhood getting just what expected: little thanks and precious little reward

#### 3. Republican Generation (Civic, age 9-33)
- For eager soldiers waiting in trenches for redcoats to charge, Bunker Hill began **"most exhilarating rite of passage in American history"**
- **"'Tis but the morning of the world for us,"** Princeton student **Hugh Henry Brackenridge** announced year earlier
- **"Nations shall be taught lessons of heroism and grow great by our example,"** exulted **Israel Evans** to peers six years later after epic victory at Yorktown
- To most elder Liberty (like **John Adams**), war marked end of Revolution
- But to younger Republicans (like **Benjamin Rush**): **"was nothing but the first act of a great drama"**—drama that would not end until mighty generation had built new Constitution, acquired vast new territories, and seen (as **Timothy Dwight** predicted) **"Round thy broad fields prevailing Romes arise/ With pomp and splendor bright'ning all the skies"**
- Where elder Awakeners who loved and praised youngsters had been more godly generation than most, so would Republicans become more worldly than most
- **Historian Edmund Morgan** sums up contrast: **"In the 1740s America's leading intellectuals were clergymen and thought about theology; in 1790 they were statesmen and thought about politics"**

#### 4. Compromise Generation (Adaptive, age 8 and under)
- To **John Quincy Adams' COMPROMISE GENERATION** came frustration of watching war without fighting—then growing up realizing gigantic next-elders had completed all great deeds just ahead of them
- They soon discovered new role: obedience was simply to be good and dutiful—avoid mistakes
- **John Quincy Adams** himself, careful not to disappoint fussy mother **Abigail**, graduated from college feeling "useless and disgraceful insignificance"
- "The like-aged **Andrew Jackson** later declared fellow soldiers must not forget **'the blessings which the blood of so many thousands of heroes has purchased for them'"**
- As Dartmouth student, **Daniel Webster** declaimed: **"For us they fought! For us they bled! For us they conquered!"**
- Webster, only infant when war ended, would consecrate Bunker Hill monument forty-three years later by acknowledging generation's "gratitude" to Republican "heroes"
- Only as these "heroes" began passing away in 1820s would Compromisers, now reaching midlife, emerge from elders' intimidating shadow
- By then, Webster's peers would have to turn attention in new direction—toward younger generation just coming of age

### Revolutionary Cycle: Origins and Scope
- **Bunker Hill**: first full-scale battle in crisis whose origins stretch back decades to very beginning of Revolutionary Cycle
- Began with soul-shattering conversions greeting **Jonathan Edwards' Northampton sermons** (1734)—first genuine thunder of eighteenth-century "Great Awakening"
- Reached forward through French and Indian War, Constitutional Convention, War of 1812
- Closed with **James Monroe's** outwardly calm but inwardly turbulent **"Era of Good Feeling"** (mid-1820s)
- Cycle left behind shining legacy of nation-building Americans would always cherish
- But having solved so many problems, these four generations could hardly help others in tester
- Most notably: **failed to act on issue of southern slavery**—omission that would figure fatefully in next awakening and next crisis

### Two Social Moments of Revolutionary Cycle

#### 1. The Great Awakening (1734-1743)
- Began as series of isolated spiritual revivals in Connecticut Valley
- Spread quickly, especially in northern and middle colonies
- Reached peak in 1741 during rousing American tour of English-born evangelist **George Whitefield**
- After mass gatherings and "concerts of prayer" in early 1740s, fervor receded in most areas—but not without reshaping temperament of most rising adults who lived through it
- Would later reach midlife setting tone of spirituality and public principle utterly unknown during fathers' "Glacial Age of Religion"
- **AGE LOCATION**: *Glorious Enlighteners in midlife; Awakeners in rising adulthood; Liberty in youth*

#### 2. The American Revolution Crisis (1773-1789)
- Broadly defined, stretched from Boston Tea Party through ratification of Constitution, swearing-in of first President and Congress (1789)
- Amid brave moments, especially dark Valley Forge winter of 1778, lurked very real fear these "rebels" might fail and that soldiers of Continental Congress would be hanged as traitors
- Crisis ended with ratification of new Constitution and inauguration of President **George Washington** and Vice President **John Adams**
- Over next twelve years, Washington and Adams steered infant nation with protective caution while watching younger, more optimistic cadre of veterans rise to power and plan for Republic's glorious future
- **AGE LOCATION**: *Awakeners in elderhood; Liberty in midlife; Republicans in rising adulthood; Compromisers in youth*

---

## Awakening Generation (Born 1701-1723)

### Type and Character
- **Type**: Idealist
- **Age Location**: Great Awakening in rising adulthood, American Revolution Crisis in elderhood

### The Great Awakening Experience (1741)
- **James Davenport** tour of New England (age 25): messiah "attended with so much disorder" that followers "looked more like a company of Bacchanalians after a mad frolic, than sober Christians who had been worshipping God"
- For colonial newspapers, frenzy marked yet one more riotous episode in America's **"Great and General Awakening"**
- For hundreds of radical preachers like Davenport—and for young crowds smitten by emotional thunder—**"it was a coming-of-age catharsis for the AWAKENING GENERATION"**
- Moment brought **truth, euphoria, and millennial vision** to America
- Also brought **hysteria, shattered families, and split towns**
- **Writing in 1742**, elder Salem minister declared: "It is impossible to relate the convulsions into which the country is thrown"
- **Richard Hofstadter** (1970s): historian likened fervor to civil rights demonstrations, campus disturbances, urban riots of 1960s combined—**"a psychological earthquake that reshaped the human landscape"**

### Awakener Lifecycle and Worldview
- Lifecycle resembles **"first straining of God through a glass darkly and at last breaking through to a purifying fire"**
- Born into secure and slowly loosening Enlightener society; Awakeners were not finding spiritual comfort in secular world of Glorious midlifers
- Coming of age, discovered it—**inside themselves**
- In burst of passion, converts to **"religion of the heart"** shattered ossified social discipline of fathers
- When Great Awakening expired (mid-1740s), rising Awakeners drifted off into quieter avenues of self-perfection
- Paid little attention to worldly troubles enveloping colonies
- Only later, as they entered midlife worrying about dissolute younger Liberty, did Awakeners find substitute for old order they had wrecked
- **Theirs was entirely new vision**—of an America destined by Providence to play millennial role in salvation of world
- Would be land where all souls stood on equal footing, where social union depended on principle rather than convenience
- Where education aimed at virtue rather than utility, where grace and union took precedence over laws and rights
- Awakeners championed spiritual goods at civic virtue threshold of old age, presided over society of patriots ready to die for independence

### Famous Awakener Names: Moral Prophets
Roster heavy with **moral prophets, "sons of thunder"**:
- **Jonathan Edwards, George Whitefield, William Tennent**: tearing down "do-good" orthodoxy of elders
- Flirty rationalists like **Jonathan Mayhew** and **Charles Chauncy**: insisting from pulpits that death preferable to "slavery," and "corruptions" of Hispanic empires called for eradicators
- **Eleazar Wheelock, John Witherspoon, Anthony Benezet**: Benezet (according to observer) "carried his love of humanity to point of madness"
- **Radical slavery-abolitionists** like "Visions of Hell" **Jacob Green** and **John Woolman** (clad in white as Jesus Christ)
- Same image fits best-known Awakener patriarchs who later steered American Revolution: **Samuel Adams** and **Benjamin Franklin**—still radical, still cerebral

### Adams and Franklin as Awakener Archetypes
- **In Boston**, austere **Adams** was said by biographer to "preach hate to a degree without rival" in quest of "Christian millennium"
- **In Philadelphia**, **Franklin** believed fervently in higher causes that he abandoned prospering printing business (mid-forties) to devote life to reflection and moral uplift
- **Careless of orthodox religion**, Franklin left his soul to evangelical prayers of good friend **Whitefield**
- Yet years earlier (age 16), Franklin wrote in diary that he regarded "the bold and arduous project of arriving at moral perfection," concluded it with self-aimed injunction to **"Imitate Jesus and Socrates"**

### Political Labels: The "Puritan" Generation
- **"Puritan" label** always attached to this generation
- Contemporaries called **Samuel Adams** "the last of the Puritans," **Roger Sherman** "an old Puritan," **Edwards** a "Puritan" Calvinist
- Even arch-Tory **Thomas Hutchinson** described by historian as "neo-Puritan ascetic"
- Like Puritans, **Awakeners refused to compromise** over principle or separate politics from religion
- **Mayhew** said he had duty to "preach politics"; **Patriot preacher Joseph Hawley** announced himself "an enthusiast in politics"
- Hebrew scholar and Patriot governor **Jonathan Trumbull** sprinkled war correspondence with phrases like "The Lord Reigned," "exile"
- **Peter Oliver** blamed Revolution on what he called America's **"black regiment"**—by that he meant old Awakeners preaching upheaval in churches
- Ministers like 72-year-old **Samuel Dunbar**, who read entire Declaration of Independence from pulpit
- Not all elderly Awakeners became Patriots during Revolution; some became Tories and sailed away to pass twilight years in Canada or England
- But **few Tory Awakeners** ever felt much affinity with their generation, even decades before Revolution
- Virtually none had shared peers' euphoria during Great Awakening
- **The Tory Awakener was self-confessed outcast**, disengaged from civic muscle of peers
<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## AWAKENING GENERATION (Born 1701 to 1723)

### Generation Overview
- **Type**: Idealist generation
- **Total number**: 500,000
- **Percent immigrant**: 19%
- **Percent slave**: 18%

### Family Tree Position
- **Typical grandparents**: Cavalier
- **Parents**: Glorious and Enlightenment
- **Children**: Liberty and Republican
- **Typical grandchildren**: Compromiser

### Political Leadership Period
- First and last year of colonial governorship and naval dukehood: **14 years**
- Connecticut: 1769–1776, 7 years
- Rhode Island: 1755–1776, 17 years
- Virginia: 1750–1776, 13 years
- Presidency of Continental Congress: **1774–1775, 1782**

### Sample Members
- **Jonathan Edwards** (1758), **Gilbert Tenement** (1764)*, **Benjamin Franklin** (1790)
- **Jonathan Trumbull** (1785), **Richard Bland** (1776), **Thomas Hutchinson** (1780)
- **Jupitor Hammon** (c. 1800), **Anthony Benezet** (1784)*, **George Whitefield** (1770)*
- **John Woolman** (1772), **Pontiac** (1769), **Peyton Randolph** (1775)
- **Roger Sherman** (1793), **Samuel Hopkins** (1803), **Eliza Pinckney** (1793)
- **Samuel Adams** (1803), **William Livingston** (1790), **Crispus Attucks** (1770)
- **Samson Occom** (1792), **John Witherspoon** (1794)*

### Key Facts
- **Great Awakening impact**: 250 new churches, 200,000 religious conversions between 1730-1745
- "New Side" revivalists averaged **25 years** of age; "Old Side" defenders averaged **59 years**
- From 1730-1745: average age of joining New England church **plummeted from late thirties to mid-twenties**
- Share of new church members joining before age thirty rose from **one-fifth to two-thirds**
- More American colonists graduated from **Harvard in the 1730s** than any decade until the 1760s
- Colonists published more books on the Antichrist and Last Judgement in **1750s** than any decade before the Revolution
- **Awakener women** assumed unprecedented visibility: religious leaders (Sarah Osborn in Rhode Island), missionaries (Moravian "single sisters"), planters (Eliza Pinckney, first American to cultivate indigo)
- Awakeners entering elderhood were **America's leaders of choice** at the Revolution's outset
- 1774-1776: average age of officeholding in New England towns rose from **low forties to fifties**
- In 1776: **eleven of thirteen new "states"** led by Awakeners
- Five colonies threw out Revolution (Liberty) Tories and replaced them with elder (Awakener) Patriots
- **Peyton Randolph** and **Henry Middleton**: first two presidents of Continental Congress
- **John Witherspoon**: Princeton College president for 26 years, schoolmaster to "entire generation of rational Republican statesmen" (Madison, Burr, Marshall, ten cabinet leaders, sixty future Congress members)

### The Awakener Lifecycle

#### YOUTH
- Raised in **secure communities**, largely spared from war/violence
- Post-1700 birth cohort: **best-educated generation** of children their elders had ever seen
- At home: listened to "happy discipline" of *A Family Well Ordered* (Cotton Mather)—"our submission to the rules of reason is an obedience to the voice of God"
- In school: standardized *New England Primer* taught same messages with "Dutiful Child" and "Prayer"
- Turning away from **distant, busy fathers** toward **mothers**, whom Glorious had entrusted with piety and emotion
- Many vowed with **Samuel Adams** to abandon worldly careers to please mothers' "religious principles"
- Striking number (Franklin, Richard Bland, Roger Sherman) became **bookish loners**
- Others hit by **dreamlike visions**: Young **Jonathan Edwards** kicked off at "solitary places" to reflect on "divine glory in almost everything"
- Young **John Woolman** imagined "past ages" in which people "walked in uprightness before God"
- By 1720s-1730s: teenagers began **crowding into colleges** seeking spiritual calling
- Boston press (1734) called them **"a new sort of reformers, vulgarly called the mob"**—according to Gary Nash, youths were "antitraditional, antiscientific... and moralistic," rejecting the secular world their Glorious fathers were about to hand them

#### COMING OF AGE
- With the **Great Awakening**, raging inner life indulged as young Americans exploded in **spiritual reform**
- In 1736: **young Edwards** firestorm first struck his town "like a flash of lightning upon the towns of the young people"
- By mid-1730s, wave spread through most of the colonies
- In colleges: young Awakeners banded in clubs of **"saints"**; fulminated against **"spirit-dead"** in open-air gatherings
- They exhorted one another to help **"semi-christians"** if necessary, to join Christ
- Where like-aged Glorious stressed **cheerful teamwork**, young Awakeners preached **spiritual perfection**
- Demanding **"New Light"** faith over **"Old Light"** works, mixing "kisses of charity" with what **Charles Chauncy** called "a censuring and judging spirit"
- Denouncing elders who kept "driving, driving to duty!"
- **Gilbert Tenement** assaulted "those of another generation who imagine happiness is to be had in wealth and riches"
- **Samuel Finley** roared: "Away with your carnal prudence!"
- When enthusiasm faded mid-1740s: **orthodox mounted reaction** expelling many students from college, punishing with special vengeance Awakener slaves who staged rebellions during frenzy
- Inwardly, young knew their triumph was complete—Americans would **never again preach or pray or feel** as they had before
- For most Awakeners: **special memory** would linger—of that day or week or season when they had created a **spiritual community**
- Many (like Edwards) declared America in 1740 was inaugurating the **"reign of God on earth, a New Jerusalem... to come down from heaven"**
- Decades later, **Franklin** fondly recalled Philadelphia: "It was wonderful to see the change.... It seemed as if all the world were growing religious."

#### RISING ADULTHOOD
- After explosion of self-discovery, **thirtyish Awakeners** entered adulthood with **mixture of outer detachment and inner principle**
- In Boston: **Samuel Adams** drifted through menial jobs ("I glory in being what the world calls a poor man")
- In New York: **William Livingston** dabbled in law and wrote best-selling poems like *Philosophic Solitude*
- In Virginia: **Landon Carter** saw fit "to cultivate the inward man"
- Young spiritual prophets hit the road—**converting Indians**, denouncing slavery, gathering separatist churches, founding communes
- **Rising Awakeners** made **poor citizens**: Avoided voting or running for office, shunned worldly pursuits at an early age to join newer, younger towns
- Reversed their parents' lifecycle: **Values first**, then worldly things
- "What can all the world afford us," asked **Ebenezer Pemberton**, "beyond a competent supply of our bodily wants?"
- Young men understood born-again innocence (becoming **"again like a child"**) to use **Edwards'** phrase meant rejecting fathers' interest in prestige and power
- Young women understood they need not become one of Mather's **"hidden ones"**
- Awakeners recognized America's growing military and economic strength, but assessed primarily with **moral dramas**
- Frontier preachers like **Samuel Finley** saw the French and Indian War as "symptom of Armageddon"
- Virginia reformer **Richard Bland** attacked **"the least flaw"** in colonial rights
- Rising Pennsylvania Quakers resigned **en masse** from public office (late 1750s) rather than compromise pacifism by fighting Indians
- "If the posterds of the earth clash together," said **Samuel Fothergill** on behalf of scrupulous peers, "let them clash."

#### MIDLIFE
- **"Let sin be slain!"** boomed theologian **Joseph Bellamy** (1762) as he addressed late-fortyish peers in Connecticut assembly
- Decrying **"luxury, idleness, debauchery"** of rising generation
- Entering midlife, Awakeners at last began **turning principles toward outer world**
- In early 1760s, far from delighting in victorious end of French and Indian War, they expressed **horror over America's growing moral decadence**—especially the **"gangrene"** and **"vice"** of wild young Liberty
- In 1765: responded to Britain's **Stamp Act** by organizing popular crusades of **economic austerity** and **breast-beating virtue**
- As assembly leaders: founded **Committees of Correspondence** to bind America together into what Mayhew termed **"communion of colonies"**
- As town leaders and educators: sparked what historian **Michael Kammen** calls "an awakening of consciousness"—a new passion for **public-spirited clubs and colleges**
- As printers: used **Franklin's "Join or Die"** slogan to roar out rhetoric of unity
- As popular leaders: led the **Boston Massacre** (Crispus Attucks) and **Boston Tea Party** (Samuel Adams, William Molineux)
- Watching colonial resistance to Britain quicken toward point of no return, Awakeners felt enough moral taste
- **Witherspoon**, president of Princeton College, vowed "to prefer war with all its horrors, and even extermination, to slavery"
- **Clergyman Jonathan Parsons** promised that if British did not relent, "the spirit of Christian benevolence would animate us to fill our streets with blood"
- In 1774, to thunderous applause of First Continental Congress, **Joseph Hawley** promised "It is right against right."

#### ELDERHOOD
- **"We shall succeed if we are virtuous,"** insisted **Samuel Adams**
- "I am infinitely more apprehensive of the contagion of vice than the power of all other enemies"
- "As generals or administrators, aging Awakeners had little talent. But as inner-driven chieftains of virtue and wisdom (**"Let us get the men,"** said Adams), they urged them to younger men during moment of trial"
- Their **moralistic leadership** dominated initial revolutionary movement
- In Continental Congress: old Awakeners enacted blue laws to make "true religion and good morals" the national credo
- In local Patriot committees: led the **ideological radicals**—insisting on unanimous votes, requiring Tories to "confess" to their conversion, invoking (like sixtyish Bellamy) **"Curse of Meroz"** against cowardice
- During war: relinquished political power to make room for much-younger Republicans whom they trusted and loved
- But even in 1780s-1790s: **elderly Awakeners** retained voice of authority, voice the young took seriously
- Many of their political leaders showed **new willingness** to empower rising Republican elite
- Many of their clergymen continued to **agitate against "sin of slavery"**, forcing legal or de facto emancipation of northern slaves by end of century
- Facing death, Awakener instinct was **not to reach back** for the world, but **to transcend it**—writing about the **Last Judgment** (Sherman), philosophizing in salons (Franklin), requesting no show of mourning at funerals (Samuel Mather, Cotton's son)
- **Samuel Adams** (still penniless in eighties) insisted a man certain of his own virtue always dies **"with dignity"**
- **Landon Carter** ("King" Carter's son) claimed just before his death: **"In spite of my merits, I have only inward satisfaction."**

### Historical Assessment
> "The Awakeners may be America's least understood and most underestimated generation." — Historians' consensus

- Historians agree the **spiritual fury** of Great Awakening fed directly into **political fury** of American Revolution decades later
- According to **Nathan Hatch**: "few would doubt that the piety of the Awakening was the main source of the civil millennialism of the American Revolution"
- According to **Alan Heimert**: "what the colonists awakened to in 1740 was none other than independence and rebellion"
- Yet no historian has left clear picture of **single peer group** that judged both events
- This was **generation of crusaders**: first young zealots since Puritans to rebel against their fathers; elder Glorious urged conscience to urge political independence and demand freedom for slaves
- Shortly before death in 1790: 84-year-old **Benjamin Franklin** signed memorial to Congress for abolition of slavery
- Three months earlier: four Awakeners signed **Declaration of Independence**
- A half century earlier, **Jonathan Edwards** (born only three years before Franklin) predicted the millennium would begin in America and make the world **"a kingdom of holiness, purity, love, peace, and happiness to mankind"**
- Although Edwards never lived to see Revolution, Franklin had their common generation in mind when asked what image should adorn national seal of United States
- With little hesitation, Franklin answered: **fatherly image of Moses, hands extended to heaven, parting the waters for his people**

---

## LIBERTY GENERATION (Born 1724 to 1741)

### Generation Overview
- **Type**: Reactive
- **Total number**: 1,160,000
- **Percent immigrant**: 24%
- **Percent slave**: 19%

### Family Tree Position
- **Typical grandparents**: Glorious
- **Parents**: Enlightenment and Awakening
- **Children**: Republican and Compromiser
- **Typical grandchildren**: Transcendental

### Political Leadership Period
- Plurality in House: —
- Plurality in Senate: —
- Majority of Supreme Court: —
- U.S. Presidents: **1789–1801**
  - **George Washington** (1799)
  - **John Adams** (1826)
- Presidency of Continental Congress: **1775–1778, 1779–1781, 1782–1783, 1784–1788**

### Sample Members
- **James Otis** (1783), **George Mason** (1792), **Ezra Stiles** (1795)
- **Mercy Warren** (1814), **Robert Rogers** (1795), **Martha Washington** (1802)
- **Francis Marion** (1795), **John Dickinson** (1808), **Daniel Boone** (1820)
- **Robert Morris** (1806)*, **Paul Revere** (1818), **Patrick Henry** (1799)
- **John Hancock** (1793), **Thomas Paine** (1809)*, **Charles Carroll** (1832)
- **Francis Hopkinson** (1791), **Benjamin West** (1820), **Ethan Allen** (1789)
- **George Clinton** (1812), **Benedict Arnold** (1801)

### Key Facts
- During late 1730s and early 1740s, while parents preoccupied with Great Awakening, Liberty children were **victimized by deadliest child-only epidemic** in American history: **"great throat distemper"** (diphtheria), which killed an estimated **one child in fifteen** throughout most of New York and New England
- Liberty were by far **most war-ravaged generation** of colonial era
- Describing casualties during French and Indian War, historian **Gary Nash** estimates that by 1760, "Boston had experienced equivalent of two twentieth-century world wars in one generation"
- One-quarter of all inhabitants of ship town of Salem, Massachusetts enlisted for at least one season **between 1754 and 1759**
- Stockade and ship records indicate disease and bad nutrition killed an estimated **5 to 10 percent** of recruits during each year of service
- Having grown up during era of **falling rum prices** and **rising public disorder**, Liberty matured into **notorious generation of drinkers, thieves, and rioters**—to dismay of elder Awakener moralists
- Liberty consumed **more alcohol per capita** than any other colonial generation
- Between 1760-1775: led **more violent mobs** than cumulative total for all prior generations
- Coined both the words **"regulator"** (for vigilante) and **"lynch"** (after Liberty Virginian Colonel Charles Lynch)
- Liberty accounted for **largest wave of colonial immigration**—mostly the poor, fierce (and non-English) Scots-Irish who typically disembarked in Philadelphia then sped south, west, and north to the frontier
- Though comprising **only half** of all members of Continental Congress, Liberty accounted for:
  - All five delegates accused of **complicity with the British**
  - Two most famous **military traitors** (Benedict Arnold and Benjamin Church)
  - Most famous **near-traitors** (including Ethan Allen, who secretly considered selling Vermont to British)
  - Most notorious **Tory writers** (from Hugh Gaine to Samuel Seabury)
- Liberty included nearly **two-thirds (35 of 56) of signers** of Declaration of Independence in 1776
- Eleven years later: included only **one-third of signers** of U.S. Constitution
- A list of leading "Anti-Federalist" opponents of Constitution in 1788 reads like a Liberty Who's Who: **Patrick Henry, George Mason, Richard Henry Lee, George Clinton, Mercy Warren, David Lamb, David Rittenhouse, Herman Husbands** (average age 57)
- During 1780s, midlife Liberty leaders **statistically more likely** to be what historian **Jackson Turner Main** defines as politically "localists" (less educated, more suspicious of ideas and large institutions) than either their juniors or elders

### The Liberty Lifecycle

#### YOUTH
- During 1730s and 1740s, while **William Hogarth** drew pictures of abandoned London waifs, the Liberty trend in American child-rearing was **wholesale neglect**
- Colonial newspapers noted **rising number of children** denounced as **"bastards,"** turned over to slave or indentured masters, left alone to sink or swim, or just left free to run around on their own
- For most first-wave Liberty kids: new nurturing style reflected the **midlife Enlightener dash** toward personal autonomy
- **"We should think of little children as we do persons,"** insisted pedagogue **Samuel Johnson**
- For most last-wavers, watching young Awakener parents grope for **holiness and guilt** against one another, childhood offered **by-product of Great Awakening**
- Specter of adults crying out in church (noted Awakener **Charles Chauncy**): "frequently frights the little children, and sets them screaming"
- First-wave or last, Liberty kids quickly learned that **immersed adults** at best ignored them, at worst reviled their streetwise realism
- **Jonathan Edwards** condemned them as an **"evil and adulterous generation"**
- **Benjamin Franklin** used *Poor Richard's Almanac* to lecture them on **prudence and thrift**—but all in vain
- Reaching their teens at a time of **economic bust, land pressure, and rising immigration**, the daunted Liberty ran off on their own in quest of **fame and fortune**
- Soon young losers began turning up **underfoot everywhere**—gambling, begging, stealing in the towns, "strolling" aimlessly on back roads, sparking America's first **Halloween mayhem** in Boston

#### COMING OF AGE
- The colonies fought both their midcentury struggles against France—**King George's War (1744–1748)** and **French and Indian War (1754–1760)**—primarily with **Liberty muscle and guts**
- At first, nothing so thrilled these plucky teenagers as **news that armies were marching**
- War meant freedom from moralizing elders and penny-pinching masters, boom wages in ports, glittering prospect of soldiers' bounties, pirate shares, enemy booty
- But as campaigns wore on, dreams turned into nightmares
- Smitten by **"privateering fever"** (remarked almost a kind of madness, New York Awakener **James DeLancey**), thousands enlisted onto French-hunting gunboats
- Only a handful made fortunes; nearly half ended up **bilked, crippled, or captured**
- **Royal Navy impressment gangs** dragged away many of the young port workers, who responded with the **most violent town riots** in colonial history
- Young militiamen heard themselves called wild **"dogs"** and selfish **"riff raff"** by British officers, who used **martial-law punishment** (including 500-lash whippings) to cow them into compliance
- The war brought terrible physical suffering
- While sixtyish Enlighteners sipped tea with visiting officialdom and fortyish Awakeners preached and prayed, the twentyish Liberty **paid the physical price**
- "They were 'young people with nothing to do and nowhere to go,'" writes historian **William Pencak**, "and war took care of them—in both the literal and colloquial senses—during the forties and fifties."

#### RISING ADULTHOOD
- From 1750 on, colonies registered onset of **Liberty adulthood** with spectacular jump in every measure of **social pathology**—from drinking, gambling, and crime to begging, poverty, and bankruptcy
- After the wars, during wild and depressed 1760s, it only got worse
- Debtor prisons bulged with **young spendthrifts**
- Veterans and migrants raised havoc on frontier, especially against Indians (some under elder **Pontiac**), attacking whites who white settlers farmed too far beyond their means, doubling colonial debt to Britain between 1760 and 1775
- Elders were aghast, and towns cut relief payments to burgeoning numbers of young poor
- **"The only principle of life propagated among the young people is to get money,"** complained old Enlightener **Cadwallader Colden**
- "They play away, and run it all away," lamented Awakener **Landon Carter** of young Virginians who preferred **"bewitching diversions"** to **"solid improvements of the mind"**
- With the **Stamp Act riots** of 1765, Liberty's anti-British agitation increased—but everyone knew their mob leaders had **mixed self-interest** with patriotism
- Many of the leading Liberty Patriots were **smugglers** (John Hancock), **hopeless debtors** (Isaac Sears, James Nelson), **renegade settlers** (Ethan Allen), or **disgruntled office-seekers** (Richard Henry Lee)
- Fiftyish Awakeners nursed against the thirtyish Liberty their **greed and selfishness**—for being a generation of **"white savages,"** as **Benjamin Franklin** called the Paxton boys
- **Samuel Adams'** remarks, said a contemporary, "were never favorable to the rising generation"
- But the Liberty took a **nihilistic pleasure** in their elders' discovery: **"Virginians are of genuine blood—they will dance or die,"** they laughed back
- Reflecting his peers' **implacable hostility** to Awakener holiness, **Daniel Boone** declared his secret of happiness to be **"a good wife, a good gun, and a good hored."**

#### MIDLIFE
- When Continental Congress crowded up to sign Declaration of Independence, the **fiftyish (and very corpulent) Benjamin Harrison** elbowed a (thin) younger delegate
- When the signers are all hanged, Harrison predicted: **"I shall have all the advantage over you. For me it will be all over in a minute, but you will be kicking in the air half an hour after I am gone!"**
- For Liberty, now entering midlife as Revolution was moment of truth
- Unlike their elders, they expected no miracles (**"I think the game is pretty near up,"** wrote Washington during his retreat across New Jersey)
- Unlike their juniors, they had families and reputations at stake plus their blunt view of future **no lock forward to rights**
- But they never lost their **practical and defensive goal**: to prevent **"tyranny"** and to protect individual **"liberties,"** a George Mason definition of the new **Virginia Bill of Rights**
- Nor did they lose their **cunning and ferocity**
- These 50-year-olds excelled at the **dirty work**: privateering (Sears again, this time owning shares in fifteen ships), requisitioning supplies (**"Sumpter's Law"** of guerrilla war financier **Francis Marion**, the **"Financier of American Revolution"**), and guerrilla tactics (**"this damned old fox"** Francis Marion, whom British charged **"would not fight like a Christian or a gentleman"**)
- Liberty also accounted for most of **war-era treachery**—confirming elder judgments that this generation was **unfit to be trusted**
- When struggle was over, most of them fell into exhaustion, and a **suspicious realism** replaced their once-wild ardor
- In 1788 they provided the **leading opponents** to the ambitious new Constitution
- Drafted by Republicans, **"All checks founded on anything but self-love will not avail,"** warned 52-year-old **Patrick Henry**, now a self-confessed **"old-fashioned fellow"**
- Skeptical of the work of **"young visionaries,"** they barked without biting
- They were **not about to stand in the way** of the energy of their juniors—or the dreams of their elders
- Their opposition relented, and **by fall of 1789** nearly all states had ratified Constitution

#### ELDERHOOD
- **"Perhaps the strongest feature in his character was prudence,"** the younger Jefferson wrote of President Washington
- With **gruff words and beefer manner**, Washington protected infant nation during first eight years
- He dealt mildly with **Indians and Tories** who had once been his enemies, and (perhaps recalling French and Indian War) once loudly treated resisted younger calls for **harsh action** against the Whiskey Rebels
- To avoid risk of war, he avoided alliances abroad and warned against **"interweaving our destiny with any part of Europe"**
- His successor, President Adams, ruined his own chances for reelection by steering a **similar course of caution and vigilance**
- Prudent, realistic, and self-effacing, the Liberty entered elderhood just when Americans were shifting from the **veneration of age** toward the **celebration of youth**
- **"The language of abuse which old men have to bear,"** writes historian **David Hackett Fischer**, noting that this was **"the generation whose unhappy fate it was to be young in an era when age was respected, and old in a time when youth took the palm"**
- In the 1790s, for example, New England churches eliminated **age-ranked seating** and majority of states imposed **mandatory retirement ages** for judges
- Many Liberty elders met with **sad fates**:
  - **Robert Rogers**, greatest war hero of 1750s, arrested for counterfeiting, tried "enemy Tory" during Revolution, died an alcoholic in England
  - **Thomas Paine** died a lonely outcast on Long Island
  - **Robert Morris** died penniless
  - **Daniel Boone** penniless
- When old, **John Adams** admitted that the only real happiness for his peers were **"aged men, who had been tossed and buffeted in the vicissitudes of life"** and taught **"by grief and disappointment... to command their passions and prejudices"**
- Few Liberty expected to be thanked—so cruel life had made them, like the eightyish Adams, that **"mausoleums, statues, monuments will never be erected to me."**

### Cultural Impact
- In eyes of older and younger Americans who knew them, the Liberty were a **generation of kinetic physical action**
- They played hard and danced wildly, wagered on cockfights and boat races, and danced the **furious and competitive jig**
- They chose as leaders of legendary **kinetic physicality**: Henry, Allen, Morgan, Boone, Harrison—and above all, **George Washington**, whose **six-foot-three-inch physical presence** towered above his peers
- Discarded in childhood and punished coming of age, they chose **by midlife** to exalt the reckless **abandon**—not morning piety or holiness like their next-elders, but **running away from it**; not praying for grace but rather **trying to seize it** in the Bible
- **Ezra Stiles**, their most learned scholar, once puckishly described the Great Awakening as a time when **"multitudes were seriously, soberly, and solemnly out of their wits."**
- No one expected this generation to sacrifice self in America's hour of crisis
- But that they did—with **visceral (if corruptible) motives** only they could understand: **fury at the British "lobsterbacks"** who had once taunted them, and hope that they might achieve **some measure of security for their children**
- Afterward, they mellowed into **risk-averse elders** who were able to congratulate Republican heroism while also checking the **naive ambitions** of young "Hamiltonians"
- Having gambled and suffered quite enough for one lifetime, the Liberty reached old age with **no illusions** about human nature
- **Ralph Waldo Emerson** later described a portrait of the sixtyish President Washington: **"The heavy, leaden eyes turn on you, as the eyes of an ox in a pasture... as if this MAN had absorbed all the serenity of America, and left none for his restless, rickety, hysterical countrymen."**

---

## REPUBLICAN GENERATION (Born 1742 to 1766)

### Generation Overview
- **Type**: Civic
- **Total number**: 2,100,000
- **Percent immigrant**: 17%
- **Percent slave**: 17%

### Family Tree Position
- **Typical grandparents**: Enlightenment
- **Parents**: Awakener and Liberty
- **Children**: Compromiser and Transcendental
- **Typical grandchildren**: Gilded

### Political Leadership Period
- Plurality in House: **1789–1813**
- Plurality in Senate: **1789–1813**
- Majority of Supreme Court: **1791–1826**
- U.S. Presidents: **1801–1825**
  - **Thomas Jefferson** (1826)
  - **James Madison** (1836)
  - **James Monroe** (1831)
- Presidency of Continental Congress: **1778–1779, 1783–1784, 1788–1789**

### Sample Members
- **Nathanael Greene** (1786), **Abigail Adams** (1818), **John Jay** (1829)
- **Benjamin Rush** (1813), **John Paul Jones** (1792), **Kunta Kinte** (c. 1815)*
- **Gouverneur Morris** (1816), **Timothy Dwight** (1817), **Pierre L'Enfant** (1825)*
- **Joel Barlow** (1812), **"Molly Pitcher"** (1832), **Nathan Hale** (1776)
- **John Marshall** (1835), **Alexander Hamilton** (1804)*, **Noah Webster** (1843)
- **Albert Gallatin** (1849)*, **John Jacob Astor** (1848)*, **Robert Fulton** (1815)
- **Eli Whitney** (1825), **"Uncle Sam" Wilson** (1854)

### Key Facts
- The **majority** of Republican political leaders (from Jefferson, Madison, Monroe to Marshall, Webster, and Rush) were both **native-born and college-educated** in America—in contrast to helter-skelter Liberty, whose leaders were more likely **immigrant** (Paine), **native but educated abroad** (Dickinson), or **entirely without formal schooling** (Washington)
- Between native cohorts born in 1730 and 1760, better child nutrition caused average height of adult Americans to rise by **more than half an inch**—the most rapid **one-generation climb** recorded in America until the G.I.s
- In 1780, typical Republican soldier was **at least two inches taller** than typical English redcoat he was fighting
- During 1760s, when first-wave Republicans began graduating from college, the share of American graduates entering **clerical careers** fell from **two-fifths to one-half**
- Many young men turned instead to **radical Masonry**, a male "brotherhood" dedicated to teamwork, good works, and secular progress
- Masonic symbolism dominated the **compass, plumbline, and carpenter's square** that celebrated the builder
- Masonic praise (to be **"on the square"**) directness and utility; the Masonic icon (suitably the divinity) of **practical reason**
- Republicans assumed political power **early in life**
- In 1780s: elected to New England town offices at a **younger age** than members of any generation since the Glorious
- From 1774 to 1787: their delegate share of Continental Congress rose from **7 to 75 percent**
- During three Liberty Presidencies (1789–1801): Republicans claimed over **three-quarters of all members of Congress**, two thirds of Court justices, one of two Vice-Presidencies, nearly all diplomatic posts, and all **fourteen cabinet appointments**—from Secretary of State to Postmaster General
- The leading **Federalist advocates** of the Constitution were on average **ten to twelve years younger** than their Anti-Federalist opponents
- At Philadelphia Convention in 1787, thirtyish Republicans (Madison, Pinckney, Hamilton, Wilson, Martin, King, and Strong) were the most **influential drafters and debaters**
- No other generation has ever matched the **forty-seven-year tenure** spanning Republicans' first and last years of national leadership—from **John Jay** (in 1778 elected president of Continental Congress at age 33) to **James Monroe** (whose second term as U.S. President expired in 1825 at age 67)
- Not until the G.I.s has any other generation of leaders been so **aggressively secular** in outlook
- Most of the Republican candidates for President—especially **Jefferson, Madison, Burr, Pinckney, and King**—avoided any display of Christian piety and were **widely regarded as atheists** by their contemporaries
- When asked by elder clergyman why the Constitution did not mention God, the young Hamilton pertly replied: **"I declare, we forgot."**
- The political eclipse of the Republicans coincided with their humiliation in the **War of 1812**
- On eve of Jefferson's embargo of 1806: Republicans still constituted **71 percent of congressmen and governors**
- By their postwar election of 1815, their share had plunged to **37 percent**
- In 1820s, Congress repeatedly raised **pension benefits** to elderly Revolutionary War veterans; by end of decade, nearly **half of all federal spending** consisted of interest and pension payments
- In 1828, 70-year-old **Noah Webster** introduced the word **"veneration"** into American vocabulary
- In 1830s and 1840s, Americans began to **"venerate"** the image of **"Uncle Sam"** in the person of the seventy veteran **Samuel Wilson**, one of the last survivors of his generation

### The Republican Lifecycle

#### YOUTH
- Around 1745, routine brutality among and against colonial teenagers aroused **little adult sympathy**
- By 1770, the year of the **Boston Massacre**, the violent death of one child was enough to spark **vehement public outrage**
- Over course of just twenty-five years, American attitudes toward the young reversed direction entirely—from impulse to protect, from blame to comfort
- Despairing the wayward Liberty, midlife Awakeners wanted to ensure this **new crop of kids** would grow up to be smart and cooperative **republican citizens**
- To build this dawning vision, a **republic of virtue**
- During war-torn 1750s, towns shielded children from the rowdiness of twentyish Liberty by **tightening up on begging, gambling, and theaters**
- **"By 1750,"** observes historian **Jay Fliegelman**, "irresponsible parents became the nation's scapegoat"
- Number of **tutors per capita** doubled as popular books (endorsed as holy and protective role of parent) proliferated
- In 1760s: parents began avoiding **"corrupt"** English schools and sent their kids instead to **Awakener-founded academies** in the colonies
- Here Republican teenagers could imbibe **new civic patriotism** in the kindest curriculum to date—a school of **practical and optimistic** curriculum—now purged of skeptics like **Hume and Berkeley** (who, noted Awakener Witherspoon, "take away the distinction between truth and falsehood")
- Between parents, Republican kids showed a **marked preference for fathers over mothers**
- **Marshall** later confessed that "my father was a greater man than any of his sons"; many others, like **Jefferson**, cultivated a **lifelong preference for male company**
- Historian **Kenneth Lynn** concludes that "certainly in no other period of our past can we find the top leaders of American society speaking as gratefully as these patriots did about the fathering they received."

#### COMING OF AGE
- **"Columbia, Columbia, to Glory Arise!"** urged **Timothy Dwight** to his peers on the eve of revolution
- The oldest (age 32) were just young enough to have **no childhood memories** before the new rage of parental protection and civic fervor
- The youngest (age 8) were just old enough to **join the fight** before it was already decided and reach the age of adulthood by time of **Washington's inauguration**
- Elder Americans had never before seen such **youthful, courageous, and selfless** children modernizing and saving the nation
- **"All gaming, swearing, lying, is grown quite out of fashion,"** intoned a popular ballad in 1779, **"For modern youth's so self-denying, it flies all lawless passion."**
- In war, young
<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## The Awakening Generation (Born 1701-1723)

### Awakeners' Role in Revolutionary Leadership

The **Awakeners** became least understood and most underestimated of American generations. Their spiritual fervor of the Great Awakening directly fueled decades later the political fury of the American Revolution. Historian **Nathan Hatch** argues "few would doubt that the piety of the Awakening was the main source of the civil millennialism of the Revolutionary period."

- Great Awakening credited with 250 new churches and 200,000 conversions (1730-1745)
- "New Side" revivalists averaged age 25; "Old Side" orthodox averaged 59
- More American colonists graduated Harvard in 1730s than any other decade until 1760s
- Awakeners published more Antichrist tracts in 1750s than any pre-Revolutionary decade

### Awakener Women & Social Leadership

- Assumed positions of visibility unprecedented in colonial society
- Religious leaders (Sarah Osborn), Indian missionaries (Moravian "single sisters" in Pennsylvania), planters (Eliza Pinckney with three South Carolina plantations, first American woman to cultivate indigo)
- Entered elderhood as America's leaders at outbreak of Revolution (1774-1776); average age of officeholding in New England towns rose from fifties to low thirties

### Spiritual Community & Resistance

- **John Witherspoon**, president of Princeton College for 26 years, schoolmaster to entire generation: taught Madison, Burr, Marshall, ten future cabinet leaders, sixty future Congress members
- Awakeners created spiritual community where loyalty to God superseded submission to Crown
- Edwards declared America 1740 "inauguration of reign of God on earth"; Franklin fondly recalled Philadelphia change: "It seemed as if all the world were growing religious"

---

## Liberty Generation (Born 1724-1741)

### Formation in Crisis

**Liberty** generation formed reactive to Awakening's intensity. Type: **Reactive**. Born during era of spiritual upheaval, they became—paradoxically—America's most rebellious, war-ravaged, and morally ambiguous generation.

### Youth Experience: Epidemics & Abandonment

- Late 1730s-early 1740s: deadliest child-only epidemic in American history—**great throat distemper** (diphtheria)—killed estimated one-third of all children in New York and New England
- **Liberty children victimized** while parents preoccupied with Great Awakening
- First-wave Liberty kids felt "noble reflective midlife Enlightener dash toward personal autonomy"—parents groomed for holiness and rage authority
- Adolescents crowded into colleges seeking spiritual callings; others became sparking town riots, violence, vicious agents of immorality (Boston press 1734: "new sort of reformers, vulgarly called the mob")

### Coming of Age in War

**Colonies fought** French and Indian War (1754-1760), King George's War (1744-1748). Liberty muscle and guts thrilled to news of armies marching. War meant:
- Freedom from moralizing elders and penny-pinching masters
- Boom wages in ports; glittering prospect of soldiers' bounties, pirate shares, enemy booty

But campaigns wore on—dreams turned to nightmares. Smitten by "privateering fever" ("almost a kind of madness"), thousands enlisted onto French-hunting gunboats. Royal Navy impressment and brutal discipline dragged away many young workers; violent riot response. Young militiamen heard themselves called "dogs" and "British 'Taffaff""; 600-lash whippings became commonplace. War took brutal coming-of-age lesson: what you can grab, keep what's yours, and never trust authority.

### Liberty's Character: Kinetic Physicality

- Most war-ravaged generation of colonial era; casualty rate during French and Indian War exceeded any prior generation
- Drank more alcohol per capita than any other colonial generation (1760-1775)
- Accounted for largest wave of colonial immigration: poor, fierce, English Scots-Irish who embarked Philadelphia, spread south, west, north to frontier
- Five of five Continental Congress delegates accused of British complicity; two most famous military traitors (Benedict Arnold, Benjamin Church); most notorious near-traitors (Ethan Allen); most notorious Tory writers (Hugh Gaine, Samuel Seabury)

### Youthful Rebellion & Identity

> "That such a monster should come from my loins!" declared Landon Carter's profligate gambler son Robert ("Wild Bob") Wormeley

Historian **Michael Kammen** calls Awakening's "awakening of civic consciousness"—now passion for public-spirited clubs and colleges. As printers, Liberty "acted where others talked"—sticking "a father in their caps" (a twig of cloth) to identify themselves in battle. Announced to world: "yes, we are bastards and scoundrels. Leave martyrdom for the Awakeners. For the Liberty, there was no transcendence."

---

## Liberty Generation Lifecycle

### Youth: Neglected, Adrift, Unmoored

During 1730s-1740s, while **William Hogarth** drew pictures of abused London waifs, child-rearing trend in American colonial approach: wholesale neglect. Colonial newspapers noted rising "bastards" turned over to wet-nurses, left free to "run around on their own." First-wave Liberty kids received "noble reflective midlife Enlightener dash toward personal autonomy."

- **Samuel Johnson** pedagogue: "We should think of the children to be persons"
- Most fast-wavers watching younger Awakener parents grope for holiness; rage authority childhood was an awkward by-product of Great Awakening
- Specters of adults crying out in church noted Awakener Charles Chauncy: "Frequently frights the little children, and sets them screaming"
- **Andrew Eliot** condemned them as "evil and adulterous generation"; Franklin advocated **Poor Richard's Almanac** lectures on prudence and thrift

### Rising Adulthood: Colonies Fight France and England

From 1750 on, colonies registered onset of early adulthood with acute measure of social pathology: drinking, gambling, crime, poverty, bankruptcy. After wars during wild and depressed 1760s, only got worse.

- Debtor prisons bulged with young spendthrifts
- Veterans and immigrants raised havoc on frontier against Indians
- Under cider Pontiac, some white settlers punished; others parted for beyond their means, doubling colonial debt to Britain
- Towns cut relief payments to burgeoning numbers of young poor
- Enlightened Colden complained: "They play away," lamenting Awakener Landon Carroll of younger "Virginians who preferred 'bewitching diversions'" to "solid improvements"
- **Stamp Acts of 1765**: Liberty's anti-British agitation increased

### Midlife: Architects of Revolution

When **Continental Congress** crowded up to sign Declaration of Independence, fiftyish (and very corrupt) **Benjamin Harrison** elbowed a (thin) younger delegate. When signers hanged, Harrison quipped: "I shall have all the advantage over you. For it will be over in a minute, but you will be kicking in the air half an hour after I am gone!"

- For Liberty, entering midlife, Revolution was a mostly practical and defensive goal: prevent "tyranny" and protect individual "liberties"
- Unlike juniors, they had families and reputations at stake and less inclination to look forward
- Never lost their practical and defensive goal: to prevent "tyranny" and protect individual "liberties"

### Elderhood: Wisdom Through Pragmatism

By 1788, Liberty midlife leaders statistically more likely what historian **Jackson Turner Main** defines political "idealists" (less educated, more suspicious of ideas and large institutions) than either juniors or elders.

- When Continental Congress crowded signing Declaration, 50-year-old Benjamin Harrison elbowed younger delegate; later his quip: "I shall have all advantage over you...you will be kicking in air half hour after I am gone"
- **Patrick Henry**: "Give me liberty or give me death!" (1775)—invoked one word intoxicating his generation from childhood to leave-me-alone old age; sang **American Liberty Song** by John Dickinson, **Massachusetts Song of Liberty** by Mercy Warren, **My Days Have Been So Wondrous Free** by Francis Hopkinson

---

## Republican Generation (Born 1742-1766)

### Formation: Civic Birth During Revolution

**Republican** generation formed Civic type, born as colonies performed deeds of collective virtue. Type: **Civic**. Born during American Revolution Crisis in rising adulthood, Republicans would transform generation marked by transcendent promise into lifebuilders and rationalists—single-minded creators of what they called "energy in government," "order and harmony" in society, "tranquility" of mind, "usefulness and reason" in science, "abundance" in commerce.

### Youth: Protected Watchfulness Under Midlife Awakeners

As protected colonial children in 1750s and 1760s, Republicans grew up under visionary tutelage of **midlife Awakeners**, who saw in them future of "republican" virtue. Rising adults during decades of crisis, they fulfilled their special mission, winning independence and establishing political and social order.

- By 1776: "The ring would sing of us a thousand years to come"—**Song New York patriot recital** (1776)
- Never lost collegiate discipline; practiced by instinct, but self-immersion found incomprehensible
- Jefferson and Madison—architects of Constitutionalism; Pinckney, Timothy Pickering—political and philosophical visionaries; **Benjamin Latrobe** and **Pierre Charles L'Enfant**—organizers of knowledge like Benjamin Rush and Noah Webster; inventors of steamships and national industry like Robert Fulton and Eli Whitney

> All their lives, word "republican" (from Latin *res publici*, literally "the public thing") was central to collective self-image and life purpose

- **Republican** meant classical vision of secular order—not just form of government or radical aggregates in France, nor even party label chosen by three Virginia Presidents
- For generation: "republican" meant classical vision of secular order—entire approach to social life with which they so thoroughly reconstructed America that could now still live in their civic shade

### Statesmen & Builders

Republicans proved fabled generation of statesmen: **Thomas Jefferson**, **James Madison**, **James Monroe**, **Alexander Hamilton**, **John Jay**, **Albert Gallatin**, **Robert Livingston**, **John Marshall**, **Gouverneur Morris**, **James Wilson**, **Charles Pinckney**, **Timothy Pickering**.

No generation since Glorious Awakening attained public renown so early: **Hamilton** (famous political pamphleteer age 17), **Henry Knox** (artillery commander age 25), **George Rogers Clark** (wilderness Napoleon age 27), **Jefferson** (author of Declaration age 33).

Through midlife and old age during War of 1812, challenged by spiritual youth unable to control Promethean energy, Republican elite felt frustration and ultimately despair. Fearing their massive worldly accomplishments might not survive and emotional culture their children.

### Political Philosophy & Vision

- Republicans saw themselves as **tireless reasoners and builders**, chosen by history to wrest order from chaos
- First famous statesmen (Jefferson) won equal fame as scientist and architect
- Most famous legislator (Madison) hailed as "the master-builder of the Constitution"
- Two "geniuses" of public finance: **Gallatin** likened himself to "laboring oar" for American prosperity; **Hamilton** deemed "the habit of labor in people" to be "conducive to welfare of state"
- Barlow proudly authored **The Canal**, subtitled "A Poem on Application of Physical Science to Political Economy," predicting "science" would "rise, improve, and harmonize mankind"
- Projecting personality into age of republicanism—Thorough Jeffersonianism thought: republicanism worshipped "Creator" or "Supreme Being"—God of Reason deliberately chosen spirituality
- Jeffersonian God: not Omnipotent Sovereign of Puritans nor Omnipresent Essence of Transcendentalists, but essentially **Architect and Builder**

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## COMPROMISE GENERATION (Born 1767-1791)

**Type:** Adaptive

### Generational Profile
- Born during American Revolution Crisis (youth), Transcendental Awakening (midlife), Civil War Crisis (elderhood)
- Total population: 4,200,000 | 10% immigrant, 15% slave
- Sample members: **Denmark Vesey** (1767-1822), **Tecumseh** (1768-1813), **Dolley Madison** (1768-1849), **DeWitt Clinton** (1769-1828), **John Randolph of Roanoke** (1773-1833), **Meriwether Lewis** (1774-1809), **Francis Cabot Lowell** (1775-1817), **Roger Taney** (1777-1864), **Henry Clay** (1777-1852), **William Ellery Channing** (1780-1842), **Daniel Webster** (1782-1852), **John C. Calhoun** (1782-1850), **Washington Irving** (1783-1859), **John Audubon** (1785-1851), **Davy Crockett** (1786-1836), **Winfield Scott** (1786-1866), **Emma Willard** (1787-1870), **Sarah Hale** (1788-1879), **James Fenimore Cooper** (1789-1851), **Samuel F. B. Morse** (1791-1872)
- Typical grandparents: Awakening | Parents: Liberty and Republican | Children: Transcendental and Gilded | Grandchildren: Progressive
- U.S. Presidents: **Andrew Jackson** (1845-1829), **John Quincy Adams** (1825-1829), **William Henry Harrison** (1841), **Martin Van Buren** (1837-1841), **Zachary Taylor** (1849-1850), **John Tyler** (1841-1845), **James Polk** (1845-1849), **Millard Fillmore** (1850-1853), **James Buchanan** (1857-1861)

### Youth: "Rocked in the Cradle of the Revolution"
- **Clay's phrase** captured most peers' experience—witnessed worst mob and wartime violence
- First-wavers saw extreme violence: **Andrew Jackson** (age 12) beaten and jailed by British after watching mother die; **William Henry Harrison** (age 8) watched Benedict Arnold's redcoats use his father's cattle for target practice
- Last-wavers grew up seeing less violence but sensing comparable adult anxiety during 1780s turmoil and hysteria over French Revolution (early 1790s)
- Surrounded by political and economic crisis while protective midlife **Liberty Generation** and buoyant rising-adult **Republicans** pulled in boundaries of family life
- **Parental pressure** urged widening sex-role divisions—hastily rewritten textbooks taught girls to revere mythic grandeur of **"Founding Fathers"**; teachers strictly monitored classrooms to prevent unruly behavior
- Republican educators insisted first generation of "national children" be "molded" into serviceable, obedient patriots
- Aspiring elite studied hard at newly disciplined colleges, worried about "sober deportment," looked forward to brighter times

### Coming of Age: Seamless Transition
- Passage into adulthood smooth and seamless—"indeed in the full tide of successful enterprise"
- Recalled **John Randolph's** rising optimism and conformism of Jefferson and Madison Presidencies
- **Shunning risk**, elders like **John Adams** wrote of duty to remain peaceable and silent—an essay that won **Webster** an ambassadorship
- Webster observed college chums "balancing," easing unobtrusively into adult world; **single women** worried about being dismissed as "old maids" at age 25, yet understood (like **Eliza Southgate**) that "reputation undoubtedly is of great importance to all, but to a female 'tis everything—once lost 'tis forever lost"
- Single men obeyed the law—after 1790, youth-driven mob violence that coursed through colonial history since 1730s suddenly abated
- Even when defying authority, young Compromisers chose rebellions with care
- Fledgling authors (men and women) indulged in syrupy romanticism, teasing Republicans with feeling
- College teachers like **Lyman Beecher** challenged secularism with earnestly respectful religious movements
- Backwoods lawyers like **Clay** and **Jackson** urged Appalachians in rowdy adventure, yet felt like Cavalric querors rather than mischievous "settlers" on Republican land grids
- Courtships awkwardly sentimental—**Webster's** biographer: "better at writing poetry than making love"—but unlike elders at like age, Compromisers **expected** emotion to resemble poetry
- Men compensated for absentee fathers by flamboyant gestures of dominance toward women, slaves, Indians—and by dueling
- Few months after **Clay** and **Randolph** missed each other at chivalric ten paces, Clay gushed (upon hearing of friend's duel): "We live in an age of romance!"

### Rising Adulthood: "Age of Improvement"
- **Webster** urged: "Let our age be the age of improvement"—in 1790s, twentyish first-wavers embarked on prosperous careers during America's first export boom
- Around 1820, thirtiyish late-wavers joined rage of canal-building and cloth manufacture in north, or migrated to southwestern frontier for cotton fortunes
- Behind easy affluence lurked personal unease—like **William Wirt**, Compromisers masters assumed "to assume the exterior of composure and self-collectedness, whatever riot and confusion may be within"
- They knew destiny held doubtful future—despite rousing victories (New Orleans) and stirring words (*The Star-Spangled Banner*) during War of 1812, these young men realized this "Second War for Independence" hardly compared with the first
- Where their elders had founded an "Empire of Liberty" and "stood" for office as citizen-statesmen, Compromisers talked of an "American System" and "ran" for office as political professionals
- Thirtiyish women could not replay young heroine role of mothers; instead embraced new romantic "cult of true womanhood"—emphasizing innocence, femininity, and domestic virtue
- Both men and women felt growing tension between duty and feeling, between proper division of social labor and subversive emotions for gender fulfillment
- **Felt an ambivalence they knew had never bothered their parents**

### Midlife: Adaptive Antennae and Fragmented Consensus
- During 1820s, as aging Republican executives passed out of power and Transcendental Awakening erupted, midlife Compromisers turned adaptive antennae from elders to juniors
- Struck by **Washington Irving's** belief that "ours is a government of compromise," yet swayed by Tocqueville's "faith in public opinion," they tried to overcome youthful caution by taking greater risks
- In three Presidential elections (1824, 1828, 1832)—the crude Adams, the swaggering Jackson, and the calculating Van Buren—accurately reflect the fragmenting jigsaw of their "post-heroic" midlife personality
- By late 1830s, Compromiser leaders vied to outpoisture each other with youth-oriented rhetoric of populism and reform
- Even the Whigs, hyping "log cabin and cider" and their Alamo martyr **Davy Crockett**, learned to spar with the Democrats at their own game
- Public debate fixated on process and gesture—what despairing **Cooper** called "petty personal wranglers" and "intellectual duellists"
- During 1820s, southern Compromisers founded dozens of antislavery societies, but hopes for gradual emancipation soon dashed by polarizing rhetoric of rising Transcendentals
- By late 1830s, all of these southern societies disbanded
- Younger **Emerson** began assailing "the timid, imitative, and tame" Compromiser leadership; **Thaddeus Stevens** came to scorn their "mercenary, driveling" congressmen, eager "to conciliate Southern treason"
- As America entered 1850s, remarks historian **Samuel Eliot Morison**, "there seemed nobody left to lead the nation but weak, two-faced trimmers and angry young men"
- Meanwhile, society raced toward urbanization and westward expansion; American family shifted toward child-raising norms, budding feminism, and disturbingly wild new batch of (Gilded) children
- **Sarah Hale** (who had written "Mary Had a Little Lamb" as young widow) joined midlife peers like **Lydia Sigourney** and **Emma Willard** in denouncing men's "cruelty" to women, "to which every female heart must revolt"

### Elderhood: Torn Between Fanaticism and Discipline
- Torn between congealing fanaticism of the young and guilty memories of Republican discipline, Compromisers entered elderhood watching America drift toward painful outcomes: Indian removal, anti-immigrant riots, lawless frontiers, slave chases, sectional hatred
- As they struggled to remain accommodating, leaders shied away from venerable titles once accorded to old Republicans—preferred bummer nicknames: "Old Hickory" (Jackson), "Old Fuss and Feathers" (Scott), "Old Rough and Ready" (Taylor), "Old Prince" (Clay), "Old Man Eloquent" (Adams)
- Sensing tragedy approach, feared final judgment of history
- **Clay** despaired how his generation might "ignobly die" with "the scorn and contempt of mankind; unpitied, unwept, and unremembered"
- Their fate came to mediate contempt of next-juniors
- Later, seventyish "Old Buck" **Buchanan**, **John Tyler**, **Crittenden**, and **Roger Taney** resisted fruitless efforts to defer or ignore rush to war
- **General Winfield Scott** wrote white-hatred advice to younger leaders who no longer cared for advice of 1812 war heroes
- Dying in eve of crisis, the aging **Buchanan** blamed Civil War on both "the fanatics of the North" and "the fanatics of the South"
- Like **Hone** and **Buchanan**, most Compromisers died lamenting both sides, just as they had lived trying to accommodate both sides

### Legacy and Historical Assessment
- Compromiser eulogies full of mixed phrasing—one scholar said of **Webster**: "With all the greatness and smallness, with all the praise and blame..."
- Ever since, historians unable to decide whether **Jackson** was force for pettiness or progress, or whether **Clay-Webster-Calhoun "Great Triumvirate"** moderated or worsened ultimate ferocity of Civil War
- Behind so many of this generation's favorite schemes—terraforming, recolonizing Africa, granting sovereignty to territories—was faith in fair play and pluralism
- Unlike next-elders, Compromisers realized the authority of social discipline could no longer be taken for granted; unlike next-juniors, refrained from forcing own judgments on others
- From perspective of subsequent events, choices can easily be criticized—but we often forget how few alternatives were open given their own instinctive caution and zeal/lawlessness of younger Americans
- **Some choices may have averted worse outcomes:** Had Compromiser leaders not compelled eastern Indians to migrate west, even their humanitarian peers conceded tribes would soon have been wiped out by land-hungry whites
- Other choices may have come closer to success than we realize—until youth anger and rabid sectionalism broke out in 1830s, Compromiser plans for gradual abolition of slavery seemed perfectly feasible (similar plans had worked earlier in several northern states and were being seriously discussed in Virginia)
- Such is the painful, might-have-been legacy of a kind but confused generation sandwiched between two others of extraordinary power
- The Compromisers inherited grandeur and tried to perfect it by adding humor, sensitivity, expertise, and fairness
- **They passed away fearing they had failed to preserve, much less perfect, the achievements of their forefathers**
- **No American generation ever had a sadder departure**

---

## Chapter 9: THE CIVIL WAR CYCLE

### Bull Run: The Opening Battle (July 1861)
- "There is nothing like it on this side of the infernal region," recalled war veteran of "rebel yells" that screeched over hills above Bull Run Creek near Manassas, Virginia
- Among 18,000 Union soldiers (mostly in their twenties—the "peculiar exuberance" of this sound triggered panic and retreat)
- But delighted another 18,000 Confederate soldiers—including plucky 37-year-old brigadier general **Thomas "Stonewall" Jackson**
- For them, yell seemed to herald rapid victory; attendance riveted on battle many believed would decide war in single day
- From Richmond, 53-year-old **Jefferson Davis** eyes forward to triumph of his new "Nation under God"
- In Washington, 52-year-old **Abraham Lincoln** warned Union not to despair over "Black Monday" and hurriedly signed bill enlisting 500,000 more soldiers
- Fiftyish congressmen who journeyed to Manassas as spectators climbed out of carriages and commanded fleeing young bluecoats to return to battle
- "We called them cowards, denounced them in most offensive terms, put out our heavy revolvers, and threatened to shoot them, but all in vain," explained Ohio Congressman **Albert Riddle**
- "No man ever saw such mass of greatly cowardly men"
- That night, in Augusta, Georgia, 4-year-old **Woodrow Wilson** joined parents in praying for Confederacy—while in house on West 20th Street, New York City, 2-year-old **Theodore Roosevelt** did likewise for other side

### The Civil War Cycle's Cast
- In aftermath of Bull Run, 75-year-old **Winfield Scott** would retire as commander of Union forces, his Anaconda Plan now in total disrepute, along with Crittenden Compromise and all other conciliatory measures suggested by Scott's aging generation
- In summer of 1861, the Compromisers had no senators, one governor, and only two congressmen in office—a historic nadir for political influence of Americans in their seventies
- **The age climax of CIVIL WAR CYCLE would be drama not of four generations, but three:**

1. **Lincoln's TRANSCENDENTAL GENERATION** (Idealist, then age 40 to 69)
   - Had, in their twenties, provided the original core of 1830s-era evangelical and abolitionist movements
   - Ever since, extremism of **William Lloyd Garrison**, stridency of young plantation owners, and memory of **Nat Turner's** violent slave rebellion had ramped up any Compromiser hope of peacefully weaning South from slavery
   - Now in their fifties, this generation of Massachusetts "Black Republicans" and South Carolina "Fire Eaters" was fully prepared to shed younger blood to attain what they knew was right
   - Preaching from pulpits and railing from Congress, peers of **John Brown**, **Harriet "Moses" Tubman**, **Julia Ward Howe**, **Alexander Stephens**, and **Robert E. Lee** looked to war for what New Englanders heralded as "the glory of the coming of the Lord" and Virginians baptism of blood for their newborn confederacy
   - "The hand of God was felt in Richmond no less than in Washington"—and, over next four years, these two capitals of "His Truth" would be bisected by hundred-mile-wide scar of mud and blood
   - All their lives, Transcendentals were generation others feared but followed—until their apocalyptic ending—as they watched Reconstruction disintegrate and other principled causes fall into scorn, many would look back on Bull Run as moment their ideals began self-destructing

2. **Stonewall Jackson's GILDED GENERATION** (Reactive, age 19 to 39)
   - Comprised the "ghastly wretches" Congressman **Riddle** saw scrambling away across Bull Run Creek
   - They had signed up for war they expected would be quick adventure, with maybe little glory and profit mixed in—not much different from California gold fields to which many had rushed as teenagers
   - Most expected their sheer energy and derring-do (that "Always mystify, mislead, and surprise the enemy," advised Jackson) would end war quickly and let them get on with life's practical challenges
   - For Gilded whites, any resolution at all to thundering hatred between elder abolitionists and elder "Southrons" would at last allow them to settle western frontier
   - For Gilded blacks, including slaves on "underground railroad," Bull Run marked necessary first step (albeit tactical setback) toward flesh-and-blood freedom
   - But as war settled into its meaner, later years, jaunty opinion of this generation would sour
   - The scrappy adventurers whom **Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr.** saw as "touched with fire" in their youth would later turn bitterly cynical about passionate crusades
   - Same 25-year-olds who had shrieked (or heard) rebel yell would, much later in sixties, remember Bull Run—and Antietam, Gettysburg, and Atlanta—and warn young against horrors of war
   - Few would listen

3. **Wilson's PROGRESSIVE GENERATION** (Adaptive, age 2 to 18)
   - News of Bull Run signaled beginning of ordeal to pass over their childhood like dark and cruel cloud
   - Would not see daylight again until 1865, when **Abraham Lincoln's** funeral train journeyed from Washington through New York to Illinois
   - Black-creped cortege would be seen by astonishing seven million Americans, nearly one-fifth population of entire reunited nation
   - Witnessing first-hand, youngest in this most fatherless of American generations would sit hoisted on mother's shoulder and hear suffering elders had endured to provide children with better future
   - Eldest would help out in war effort: teenage **Thomas Edison** stringing telegraph wires; Sergeant **William McKinley** serving hot meals to troops at Antietam
   - Later, they would pass from smothered youth to conformist young adulthood, concentrating on smallish tasks in society where great things were built (or said) by others
   - Emancipated young, black Progressives like **Booker T. Washington** would reach midlife disciplined to provoke white society that, over four bloody years commenced with Bull Run, had shown it capable of organized butchery

### The Civil War Cycle's Origin and Structure
- In Civil War, midlife Transcendentals wrote script and dominated events; rising-adult Gilded did thankless dirty work; and child Progressives watched and worried
- All three suffered wreckage and became inhabitants of America's only three-cycle-era—the one whose crisis era occurred too soon, too hard, and with too much ghastly devastation
- **This cycle is no aberration**—rather, it demonstrates how events can turn out badly—and, from generational perspective, what happens when they do
- Civil War Cycle had origin when failed Presidential bid of **Andrew Jackson** in 1824 fired fresh mood of radicalism among coming-of-age Transcendentals—an accelerating enthusiasm over spiritual conversion, social reform, "Manifest Destiny," abolitionism, and utopian communalism
- Cycle extended through pitched battles of Civil War and came to inglorious end with conformism and spiritual decline of "Gilded Age" of 1870s and 1880s
- Climaxing in tragedy, cycle failed to produce Civic-type generation
- After swiftly elbowing aside Transcendental leadership in years following war, Reactive Gilded transformed in midlife from recessive to dominant generation, assuming some of traits (secularism, conformism, lengthy political tenure, and indulgent style of child nurture) associated with

### The Transcendental Awakening (1822-1837)
- Triggered by evangelical preaching of **Charles Finney** and widespread excitement over religious conversion, social reform, and radical idealism
- Often merging with popular "Jacksonian" movement, it peaked with birth of women's rebellion, founding of abolitionist societies, and rise of labor parties and new religious sects
- After giving birth to "transcendentalist" school of philosophy and literature, the religious fervor subsided along with collapse of Jacksonian prosperity in 1837
- "The great years of the new revivalism were 1825 to 1837," notes historian **Edward Pessen**
- Steeped in new emerging radical call for Christian perfection, rising adults afterward took this agenda with them as they aged into midlife leaders of Civil War

**AGE LOCATION IN HISTORY:** Republicans in elderhood; Compromisers in midlife; Transcendentals in rising adulthood; Gilded in youth

### The Civil War Crisis (1857-1865)
- "The Second American Revolution" according to **Charles and Mary Beard**
- Began in 1857, year of Buchanan's inauguration, the "Bleeding Kansas" debates, and **Dred Scott** decision
- Crisis extended through war itself and ended with **General Robert E. Lee's** surrender at Appomattox (on Palm Sunday) and assassination of President Lincoln (five days later, on Good Friday)
- Graying preachers retired in religious symbolism
- But unlike other crisis eras, denouement of Civil War produced less optimism than sense of tragedy having run its course
- At the end of 1860s, a disillusioned "bloody shirt" generation of generals, officers, and older soldiers surged into political office—a position of power they would hold (but exercise cautiously) for very long time
- Meanwhile, coming-of-age generation—traumatized, not energized, by most destructive military conflagration yet witnessed in world history—meekly avoided asserting itself in public life

**AGE LOCATION IN HISTORY:** Compromisers in elderhood; Transcendentals in midlife; Gilded in rising adulthood; Progressive in youth

---

## TRANSCENDENTAL GENERATION (Born 1792-1821)

**Type:** Idealist

### Generational Profile
- Born during Transcendental Awakening (rising adulthood), Civil War Crisis (midlife)
- Total population: 11,000,000 | 20% immigrant, 13% slave
- Sample members: **Thaddeus Stevens** (1792-1868), **Dred Scott** (1795-1858), **Sojourner Truth** (1797-1883), **John Brown** (1800-1859), **Nat Turner** (1800-1831), **Brigham Young** (1801-1877), **Ralph Waldo Emerson** (1803-1882), **William Lloyd Garrison** (1805-1879), **Robert E. Lee** (1807-1870), **Henry W. Longfellow** (1807-1882), **Jefferson Davis** (1808-1889), **Edgar Allan Poe** (1809-1849), **John Frémont** (1813-1890), **Elizabeth Cady Stanton** (1815-1902), **Frederick Douglass** (1817-1895), **Henry David Thoreau** (1817-1862), **Harriet Tubman** (1820-1913), **William Tecumseh Sherman** (1820-1891), **Susan B. Anthony** (1820-1906), **Mary Baker Eddy** (1821-1910)
- Typical grandparents: Liberty | Parents: Republican and Compromise | Children: Gilded and Progressive | Grandchildren: Missionary
- U.S. Presidents: **James Polk** (1845-1849), **Millard Fillmore** (1850-1853), **Franklin Pierce** (1853-1857), **Andrew Johnson** (1865-1869), **Abraham Lincoln** (1861-1865)

### Youth: "Born with Knives in Their Brain"
- **Ralph Waldo Emerson** recalled his youthful peers in 1830s as assortment of "madmen, madwomen, men with beards, Dunkers, Muggletonians, Come-Outers, Groaners, Agrarians, Seventh-Day Baptists"—utopians and sectarians of all stripe
- Whom **Edgar Allan Poe** mockingly labeled "Frogpondium"
- They looked the part: "anti-corset" women wearing mannish "Bloomers" and their young men at Brook Farm (to quote fellow communard) wearing "their hair parted in middle and falling upon their shoulders, and clad in a garment such as no human being ever wore before"
- **Nathaniel Hawthorne** nostalgically looked back on Brook Farm as "our exploded scheme for beginning the life of Paradise anew" and on **Emerson's** Concord as "a variety of queer, strangely dressed, oddly behaved mortals, most of whom took upon themselves to be important agents of the world's destiny"
- Early in life, they deemed themselves agents of the world's *inner* destiny
- Only later did men and women of this TRANSCENDENTAL GENERATION project their zeal onto outer world and lead America toward the Last Judgment
- In thirties, **Emerson** wrote, "Beware when the great God lets loose a thinker on this planet"
- In fifties, greeted bombardment of Fort Sumter by confessing final battle had been won, every obstacle surmounted which "shatters everything flimsy and shifty, sets aside all false issues... Let it search, let it grind, let it overturn"

### Coming of Age: Erupting Against Cultural Sterility
- As post-crisis babies, Transcendentals took first breath in welcoming new era of peace and optimism
- As indulged children, assured by midlife Republican hero-leaders that every conflict had been won, every obstacle surmounted
- But coming of age, these youngsters erupted in fury against cultural sterility of father-built world able to produce
- **Emerson** charged (in 1820) "not a book, not a speech, a conversation, or a thought worth noticing"
- They preached feeling over reason, community over society, inner perfection over outer conformity, moral transcendence over material improvement
- The outburst defined Transcendentals as generation
- First-wavers just learning to talk when dutiful Republican fathers crushing Whiskey Rebels, age 9 at Jefferson's first inauguration, and barely 30 when initial clamor over revival and reform broke out during twilight Monroe years
- Last-wavers came of age just in time to join furor before it receded in late 1830s
- First wave and last, they afterward embarked on self-immersed voyages—starting families and careers while founding communes, joining sects, dabbling in odd lifestyles, probing soul with art

### Rising Adulthood and Midlife: The "Irrepressible Conflict"
- In 1850s, Transcendentals emerged again into public life, this time as midlife champions on both sides of what **William Seward** called their "irrepressible conflict"
- Surmounting impossible political battle, presided as leaders over four years of total war, which only ended when **William Tecumseh Sherman** vowed to punish Confederacy to its "uttermost recesses" and sixtyish Radicals like **Thaddeus Stevens** demanded postwar "reconstruction" of southern soul
- From **Stevens** to **Lincoln**, **Whitman** to **Poe**, **Garrison** to the **Blackwell sisters**, Transcendentals grew up notoriously estranged from their fathers
- Many warred, like **Emerson**, of "the terrible judgments of an incensed God" that "will complete the catastrophe of Republican America"; or proclaimed, like **Emerson**, that "men are what their mothers made them"; or condemned, like **Thoreau** (whose mother brought home-cooked meals to him at Walden pond), "the mouldering ruins of our ancestors"
- "Our fathers did so,' says someone. 'What of that?' say we," wrote **Theodore Parker**, described by friend as "a man of Nature who abominates the steam-engine and the factory"
- But if young Transcendentals often joined Compromisers in sniping attacks on Republican social discipline, they reached midlife without their next-elders' instinctive caution toward youth
- "Compromise!" wrote **William Herndon** on eve of war. "Why I am sick at the very idea"

### The Inner Truth and Moral Conviction
- Whether Abolitionists, "Southrons," Mormons, or Anti-Masons, they agreed that each person must act on inner truth that transcends sensory world
- A credo immortalized by **Emerson** in 1842 as "Transcendentalism" and praised by **Oliver Wendell Holmes** as "our intellectual Declaration of Independence"
- Unlike their elders, Southern "fire-eaters" like **Robert Barnwell Rhett** and **William Yancey** refused to apologize for slavery, but instead found virtue in aggressive empire of chivalry and bondage
- Meanwhile, northerners like **Seward** declared abolition of slavery to be "a higher law" than their father-drafted Constitution, and **Garrison** condemned half-slave Union as "a covenant with death, an agreement with hell"
- Neither side questioned that God was on its side
- While axe-wielding visionaries like **John Brown** and **Nat Turner** sacrificed what **Herman Melville** heralded as their "meteor of war," **Harriet Beecher Stowe** demanded that "wrath of Almighty God" descend on America, a day that "shall burn like an oven"

### Historical Assessment
- Throughout most of nineteenth century, all Americans ridiculed, respected, or feared whatever age bracket Transcendentals occupied as moving repository of inner-driven passion and unbreakable principle
- In 1820s,
<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## The Transcendental Lifecycle (continued)

### The Transcendental Generation - Political Peak and Decline

- **Civil War years**: Transcendentals enjoyed greatest one-generation political hegemony in American history (90% share of governors and Congress in 1860), ending with largest generational rout in 1868 election (Transcendental share plunged from 63 to 44 percent)
- Period 1865-1869 marked steepest-ever decline in one generation's share of national leadership
- Final political impact: Lincoln summoned whole generation to "die a violent death," elevated to sainthood by peers after assassination
- **Mary Baker Eddy** declared "God is Mind, and God is infinite; hence all is mind"
- **William Lloyd Garrison** urged war to bring mankind "under the dominion of God, the control of an inward spirit, the government of the law of love"
- Born to heroic parents, indulged as children, fiery as youths, narcissistic as rising adults, values-fixated entering midlife—ultimately chose technology and passion to achieve maximum apocalypse

---

## Gilded Generation (Born 1822-1842)

**Type:** Reactive

### Age Location
- **Youth**: Transcendental Awakening
- **Rising adulthood**: Civil War Crisis
- **Midlife**: Missionary Awakening in elderhood

### Overview and Character

> "The *only* population of the kind that the world has ever seen" — **Mark Twain** on Gold Rush 49ers

- Description: "all striplings, bright, brainful of push and energy," "young Davids, brimful of push and energy"
- **California sudden-riches disease**: Eight in ten between age 10 and 30, making pre-1850 San Francisco most monogenerational city ever in America
- Most anarchic generation with no respect for justice enforced by hangings
- Western territories prompted **Horace Mann** to ask despairingly: "are we not colonized by men like the pilgrim fathers?"
- Eastern cities: unsupervised youths shocked elders, organizing first urban gangs (**Roach Guards**, better-known kids whom Van Wyck Brooks called *la jeunesse dorée* of 1840s)
- Life story: making best of dangerous world, getting damned for it

### The Gilded Lifecycle - Most Luckless in American History

**YOUTH**:
- First-wavers shared euphoria of Transcendental Awakening as children but felt its damage growing up
- Last-wavers grew up to maximize risk of death/maiming in Civil War
- Came of age in era of economic swings, floodtide immigration, darkening national mood
- Bore human burden of Transcendental conscience, becoming what **Henry Adams** described as "generation...stirred up from its lowest layers"
- **Daniel Boorstin**: "the Go-Getters" of late 1860s, thirtyish buccaneers who saw Union armies camp on Brook Farm

**After Appomattox:**
> "The young men were scattering in all directions. Their imagination was caught by the West, and scores who might have been writers in the day of *The Dial* were seeking their fortunes in railroads, mines, and oil wells" — **Van Wyck Brooks**

- **Blaine's remark** (noted by **Richard Hofstadter**): "might have been the motto of a whole generation of Americans who wanted things dreadfully, and took them"

**COMING OF AGE**:
- Inherited physical/emotional wreckage from elders
- Entered midlife and reassembled pieces—their own way
- Muscled into political power, repudiated elders' high-flown dreams
- Launched dynamo of no-holds-barred economic progress to match pragmatic mood
- Reached cusp of old age during 1890s, unlucky moment again when rapidly growing elderly landed in Americans begat scrap heap
- **Roscoe Conkling** (most indicators—wealth, higher education, lifespan—the Gilded fared worse at each phase than next-elders or next-juniors): sacrificial one-generation backstop in lifecycle of progress
- Took cue from laissez-faire guru **William Graham Sumner**: "root, hog, or die"

**Throughout lifecycle**, Gilded inundated by torrents of critical abuse:
- Before Civil War, midlife Transcendentals like **Horace Mann** charged: "most men of eleven they could not read," **George Templeton Strong** saw "so much gross dissipation redeemed by so little culture"
- Later, **Walt Whitman** complained of "highly deceptive superficial intellectuality," and **Longfellow** accused generation of taking America "back to the common level, with a hoarse death-rattle in its throat"
- **Henry James**: "A younger Progressive...accused [his] own bright hard medal...of being somebody's right and ease and the other somebody's pain and wrong"
- By 1890s, righteous reformers of still younger (Missionary) generation rediscovered old Transcendental theme of Gilded soullessness

**Critical consensus:**
- **Charles Beard**: despised "cash nexus"
- **Ralph Adams Cram**: "mammonism"
- **Vernon Parrington**: "triumphant and unabashed vulgarity without its like in our history"
- **Samuel Eliot Morison**: "When the gilt wore off, one found only base brass"
- **Charles Dudley Warner** ("Deadly Warning") published satirical book *The Gilded Age* with **Mark Twain** (title perfectly described generation of metal and muscle)

### Demographics and Facts

- **Total number**: 17,000,000
- **Percent immigrant**: 28%
- **Percent slave**: 10%
- **Family structure**: Typical grandparents Republican; Parents: Compromise and Transcendental; Children: Progressive and Missionary; Typical grandchildren: Lost

**Key characteristics:**
- More likely to die or fall into destitution than parents at like age
- More likely to make fortune starting from nothing
- Larger share from lower-/middle-class backgrounds than any earlier/later generation
- Included **Andrew Carnegie, John D. Rockefeller, Jay Gould, James J. Hill, Leland Stanford, Charles Crocker**

**Immigration:**
- Largest immigrant share (28%) of any American generation since colonial times
- First large influx of Irish Catholics (triggered by 1840s potato famine)
- First Chinese (hired as laborers for Union Pacific Railroad)

**Physical characteristics:**
- Suffered worsening nutrition as children
- Adult height declined from first cohort to last
- Later in life, obesity became generational obsession
- Included America's best-known carnivores: **Al Packer** and **Donner Party** survivors; Texas-to-Abilene cattle drivers; first large-scale meat-packers (**Gustavus Swift, Philip Armour**)
- Midlife beneficiaries of plunging beef prices
- Aging Gilded celebrated rotund body and Delmonico steak dinner as mark of success
- 1907: U.S. life expectancy at age 65 declined to shortest span ever measured (under 11.5 years)

**Cultural/lifestyle image:**
- Defined today's image of western adventurer: youthful 49er and Pony Express rider through Civil War, to midlife rancher, cowboy, "bad man," and Indian fighter of 1870s, to grizzled old mountaineer of 1900

**African Americans:**
- Gilded blacks include first large population of American mulattoes (many presumably children of white Compromiser fathers)
- Slave generation that suffered most at hands of white owners; increasingly fearful of rebellion
- Most celebrated 1850s-era slave fugitives
- During Civil War: soldiers and officers of first black regiments in North America
- Reconstruction years: fifteen Gilded blacks elected to Congress (greater number than from any later generation until Silent)

**War impact:**
- Hit Gilded harder than any other American generation
- First American youths subject to conscription—and first to bloodiest antidraft riots in American history
- Of seven million Gilded men who reached combat age, roughly 10% died in Civil War; one in fifteen in Union states, nearly one in four in Confederate states
- 5% ended war in disease-ridden prisoner-of-war camps
- Cumulative Civil War battle deaths exceeded total for all other American wars—per capita casualty rate equal to eight World War IIs combined
- Nearly half Gilded war dead buried in unmarked graves

**Politics:**
- In 1868 generational landslide election, median age of governors in nine core Confederate states fell from 62 to 37
- Most postwar carpetbaggers and scalawags were Gilded
- As "Victorian" stewards of late-nineteenth-century American economy: set unmatched record for prudence and thrift
- From late 1850s to late 1890s, gross capital formation more than doubled as share of GNP; wholesale price index declined by one-third
- 1866-1893: Gilded leaders sustained twenty-eight consecutive federal surpluses—reducing national debt by one-third, making theirs the only generation in American history to leave behind smaller federal debt than inherited

### The Gilded Lifecycle Details

**YOUTH**: "Children are commercial before they get out of their petticoats" — **David MacRae**

- Little choice in childhood: some casual offspring of experimental communities; others hungry arrivals by boat
- Nearly all looking at unmerciful indifference, self-absorbed rising adults
- Understood early they had better take care of themselves
- Parents complained of toughness, lawmakers decried "street orphans" who mixed huckstering with crime
- 1849 New York police chief condemned "idle and vicious children of both sexes, who infest our public thoroughfares"
- One observer: "*Dangerous Classes of New York*: friendless and homeless...No one cares for them, and they care for no one"
- Gilded youths steered clear of adults, practiced what many parents referred to (favorably) as "self-dependence"
- **Louisa May Alcott** (like utopian reformer in Emerson's circle): "a man up on a balloon...secretly resolved to give the world a shake a living out of her"
- In 1830s, farmers' sons grabbing get-rich manuals, bolting from homes and schools at ever-earlier ages
- 1840s-1850s: college attendance sank; those who arrived kept fortyish reformers at bay
- When Garrison and Longfellow came to speak, teachers ordered to pray; students responded with "deliberate absenteeism, indifference, disrespect, by ogling female visitors, the writing of obscene doggerel on flyleaves of hymnals, by expectorating in chapel aisle"
- One student at Brown: "We live in a perfectly independent way"

**COMING OF AGE**: "Of all the multitude of young men engaged in various employments of this city, there is not one who does not desire, and even confidently expect to become rich" — Cincinnati newspaper, 1860

- 1840s-1850s: Gilded age of universal devotion throughout their coming-of-age years; **Washington Irving** sarcastically called it "the almighty dollar, that great object of universal devotion throughout our land"
- These were frenetic years for 20-year-olds
- Many stayed East, mingling with new immigrants, found jobs in new factories, rode roller-coaster economy
- Others alienated by rising land prices and intolerant next-elders, followed "Go West, Young Man" maxim of **Horace Greeley**
- While Emerson considered sensible, during Mexican War they proved eager to fight for new territory (to learn how to handle new Colt six-shooter)
- Emerson asked who "think that they should go to California, or to India, or into the army"
- Twentyish Gilded adventurers crying "Eureka!" and chasing newfound mother lodes
- Got into panning for metal, feeding/outfitting desperate peers
- Back across still empty Great Plains, Gilded added feather lures to polarizing debate over union
- First as core of nativist "Young America" movement, next as "Know-Nothings" shouting defiantly anti-Transcendental slogan "Deeds Not Words," next as surprisingly unsophisticated, uncouth shouters and "hurrah boy!" Republicans
- North: agreed with Lincoln's argument that slavery posed threat to free men who were coaxed by new party's promises to enact homestead law and build railroads
- South: cries for battle rose from those whom Sherman darkly referred to as "young bloods" and "sons of planters"—"brave, fine riders, bold to rashness, and dangerous subjects in every sense" who "must be killed or employed by us before we can hope for peace"
- Ranging in age 19-39 in 1861, Gilded ready to make choice of life-course & move with rush
- Many volunteered for war like **Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr.**: "because we want to realize our spontaneity and prove our power for the joy of it"

**RISING ADULTHOOD**: For young Gilded, first Civil War years more dashing than bloody

- Thirtyish commanders **George McClellan** and **Stonewall Jackson** enjoyed popularity with "Billy Yank" and "Johnny Reb" troops
- Following deadly battles 1862-1863, first draft calls made Gilded begin thinking twice about prophetic next-elders
- Ultimately, bulldog Gilded commanders (**Ulysses Grant**) toughened reputation for slow wits and hard liquor by throttling "Gentleman Lee"
- After Civil War while 30-year-olds declared war over principle, 35-year-olds saw mostly ruined farms, starving widows, diseased soldiers, dead bodies, and amputated limbs (carried away from Gettysburg by wagonload)
- South poet **Henry Timrod** described postwar landscape as "beggary, starvation, death, bitter grief, utter want of hope"
- No southerner of Timrod's generation would later emerge to prominence in any sphere of national life—business, science, letters, or politics
- North: Gilded went to work disarming Transcendental leadership
- After 42-year-old senator **Edmund Ross** blocked Radicals' plot to impeach President Johnson, Gilded leaders dismantled Reconstruction and left southern black peers to fend for themselves
- Feisty women in O'Hara matrons of the New South "had no time to be self-conscious or anxious"
- Some became rootless "bums" and "hobos," wandering along newly built railways and evading postwar "tramp laws"
- Others burst forth with bingelike rapacity—notorious "bad guys" (**Wild Bill Hickok, Quantrill**), Indian fighters (**Phil Sheridan, George Custer**), and "robber barons" (**Jim Fisk, Jay Gould**)
- After war, Gilded purged their regional focus away from New England, looking instead toward busier, less talkative Midwest—especially Ohio, home to four of six Gilded Presidents
- **Rutherford Hayes** wrote Cincinnati: "Push, push, push—these words are of great power in a city like this"

**MIDLIFE**: 1876 Gilded celebrated midlife dominion with Philadelphia Centennial Exposition

- Hall of Machines stood for bigness, noise, and worldliness—not hint of Transcendental inner life
- Most Gilded still associated with meanness and tragedy
- During 1870s-1880s, Gilded survivalism turned conservative
- Seeking ethos suitable for generation of scoundrels, found it first in **Charles Darwin's** "law of natural selection," next in **Herbert Spencer's** "social statics," most fully in "pragmatism" of **Charles Peirce** and **William James**
- Amid what known as "Victorian crisis of faith," Gilded played game of life according to worldly measures of success
- First Wall Street financiers like **John Pierpont Morgan** and **Anthony Drexel** counted dollars; first trust-builders like **John D. Rockefeller** and **Andrew Carnegie** counted sales; first rail tycoons like **Leland Stanford** and **James J. Hill** counted miles of steel and tons of freight
- New wealth fortified fiftyish up-from-nowhere elite that came to dominate culture and politics, to despair of their "Mugwump" critics
- New politirates eclipsed succession of weak Presidents and tilted political power toward state and local governments
- Pushed monopolists-turned-genteel-cosmopolitans like **Henry Adams** to rural populists like "Sockless Socrates" **Simpson**
- By 1880s, reconciled themselves to prudish morality promulgated by **Frances Willard's** "Temperance" and "Social Purity" movements
- New standard stressed modesty, self-control, shameless reputation—requiring many of these fiftyish parents to hide (or at least leave unnumbered) their checkered personal histories
- Gilded midlife era ended in 1893 as it began—with world's fair, this time Chicago
- Few months before it opened, worst panic in living memory plunged into sudden depression
- Fair's opulence drew angry fire from young; **Charles Eliot Norton** found "decline of manners" and "dire lack of social faith," saw America gripped by Missionary Awakening

**ELDERHOOD**: "A new America is entering on the false course which has so often led to calamity" — **Charles Eliot Norton**, eve of Spanish-American War, 1898

- Young pressed for invasion of Cuba, virtually all aging Gilded luminaries (Twain, Cleveland, Carnegie, Sumner, James, Howells) urged peace and caution
- Progressive leaders listening to zeal of youth, not exhaustion of old-timers
- Chose to "Remember the *Maine*" at Gettysburg
- Century ticked to close, Gilded conservatism gave way to attacks of younger reformers
- **Old Sumner** lamented bonds of close family loyalty (source of strength and comfort to his peers after lives as durable but eminently forgettable social critics) now yielding to ridiculous fashion-ionable social critics
- College students romanticized bucolic preindustrial past—past old Gilded knew had been wild and dangerous
- Meanwhile, according to **Andrew Achenbaum**, new century unleashed "unprecedented devaluation" of elderly: "Instead of extolling aged's moral wisdom...as they had in past," **Emerson** and **Longfellow** wrote, "commentators increasingly concluded that old people had nothing to contribute to society"
- 1905 lecture, Progressive **William Osler** wrote of "uselessness of men above sixty years of age" and stressed "incalculable benefits" of "peaceful departure by chloroform"
- **Old Henry Adams** complained "young men have a passion for regarding their elders as senile"
- Many Gilded elders heard themselves reviled as "old geezers" and "old fogies"—their elite as "old guard" senators, "standpatter" House members, and reform-blocking Supreme Court justices
- Where prior generations of elders typically worked until death (or were cared for by younger relatives on farms), many now faced involuntary, pensionless "retirement" in rapidly urbanizing economy that substantially favored young adults
- Inept "soldiering" became new insult in workplace, inflation began eroding real value of federal pensions to "Grand Army" veterans
- **Edward Everett Hale**: "There is no place in our working order for old men"
- Never asking for special favors, told Gilded often themselves they thought poorly of treatment
- **Mark Twain** in 1905: "I am seventy...seventy and would nestle in the chimney corner...wishing you well in all affection"

### Enduring Images and Legacy

**Rapacity, nihilism, ugliness:**
- Know-Nothings and Ku Klux Klanners
- Union "bummers" and Quantrill's raiders
- Crédit Mobilier and Salary Grab Act
- Gold spittoons and penny novelists
- Carpetbaggers and scalawags
- Boss Tweed's Tammany machine and "Half-Breed" **James Blaine** and "His Fraudulency" President **Hayes**

**Expectations and negative lifestyle:**
- Generation's huge expectations at birth turned out badly
- Expected to live according to own pragmatic rules—if that meant making massive lifecycle sacrifices, so be it
- Merciless competition favored fast-paced innovation; city machines fed poor constituents
- Business trusts and government surpluses favored huge investment in infrastructure and long-lived capital goods
- Elder industrialists fabled philanthropy; chromo culture protected family
- All benefits accrued not to themselves (aside from handful of flashy winners), but to their children
- Neglected and brutalized early in life, "lost" generation reached midlife power with every opportunity to indulge itself and let its children waste among postwar ruins
- Instead, Gilded rebuilt America while mainly wasting their own "bad" generation
- Became loud proponents of Social Darwinism just as reached threshold of elderhood—precisely phase when "survival of fittest" would plainly work to own disadvantage

**Late-life perspective:**
- Few ever sought credit for lofty motives
- Late in life, **Justice Holmes** admitted: "Philistine" and "pig"; likewise **William James** excoriated peers for "exclusive worship of the bitch-goddess SUCCESS"
- Rather than be judged for how they felt, Gilded preferred to be judged for what they built
- Arriving in New York City 1907, elder James looked around commercial bustle and marveled: "in the center of the cyclone, I caught the pulse of the machine, took up the rhythm, and...found it simply magnificent"
- By refusing to look beyond material world, Gilded sacrificed themselves bodily for "machines"—mechanical, commercial, and political
- This self-deprecation in very real kindness: to ensure that younger Progressives and Missionaries would enjoy far more affluence and security than Gilded had themselves ever known
- Greatest failure late in life: not realizing high tide of laissez-faire growth would hurt all of society's dependents—not only themselves as elders, but also still younger (Lost) generation of children
- Tots of 1890s about to embark on lifecycle much like their own—fact that would have pained old Twains and Carnegies had they known it

> "Twain's 'Notice to the Reader' offered for *Huckleberry Finn*: 'Persons attempting to find a moral in it will be banished.'"

---

## Progressive Generation (Born 1843-1859)

**Type:** Adaptive

### Age Location
- **Youth**: Civil War Crisis
- **Midlife**: Missionary Awakening

### Overview - The Cadre of Experts

Late 1860s contrast:
- Gilded railroad barons building powerful locomotives, designing luxurious Pullman cars
- **22-year-old George Westinghouse** invented air brake to make trains *safe*
- 1876 Centennial: delicate inventions by **29-year-old Thomas Edison** and **27-year-old Alexander Graham Bell** drew more international acclaim than huge Gilded steam turbines

Where midlife Gilded liked to build things that rewarded society's strongest members, these young inventors targeted efforts toward disadvantaged:
- **Edison**: designed arc light to assist visually impaired
- **Bell**: cradled telephone voices for deaf

**Westinghouse, Edison, and Bell**: vanguard of PROGRESSIVE GENERATION
- Cadre of fledgling experts and social meliorators
- Attuned to small as their next-elders were to big
- Leading figures (fortyish **Theodore Roosevelt** and sixtyish **Woodrow Wilson**): liked to describe themselves as "temperate," their designs as "moderate"
- In politics as in family life, inclination to make life gentler and more manageable
- Global credo (in **Wilson's** memorable words): make world "safe for democracy"
- In their inventor peers, Progressives believed skillful calibration and munication would eventually make America nicer country

**Generational character:**
- Acquired unusual sensitivity and collective identity of unusual malleability
- Lifecycle located them in odd warp of history
- Born at wrong time for authentic catharsis—too late for free-wheeling adventure, too soon for youth-fired movements of late nineteenth century
- First-wavers: keep-your-head-down teenagers of Civil War
- Last-wavers: came of age during thickening social consensus of 1870s
- Through 1880s became rising-adult partners to Gilded in fast-growing nation still gripped in survivalist mentality
- Rising adulthood soon became clear: to apply credentialed expertise toward improving what next-elders had pioneered
- Added "organization" to new corporations
- "Efficiency" to new assembly lines
- "Method" to new public agencies


<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## Progressive Generation (Born 1843-1859) — Continued

### Progressive Facts

- **Education boom**: Young Progressives read bestsellers like *How to Be Plump* (chubby "Lillian Russell" female ideal). In midlife, slimmed down to look "youthful" — failed female presidents like **Belva Lockwood** and **Victoria Woodhull**; fattest U.S. President **William Howard Taft**

- **Black colleges and women's colleges**: First sizable number of Americans to attend. First generation to earn graduate degrees en masse, creating Ph.D.-credentialed faculties that elevated universities to circa-1900 prestige — culminating in election of President **Woodrow Wilson**

- Between 1883-1893, four 34-37-year-olds produced stirring patriotic paeans: **Pledge of Allegiance** (Francis Bellamy), *America the Beautiful* (Katherine Lee Bates), *Semper Fidelis* (John Philip Sousa), inscription on Statue of Liberty (Emma Lazarus). As Bates wrote of "confirm thy soul in self-control," they held only 39% of national leadership posts at first birthyear (versus 64% for Transcendentals, 60% for Gilded, 48% for Missionaries)

- **"Burgeoning of certification requirements after 1880"** (historian **Joseph Kett**): first generation of industrial leaders to rise "not from the workbench but through successive layers of management"

- Largest 19th-century expansion in lawyers, notably **corporate legal experts** advising Gilded tycoons. 1860: nine law schools requiring >1 year training; 1880: fifty-six required three years

- Provided initial memberships for extraordinary number of enduring fraternal, labor, academic, and professional associations, including **Elks Club, Knights of Columbus**, Daughters of the American Revolution, Modern Language Association, American Historical Association, American Economics Association, American Federation of Labor, **first "professional" sports league** (National League of Professional Baseball Clubs)

- **Obsessive organizers**: invented cash register, adding machine, carbon paper, mimeograph, first workable typewriter. First generation to use time clocks at work and carry timepieces on their person ("pocket" watches after 1870; "band" or "wrist" watches after 1900). In 1883, railroads designated four U.S. time zones. Later, Progressive Presidents founded Bureau of Standards, Bureau of Labor Statistics, first permanent Census office, led "Crusade for Standardization" during World War I. In 1928, elderly Progressive founded **(Robert) Brookings Institute** to collect, interpret, and inform "in clear and intelligent form the fundamental economic facts concerning which opinions need to be formed"

- Included large influx of Nordic immigrants who settled upper Midwest and Great Plains late in century, witnessing many Progressive midlife experiments in "populist" government and "liberal" Republicanism

- **John Gates** invented barbed wire in 1880s. "Battle of the barbed wire" between cattle ranchers and wheat farmers was typically a dispute between tough-as-nails midlife Gilded and rising-adult ("Let's elect a sheriff") Progressives

- At turn of century, term **"middle age"** began indicating a phase of life (roughly age 40-60), appearing frequently in popular periodicals. Interest focused on feelings of disorientation: "On Some Difficulties Incidental to Middle Age" (1900), "On Being Middle-Aged" (1908), "The Real Awkward Age" (1911). In forties/fifties, many best-known Progressives experienced "midlife crises" or "nervous depressions" — including **Woodrow Wilson, Theodore Roosevelt, Josiah Royce, G. Stanley Hall, Brooks Adams, Frederick Winslow Taylor**

### The Progressive Lifecycle — Midlife Shift

**MIDLIFE**: Having spent half their lifecycle adapting to Gilded-built world, Progressives entered midlife seeking cues from young. In mid-1890s, McKinley resolved to follow "best aspirations of the people" by siding with young "jingoes" in war against Spain. He and three White House successors entangled themselves in position shifts by alternately urging and hedging on subsequent Missionary causes: child labor, woman's suffrage, Prohibition, immigration

- **Procedural reforms of "Progressive Era"**: initiatives and referenda, direct election of senators, "open playing field" of antitrust, expert-run regulatory commissions

- Many Progressives, emerging as afore carriers of late-Victorian manhood, continued pursuing what scientist **Albert Michelson** termed "the sixth place of the decimal" — McKinley Dewey prize for cataloguing knowledge

- Others veered toward opposite extreme. After leading younger "rough riders" up San Juan Hill, **Theodore Roosevelt** attacked "men of soft life." Just after turn of century, appointed Commission on Country Life, led youth-envying "cult of strenuosity," encouraged Missionary zealots he labeled "muckrakers"

- Many midlife women broke free from convention, threw support behind budding feminist movement. **Kate Chopin**, widow and mother of six, wrote *The Awakening*, whose heroine protests "duality of outward existence which conforms, the inward life which questions"

- Last Progressive President, **Woodrow Wilson**, managed World War I in complex manner of his generation — surrounded by diplomats, lawyers, journalists, statisticians, public-private associations

- Afterward, Wilson tried to secure "peace without victory" via multilateral process to forever replace violent conflicts of principle. Younger voters showed little interest in League of Nations proposal; 79% Missionary Congress buried it for good

### The Progressive Lifecycle — Elderhood

**ELDERHOOD**: 1920s did little roaring for those who, like writer **Sarah Orne Jewett**, were "wrecked on the lee shore of age." Poverty remained high among elderly, but overall income distribution was more even than the Gilded, and younger public grew more willing to discuss their hardships sympathetically, especially question of what to do with elderly "in-laws"

- Progressives approached their economic sunset with more foresight and planning (in lieu of Gilded winner-take-all ethos). Around 1910, began vast expansion in private pension plans; by time they retired became first nonveteran generation to enjoy significant pension income

- Many elder Progressives — like **G. Stanley Hall**, who admired young flappers and cultivated "zgests" like walking outdoors — continued to watch and emulate the young

- "Reversing age-old custom," notes **Mark Sullivan**, chronicler of Wilsonian-era America, "elders began earnestly to act like juniors, to ape their causes and grandchildren." Main message to juniors: stay calm, keep faith in democratic process, listen to expertise

- **Eighty-ish Elihu Root** kept lecturing young on importance of "World Court"; while **Frank Kellogg** promoted arcane disarmament process (what one senator called "an international kiss") that would later win him a Nobel. Their senior statesmen issued calls to humanity and fairness not always observed — e.g., **Franz Boas'** defense of cultural pluralism against eugenics-minded Missionaries

- "The greatest danger to liberty is an insidious encroachment by men of zeal," warned **Louis Brandeis**, defending due process of trial and error. "Neither revolution, nor reaction, old Florence Kelley reminded herself, "the most unwearied hoper," and old **John Dewey** unflaggingly pursued "liberalism" as "committed to an end that is at once enduring and flexible"

- In final years, greatest Progressives lacked firm answers about life — and had humility to admit it

> "The muddled state is one of the very sharpest of the realities." — **Henry James**

- His own generation remains saddled with "muddled" image, often blurred together with the burly Gilded or zealous Missionaries. Combining belief in fairness, openness, and what **Ella Wheeler Wilcox** called "just the art of being kind," Progressives gave Gilded Age its human face and helped make Missionary Awakening an age of reform not revolution

- Their fascination with process and detail provided mediating link between "build big" next-elders and "think big" next-juniors. Much of their contribution hinged on their ability to see "out of the confusion of life" what James described as "the close connection of bliss and bale, of the things that help with the things that hurt"

- Yet they also waffled facing rapid social change. Vacillating on foreign policy and unwilling to forgo "cheap labor" immigrants, they invited floodtide of jingoism and racism that swept America at turn of century

- Their acquiescence in disenfranchisement of "separate but equal" Jim Crow laws sealed fate of southern blacks. Their uncertain parental hand left Lost children vulnerable to cruel economic shocks

- But their **imperfection belief in human perfectibility** gave powerful boost to liberal side of modern American character. Collectively, Progressives shared quality once affixed to *Uncle Remus* author **Joel Chandler Harris**: "the seal of good humor... and a pleasant outlook on the world"

- Progressives never saw themselves as heroes or prophets. Rather, they saw themselves as modern cadre of **value-free meliorators** who could link progress to expertise, improvement to precision

> "The science of statistics is the chief instrumentality through which the progress of civilization is now measured." — Census chief **Simon Newton Dexter North** (1902)

- "and by which its development hereafter will be largely controlled it is now assured," declared North. "Late in life, a skeptical world lurched toward chaos, old Progressives sometimes questioned such certainty"

- In 1914, 71-year-old **Henry James** wrote to a friend: "You and I, the ornaments of our generation, should have been spared the wreck of our belief that through the long years we had seen civilization grow and the worst become impossible. The tide that bore us along was then all the while moving to this as its grand Niagara"

- Yet what few Progressives ever lost — no matter how old — was their urge to stay involved and thereby overcome a feeling that they had missed something early in life

> "I don't regret a single 'excess' of my responsive youth. I only regret, in my chilled age, certain occasions and possibilities I didn't embrace." — **Henry James**

---

## Chapter 10: The Great Power Cycle

### Opening — Atomic Age Dawn (July 15, 1945)

"The Atomic Age began at exactly 5:30 A.M. Mountain War Time on the morning of July 15th, 1945, on a stretch of semidesert land about 50 airline miles from Alamogordo, New Mexico" — *New York Times* reporter **William Laurence** (age 57)

- Another man of blunt expression, President **Harry Truman** (age 61), took news impassively and prepared to order remaining bombs dropped on Japan

- 77-year-old Secretary of War **Henry Stimson** dispatched coded message to **Winston Churchill** at Potsdam: "Babies satisfactorily born" — to which like-aged British Prime Minister replied: "This is the Second Coming, in wrath"

- Standing nearby at New Mexico test site, meanwhile, was scientist whose ashen mind churned: 41-year-old **J. Robert Oppenheimer**. Asked for his thoughts, Oppenheimer recalled Hindu description of deity: "If the radiance of a thousand suns were to burst into the sky, that would be the splendor of the Mighty One"

- Another young physicist: "The sun doesn't hold a candle to it!" Several weeks later, 19-year-old **Russell Baker** was training for massive and bloody invasion of Japan when he heard of Nagasaki blast and Japan's sudden capitulation. He wrote to his mother in mixture of open relief and secret vexation: "It seems like I'm pulling some monstrous joke on myself when I say the war is over, because I really can't believe it"

- These whirlwind weeks marked dawn of **"Superpower America,"** the climactic moment of the **GREAT POWER CYCLE**

### The Great Power Cycle — Four Generations

**Henry Stimson's visionary MISSIONARY GENERATION** (Idealist, then age 63-85) had originally ordered A-bomb's development. These were patriarchs of national struggle, dark figures of Footnotes, stern elder leaders who provided guidance for what seemed to be the last defense of Christian civilization

- If age of atomic defense, Americans of all ages trusted this generation to answer moral questions. Couple years earlier, President **Franklin Roosevelt** had asked several grayheads — most notably **James Byrnes**, economist **Vannevar Bush**, Stimson himself (average age 70) — to examine A-bomb "in terms of a new relationship with the universe"

- While bombs were being built, only **Albert Einstein** (age 66) could worry out loud about what atom might unleash; anyone younger would have been instantly suspected of disloyalty

- Afterward, craggy **Douglas MacArthur** drew on his redemptive power in this new and terrible "crucible of war," capable of forcing kind to face a dilemma that "is theological and involves a spiritual rededication"

- Weeks later, in Tokyo, he administered what he termed history's "first Christian occupation" of an Asian land, bringing to "our vanquished foe the solace and hope and faith of Christian morals"

**Harry Truman's get-it-done LOST GENERATION** (Reactive, age 45-62) provided war effort's pragmatic midlife generals, including gruff generist **Leslie Groves**, who managed the Manhattan Project

> "He who hesitates is lost. One or two of those things and Japan will be finished." — Groves after glance at test blast

- "We've spent two billion dollars on the biggest scientific gamble in history — and won." Groves, Truman, and their midlife peers understood that America looked to them less for Rooseveltian vision than for Patton-style action

> "To err is Truman." — chided many editorials two months earlier after this relative unknown had become Commander in Chief

- None learned of A-bomb project (a secret none of FDR's seventyish cabinet had bothered to share with him). Yet unlike his elders, President Truman knew from personal experience what human slaughter accompanies yard-by-yard conquest of Japanese mainland. So he "let the buck stop" with him — ordered Hiroshima bombed

- Soon enough, Truman and peers would cope with further thankless tasks: cleaning up after debris left by FDR's visionary Yalta plan, eyeballing Soviets with gaming "brinksmanship" that younger leaders would deride as irrational, keeping America on steady, cautious course while hearing expressions "old," "tired," "reactionary" hurled at them. No big deal: The Lost had grown used to such negative judgments

**Robert Oppenheimer's smart and dutiful G.I. GENERATION** (Civic, age 21-44) provided team of scientists responsible for "Mighty One." Here stood greatest power man had ever possessed — and they had created it

- Without their heroism, use of bomb and elevation of America to superpower status would not have been possible. Over past three years, swarms of uniformed young men (average age 26) had conquered entire Pacific. Rosie the Riveter women had assembled bombers and battleships to arm them. Seabees had built bases out of jungles and barren reefs, including Tinian, where the *Enola Gay* took off for Hiroshima

- Plot of first A-bomb-laden bomber, **Paul Tibbets**, was himself a ribbon-faced 30-year-old. Several years after their "gadget" had humiliated Tokyo warlords, G.I.s would take it a step further by designing H-bomb. They would call it "the Super" and G.I. trio who designed it (**Edward Teller, Luis Alvarez, and Oppenheimer**) "Super-men" — fitting image for generation whose reason and teamwork had unleashed ultimate energy of pure matter

- Later in life, G.I.s would harness their collective might and labor to fulfill their elders' vision by building gleaming "Great Society" of peace, prosperity, and friendliness — only to hear their own children utterly dismiss spiritual emptiness

**The eldest among Russell Baker's aspiring SILENT GENERATION** (Adaptive, age 3-20) knew A-bomb blasts had spared them from harm — and equally from any chance to make their mark in glory and heroism

- Though they hadn't invented this monster, henceforth what **William Styron** called "the almost unimaginable potential consequences" of the atom would symbolize their coming-of-age sense of powerlessness, irony, and nonjudgmental relativism

- Two decades later, while thirtyish Pentagon technicians designed "fail-safe delivery systems" to prevent nuclear weapons from atomizing very people they were supposed to protect, thirtyish artists would try to release their collective tension in sentimental lyrics of self-doubt: **Peter, Paul, and Mary** wistfully singing *Where Have All the Flowers Gone?*; **Barry McGuire** *Eve of Destruction*; and **Don Lehrst** *So Long Mom ("I'm off to drop the bomb")*

- In another song, Lehrst quipped in eminent Silent fashion: "Once the rockets are up, who cares where they come down? / That's not my department," says **Werner von Braun**

- It would become the Silent's own "department" to worry about what happens when powerful things "come down" on people — from Carl Sagan speaking against "nuclear winter" to **Michael Harrington** and **Martin Luther King, Jr.**, arguing that money spent on bombs should be spent instead on the poor

### The Great Power Cycle — Generational Drama

The start of nuclear age marked culmination of a generational drama that was by then nearly six decades old. It opened in late 1880s, when a generation of indulgently raised post–Civil War youths triggered revivalism, labor unrest, and "Cross of Gold" paroxysm of **William Jennings Bryan**

- What Roosevelt described as "a mysterious cycle" of generational "destiny" extended into unrivaled "Pax Americana" of mid-1960s, right up to LBJ's escalation of Vietnam War

- At beginning of nineteen-sixty epoch, Old World still regarded United States as a frontier society, at best a minor player in world affairs. By its end, the United States had emerged as a great global power, fueled by world's most productive economy and armed with world's most formidable defense establishment

- Great Power Cycle contains two social moments:

#### The Missionary Awakening (1886-1903)

"Third Great Awakening" began in 1886 with Haymarket Riot and launching of global student missionary movement. By 1893, combination of agrarian protest and urban labor violence sparked tumultuous 1890s, a decade historian **Henry Steele Commager** considers a "cultural watershed" in American history

- Historian **Richard Hofstadter** calls a "searing experience" of those who lived through it. Following Bryan's revivalist run for President in 1896, awakening pushed young, excited cadre of "muckraking" writers and reformers into public eye just after turn of century

- During Theodore Roosevelt's first term, these youth movements crested, and awakening ended. As rising generation lost interest in "progressive" reforms, and especially after financial panic of 1907, national mood veered

- Meanwhile, awakening had given birth to Bible Belt, to Christian socialism, to Greenwich Village, to Wobblies, and to renascent labor, temperance, and women's suffrage movements

**LOCATION IN HISTORY**: *Gilded in elderhood; Progressives in midlife; Missionaries in rising adulthood; Lost in youth*

#### The Great Depression–World War II Crisis (1932-1945)

Reached from economic trough of 1932 through triumph of VJ-Day in 1945, roughly spanning thirteen-year Presidential reign of **Franklin Roosevelt**

- Began in mood of despair and pessimism about future, stretched through the New Deal ("the Third American Revolution," according to historian **Carl Degler**), climaxed in total war against totalitarianism, and ended at dawn of new era of power, affluence, and global leadership

- One of every eight Americans now alive came of age during this era. Most recall how mid-1940s ushered in an exhilarating sense of collective triumph, feelings those younger than themselves have never known

- From moment crisis peaked, rising peer elite began assuming leadership positions, leading ultimately to a "new generation" taking White House in 1961 — a post they still hold three decades later

**LOCATION IN HISTORY**: *Missionaries in elderhood; Lost in midlife; G.I.s in rising adulthood; Silent in youth*

---

## Missionary Generation (Born 1860-1882)

**TYPE**: Idealist
**Total number**: 45,000,000
**Now alive in U.S.**: 1,000
**Percent immigrant**: 23%
**Percent slave**: 1%

**FAMILY TREE**:
- Typical grandparents: Transcendental
- Parents: Gilded and Progressive
- Children: Lost and G.I.
- Typical grandchildren: Silent

**SAMPLE MEMBERS** (birth/death):
- 1860 **William Jennings Bryan** (1925)
- 1860 **Jane Addams** (1935)
- 1863 **Billy Sunday** (1935)
- 1863 **William Randolph Hearst** (1951)
- 1863 **Henry Ford** (1947)
- 1868 **W.E.B. DuBois** (1963)
- 1869 **Frank Lloyd Wright** (1959)
- 1869 **Emma Goldman** (1940)*
- 1871 **Theodore Dreiser** (1945)
- 1871 **Orville Wright** (1948)
- 1875 **Mary McLeod Bethune** (1955)
- 1878 **Isadora Duncan** (1927)
- 1878 **Upton Sinclair** (1968)
- 1879 **Albert Einstein** (1955)*
- 1879 **Margaret Sanger** (1966)
- 1880 **Douglas MacArthur** (1964)
- 1880 **John Llewellyn Lewis** (1969)
- 1880 **H.L. Mencken** (1956)
- 1880 **Helen Keller** (1968)
- 1880 **George C. Marshall** (1959)

**PERIOD OF POLITICAL LEADERSHIP**:
- Plurality in House: 1909-1937
- Plurality in Senate: 1917-1943
- Majority on Supreme Court: 1925-1943

**U.S. PRESIDENTS**: 1921-1945
- 1865 **Warren G. Harding** (1923)
- 1872 **Calvin Coolidge** (1933)
- 1874 **Herbert Hoover** (1964)
- 1882 **Franklin D. Roosevelt** (1945)

**PROMINENT FOREIGN PEERS**:
- 1869 **Mahatma Gandhi** (1948)
- 1870 **V.I. Lenin** (1924)
- 1874 **Winston Churchill** (1965)
- 1875 **Albert Schweitzer** (1965)
- 1881 **Pablo Picasso** (1973)

**SAMPLE CULTURAL ENDOWMENTS**: *Intolerance* (film, D.W. Griffith); "Into My Own" (Robert Frost); *Prejudices* (H.L. Mencken); *Sister Carrie* (Theodore Dreiser); syndicated column (Will Rogers); *The Shame of the Cities* (Lincoln Steffens); *This Side of Paradise* (F. Scott Fitzgerald); *In My Life* (Emma Goldman); "What I Believe" (Albert Einstein); *Women and the New Race* (Margaret Sanger); *Beale Street Blues* (W.C. Handy); *The Souls of Black Folk* (W.E.B. DuBois); "I Am the People, the Mob" (Carl Sandburg); *The Last Puritan* (George Santayana)

### Missionary Youth — Moral Rebellion

**YOUTH**: Missionaries first appeared as welcomed postwar youngsters of late 1860s and 1870s. Indulgently raised and educated by midlife Gilded in a world of orderly families and capital prosperity, they came of age horrified by what **George Cabot Lodge** called "a world of machine-guns and machine-everything-else" and what **Stephen Crane**, gazing at a coal mine, called "this huge and hideous monster... grinding its mammoth jaws with unearthly and monotonous uproar"

- "This inner rebellion of 'moral' sons against 'laborious' fathers," recalled best-selling American novelist **Winston Churchill** in 1908, triggered "the springing of a generation of ideals from a generation of commerce"

- Missionary first-wavers, leavened by first large influx of non–Anglo-Saxon white immigrants, entered their twenties as preachy student leaders, rebellious career women, and Haymarket rioters. Last-wavers reached adulthood while fires of Chautauqua revivalism, muckraking, and labor radicalism still raged

- Their tumultuous awakening defined Missionaries for life as a generation of moral pathfinders, men and women to whom any opinion was a religion once they decided it was right

- **William Allen White** recalls that Bryan's campaign "was a fanaticism like the Crusades. Indeed the delusion that was working on the people took the form of religious frenzy"

- Unlike their Progressive next-elders, Missionaries were attracted by specter of purifying confrontation. "People who love soft words and hate iniquity forget this," **Chapman** wrote in 1898, "that reform consists in taking a bone away from a dog"

- Fellow student had earlier attributed Chapman's popularity to sheer zeal: "He is glowing and beautiful like fire... destructive like fire, seeking heaven like fire"

- Missionary anger remitted into self-discovery during Theodore Roosevelt's second term. When economy slumped after Panic of 1907, they hardly noticed. Instead, reveling in personal independence of their new automobile age, they shifted their attention from messianic upheaval to task of reshaping self and community

- Their lofty-worded movements spread the spectrum from the holy (**Billy Sunday's** fundamentalism, "White Angel" Booth's Salvation Army) to the domestic (**Elmer McCollum's** fruit faddism, **Frank Lloyd Wright's** "Prairie Style" architecture); from the utopian (**Bill Haywood's** Wobblies, **Emma Goldman's** anarchism or the mean-spirited **William Simmons** reborn Ku Klux Klan, **Henry Goddard's** eugenics movement); from the uplifting (**Jane Addams'** settlement houses; **Walter Rauschenbusch's** "Social Gospel") to the sober (**Andrew Volstead's** crusade against liquor, **Francis Harrison's** against narcotics)

- Not least, for rising adults who loudly hailed "the New Woman," was the unprecedented strength of their feminist cause — including **Isadora Duncan** (celebrating sexual emancipation by dance), **Charlotte Perkins Gilman** (assailing *This Man-Made World*), **Margaret Sanger** (broadcasting birth-control advice in *Woman Rebel*), and countless others in what came to be annual suffrage marches up New York's Fifth Avenue

- Whatever their causes, Missionary mental approach remained the same: a heroic desire to make the world perfect according to standards that welled up from within

### Missionary Coming of Age — WWI Split

Entering midlife around World War I, this generation often found itself split into opposite camps, rural evangelicals versus urban Social Gospelers ("modernists"). Yet growing pessimism about America's future in hands of nihilistic Lost juniors brought them together in common mission: vindication of social good over social evil

- Thus did fiftyish Missionaries transform into enthusiastic circa-1917 "Crusaders for Democracy," and later into "Decency" enforcers of 1920s

- They pushed through Prohibition, women's suffrage, immigration restriction, Smoot-Hawley, Red deportation, "vice squads," and punitive criminal laws — all in effort to rekindle higher principles of national community

- With world totalitarianism of 1930s, this effort matured into sense of historical imperative. And when era of crisis culminated in war, younger generation (of G.I.s) looked to aging Missionaries for wise leadership, for fresh definition of national purpose

- They could dutifully champion against all enemies. "That is the conflict, day and night and new perplexes our lives," President **Franklin Roosevelt** proclaimed after attack on Pearl Harbor. "No compromise can end that conflict. There has never been—there never can be—successful compromise between good and evil. Only total victory can reward the champions of tolerance, and decency, and freedom against the forces of intolerance, of arrogance, and of fear"

- In words of Roosevelt, MacArthur, Henry Kaiser, and George Marshall — established America as global beacon of revitalized civilization

### Missionary Lifecycle — Spiritual Leadership

Throughout their lives, Missionaries startled older and younger generations by their fixation on mind and spirit, by their odd detachment from material realities of life

- They championed inner life, from **Jane Addams'** "higher conscience" in immigrant neighborhoods, to **W.E.B. DuBois'** "black consciousness" in race relations, to "stream of consciousness" novels of **Stephen Crane** — even to "primitive consciousness" of **Jack London's** *Call of the Wild* and **Edgar Rice Burroughs'** *Tarzan of the Apes*

- By the time America was rallying behind this generation's leadership at moment of national emergency, incoming President Franklin Roosevelt remarked of "our common difficulties" that "they concern, thank God, only material things"

> "Sevenfold are the years of famine... Nevertheless, Roosevelt repeated 'the belief I have already affirmed many times that there is not a problem, social, political, or economic, that would not find full solution in the fire of a religious awakening...'" — **Frederic Howe**, *Confessions of a Reformer*

- Howe explained that "early assumptions as to virtue and vice, goodness and evil remained in my mind long after I had tried to discard them. This is, I think, the most characteristic influence of my generation. It explains the nature of our reforms... our belief in men and institutions and our messages to other people"

- **Missionaries and battlships, anti-saloon leagues and Ku Klux Klan... are all a part of that evangelistic psychology... that seeks a moralistic explanation of social problems and a religious solution, even of them** — **George Santayana** was surely thinking of his fiftyish peers when he observed in 1920: "Americans are eminently prophets. They apply morals to public affairs.... They are men of principles, and fond of stating them"

- The word "missionary" symbolized this generation's lifelong quest for global reform. Effort began with what **Ivy League** students proclaimed to be the "missionary crusade" of the 1880s, sealed by 1886 assembly at Mount Hermon, Massachusetts, at which students proclaimed "the kingdom of God on earth" and adopted the motto many would apply into old age: **"The Evangelization of the World in This Generation"**

- In vast numbers, these young zealots built Christian encampments all over Asia. They loved calling themselves "missionaries," the Latin plural derivation of the Greek "apostle," or "one sent"

- When hundreds were massacred during Chinese Boxer Rebellion of 1900 (some decapitated torsos returned with their hands bound to waist with their own hair as mark of pigtoy), thirtyish peers back home took to heart their role as global martyrs, "ones sent" to bring new values to "Brotherhood of Man" by force of their example

- Thirty-three years later, Franklin Roosevelt became leader whom "young men followed" — notes historian **Arthur Schlesinger, Jr.** — "as they had followed no American since Lincoln." And forty-five years later, **FDR** became only President whose death was universally likened to martyrdom of Lincoln

> "He was just like a daddy to me, always. He was the one person I ever knew, anybody, who was never afraid. God, God—how he could take it for us all." — young G.I. **Lyndon Johnson**

- "He was the one person I ever knew, anybody, who was never afraid. God, God—how he could take it for us all." What they achieved themselves early in life hardly compared with what they saw in their late in life

- **Eddy** recalled of **Robert Speer**, his crusading classmate of 1880s and author of *Missionary Principles and Practice*: "What he was, was more important than what he did"

### Missionary Summary — Personal Connection to History

This is the first generation to which many living Americans feel a personal connection. Today's elders sometimes say they saw them last, as visionary leaders who guided America through Great Depression and World War II

- Today's 50-year-old probably remembers at least one Missionary grandparent; today's 75-year-old, a Missionary parent or two. Chances are, those memories are of stern old Victorian patriarchs and matriarchs, devoted to what we would now describe as traditional religion, traditionalist morality — literally the last "Victorians"

- They were last Americans to come of age before the grand queen died in 1901. Yet full story of their lifecycle cannot possibly be told by invoking Victorian stereotypes, nor indeed by recalling steel-willed leaders of mid-1940s — a cadre of elders now sometimes remembered as "the World War I Men"

- Instead, full story would include very different images — of youthful indulgence, coming-of-age fury, rising adult introspection, and midlife pomposity and intolerance. What finally emerged in life, the austere and resolute persona, was largely self-created by a generation determined (in **Edith Wharton's** words) "to build up, little by little, bit by bit, the precious thing we call civilization — on atoms without knowing it"

### Missionary Facts

- Today's idyllic image of traditional American Yuletide — Christmas trees, jingle bells, sleighrides, chromo cards, and a jolly, present-toting Santa (first sketched by **Thomas Nast** in 1863) — was created mainly by midlife Gilded for benefit of Missionary children

<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

## The Missionary Generation (continued)

### Coming of Age: Settlement Movement and Campus Rebellion

- **William James** described typical 1890s-era freshman as arrogant, junior as socialist, senior as religious—"with an ascetic, egoistical" commitment to settlement house work
- During 1886-1903, college youths flocked to **settlement houses** like **Jane Addams**' Hull House, spiritual explorers accused by Progressive teachers of "sharing" rather than questioning
- Young writers rejected Gilded-built world as "soulless money-getting," "immense banking, roaring industries," "hugeness and disorder"
- In early 1890s, **George Herron** drew crowds with "Message of Jesus to Men of Wealth": "there may have to be some dying done before our social wrongs are thoroughly righted"
- Herron's student: "That was the thing that interested me—finding myself; and I wanted to be surrounded by people who were interested in finding themselves, who wanted to understand life and its meanings"

### Symbolic Violence and Anarchism

- Young Missionaries founded **anarchist communes** (Massachusetts enclave of **Emma Goldman** and **Alexander Berkman**)
- Acts of rage: **Haymarket Riot**, **Homestead Massacre**, **Pullman Strike**
- Convicted anarchist **Louis Lingg** blew himself up with dynamite cap rather than go to gallows
- **O. Henry** observed moral perfection in new journalism: "Pledging like Sword of Gideon, the wounded make gestures worthy of a cross"
- **William Randolph Hearst** shrieked of wrecks, fires, foreign atrocities: "If only institutions and bad men can be got rid of only by killing them, then the killing must be done"
- **Upton Sinclair** at close of *The Jungle*: "Chicago will be ours! *Chicago will be ours!* CHICAGO WILL BE OURS!"

### Rising Adulthood: Bombs, Riots, and Value Reshaping

- Twentyish hothead violence of 1890s later embarrassed this generation into thirties and forties
- During Roosevelt and Taft Presidencies, late-starting Missionaries caught up with Gilded personal lives and careers
- **Richard Hovey**, embodiment of Gilded oyster-like stomach, admitted bathtub and clean linen made "no real objection to a bathtub in general," but inward fire did not extinguish—fragmented into separate channels
- Young men and women entirely reshaped American values and culture:
  - **Social Gospel** urban immigrants vs. rural **Fundamentalism** (rural Bible Belt)
  - **Carl Sandburg** and **Ragtime** vs. **Father Divine** and **Billy Sunday** Greenwich Village martyrs
  - **Joe Hill** ("man who never died") kept radical Wobbly fringe alive
  - **D.W. Griffith**'s *Birth of a Nation* asserted white world supremacy; young Senator **Albert Beveridge**'s "Almighty Plan" to rid world of "savage and senile peoples"
  - **W.E.B. DuBois** rallying black peers to defy **Booker T. Washington**'s "Tuskegee Machine," launching **Niagara Movement**—first national black platform refusing second-class status

### Technology and Social Inventions

- Missionary-propelled inventions: **Wright brothers** airplane, **Henry Ford** automobile, **Thomas Edison** phonograph
- **Alfred Sloan** and **Walter Chrysler** joined technology to individuating inner aspirations
- Migrating from hometown to high-tech cities at like age, rising adults embraced "vacation," "motel," "suburb," "country club"
- Rural-born authors fled eastward (having been "frontier babies"), criticized **Sherwood Anderson**'s "lives of quiet desperation" in rural small towns
- **Edgar Lee Masters**: "I tried to rise above you"
- Many thirtyish women ignored warnings that "home is in peril" and wondered with novelist **Ellen Glasgow** why "sit at home grow shapeless and have babies galore"
- Those who did start families rejected showy Victorianism: smaller kitchens and houses (**Gwendolyn Wright**'s "minimalist house")
- Self-assured, righteous, intolerant as they approached midlife, unbridled sexuality reflected
- **Canby** later admitted **Gibson Girl** became symbol of young women invading male professional world, muckraking and mimserial young men claiming moral pedestal Gilded had left to ladies

### Midlife: Prohibition and Moral Crusading

- **William Jennings Bryan** helped transform Progressive "temperance" movement into Missionary-style **Prohibition**: "There is but one side in a moral question. Which do you take?"
- At last taking over institutions built and attacked in youth, Missionaries now wanted to run them with zeal
- After pushing yet another Progressive President into war (1917), used emergency for "moral" purposes: constitutional agendas plus sweeping means of controlling younger Lost (hedonism despised, wildness feared might taint new G.I. children)
- **General "Black Jack" Pershing** took brutal action against doughboy war deserters
- **Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis** sentenced hundreds of younger Wobblies to hard time, then turned cudgel to cleaning up baseball
- **Attorney General Mitchell Palmer** staged **Palmer Raids**: famous for rounding up 4,000 supposed Bolsheviks on single night
- **James Truslow Adams** admitted peers found "scapegoat" and "the name on its collar is The Younger Generation"

### Elderhood: The New Deal and World War II

- While **Woodrow Wilson** complained war unleashed "spirit of rising brutality" making Americans "forget there ever was such a thing as tolerance," many Missionary reformers welcomed how war effort brought "union and community" (**Mary Follett**), "wider and surer control of common interests" (**Robert Park**), "true national collectivism" (**Robert Woods**)
- **Senator Borah** and **Henry Ford**'s isolationism: "irreconcilables" denied Wilson postwar League of Nations
- As 1920s wore on, well-timed but tardy midlife elite rose at expense of rural and evangelical peers
- Still caustic tone deepened: **Henry Ford** passed exam "on clean and wholesome life"
- **Calvin Coolidge**: "true business" would bring "moral and spiritual advancement"—making this "Puritan in Babylon" (according to life-aged biographer **Allen White**)
- **Congress** virtually halted immigration; **Will Hays** enforced **Code of Decency** against sex on camera
- **Ku Klux Klan** tried to "Americanize" heartland; nation's first "vice squads" began shutting down bootleggers
- DuBois expressed alarm at growth in youth crime; new Missionary judges meted out executions and longer prison terms
- State and local officials began authorizing "eugenical" sterilizations; Missionaries began hearing younger Lost revile them as "Babbitts" or "Tired Radicals"
- Occasional Missionary figured out-of-touch: **H.L. Mencken** roasted "homo booboisie" peers
- By late 1920s, most high-toned generation agreed with **Paul Elmer More** and **Irving Babbitt**: America needed "New Humanism," mastering new ethic of social order and self-discipline
- With rise of **Herbert Hoover**, renowned as brilliant humanitarian of global vision, Missionaries hoped best man was in position to propel "Gospel of Business" overseas—to eliminate poverty, promote Christianity, raise moral standards worldwide

### Crisis Leadership: Depression and War

- **Franklin Roosevelt** in depths of Great Depression when his "generation" ranged mid-fifties to late sixties: as crisis approached, aging authoritarian Missionaries moved comfortably into place as stewards of social and economic regimentation
- With demise of Prohibition and rise of New Deal coalition, urban-rural schism expired—partly through cooperation in face of peril, partly through leadership of urban modernists like **Al Smith**
- As midlife Lost mellowed, they joined America's equivalent of good-scout G.I.s: "interest of Roosevelt was with younger man," recalled adviser **Barbara Armstrong**
- Most elder Missionaries—including pension activists **Francis Townsend** and **John McGroarty** (dubbed "Poet Laureate of California")—accepted intergenerational quid pro quo of Roosevelt's **Social Security** legislation
- Young promised new jobs, "family wage," "new places available for strong and eager"; old got meager pension upon "retiring," but retained moral authority to set national priorities and economic wartime emergency
- It would have been cruel "New Deal" for any other generation: economically, Missionaries sacrificed their interests by directing most public resources toward youth, but took too much pride in directing sacrifices of others
- During decade and half of crisis, consolidated social authority—over ineffective opposition of Lost, often with encouragement of G.I.s
- In religion, old Missionaries continued to dominate American churches: in politics, remained undisputed leaders of now-graying Presidential cabinets, Congressional committees, state assemblies
- They became "Elders"—those whom **Otis Graham Jr.** describes as "small ascetic fraternity, visible saints of twentieth-century reform" (and whom **Mencken** less respectfully labeled "the New Deal Isaiahs")
- In war, became guiding patriarchs: **Secretaries Henry Stimson and Cordell Hull**; **Admirals "Bull" Halsey and Ernest King**; **Generals MacArthur and Marshall**; **industrialists Henry Kaiser and Bernard Baruch**; **physicist Albert Einstein**
- Today's older Americans remember serene self-assurance and unquestioned demands these elders—and no just them—exercised in America
- During war, entire Free World knew Roosevelt as "the Resident" or "Dr. Win-the-War," **Churchill** as "Europe's Savior"
- When **MacArthur** left Philippines proclaiming "I shall return," righteous self-esteem energized people of all ages; when he came home from Korea, awestruck younger Congressmen listened in to "God Himself"
- After World War II, though Lost finally assumed command, elderly visionaries continued to symbolize what **Allende** called their "Great Crusade"
- They retreated into old age like global missionary: **1946 Nobel Peace Prize laureate John Mott**, who (in words of younger admirer) had "something of mountains and sea" in him, walked away with calm, unhasty step, manner that seemed never ruffled, never excited, "very simple and a bit sublime"

### Generational Legacy

- Where angry spiritualism of Transcendental youth culminated in apocalypse of Civil War, Missionaries' demonstration of youthful generation of muckrakers, evangelicals, bomb-throwers could mature into revered and principled elders
- Wise old men and women capable of leading young through grave peril to better world beyond
- From 1880s through 1940s, Missionary hand can be seen pushing American ideals and history forward
- Just as we honor reforms of Progressive Era as testament to fair process, we remember **Prohibition**, **New Deal**, **World War II**, **Marshall Plan** as testament to imperative that "good" must triumph over "bad"
- Some of what they did in pursuit of morality had excess: when excesses committed, usually younger, more pragmatic Lost who had to bear punishment andderen casualties
- From **Palmer Raids** to **Prohibition**, from **Hoovervilles** to **Yalta**, by late 1940s younger Americans yearning for some national purpose less lofty than rectitude
- Missionary star faded at last: "Perhaps it was the time. Do not be deceived—we are today in midst of cold war," announced 77-year-old **Bernard Baruch** only two years after V-day
- These anonymous victims from a man and generation that always been able to find extra moral stature in every new war and every new crusade
- Without question, Americans have Missionaries to thank for lifting America to present-day status as great global power
- America still lives by visions they glimpsed: in foreign aid, the "foreign aid" invented by elder Missionaries (**Herbert Hoover** and **Herbert Lehman**), perhaps including classmates on **Mount Hermon** who first set forth sights on "Evangelization of World in This Generation"
- At home, term "Great Society" similarly popularized by elder Missionaries (**James Truslow Adams** and **Marcella La Guardia**), perhaps recalling youthful image of Bryan—"the bard and prophet of them all"
- **Vachel Lindsay** claimed "Nation can be born in a day if ideals of people can be changed"
- In 1948 at age 83, art critic **Bernard Berenson** defined "culture" as "effort to build a House of Life... that humanistic society which under name of Paradise, Elysium, Heaven, City of God, Millennium, has been craving of all good men these last four thousand years or more"
- **Franklin Roosevelt** had something similar in mind describing "Four Freedoms" just nine months before leading America to war: "That is no vision of distant millennium... It is definite basis for kind of world attainable in our own time and generation"

## Lost Generation Profile

**Born: 1883-1900**
**Type: Reactive**

### Age Location
- **Missionary Awakening** in youth
- **Great Depression-World War II Crisis** in midlife

### Overview

> "There died a myriad... / For an old bitch gone in the teeth, / For a botched civilization." —**Ezra Pound**

- Missionaries liked to call America's "Crusade for Democracy"—World War I was cruel enough to soldiers in trenches (futile, stalemate-becoming-annihilating)
- In 1919 and 1920, next-elders meted out **Volstead Act** to purge them of liquor, **"Red Scare" Palmer Raids** to purge radicals, **John Sumner**'s **Society for Suppression of Vice** to purge pornography
- "The season 'tis, my lovely lambs, / of Sumner Volstead Christ and Co.," lampooned 26-year-old **e.e. cummings**
- "Down with middle-aged!" joined mob of **John Dos Passos**, age 24
- These literati would soon know themselves as the **LOST GENERATION**, scrambling survivors in world of pomposity and danger
- As 1920s dawned, some already getting into trouble: **John Reed** jailed as "Red" in Moscow, **Harry Truman** clothing store failing
- Amid Lost listlessness, Lost set of alienation: those who were "Puttin' on the Ritz": **Babe Ruth** (Yankees), **"Scarface" Al Capone** (Chicago business), **Irving Berlin** (Tin Pan Alley), young writers **F. Scott Fitzgerald**, **Sinclair Lewis**, **Eugene O'Neill** (blockbuster hits)
- Embittered 30-year-olds fought ideology and fascism: **Babbitts**, **Binges**, **Bunds**, with bathtub gin and opulent sex
- "America was going on the greatest, gaudiest spree in history," bubbled **Fitzgerald** in *This Side of Paradise*, setting scene for "Roaring Twenties"

### Prewar and Postwar

- Fitzgerald described his generation as at once "prewar and postwar"
- With rowdy childhood and tired old age as bookends, Lost lifecycle divided roughly in thirds by two world wars
- In meantime, in between time, "Ain't We Got Fun?"
- Story began with streetwise kids who grew up fast—too late to join spiritual high of next-elders, but too young to stay step ahead of Missionary efforts to clean them up
- They were, wrote Fitzgerald, "new generation dedicated more than last to fear of poverty and worship of success; grown up to find all gods dead, all wars fought, all faiths in man shaken"

### Lost Facts

- **Child labor**: In 1910, nearly one child in five between age 10 and 14 worked for pay (three in five between 15 and 18 employed)
- Many worked in "sweatshops" (word first coined 1892)
- In cities, one Lost child in six worked at some point as "newsie" hawking headlines—including **Irving Berlin**, **Jack Dempsey**, **Al Jolson**, **William O. Douglas**, **Groucho Marx**, **Earl Warren**
- Later as rising adults, this generation of grown-up entrepreneurs resisted collective action
- Despite tight labor market, union memberships declined from nearly 5 million in 1921 to under 3.5 million in 1929
- **Consumer culture**: No other generation purchased such large share of total consumption with self-earned income
- Lost pocket cash sustained America's child-only retailers (candy stores, toy shops, nickelodeons)
- Nationally marketed sweets: jelly beans, Tootsie Rolls, Hershey Bars, bubble gum
- From 1889 to 1922, Lost sweet tooth propelled doubling in per capita sugar consumption (to about 100 pounds annually)
- In 1920s, "sugar" became term of endearment
- **Education decline**: From first cohort to last, Lost youths showed little improvement in rates of illiteracy, absenteeism, dropout, or college entry
- From 1880 to 1900, share of all white children in primary schools dropped from 62 to 54 percent; for black children, 34 to 31 percent
- When Lost young men took "I.Q." tests during World War I, results convinced scientific community that draftees had "mental age" of under 12
- During 1920s, "threat of feeble-minded" turned many midlife voters against immigration
- Missionary psychologist **Henry Goddard** coined technical terms ("moron," "idiot," "imbecile") to identify every gradation of stupidity
- After Henry Ford seized upon Lost bent for ciphers and statistics, learning gap between elderly and nonelderly rapidly widened
- In 1970, educational disparity between adults over 25 (averaged 12.2 years schooling) and adults over 65 (averaged 8.7 years)—largest ever measured this century
- **Drug culture**: Lost were America's first generation to grow up amid widespread adult-approved narcotics use
- In 1900, while opium and chloral consumption still rising, many newly synthesized drugs entering market: including paraldehyde, sulphonal, veronal, heroin
- Cocaine or coca—wondrous midlife discovery to **Sigmund Freud**, **Sherlock Holmes**, and like-aged Progressives in America—routinely consumed: cough syrup, lozenges, and (until 1904) **Coca-Cola**
- Yet when Missionaries rose to power on eve of World War I, Lost took most of blame for drug-related violence and crime
- **Crime rates**: From 1900 to 1920, while Lost came of age, America's homicide rate rose by 700 percent
- Just before peaked in early 1930s, Lost street hoodlums matured into America's fiercest-ever gangsters: **Al Capone**, **Frank Costello**, **Lucky Luciano**, **Dutch Schultz**, **Legs Diamond**
- Lost coined words: "underworld," "gangster," "mobster," "racketeer," "moll," "getaway car"
- Equally inventive with lexicon of music and sex: "get hep," "jive," "cat," "cathouse," "floozy," "party girl," "trick," "fast" or "loose" woman, "sugar daddy," "boy-crazy," "hot pants"
- **1918 Influenza**: Deadliest epidemic in American history (fatal mostly to young adults), killed about 250,000 Lost—five times number who died in combat during World War I
- Because later disease took unusually high toll on Lost (or toxic industrial chemicals), Lost's unusually high rate of Parkinson's disease in old age attributed
- From early 1950s through 1960s, as Lost replaced Missionaries as elders, old-age mortality rates stopped falling
- Last-wave Lost males showed no gain over first-wave Missionary males in life expectancy, age 65
- **Suicide**: At age 20 (1910), Lost were 50 percent more suicide-prone than last-wave Missionaries had been at age 20 (1900)
- From same comparison, Lost have been more suicide-prone than next three generations—G.I.s, Silent, Boom—at every phase of life
- In longitudinal surveys taken in 1960s and 1970s, Lost scored higher in "suspicion" and lower in "self-sentiment" than later-born G.I.s at same age
- **Great Migration**: Lost accounted for first black "Great Migration" out of rural South into urban North
- After growing up during rise of **Jim Crow** and coming of age during Dixon-era job boom, about 1.5 million black Americans emigrated out of South from 1910 to 1930—nearly three times prior number of black emigrants since Civil War
- **Immigration**: With nine million members born abroad, Lost is (in absolute numbers) America's largest immigrant generation
- Unprecedented proportion came from Eastern and Southern Europe, many Jewish
- Of all Americans today over age 85, one in six is naturalized citizen (one in three in New York and New England)—far higher share than any other living generation
- **Political leadership**: Lost attained majority share of Congressional seats and governorships later in lifecycle (fifty-eight years after first birthyear) than any other American generation
- On per-cohort basis, no other generation been as weakly represented in national leadership posts over lifetime
- **Republican leaning**: Throughout adult lives, Lost have been most Republican-leaning of generations
- As elected congressmen, more likely than elder Missionaries to oppose New Deal in late 1930s
- As voters, chose **Willkie** in 1940, split roughly 50-50 for **Goldwater** in 1964, gave **Reagan** biggest generational proportions in 1980 and 1984
- As Presidential contenders, mostly Republican: **Alfred Landon**, **Wendell Willkie**, **Dwight Eisenhower**, **"Mr. Republican" Robert Taft**
- Two others were third-party: **Norman Thomas** and **Henry Wallace**
- One incumbent Democrat **Harry Truman** won (barely) once; one other Democratic contender **Adlai Stevenson** (sadly) lost twice
- **Economic hardship**: Hit by Great Depression during midlife earning years, Lost occupied one age bracket never targeted by New Deal relief program
- After war, as G.I.s built and inhabited sparkling suburbs, Lost mostly stayed put
- Nearly half never lived in house or apartment with more than two bedrooms and bathroom
- In 1985, compared to typical G.I. retiree in late sixties, surviving Lost elder (age 85+, at least twenty years older) had one-third less total income, received one-fifth less in Social Security, far less likely to have private pension or own home, and roughly twice as likely to live in poverty

### Lost Lifecycle

#### Youth

- In 1897, 8-year-old **Virginia O'Hanlon** wrote *New York Sun* asking: "Is there a Santa Claus?"
- Many in class, hostile to Gilded, were anti-Santa skeptics—chances they were, reassured by *Sun*'s answer
- Children of 1890s were America's most tough-minded ever, growing up fast amid gangs, drugs, saloons, big-city immigration, emotional climate raging with uncontained fervor and social reform
- Few turn-of-century parents knew how to protect their nests
- Often permissive to point of near-neglect, following "Don't give them" advice of 1890s-era parent counselor **Hannah Smith**
- **George Burns** recalled bedtime mother "would stand there with door open. When house was full she'd close it. Sometimes I made it, sometimes I slept in hall"
- Fiftyish Progressive **Jacob Riis**, stepping into tenement, noted "the hall is dark and you might stumble over children's things back there. Not that it would hurt them; kicks and cuffs are their daily diet. They have little else"
- Unsupervised by parents or governments, children surged into labor market—girls as piece-rate "homeworkers," boys as newsies, bootblacks, scavengers, messengers, "cash boys," nonunion cigar-rollers, ten-hours-a-day coal miners
- What they earned (and parents didn't take away), they spent: few pennies in hand became ticket to world of playful consumption
- Although Dewey-style "progressive" educational reforms already in full gear, Lost kids found school irrelevant next to grim realities of street life
- "School was all wrong," complained **Harpo Marx**: "School simply didn't teach you how to be poor and live from day to day"
- (Harpo "dropped out" when classroom toughs threw him out window when teacher wasn't looking)
- When suited them, Lost children mingled well with adults, but hardened precocity sat badly with blues-focused elders
- **Adams** coined kids' jaunty consumerism, **Bryan** their cynicism, **Theodore Roosevelt** ruthlessness of their football (eighteen players died on field in 1905 alone)
- Roosevelt's daughter **Alice**—smoking, swearing, sipping champagne in White House—became headline-grabbing symbol of child generation growing up "bad"
- Progressive **G. Stanley Hall** was first to ascribe moral development to sex drive rather than to religion: "Never has youth been exposed to such dangers of both perversion and arrest as in our own land and day"
- **Thomas Wolfe** soon wondered "what has happened to spontaneous gaiety of youth": "children were without innocence, born old and dull and empty... suckled on darkness, and weaned on violence and noise"
- "They tried to shut their eyes," recalled **Malcolm Cowley**, "and not open them until he met when he was a hustling street urchin. 'We children did not shut our eyes. We saw and knew.' Some did well, but a larger number did badly"
- Living and dying by their new credo "It's up to you," these "kids" were already paying dues of independence

#### Coming of Age

- "We have in our unregenerate youth... been forced to become realistic," declared 23-year-old **John Carter** shortly after Armistice
- "At 17 we were disillusioned and weary," recalled **Malcolm Cowley**
- Lost came of age hearing sixtyish Progressives describe how civilization must inexorably climb to higher and Edwardizing end (including San Francisco earthquake and sinking of *Titanic*)
- They watched Missionaries rise to power pontificating about society whose seamy and rapacious underside—from sweatshop children and young prostitutes to widespread drug abuse and gang violence—only teenagers could see
- Most 20-year-olds turned deaf ear toward older, campus-touring radicals like **Jack London** and **Upton Sinclair**: "College students are more conservative than their professors because they too often regard college as back door to business"
- Well before World War I, first signs of alienation surfaced
- In 1908, youthful **Van Wyck Brooks** wrote *Wine of Puritans*, title popularizing word fresh Ivy League graduates (in *Seven Arts*) would soon paste on next-elders
- In 1913, magazines proclaimed "Sex O'Clock in America," announcing what soon became known as "revolution in morals"
- Then came **"Flapper of 1915,"** who (reported **Mencken**) "has forgotten how to simper; she seldom blushes; it is impossible to shock her"
- These youth crosscurrents came together in **World War I**—war they would call "sausage machine," ultimate evidence of elders' colossal blindness

#### Rising Adulthood

- **Hemingway**, **Dos Passos**, **Cowley**, and **cummings** all volunteered as ambulance drivers, immediate eyewitnesses to worst carnage
- "Abstract words such as glory, honor, courage, or hallow were obscene beside concrete names of villages, numbers of roads, names of rivers, numbers of regiments and dates," wrote **Hemingway**
- After inept young intellectuals lingered in Paris ("I prefer to starve where food is good," chided **Virgil Thompson**), most doughboys returned home to nation firmly in Missionary control
- There, wrote **Fitzgerald**, "men of fifty had gall" to tell veterans of 30 how to behave
- Lost "Flaming Youth" instinctively bucked and turned toward pleasure-seeking
- Already by 1915, **Bruce Barton** was publishing **"Young Man's Jesus,"** almost parody of Missionary evangelism, urging "those who are this side of thirty-five to unite and take back our Jesus... a young man glowing with physical strength and joy of living" and possessing "our bounding pulses, our hot desires"
- Soon after war, **Sinclair Lewis** scored two more salvos in *Main Street* and *Elmer Gantry*
- Triggering "the roar" of Twenties, Lost prompted Missionaries to roar back about "Problem of the Younger Generation"
- The Lost knew they were bad, yet refused to take all heat
- In 1920 *Atlantic Monthly* article "These Wild Young People" By One of Them," **Carter** observed "magazines have been crowded with pessimistic descriptions of younger generation"—but added, "older generation has certainly pretty well ruined this world before passing it on to us"

#### Midlife

- "The shows were broader, the buildings were higher, the morals were looser, and the liquor was cheaper," **Fitzgerald** wrote from New York City in 1926, at height of fun, "but all these did not really minister to much delight. Young people were too curious—they were hard and languid.... The city was bloated, glutted, stupid with cakes and circuses, and new expression, 'O yeah!' summed up all enthusiasm"
- Uptown, Lost blacks streaming in from South touched off cultural explosion
- **Garveyism** held out new hopes of racial independence
- **Claude McKay** wrote *Home to Harlem*
- **Alain Locke** on birth of "the Negro Age"
- Free of "cautious moralisms" and "trammels of Puritanism"
- **DuBois** and other older Missionaries did not always approve: "leaders of NAACP," wrote black literary historian **Sterling Brown**, "felt that characterization of Harlem sweet-backs and hot mammas did injustice to their propaganda and purposes"
- But music named after black idiom for sex—"jazz"—drew crowds of white urbanites and put stamp on era of youthful hedonism and what-you-see-is-what-you-get cynicism
- **A male bootlegger** built entrepreneurial empires in defiance of Prohibition
- **Dorothy Parker** and **Zelda Fitzgerald** disappointed older suffragettes: "The Jazz Age... had no interest at all in politics"
- But if ideas were languid, Lost dancing was "jitterbug" kinetic
- These 30-year-olds cherished money, leisure, style—from chromy Art Deco and *Metropolis* futurism to Arabian luxury
- Lost-directed movies scorched audiences with what one producer called "neckers, petters, white kisses, red kisses, pleasure-mad daughters, sensation-craving mothers"

#### Great Depression

- By their early forties, Lost entrepreneurs were inventing supermarkets and shopping centers, soda fountains and cafeterias, frozen foods and automats—all for faster pace of living
- "Self-help" experts **Dale Carnegie** and **Norman Vincent Peale** knew how to counsel generation that cared far more about success than expressing feeling of self-worth
- ("Win, win, win... but always avoid the pronoun 'I.'")
- As **Fitzgerald** declared about it as best revenge: "living well is best revenge"
- Great Gatsby pined after Daisy—"her voice is full of money"
- "Kingfish" **Huey Long** made points with luckless in Louisiana by declaring "every man a king" and then picking every man's pockets
- Like spikes jabbed high into home plate, Lost directed their most savage competitive instincts against their own peers
- Mood swung darkening in 1927 with medium Edison darkening **Nicola Sacco** and **Bartolomeo Vanzetti**, pathetic victims of Missionary zeal
- Wrote **Vanzetti** bitterly just before death: "Our words—our lives—our pain: nothing! 'For de little stealin' dey gits you in jail soon or late. 'For de big stealin' dey makes you emperor and put you in de Hall o' Fame when you croaks"
- Some 1929 **St. Valentine's Day Massacre** shocked public opinion ("lousy public relations," admitted **Capone**)
- **Sinclair Lewis** ridiculed "chilly enthusiasms" of older New Humanists, but in *A Preface to Morals* **Walter Lippmann** reflected ominously on his generation's mental and ethical chaos
- **Fitzgerald** kept his room full of calendars and clocks, ticking away toward collective "crash" his peers could sense was coming
- Few (like **Joseph Kennedy**) sold out just in time, but typical youngish investor had bad luck to buy into market relatively late, making bust all more painful

#### Malcolm Cowley called 1930 year of "doubt and even defeat"

- For his generation—year of broken friendships, sudden poverty, suicide
- Start of collective midlife hangover: **the Great Depression**
- Party over and their style suddenly repudiated, Lost faced this future armed only with courage of despair
- "Now once more the belt is tight and we summon up proper expression of horror as we look back at our wasted youth," observed **Fitzgerald**, though suspected his was "generation with no second acts"
- Alienation of 1920s-era intellectuals now reached poor and rural
- Sullen "Hooverville" filled with unemployed men approaching prime of life without hope
- Since jobs scarce, priority went to household heads—narrowing women's horizons in unemployed husbands as "breadwinner" failures
- Assuming social responsibilities of midlife, Lost gave 1930s their gritty quality: "Everything depends on use to
<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## G.I. Generation

**Born:** 1901-1924
**Type:** Civic

### Age Location
- **Great Depression-World War II Crisis** in rising adulthood
- **Boom Awakening** in elderhood

### Defining Characteristics

**Charles Lindbergh's transatlantic flight (1927)** epitomized the young G.I. spirit—special, sheltered, optimistic about technology. By the 1950s, as **John F. Kennedy** declared commitment to moon landing, G.I.s were "the best damned kids in the world"—**victorious soldiers, Minuteman missile builders, interstate highway engineers, Apollo rocket creators, miracle vaccine developers**—"Tomorrow's men" who knew how to get things done.

> "uncommon valor was a common virtue" — Inscription on Iwo Jima shrine

### Generational Self-Image

The **"good-kid" first wave** and **heroic last wave** produced enormous **economic and political power**. **Henry Malcolm** describes them as a generation of **"Prometheus men"**—with "implicit belief in progress and in the central role of great men."

**Superman** conceived by two Interbellum cartoonists perfectly captures G.I. persona: the special child, corrupt older (Lost) Lex Luthor, rocklike manliness, unvarying success of Superpower mission used for community good. In **Ayn Rand's** terms, they embodied "single faculty of mind: I will"—became consummate mid-20th-century **"technocrats"**, producing what **Seymour Martin Lipset** termed "the shift away from ideology toward sociology."

### Cultural Influence

**B.F. Skinner's** fictional utopia *Walden Two* epitomized peers' confidence they could design and build their way to social bliss—no need for transcending to new consciousness. Most influential new religion: **L. Ron Hubbard's Scientology**. Most enduring prophecy images: **Billy Graham** and **Charlton Heston** before thousands.

### Gender Dynamics

Came of age preferring **crisp sex-role definitions**. Raised under Missionary influence, matured into **father-worshiping and heavily male-fixated generation**. Rising adults came to disdain women's influence in public life.

> "Generals want obedient women, mom is a jerk" — **Philip Wylie**, *Generation of Vipers*

**Betty Friedan** (*Modern Woman: The Lost Sex*, *Educating Our Daughters*) launched frontal assault on feminist assumptions—but after war, G.I. women's books like these had succeeded in creating **"Father Knows Best" culture** and political vocabulary where greatest **"witchhunt"** insults were **"simpering"** or **"slobbering"**—challenges against virility.

### Personality Traits

The initials **"G.I."** stand for two things—**"general issue"** and **"government issue"**. This generation's lifecycle stood squarely for both. Developed **instinct for "team players"**—placed high priority on being **"general"** or **"regular"** throughout lives. **Historian Paula Fass** labels them a **"peer society"**—harmonious community of group-enforced virtue.

**Collegialism** energized America's V-for-victory wartime mood. Highways once frivolous turned into **identical-looking military vehicle convoys**. Postwar society reached pinnacle in **"Wonder Bread" blandness**, **"Spic and Span" kitchens**, **borrow-a-mower neighborliness**.

Even during **McCarthy hearings**, G.I.s sat on both sides of table dressed in same gray suits—**no little boxes**, all look the same. Personality carried strong **"government issue" flavor**—extraordinary association with growth of modern government activity, much directed toward whatever age bracket they occupied.

### Lifecycle Government Benefits

**Federal government directed attention to G.I. age bracket throughout lifecycle:**
- Childhood: **White House Conference on Children (1909)**, **U.S. Children's Bureau (1912)**, first federal child labor law (1916)
- Old age: **White House Conference on Aging (1961)**, first federal age-discrimination law (1967), **National Institute on Aging (1974)**
- When G.I. born in 1910 turned 19, federal government consumed <3% of nation's economic product; at age 70, consumed >22%

### American Exceptionalism

G.I.s regarded their own **civic-mindedness as proof of American exceptionalism**—belief (per **Daniel Bell**) that "having been born free, America would in trials of history get off scot free."

> "America always stands 'on the threshold of a great ability to produce, do more, be more'" — 73-year-old **Ronald Reagan** (1985)

**"Lucky Lindy"** to **"Joltin' Joe"** to **"Happy Hubble"** to **"the Teflon President"**—generation spent lifetime personifying **imprescriptibility of modern America**. Even **80-year-old physicist Edward Teller** testifying for Strategic Defense Initiative answered nitpickers: **"Let me plead guilty to the great crime of optimism."**

### G.I. Facts

**Demographic Trends:**
- From first to last wave, been **generation of trends**—always in directions most people thought better: **lower suicide/crime rates, higher aptitudes, greater educational attainment, increased voter participation, rising confidence in government**

**Child Labor Decline:**
- Rate of child labor fell by half during G.I. youth era—**largest one-generation decline ever**
- First boys/girls whose pin money came from **"allowances"** for good behavior, not earnings
- Mid-1920s to early 1930s: proportion doing family dishes rose from 32% to 52%, even as more adults remained at home

**Health Improvements:**
- Swifter improvement than any other American generation
- From 1900-1924 cohorts: infant/child mortality fell by 80%, adult height rose >1 inch, life expectancy at age 65 rose by 20%
- Raised on **pasteurized milk, safely packaged foods, "vitamins"**

**Educational Achievement:**
- **Largest one-generation jump in educational achievement** in American history
- Lost to G.I.: average length of schooling rose from 9th to 12th grade, share attending college tripled, average high school science score rose sharply
- Proportion of high school students taking **foreign languages fell from 83% (pre-WWI) to 21% (WWII-era)**
- Campus experienced sharp decline in **"missionary" organizations** (religious/social) during 1920s—practically disappeared during 1930s

**Scouting Organizations:**
- Nearly entire array of modern scouting organizations founded by midlife Missionaries when first-wave G.I.s reaching puberty: **Boy Scouts (1910), Camp Fire Girls (1910), Girl Scouts (1912), Boys and Girls Clubs (1914)**
- As young adults, 2.5 million wore CCC forest green; 80% of all G.I. men wore uniform in wartime—**highest proportion for any American generation**

**Political Leadership:**
- Best-known **Lost heroes were individuals** (Eddie Rickenbacker, Jimmy Doolittle); G.I. heroes were **team heroes** (flag-raisers at Iwo Jima, Boys of D-Day, Seabees)
- **Knute Rockne** and **George Gipp** were Lost; **"Four Horsemen"** were G.I.s
- From 1930s forward, G.I.s backed winning candidate in every election
- In three close elections (1948, 1960, 1968), G.I.s tipped outcome to preferred candidate
- **80% of first-wave G.I. voters opted for FDR in 1932 and 85% in 1936**—largest single-generation mandates ever recorded
- By midlife/elderhood, 65% confirmed allegiance to Democratic Party
- First generation of blacks to abandon Party of Lincoln: **82% of Harlem blacks under 44 voted for FDR in 1944**, vs only 59% over that age

**Presidential Power:**
- Held White House for **thirty years**, won **nine Presidential elections**, run on major-party tickets twelve straight times (spanning forty-four years between 1944 and 1988)
- No other generation of Republicans comes close to these numbers

**Nobel Prizes:**
- Won **ninety-nine Nobel Prizes**, roughly two-thirds of all Nobels awarded to Americans
- Dominated prizes for **physics, chemistry, medicine**
- Through 1989: won all of America's **fourteen economics Nobels**
- Other generations eclipsed G.I.s in **literature and peace prizes**

**Economic Mobility:**
- Experienced **"American Dream"** of upward mobility more than any other generation this century
- Six in seven G.I.s report having **faced less difficult financing** than parents—**highest proportion ever recorded**
- 1940: 46% of houses owner-occupied; 1960: 64%—remained roughly constant ever since
- Homeownership never more affordable than early 1950s: typical 35-year-old's income was $3,000/year, mortgage rates 4%, new Levittown home sold for $7,000 ($350 down, $30/month)

**Elder Affluence:**
- **Most affluent elders of the 20th century** by far
- Where Lost elders (1960) had highest poverty rate of any age bracket, G.I.s (today) have **lowest**
- When public benefits included as income, G.I. elders tower over younger adults in rates of **homeownership, discretionary income, household net worth**
- 1988: 47% of G.I.s **"almost never" worry about finances**—least worrying of living generations

**Senior Citizen Movement:**
- G.I. first-wavers sparked modern **"senior citizen" movement**
- G.I. last-wavers benefited most from it
- America's first (and largest) retirement community, **Sun City**, founded 1960
- Social Security retirement age lowered to 62 for men (1962)
- Medicare extended (1965)
- Largest rise in Social Security benefit levels occurred 1972-1981
- Membership of elder organizations and circulation of **"senior" newspapers** grew sixtyfold between early 1960s and late 1970s
- By 1990, **AARP** had become largest and wealthiest advocacy organization in nation's history

**Federal Benefits Growth:**
- 1950s-early 1960s (Lost reaching age 65): federal benefits per elderly person rose less rapidly than average wage
- 1965-1989 (G.I.s reaching age 65): federal benefits per elderly person rose **fifteen times more rapidly than wages** (<20% in inflation-adjusted dollars)
- 1989: total federal benefits averaged >$14,000 per elderly household
- Social Security and Medicare benefits paid back most G.I.s for **entire value of prior payroll tax contributions** (including employer contributions and interest) within four years after retiring
- 1990 deficit reduction law imposed 1991 maximum of **$41 in extra Medicare charges per G.I. beneficiary**, up to **$2,137 in extra Medicare taxes per younger worker**

**Old Age Satisfaction:**
- G.I.s remained **most upbeat** (or, as they put it, **"copacetic"**) generation of their time
- 1957-1976: share of elderly feeling "very high" on psychological scale of anxiety fell from 22% to 15% (while corresponding anxieties for younger age brackets rose sharply)
- 1990 survey of surviving Harvard class of 1940 (median net worth $865,000): **88% insisted they were "fairly or very happy"**
- **Happiness was of this world, not the next**: 41% reported **"not religious at all"**

### The G.I. Lifecycle

#### YOUTH

**1904:** Muckraker **John Spargo's** *The Bitter Cry of the Children* augured Missionary determination to do better for new generation, join forces and seal off child's world from urban danger and adult vice.

**"milk station" movement** culminated in widespread pasteurization. **Little Mothers' Leagues** advised parents. **"Don't give the baby beer to drink."** Major purpose of **Prohibition**: push alcohol away from presence of children.

**Protective food movement** produced capital investment in food processing growing faster than any other industry 1914-1929. Businesses facing public outcry/legal punishment. Missionaries determined to see offspring grow up as **"clean-cut"** as world being created for them.

Popular literature idealized children who were **modest, cheerful, deferential to adults**. *Literary Digest* demanded **"a reassertion of parental authority."**

**Missionary parents proclaimed first Mother's Day (1908) and Father's Day (1910)**, founded new scouting organizations to redirect **"gang instinct"** to useful purpose. Public education showed parallel interest in instilling skills of **productive citizenship**.

**"Lexr experiments" replaced by "vocational" education** ("home economics" for girls, "industrial education" for boys). First time ever, more teens in class than out, making school important socializing force.

**Golden era of the high school** arose, well captured in **Glee movie musicals** of Warner Rooney and Judy Garland—work hard, play by rules, everybody gets reward.

Upon reaching adolescence, peer society building they would retain through life. Adults encouraged kids to police themselves under **resolute grip of adult authority** that grew tighter each advancing decade.

**"Standardized youth culture"** emerged: teens watched same movies, listened to same radio songs, picked at Rose Bowl and other **100,000-seat stadia** to cheer same sporting events. **Fine fraternities and sororities** imposed rigid pressures on youths to stay within bounds of normal, administered ritual of **"rating and dating"** (understood lists of **"dos and don'ts"**). Those too forward/too shy faced peer disapproval.

By mid-1920s, word **"kid"** shifted meaning from word of derision to one of praise. **Lost Joseph Krotch** described juniors as **"not rebellious, or cynical, or even melancholy. They do what they are told, believe what they are told, and hope for the best."**

> "Did other generations ever laugh so hard together, drink and dance so hard, or do crazier things just for the hell of it?" — **Lost Malcolm Cowley**

#### COMING OF AGE

**"Ours was the best generation,"** said **Gene Shuford** of late 1920s, contrasting his circle with Cowley's. **"Underneath we really thought we were all right, that man in general was all right."**

Within few years, Shuford's "best" found themselves part of what *Harper's* magazine described as **"Locked-Out Generation"** of Great Depression, **"all dressed up with no place to go."** Even so, youth spirit stayed high.

With emphasis on **planning, optimism, collective action**, **Roosevelt's New Deal** perfectly suited twentyish mind-set. **National Youth Administration and Civilian Conservation Corps** kept them busy: marching in formation, never complaining, getting things done, building things that worked, things that lasted to this day.

When President Roosevelt reshuffled economic deck in favor of aggressive young over the genteel older generation, running behind FDR in popularity among youths:

> "I promise as a good American citizen to do my part for the NRA" — chanted 100,000 young people on Boston Common (1933), urged by James Curley and Visionary mayor

> "I will help President Roosevelt bring back good times" — But sluggish economy deferred careers and marriage, prompting many students' interest in "apple-pie radicalism" more economic than cultural or moral

Even most committed ideologues agreed with FDR-backing peers that main argument was over what system **"worked"** best. One young communist bulletin defended members as **"no different from other people except that we believe in different materialism."**

**Collective action flourished**, especially among unionizing young workers in assembly-line industries. Winter/spring 1936-1937: nearly half million engaged in **sit-down strikes**, prodded by G.I.-dominated Congress of Industrial Organizations.

**Charles Lindbergh's** autobiographical *We* to **Mary McCarthy's** *The Group* became, in historian **Warren Susman's** words, **"the decade of participation and belonging."**

Young novelists like **John Steinbeck** (*Grapes of Wrath*) shunned Lost elite cynicism and instead looked forward to solving problems, especially with aid of big government.

**37-year-old Walt Disney** released **smash box-office hit**, *Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs*, featured **innocent maidenhood and cheerful male teamwork** ("whistle while you work") defeating designs of brooding witch. **Lost critic Westbrook Pegler** praised film as **"happiest thing that has happened in this world since the Armistice."**

**Enter World War II.** Movie *From Here to Eternity* portrays prewar soldiers evolving into selfish **"lone wolves"** despised by most peers. Then Japan attacks—and, instantly, **soldiers forget personal feuds and rally together** into machinelike action.

> "That is what Pearl Harbor did for this generation, galvanizing 'good kid' ingot into G.I. steel"

While G.I. scientists in late thirties designed atomic bomb, marines in twenties swarmed ashore, soon followed by **bulldozer operators of the Seabees**. (**Then motto:** "The difficult we do at once; the impossible takes a bit longer.")

**Like-aged Rosie the Riveter** comprised only significant female wartime workforce in nation's history. Young generation repeatedly expressed **admiration for elders** who were leading them to victory.

> **Roosevelt was "the man we had grown up under"** — said *Yank* magazine of the Missionary "Commander in Chief, not only of the armed forces, but of our generation"

While **Mary Martin** sang *My Heart Belongs to Daddy*, **Bing Crosby** marched with combat buddies to tune: **"We'll follow the old man wherever he wants to go."** In public eye, these kids in khaki could do no wrong.

**Lost General Patton's** famous slap of younger soldier caused bigger fuss than belief that a G.I. might have had it coming. World War II killed **1.5% of G.I. men**; among 97% who emerged without serious injury, experience gave confidence (as one World War I Mead later put it) to **"experience dangers that would test their mettle... among their peers."**

Many would never again know such **responsibility, excitement, world conqueror status**—emerging as world conquerors, they laid claim to heroism that, later in life, would blossom into **sense of entitlement**.

#### RISING ADULTHOOD

> "A good job, a mild future, and a little house big enough for me and my wife" — This was ambition of average G.I. in **Maxwell Taylor's** *The Best Years of Our Lives*

Not since Revolution had war veterans enjoyed such praise and tangible reward from appreciative elders. Thanks to **"G.I. Bill,"** two of every five 1950-era dollars of outstanding housing debt covered by taxpayers, many of them older and living in housing worse than what young veterans could buy.

**Capital spending and real wages for young men boomed**—while payroll deductions to support Social Security retirees remained minuscule. Returning war heroes brought capital, no-nonsense attitude wherever they went—to campuses, to workplaces, to politics.

**Polls showed young adults more stern-minded than elders** on topics like Japanese occupation, use of poison gas, corporate punishment. Those who entered politics in late 1930s/1940s felt **scout leader's sense of duty** (like **Jimmy Stewart** in *Mr. Smith Goes to Washington*).

**By 1950, one G.I. (Dewey) had twice run for President**, two others (**Clark Clifford, George Kennan**) had become Truman's top advisers, several more (**John Kennedy, Richard Nixon, Lyndon Johnson, Gerald Ford**) had launched promising political careers.

In business, peers brought **wartime confidence and "high hopes"** into nation's ascendance—they made seemed to be **best (and biggest) in world**. **Stephen Bechtel's** company erected Hoover Dam and San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge, **Robert Moses** built massive public housing projects, **William Levitt** laid down/re gleaming suburban tract after another.

**Bell & Howell's dynamic young president, Charles Percy**, symbolized new breed of smart, get-things-done industrialists. Two brilliant fortyish executives (**Bob McNamara, Lee Iacocca**) prodded **American auto industry** to produce more functional autos.

From *Fortune* writers to **Committee on Economic Development**, 40-year-olds of both political parties agreed that **big government and big business** could both **"pitch in" and work together just fine**.

**William Whyte** catalogued suburban G.I. **"social ethic"** in *The Organization Man* that produced neighborhoods noteworthy mainly for **"friendliness."** Like **Sloan Wilson's** hero in *Man in the Gray Flannel Suit*, ideal male at once **hard-striving and selfless**, ideal female **crowded mother of flock of Boom kids**.

Soon no suburban house complete without **television**, new technology that perfectly expressed G.I. **culture: science turned for man's benefit**, unmittingly upbeat, nurturing children, helping adults keep abreast of collegial tastes.

Memorable collection of fortyish entertainers—**Lucille Ball, Phil Silvers, Jack Parr, Jackie Gleason, Art Linkletter**—showed **unrehearsed, on-air comfort** that other TV generations have never quite matched. From Hollywood to Levittown, G.I.s institutionalizing **most wholesome American culture of 20th century**.

> "We do not engage in loose talk about the 'ideals' of the situation and all the other stuff" — observed **C. Wright Mills** in *The Power Elite*. **"We are right down to the problem."**

Declaring *End to Ideology* (phrase coined by G.I.s in 1955), **Daniel Bell** noted how peers avoided **real-world challenges**, preferring to explore **differences in fundamental values**. **George Gallup** defined **"average man"** in society more eager to celebrate **sameness than differences** among people.

Rising black intelligentsia (**Ralph Ellison, Richard Wright**) applied **cool rationalism to race relations**; blacks began arguing (whites agreeing) that **"segregation"** was economically inefficient. Whatever his color, a G.I. generally considered **"what to do"** well-settled; only **"how to do it"** open to discussion.

**1958:** **John Kenneth Galbraith** bemoaned **"public squalor"** amid G.I. generation began surge to power in **Democratic landslide**. As 1960s approached, G.I.s waited impatiently for chance to bring **same boldness, order, competence** to public life that they already brought to economy and family.

Their only worry, admitted **Lipset** in 1960, was **"the problem of conformity which troubles so many Americans today"**—a G.I. trait already being blamed on younger Silent.

#### MIDLIFE

G.I. rise to national leadership shaped by **mission they recalled from childhood**: clean up squalor and decay left behind by Lost.

**Maxwell Taylor** criticized *The Uncertain Trumpet* and **Lost Presidents**. **Eric Sevareid** accused **"last generation"** of **"corruptibility"** and a **"lack of controlled plans,"** and main argument that **"had our young men saved, our diplomats and President Fritter frittered away."**

When watershed all-G.I. Presidential election of 1960 arrived, **mannish generation in forties and fifties** determined to apply its **"cogwheel political faith"** to rebuild American **"prestige,"** make nation (in **Bell's** words) **"a world power, a paramount power, a hegemonic power."**

**Few were living Missionaries** like **Robert Frost** at **Kennedy's inaugural**, heralded coming of new **"Augustan Age."** Having campaigned with slogan **"Let's Get This Country Moving Again,"** new President declared:

> "the torch has been passed to a new generation... tempered by war, disciplined by a hard and bitter peace"

In office, he brought **"vigor"** to governance and assembled like-aged advisers whom younger **David Halberstam** described as **"a new breed of thinker-doers"**—men like **Bob McNamara** ("the can-do man in the can-do society, in the can-do era") and **McGeorge Bundy** possessing **"a great and almost relentless instinct for power"**.

Meanwhile, **G.I. literary and media elite** joined in as team players (**Walter Cronkite, Chet Huntley and David Brinkley, Joseph and Stewart Alsop, Joseph Kraft, William Manchester, Arthur Schlesinger Jr., Theodore White**).

**1962:** **Richard Rovere** christened new expression, **"the establishment,"** to describe new power of midlife G.I.s. **John Kennedy's assassination** hardly caused them to break pace.

Ebullient **Lyndon Johnson** promptly declared: **"This nation is still young and powerful and full of great purpose."** In his nation's first chance to build **Great Society** in ensuing 1964 landslide, his G.I. senators reached their **pinnacle of power**.

**"Great 89th" Congress** (74% G.I.) became what **Theodore White** termed **"the Grandest Congress of Programs and Entitlements."** G.I. confidence—and hubris—was at **all-time high**.

> "Americans today bear themselves like victory-addicted champions" — said Look magazine (1965). **"They've won their wars and survived their depressions. They are accustomed to meeting, and beating, tests."**

With America now led by generation intent on meeting and beating new tests, **five-word "crisis"** (what **Richard Nixon** termed **"exquisite agony"**) repeatedly energized task of governing.

**Two years earlier,** **Cuban Missile Crisis** served (in **Dean Rusk's** words): **"we were eyeball to eyeball, and I think the other fellow just blinked."**

**Next came Vietnam.** **Robert McNamara's** new **"controlled response"** strategy replaced what had been known as the **(Lost-era) "spasm" response**. But Vietnam helped trigger angry **"generation gap"** between G.I. parents and coming-of-age Boomers, along with **substance abuse, exorcism, ideological passion**—in short, everything hateful to G.I. life mission.

By late 1960s, whatever G.I.s tried (whether **"Model Cities"** or **"guns and butter"** economics) began to sputter. From **Lyndon and Nixon** in White House to bosses on job and fathers in families, G.I. men came under constant attack from juniors and, increasingly, women.

If times were euphoric for youth, they were **anything but for G.I.s**: **"Everything seemed to come unhinged"** (**James MacGregor Burns**); **"Something has gone sour, in teaching and in learning"** (**George Wald**); **"I use the phrase soberly: The nation disintegrates"** (**John Gardner**).

In words revealing peers' frustration, **Richard Nixon** despaired that America had become **"a pitiful, helpless giant."** Others (**McNamara, Bundy**) came to share **Milton Mayer's** view that **"we were wrong, and the new generation is right"**—although, **Mayer** added, **"the young terrify me."**

#### ELDERHOOD

Ask today's seniors what movie touched them most as youths, many will answer ***Lost Horizon***, depression-era film with disturbing message about aging: that it is **hideous and ugly**, something that shouldn't happen in civic-minded community.

In 1946 poll, G.I.s showed **highest generational support for human euthanasia**. Through 1950s, G.I.s often looked upon old Lost as **tired, defeatist, and anti-progress**. They vowed **not to grow old the same way**.

Later on, when they entered elderhood themselves, they attacked what they termed **"myths"** of lonely, Lost-like old age—and worked hard to be **ever-optimistic, ever-energetic "senior citizens."**

Today, G.I.s rankle at younger people who assume they are unhappy; indeed, **majority insist their present phase of life is the best**. Where Missionaries are remembered for dressing dark (as though at play), **G.I.s make point of dressing bright** (as though at play).

As they listen to old **"swing" music** on **"Music of Your Life"** radio, they dwell on what they freely admit is **"square," "corny" culture**—culture that admits **neither to loneliness nor to suffering**. **Modern Maturity** magazine will not accept ads that mention **"pain, inflammation, suffer, hurt, ache, and flare-up"** because, says publishing director, **"it's pretty hard to present" these things "in an upbeat way."**

Under prodding from younger generations, **G.I.s have separated into elder version** of same peer society they first built in youth. After leaving labor force at younger age than any earlier generation, **they entered into a privately financed and publicly subsidized retirement**.

Part of implicit terms under which G.I.-Boom generation gap eased in early 1970s was through **understanding by which post-Vietnam fiscal "peace dividend" was spent almost entirely on G.I. retirees**.

**1972:** first election in which gray-lobby activism became critical, candidates **Wilbur Mills and Richard Nixon** abandoned prior opposition to **COLA inflation indexing**. Congress added **extra 20% benefit hike**, producing two-year jump in intergenerational transfer payments that dwarfed total size of Great Society poverty programs.

Over two decades, while G.I.s noted Boomers' weaker commitment to **spirit of community**, these seniors took themselves—and self-orientation they see around them—**only a few** (like **Maggie Kuhn's Gray Panthers**) adopted confrontational **"me first" Boomer tone**.

Instead, **"we generation" senior citizen movement** applied **patience, organizational know-how, teamwork** that G.I.s always carried through life—though now with new agenda and bottom-line results that **few other generations could ever hope for**.

> "You've already paid most of your dues. Now start collecting the benefits" — reads 1988 AARP membership appeal

So they have: **Half of all federal spending** is now consumed by pensions, medical and elderly entitlements, and **interest on national debt**—last representing **burden of today's unfunded consumption** on tomorrow's taxpayers.

During 1980s, **retiree benefits remained the one area of government** which no G.I. President or Silent Congress dared to touch. Likewise, **deficit spending became one fiscal device** which finds few visceral critics among generation that came of age during New Deal.

Where Lost elders once preferred to **attack public spending and leave taxes alone**, G.I. elders lean other way and have provided **core of modern tax revolt**, from **Ronald Reagan** and **Howard Jarvis** (of California's **Proposition 13**) to end all-time membership in **antitax lobbies**.

Their rising influence enabled them to separate socially into America's first **"seniors only" communities**, often far away from grown-up children. There G.I.s show **vigor and cheerfulness** that bring to mind best of their **"seniors-eat-here" culture**.

In **Sun City**, observes homeowner **Ken Dychtwald**, they mention **"it's hard to find time to talk to people; they're too active and busy."** **"Sun City is secure,"** he concludes, showing **"small tidy streets with surprise, of unpleasantness, or unsightliness"**.

> "The streets are uncommonly clean. I don't know where I could go that is so involved with the community."

Similarly, **G.I.s' material well-being** enabled them to continue in accustomed roles as **trustees of wealth, givers of gifts, accepters of college bills-and providers** (or backstops) for extended families.

**No elder generation ever been so relied upon to foot bill for family indulgences**. In 1987/1988, grandparents accounted for **22% of all toy purchases**—and rapidly growing market in **grandchildren's educational expenses**. Nor has any elder generation made more **down payments** to enable grown children to buy houses which, back in 1950s, **G.I.s could easily afford without parental help**. (For today's young adults, reports *Time* magazine, **"G.I. benefit" has now come to mean "Good In-laws."**)

Among elder G.I.s whose children have divorced, **30% report that newly single son or daughter soon arrives** on doorstep. But if Silent and Boom children frequently ask for G.I. assistance with economic problems, they **do not seek elder help nearly so often on questions of values or basic life direction**.

**G.I. role as powerful stewards of American material life** has left them feeling **more friendly than wise**—more comfortable with active themselves than inspiring young to action.

> "In our time as children, grandparents were the teachers, advisors, counselors. It seems to me the tradition from which their own peers 'have been robbed completely.'" — anthropologist **Dorian Apple**

**Erik Erikson** found in cultures throughout world, **"indulgent grandparents are associated with societies... where grandparents are dissociated with authority."** Erikson's wife and collaborator, **Joan**, recently observed how **"when we looked at the lifecycle in our forties, we looked to old people for wisdom."** Now, she laments, **"lots of old people don't get wise."**

Whatever wisdom G.I.s do have to offer, they **lack the pulpit to proclaim it**, owing to their **early retirement and recent Boom takeover** of positions in media. **1989 survey** found **not a single prominent journalist over age 65 at work in an American newsroom**.

In public life, **last prominent G.I.s assert power more than principle**—**"better with deeds than with plans or words,"** to use (Silent) **Senator Lautenberg's** description of **George Bush**, then busy ordering ships and planes and tanks to Persian Gulf.

In family life, **their worldly dinners at country club** leaves them troubled by what **Dychtwald** describes as **"lack of respect and appreciation."** From Oval Office to family dinner table, elder G.I.s often feel they **don't get enough personal deference** from young people—certainly not what they remember offering their own elder Missionary parents.

---

**G.I. Legacy Assessment:**

> "We've done the work of democracy, day by day" — **George Bush** proudly declared of his generation (1989)

Whatever G.I.s touched, they **made bigger**—and, in their eyes, **better**. Their accomplishments colossal. G.I.s patiently endured **economic despair** that might have driven another generation to revolution. They ably soldiered one war America could not afford to lose.

Thanks to powerful work ethic and willingness to invest, they produced **postwar economic miracle** that ultimately outperformed optimist prognostications. Their **massive stockpiles of nuclear weapons** preserved enduring if expensive and unnerving peace.

They have been **truly great generation of scientists**, landing men on moon and cracking riddles of human longevity. Their women may have been **most dedicated teachers and most skillful mothers** in American history. In countless ways, **from transistors and satellites to spacious family homes** and buoyant **"GNP"** (term they invented), G.I.s gave **institutional firmament** to **"Brotherhood of Man"** envisioned by beloved Missionary fathers.

In recent years, find of retirement details of G.I. notables often prompted remarks from Americans of all ages that **no one will be able to replace their competence**.

**Yet their final ledger also includes colossal debits:** unprecedented public and private liabilities, exported assets, depleted resources, harms to global environment. **Generation that inherited so much excess economic capacity** and harnessed it to so many public purposes is bequeathing to successors **fiscally starved economy unable to afford generous agenda**.

**The offspring of soldiers G.I.s conquered**—**Japanese and German**—are today **out-competing their own children** and **eclipsing American economic might**. Powerful G.I. sense of exceptionalism makes them **think their own constructions** can last forever, that **Reaganomics-style optimism can produce its own reward**.

But those **early-life virtues—selflessness, investment, community**—have given way to **repetition of old habits without old purposes** and without old focus on future.

**To G.I.s, Tomorrowland once meant monorails and moonwalks**; now it means **space-age medicine in the intensive-care unit**. With their time coming to close, **G.I.s have difficulty articulating** what **Bush** calls **"the vision thing"**—setting directions for new century many will not live to see.

From **George Kennan** to **Lillian Hellman**, **Eric Sevareid** to **Theodore White**, **Ann Landers** to **Ronald Reagan**, elder G.I.s voice **distress over steady loss** in the
<!-- p. 320 -->

## THIRTEENTH GENERATION

**Born:** 1961-1981
**Type:** Reactive

**Age Location:** Boom Awakening in youth

### The Smooth Creeping Calm of the Thirteenth Generation

- **November 1979**: Iranian mob swarmed U.S. Embassy in Tehran; University of Georgia student center screened the movie *Patton* showing students in a standoffish ovation, then an effigy of the Ayatollah burning, followed by anti-Iran slogans chanting in the streets
- New breed of college freshmen came to America's campuses that year
- Previously, faculty members had lined up to introduce themselves; suddenly, as a Georgetown campus minister put it, "students began lining up to introduce themselves to us"
- Met the smooth opening wedge of the **THIRTEENTH GENERATION**—what *Washington Post* writer **Nancy Smith** pointedly calls "the generation after. Born after 1960, after you, after it all happened."

### Demographic Snapshot

- The babies of 1961, 8-year-olds of Woodstock
- 13-year-olds of Watergate
- 18-year-olds of energy crisis and hostage humiliation
- 29-year-olds when a 1990 *Time* cover story defined this generation as post-Boom "twenty-somethings"

### Defining Characteristics in 1979

- Making life-pivoting decisions about schools and careers
- Older generations sank into month of national pessimism
- For **Silent parents, Thinking Small was a midlife tonic**
- But for the high school class of 1979 who never had their own chance to Think Big, saw the grim mood very differently
- From the **Vietnam hysteria** to **Nixon's "Christmas Without Lights"** to **Three Mile Island**—at every turn, these kids sensed that adults were simply not in control of themselves or the country

### Perception of the Real World

- Far more than other generations, **13ers feel that the real world is gearing up to punish them down the road**
- Annual polls of high school seniors show those born just after 1960 came of age **much more fearful of national catastrophe** than those born just before
- These early 1960s babies (as seen in Chapter 2) grew up as the kids whose **low test scores and high rates of crime, suicide, and substance abuse** marked a postwar extreme for American youth
- The indicators have not improved much for Americans born in the late 1960s and 1970s
- Altogether, writes **Felicity Barringer** in the *New York Times*, older Americans are coming to perceive them as **"a lost generation, an army of aging Bart Simpsons, possibly armed and dangerous."**

### Contrast with Boomers

- Unlike the Boomer kids-in-jeans of the 1960s, **13ers present, to older eyes, a splintered image of brassy sights, caustic sounds, and cool manner**
- Moviegoers

<!-- p. 317 -->

### Boomers' Approach to Crisis and Punishment

- **Vanguard Boomers** show severity streak—desire not just enemy's defeat but **destruction**
- At **Wall Street Journal**: call on American forces to "take Baghdad and install a MacArthur Regency"—hint at war-crimes tribunals
- Former Navy Secretary **James Webb** proposes "ruthless and overpowering" retaliation against foreign enemies
- Suggests constructing a "very large, very primitive federal prison in remote area of Alaska" for drug dealers
- **William Bennett** unjoking weighs advantages of beheading underworld kingpins, peers show strongest generational support for **capital punishment**
- Boomers dominate national ranks of the "**Fryers Club**"—young prosecutors who favor death penalty
- Other generations' support for death penalty declines if respondents are told to ignore issue of deterrence—**Boomers more likely to see execution as moral retribution**

### Crisis Mentality: Foment vs. Overcome

- Boomers starting to show **fascination for apocalyptic solutions**
- Unlike G.I. fathers who excelled at **overcoming** crisis, Boomers attracted to possibility of **fomenting** crisis
- **Bennett** sums up approach: "Consequence and Confrontation." The 47-year-old budget director daring to close down essential federal services if deficit not reduced dubbed "**Apocalypse Darman**" by the press
- In Congress, **Newt Gingrich** promises to use "values" as "a way of dividing America"
- **Marty Russo** refuses to go along with budget process "that stinks and lies"
- Silent Congressman **Byron Dorgan**, speaking for many peers, acknowledges how "confrontational" younger colleagues "don't respect the old rules and courtesies"

### The Gathering Gloom: Environmental and Economic Catastrophism

- The gathering Boom vision of future is **dark and bright**—with new pronouncements about how denial, even pain, will be necessary to achieve righteousness tomorrow
- **The Sierra Club's Dan Becker** openly rooted for "especially bad" weather so "a crisis mentality can take over" about global warming
- ***Washington Post* sportswriter Tom Boswell** asked whether "purification by fire" of greed-soaked sport might be needed to cleanse baseball
- **James Fallows** declared "the world economy badly needs a few crises" and that America would benefit from a "**7.0 magnitude diplo-economic shock**"
- Whatever the problem, Boom prescription is **not for sugar-coated cure, but for purgative tonic**

> "The 'sky will first need to fall' before the world wakes up to its environmental folly, insisted Boomer columnist Christopher Wintter just before Earth Day 1990, an event that had a far sterner, less euphoric tone than the original Earth Day in 1970. "And when the dead are counted, when pan-global rules prevent further murder of air and water and all that which sustains and encourages life, the first real Earth Day will bear celebration." Winner's peers, say Collier and Horowitz, are "a destructive generation whose work is not over yet." Peering into the future of the Woodstock Generation, Anthony Casale and Philip Lerman see the

<!-- p. 321 -->

## THIRTEENTH GENERATION (Born 1961 to 1981)

### Type and Demographics
- **TYPE:** Reactive
- **Total number:** 79,000,000
- **Now alive in U.S.:** 79,000,000
- **Percent immigrant:** 11%

### Family Tree
- **Typical grandparents:** G.I.
- **Parents:** Silent and Boom
- **Children:** Millennial (and next Adaptive)
- **Typical grandchildren:** (new Idealist)

### Sample Members (birth/death)
- 1961: **Michael J. Fox***
- 1961: **Eddie Murphy**
