### History and Lifecycle

**Age-Date Timeline:**
- **0-1 (1962):** U.S. government approves public sale of birth-control pill
- **0-4 (1965):** "Baby boom" ends; Supreme Court upholds right to contraceptives
- **0-7 (1968):** *Rosemary's Baby* begins decade-long popularity of bad-child films
- **0-12 (1973):** *Roe v. Wade* abortion case; Christmas Without Lights
- **0-18 (1979):** U.S. hostages seized in Iran; long lines at gas pumps
- **0-19 (1980):** Military enlistments surge; youth vote supports Reagan
- **2-22 (1983):** *A Nation at Risk* sharply criticizes students; Grenada invasion
- **5-25 (1986):** Schoolchildren watch *Challenger* shuttle explode on takeoff
- **8-28 (1989):** Surge in gang killings; "wilding"; (Heidi Wall dismantled)
- **9-29 (1990):** Rock lyrics censored; U.S. troops go to Persian Gulf

### Sample Cultural Endowments
- **Film:** *Liar's Poker* (Michael Lewis); *sex, lies, and videotape* (film, Steven Soderbergh); *Less Than Zero* (Bret Easton Ellis); *20 Under 30* (Debra Spark)
- **Music:** *The Dartmouth Review*; *Slippery When Wet* (album, Jon Bon Jovi); *Short Sharp Shocked* (album, Michelle Shocked); *Fast Car* (song, Tracy Chapman)
- **TV/Film:** *As Nasty as They Wanna Be* (album, 2 Live Crew); *Flunk of One* (album, Wynton Marsalis); *Remote Control* (MTV); *Hangin' Tough* (album, New Kids on the Block); "Too Much Fun" (graffiti art, Brett Cook)

<!-- p. 322 -->

### 13er Cultural Stereotypes and Elder Perceptions

**Popular culture portrayals of 13ers:**
- **Tom Cruise** in *Top Gun* - rule-breaking winners
- *The Breakfast Club* - teachers punishing hopeless, incorrigible "Brat Pack" teenagers
- **Steven Soderbergh's** *sex, lies, and videotape*
- **Rob Lowe** in *St. Elmo's Fire* and *Influence* - dirty life characters
- America's **kamikaze bicycle messengers** delivering for Domino's and Federal Express
- "Crack" gangs, computer hackers, would-be novelists portrayed as living fast
- **John Schwartz** (*Bicycle Days*): "live a little faster"

**13er demographics and achievements:**
- High schools: **13ers are Asian-American valedictorians and Westinghouse science finalists**
- More immigrants or children of immigrants than previous cohorts
- Fresh from college: **Yale class of 1986** - 40% entered Wall Street banking with one company (First Boston)
- Successful dealmakers who "age like dogs" - **Michael Lewis'** *Liar's Poker*
- Athletics: young Olympians leading chants of "U-S-A! U-S-A!"
- **"Air Jordan"** and **"Neon Deion" Sanders** - slam dunks and end-zone spikes
- One-armed **Jim Abbott** - imposing odds against disability
- Defenders of Saudi oilfields and Panama invaders
- **Manuel Noriega surrender** - boom boxes blasting goodbye message, soldier comment: "to them it's everything, to us it's just a battle"

**Elder generational criticism:**
- Older generations see 13ers as **frenetic, physical, slippery**
- Like their music: shocking outside, unknowable inside
- Elders suppress disappointment that 13ers are "turning out—dismissing them as a 'lost,' 'ruined,' even 'wasted' generation"
- **Ellen Goodman**: termed them "youth-bashing"
- **"Disparaging" and "numb generation"** - Russell Baker
- **"Today's youth suffer from herky-jerky brain"** - Boom evangelists
- **Larry Lea**: condemn 13ers as "factureless" and declare "spiritual warfare" on youth
- "Worship of the devil"

**Media portrayals and critiques:**
- Headline: **"Hopes of a Gilded Age: Class of 1987 Bypasses Social Activism to Aim for Million-Dollar Dreams of Life"** - *Washington Post*
- Complaints about "fiery concerns of predecessors over peace and social justice are mementos from a dimming past"
- *People* magazine: coined phrase **"Rettonization of America"** - describe how young stars sell names and reputations to highest bidder
- **Boomers shocked** by 13er chemical of choice, steroids (oppose Boom-era psychedelics, which argued body and mind unity)
- Sportswriter **Bill Mandel** dismisses baseball slugger **José Canseco** as "the perfect athlete" - "pumped up bigger than a steer and completely oblivious to the vital subtext of his sport"
- Boomer media portray 13ers as **driven by appetites**, when Jay Leno asks why they eat Doritos
- **"We're not talkin' brain cells here. We're talkin' taste buds"**
- Soft-drink commercials: don't show 13ers chanting and swaying

<!-- p. 318 -->

### Boomer Calls for Stricter Standards and Moral Regime

- **Boomers** now demand authority move toward their own moral standard—more explicit use of public authority (taxes, zoning, schools, prisons)
- Authority won't move until it reaches standards **Boomers themselves have sacrificed** for
- Once that standard is reached, Boomers will distrust any path that doesn't hurt—will care less about how many feel the "howling cold" along the way

### Boomers Not Like the G.I. Generation

- When **Lloyd Bentsen** told **Dan Quayle**: "You are no Jack Kennedy," and **Howard Metzenbaum** said of **William Bennett** that "he believes words speak louder than actions," those rockets landed on more than individual targets
- In the **G.I. mind's eye**, you could replace Quayle or Bennett with any of today's 45-year-olds, and none could match a G.I. doer in his prime
- The bellicose **Kennedy**—the war-hero President of "prestige" and "long strides"—was decidedly no Boomer
- Nor did his "best and brightest" share anything like the common thread of consciousness among Boomers (**Jody Powell**, **Hamilton Jordan**, **David Stockman**, **Peggy Noonan**, **Lee Atwater**, **Richard Darman**) who have visited the White House inner circle during the last two decades

### Boomers Dominate National Leadership

- As **Quayle**, **Bennett**, **Al Gore**, **Bill Bradley**, **Bob Kerry**, and others in their mid-forties threaten to push aside the Silent in generational succession to the Oval Office, their generation already holds:
  - One of every four seats in the House of Representatives
  - Nearly every important office in **George Bush's West Wing**
  - Broadly dominates the media—from Hollywood to National Public Radio to the editorial writers at *The Wall Street Journal*
- **Boomers** are far less interested in tangible constructions (what Metzenbaum calls "actions") than in establishing a **fresh moral regime**

### Boomers as the Magistrates of Values

- Offering themselves as the **magistrates of this new order**, Boomers are stirring to defend values (monogamy, thrift, abstention from drugs) other generations do not associate with them
- Their scorched-earth rhetoric seems misplaced in a generation of onetime draft dodgers
- Critics can and do call them smug, narcissistic, self-righteous, intolerant, puritanical
- But one commonly heard charge—that of "hypocrite," ill fits a generation that came of age resacralizing and has kept at it
- **Boomers are in no rush**—always the distracted perfectionists, they first apply a light hand, then (once they start paying attention) a crushingly heavy one
- They "graze" on munchies until they figure it's time to diet, and then they don ashes and sackcloth

### Revolutionary Rhetoric from Conservative Boomers

> "Oh, how I miss the Revolution," wrote the (conservative) Boomer columnist **Benjamin Stein** in 1988. "I want the Revolution back."

- Seventeen years earlier, **Charles Reich** had prophesied how new Boomer values would someday transform civilization "beyond anything in modern history. Beside it," he bubbled, "a mere revolution, such as the French or Russian, seems inconsequential."
- **Reich**'s vision contrasts with Stein's conservative longing—both illustrating Boomer revolutionary impulses across the political spectrum

<!-- p. 319 -->

### Boomer Leadership and Cultural Impact

- Critics misperceived the Boom's readiness to assume power and pandered to its trappings, but understood its **seriousness of purpose**
- Boomer visionaries and "wise men" continue their work regardless of bracket position: **Jonathan Schell**, **Jeremy Rifkin**, **Charles Murray**, **Alan Keyes**, **Steven Jobs**, **Steven Spielberg**

### The "Decency Decade" - 1990s Vision

- December 2, 1989: *Good Housekeeping* published full-page ad in *New York Times* welcoming America to the 1990s as **"the Decency Decade"**
- Proclaimed the 1990s would be "a very good decade for the Earth" with **New Traditionalists** leading an unstoppable environmental juggernaut
- Vision: Change and inspire corporate America toward healthier, more decent lives
- Call to "make people look for what is real, what is honest, what is quality, what is valued, what is important"

### Boomer Position in Generational Landscape

- Boomers today stand **midgame** in a many-pronged reworking of American society
- Partly applaud, partly loathe their current role
- The righteous fires of **People's Park** are still smoldering - indicating continued activist energy and unresolved cultural tensions

<!-- p. 323 -->

### 13ers' Academic Performance and Harsh Assessments

- **13ers** characterized as careening "through some hellhouse and winding up on a pile of junk" rather than on verdant hillside
- Ad Council caption: confused teenager needs "a good swift kick in the pants"
- Boomer teacher in *The Breakfast Club*: "when I get older, these kids are gonna take care of me" — "Don't hold your breath"

**Academic decline throughout 1980s:**
- Yearly reports triggered harsh assessments of 13er schooling and intelligence
- Decline began in **1983** when *A Nation at Risk* despaired of "rising tide of mediocrity" emerging from America's schools
- Allan Bloom's *The Closing of the American Mind* (1987) declared 13ers' minds "quite closed"
- Diane Ravitch and Chester Finn's *What Do Seventeen-Year Olds Know?* found grading 13ers collectively in twenty-nine subjects, Ravitch and Finn dished out twenty F's — no other grade higher than C−
- "The sympathy and indulgence once offered to low-scoring young Boomers has evaporated"

**Harsh media characterizations:**
- Columnist Richard Cohen called for "humiliating, embarrassing, mocking" young people — "just when you think America's students can't get any dumber"
- Jack Anderson (1989): another book like Steve Ailen's *Dumbth*, or another blue-ribbon report from Carnegie Foundation calling 13ers "shallow" and chastising their "uncivil speaking" and "deteriorating" campus culture
- Message to 13ers and employers: "these kids got an inferior education and are equipped with inferior minds — that they are (to quote one Boomer college president) 'junky'"

### 13ers' Self-Perception and Pragmatism

**13ers find criticisms overblown:**
- View themselves as pragmatic, quick, sharp-eyed, able to step outside themselves to understand life's game as it really gets played
- Insist they *have* to be because of the way were raised and the world they're coming of age into

**Economic realities shaping 13er worldview:**
- See no welcome mat on economic future
- Since early 1970s, while economy grew, costs (college tuitions and housing) have raced ahead of inflation
- Rewards (salaries and fringe benefits for young workers) have fallen behind
- See what economist Robert Kuttner describes as "remarkable generational economic disease... a depression of the young"
- 13ers feel "uniquely thirsty in a sea of affluence"
- Money isn't everything — but 13ers find themselves unprepared for and uninvited to most other avenues of social approval
- **Money means survival** — for a generation whose earliest life experiences taught them not to trust others, survival must come first

### Cultural Context

- Older critics seldom acknowledge the odd twists that have plagued the **13er lifecycle**
- In early 1970s, Norman Lear produced *All in the Family*—
<!-- p. 320 -->

## THIRTEENTH GENERATION

**Born:** 1961-1981
**Type:** Reactive
**Age Location:** Boom Awakening in youth

### Emergence and Cultural Moment

- **November 1979 event:** Iranian mob swarming U.S. Embassy in Tehran followed by University of Georgia student center screening of *The Deerhunter* film
  - Students gave standing ovation to effigy of Ayatollah, then ran through streets chanting anti-Iran slogans
  - New breed of college freshmen came to America's campuses

- **Georgetown campus minister observation:** "students began lining up to introduce themselves to us"
  - Labeled **"THE THIRTEENTH GENERATION"** by *Washington Post* writer Nancy Smith
  - Pointed out generational shift post-Boom

### Defining Characteristics

- **The babies of crisis years:**
  - 1961: 8-year-olds of Woodstock
  - 1971: 13-year-olds of Watergate
  - 1973: 18-year-olds of energy crisis and hostage humiliation
  - 1981: 29-year-olds when *Time* cover story defined this generation as post-Boom "twenty-somethings"

- **Life context in 1979:**
  - Making life-pivoting decisions about schools and careers
  - Older generations sank into month of national pessimism
  - **"Thinking Small"** was a mild tonic for Silent parents
  - High school class of 1979 had very different outlook from prior generation

### Contrast with Boom Generation

- **Cultural touchstones:** "Christmas Without Lights" to Three Mile Island
  - These kids sensed adults were simply not in control
  - Far more than other generations, **13ers felt the real world was gearing up to punish them down the road**

### Social Indicators and Problems

- **Annual polls of high school seniors:** Those born just after 1960 came of age more fearful of national catastrophe than earlier cohorts
- **Early 1960s babies** (Chapter 2 reference): kids whose low test scores and high rates of crime, suicide, and substance abuse marked postwar extreme for American youth
- **Indicators have not improved** for Americans born in late 1960s and 1970s
- **New York Times quote:** "older Americans are coming to perceive them as 'a lost generation, an army of aging Bart Simpsons, possibly armed and dangerous'"

### Generational Self-Image

- **Unlike Boomer kids-in-jeans of the 1960s:**
  - 13ers present to older eyes a splintered image
  - **Brassy sights, caustic sounds, and cool manner**
  - Moviegoers [text cuts off]

