<!-- p. 324 -->

### 13ers as True Children of the 1960s-1970s

- **Thirteeners, not Boomers**, were America's true "children of the 1960s" and especially the **1970s**
- Awakening era seemed euphoric to young adults but was a **nightmare** for children
  - **Self-immersed parents** with conflicting missions
  - Confused leaders
  - Culture shifting from **G to R ratings**
  - New **public-health dangers**
  - **"Me Decade" economy** tipping toward organized old and away from young

### The "Grow Up Fast" Message

- **"Grow up fast"** was the consistent adult message to 13ers
- They graduated early to **"young adult realism"** in literature and film
- **13ers turning into young adulthood** during early teens (where Boomers lingered in "post-adolescence" well into twenties)
- At every phase of life, 13ers encountered a world of **more punishing consequence** than anything Silent or Boom elders ever knew

### 13ers' Matter-of-Fact Approach vs. Sexuality

- **Matter-of-fact approach to sexuality** differs from adult complaints brought by 13ers
- **First-wavers** were just reaching puberty when:
  - Adults emitting **highly charged sexual signals** in all directions
  - Sex education in schools became common

> "Grow up fast" was the adult message. That they did, graduating early to "young adult realism" in literature and film, and turning into what *American Demographics* magazine has termed "proto-adults" in their early teens.

### Cultural Shifts 13ers Experienced

- From **child cynicism** bred by TV shows about adult world competence (late 1980s)
- To **Lear's "People for the American Way" lobby** whipsawing kids with stinging report rebuking disengagement from political process
- From being told **"no single indispensable body of knowledge"** schools should teach (gurus like **Charles Rathbone**)
- To being told **yes, there was such knowledge** schools hadn't learned (**E.D. Hirsch** in *Cultural Literacy*)
- From **"be self-reliant, independent, self-actualizing individuals"** to watching adults carefully and emulating how behave—**collectively resembling Tatum O'Neal** in *Paper Moon*

### Beach Scene as Metaphor for 13er Experience

- Imagine coming to beach at end of long summer of big crowds and wild goings-on
- The beach bunch is **sunburned, sand shopworn, hot, full of debris**—no place for walking barefoot
- You step on bottle, cop cites you for littering
- **"That's how 13ers feel, following the Boom"**

### 13ers vs. First-Wave Boomers

- Much like **River Phoenix** in *Running on Empty*, first-wave 13ers:
  - Had to **cope and survive** in whatever territory Boom left behind
  - **Early access to self-expression and independence** stripped them of pleasure in discovery and rebellion

> "looking up from the asphalt and being blinded by the sun" — **Bret Easton Ellis**

- By time Ellis' peers came of age, **symbolic meanings of sex, drugs, student rights had faded**
- What they found: **harsh realities of social pathology**
- One by one, 13ers slowed or reversed trends—**SAT decline, substance abuse, the early crime**
- **Sex continued** but 13ers felt full brunt and bore **ensuing adult criticism**
<!-- p. 325 -->

### 13er Lifecycle vs. Silent Lifecycle: Inverse Experiences

- **13er lifecycle** has been the direct inverse of the **Silent** generation's experience
- Where Silent passed through childhood in era of parental suffocation and entered young adulthood with barriers to youth removed, 13ers faced exactly opposite trend
- Where Silent grew up with childlike awe of powerful elders, 13ers acquired adultlike fatalism about weakness and uncertainty of elders—questioning their ability to protect young from future danger

### Historical Context Contrasts

- When first Silent were children, America was in depths of depression; when 13ers born, America was riding high and G.I. leaders seemed to be achieving everything at once
- As Silent reached adolescence, nation mired itself in doubt; 13ers benefited from their storybook childhood hoping to add nuance and subtlety to culture they found oversimple

### Information Overload and Complexity

- **Thirteeners** are growing up in what teacher and author **Patrick Welsh** describes as "a world of information overload"
- Hearing others declare everything too complex for yes-or-no answers, 13ers struggle to filter out noise, cut through rhetoric, and isolate the handful of practical truths that really matter

### Diverging Personalities and the "Spreading Bell Curve"

- Unlike homogeneous young Silent, 13ers coming of age with sharply diverging personal circumstances (economists call a "**spreading bell curve**") in:
  - Education
  - Family economics
  - Career opportunities
- Where parents once struggled to break free from tight generational center of gravity, 13ers wonder if they will ever be able to find one

### Powerful Survival Instinct

- Confronted with these facts of life, 13ers built powerful survival instinct wrapped around an ethos of **personal determinism**
- In their world, what a person is, what he looks like, and whether or not he succeeds depend less on what a person is inside than on **how he behaves**
- Thirteeners constantly told that whatever bad things strike people their age—from **AIDS** to **drug addiction**, from **suicides** to **homicides**—are mainly their own fault
- In this sort of youth environment, staying alert to the physical is an assertion of virtue

### Class and Economic Divisions

- Unlike Boomers at like age, a low-income 13er probably comes from world of splintered families and general hopelessness—has little in common with some "**Richie Rich**" out in suburbs
- So kids feel obliged to dress up (at age when most Boomers dressed down) to preserve a sense of personal honor and to avoid
<!-- p. 322 -->

### 13er Pop Culture and Media Portrayals

- **Tom Cruise** in *Top Gun* breaking rules to win; *The Breakfast Club* showing teachers punishing hopeless "Brat Pack" teenagers; **Steven Soderbergh's** *sex, lies, and videotape*; **Rob Lowe** in *St. Elmo's Fire* playing ultimate **Bad Influence**
- They've become America's kamikaze bicycle messengers, speeders of delivery services, murderous inner-city "crack" gangs, computer hackers, would-be novelists
- Author **John Schwartz** (*Bicycle Days*) describes them as living to "live a little faster"
- In high schools, 13ers are Asian-American valedictorians and Westinghouse science finalists, more than half of them immigrants or children of immigrants
- Fresh from college, Yale class of 1986: 40% sought employment in investment banking, with one company (First Boston) having lucky ones becoming dealmakers who "age like dogs" in **Michael Lewis's** *Liar's Poker*

### Athletic and Cultural Expression

- Young Olympians leading chants of "U-S-A! U-S-A!"
- "Mr Jordan" and "Neon Deion" **Sanders** with in-your-face slam dunks and end-zone spikes
- One-armed **Jim Abbott** winning against impossible odds in the army
- 13ers defend Saudi oilfields and invaders of Panama—one defender's boom box helped persuade **Manuel Noriega** to surrender with warm goodbye from the Panamanians
- Quote about fighting: "to them it's everything, to us it's just a battle"

### Older Generations' View of 13ers

- **Older generations** see 13ers as frenetic, physical, slippery
- Like the music they listen to, 13ers can appear shocking on outside, unknowable on inside
- Elders find it hard to suppress disappointment over turning out—dismissing 13ers as "lost," "ruined," even "wasted" generation
- **Ellen Goodman** termed "youth-bashing"
- "Disparaging them as the 'dumb' and 'numb generation'"
- **Russell Baker** says "today's youth suffer from herky-jerky brain"
- Boom evangelists like California's **Larry Lea** condemn their soul-lessness and declare "spiritual warfare" on youth "worship of the devil"

### Media and Commercial Critiques

- Headline: "Hopes of a Gilded Age: Class of 1987 Bypasses Social Activism to Aim for Million-Dollar Dreams of Life"
- *Mademoiselle* magazine complains "the fiery concerns of many of their predecessors over peace and social justice are mementos from a dimming past"
- *People* magazine coined phrase "Rettonization of America" to describe stars selling out their names to highest bidder
- **Boomers** shocked by 13er chemical of choice, steroids (argue body and dim mind, opposite of Boom-era psychedelics)
- Sportswriter **Bill Mandel** dismisses baseball slugger **José Canseco** as "the perfect athlete" pumped up by bigger than a steer and completely oblivious to vital subtext of sport
- Boomer media portray 13ers as driven more by appetites than ideals—as when **Jay Leno** tells teenage television viewers why they eat Doritos: "We're not talkin' brain cells here. We're talkin' taste buds"
- Soft-drink commercials don't show 13ers chanting and swaying
<!-- p. 323 -->

### 13er Educational Crisis and Economic Outlook

**Academic decline narrative:**
- Since early 1980s, harsh assessments of 13er schooling proliferated
- 1983: *A Nation at Risk* warned of "rising tide of mediocrity" from America's schools
- Allan Bloom's *The Closing of the American Mind* (1987) declared 13ers' minds "quite closed"
- Diane Ravitch and Chester Finn's *What Do Seventeen-Year Olds Know?* showed collective ignorance in history and literature
- **The grade-F consensus:** Ravitch and Finn gave 13ers twenty F's—no grade higher than C-
- Sympathy and indulgence once offered to low-scoring young Boomers had evaporated

**Harsh critiques of 13er generation:**
- Columnist Richard Cohen called for "humiliating, embarrassing, mocking" young people to motivate them
- "Just when you think America's students can't get any dumber," reported Jack Anderson (1989)
- Steve Allen's *Dumbth* and other reports called **13ers "shallow,"** practicing **"uncivil speaking"** and **"deteriorating"** campus culture
- Carnegie Foundation critique: these kids are the envy of any Boom-era dean
- **The employer message:** 13ers got inferior education, equipped with inferior minds—that are (to quote Boomer college president) **"junky"**

**13er self-perception—pragmatic realism:**
- **Thirteeners find criticisms overblown**
- See themselves as pragmatic, quick, sharp-eyed, able to step outside themselves to understand life's game as it really gets played
- 13ers insist they *have* to be—raised in world they were coming of age into
- **No welcome mat on their economic future:**
  - College costs (tuition and housing) raced ahead of inflation
  - Rewards for young workers (salaries and fringe benefits) steadily fallen behind
  - Economist Robert Kuttner: **"remarkable generational economic disease... a depression of the young"**
  - 13ers feel **"uniquely thirsty in a sea of affluence"**
  - **Money means survival** for a generation whose earliest life experiences taught them not to trust others
  - For 13ers: **survival must come first**

**Historical precedent:**
- Older critics seldom acknowledge odd twists that plagued the 13er lifecycle
- Early 1970s: Norman Lear produced *All in the Family*—
<!-- p. 326 -->

### 13er Self-Perception and Cultural Identity

- 13ers engage in self-mockery and "being disrespected" as entertainment, treating it like a game
- Accept and even take "perverse fun" in doing what brings adult criticism
- Being "BAAAD" (in 13er lingo) means agreeing they're wasted, but their elders think they *are* wasted
- World-weary peer competition drives nihilistic self-reference

**Cultural artifacts reflecting 13er self-image:**
- **Chris Kreski** (26-year-old writer for *Remote Control*, 13er TV quiz-show parody): show is "stupid," words like "stupid," "random" are praise
- **Bon Jovi song** *You Give Love a Bad Name*: instant hit among teens of the 1980s
- **1990 think-tank report** documented 13er issues: massive cheating, résumé fraud, teacher assaults, venereal disease, pregnancies, materialism
- Afterward remarked 13ers "seemed to agree with these findings"

### River's Edge and 13er Worldview

- **Film *River's Edge***: depicts how many 13ers "look at life, one teenager mockingly says to his buddies, 'You young people are a disgrace to all living things, to plants even. You shouldn't even be seen in the same room as a cactus.'"

### The "Patchwork Self"

- 13ers struggle to preserve optimism and self-esteem they can
- Developed what psychologist **David Elkind** calls the **"patchwork self"**
- Two decades ago, older generations saw great promise in youth; not now—not these youths
- **First-wavers** (older 13ers) find themselves elbowed aside by Boomers at every turn
- Last-wavers lock their radars onto Nintendo in fantasized quest of fortune/death, or join Spurtlegurgles in singing about Boomer's missionless childhood
- *"We're here because we're here because we're here because we're here"* mentality
- **15-year-old David Peters** (fast-food worker in California): "So why even live?" No other generation in living memory has experienced such age distrust

### 13er Agency and Media Engagement

- **Lacking ego strength** to set agendas for others, 13ers react to world as they find it
- Proud of ability to poke through hype and detail, understand older people better (they sense) than older people understand them
- Take solace in privacy that affords them

**Pop culture icons as demeaning images:**
- Max Headroom, beheaded in accident, imprisoned within TV sound bites
- Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles, flushed down toilet as children, deformed by radiation, nurtured on junk food
- Bart Simpson, "under-achiever" whose creator likens him to everyone's "disgusting little brother"—the "little Spike-Head" whom **William Bennett** says he'll "straighten out" with "a couple of soap sandwiches"
- Beyond low self-esteem and blighted minds, what these pop icons share: created and promoted

<!-- p. 327 -->

### 13er Facts (continued)

- **13ers and abortion**: The 13th is the most aborted generation in American history
  - Abortion rate rose sharply in late 1960s/early 1970s
  - Climbed another 80% during the six years following 1973 **Roe v. Wade** decision (1973-1979)
  - Through birthyears of last-wave 13ers, would-be mothers aborted one fetus in three

- **Parental divorce**: 13ers struck harder by divorce than any other American generation
  - 1962: Half of all adult women believed parents in bad marriages should stay together for children's sake
  - 1980: Only one in five thought so
  - A 13er child in 1980s faced twice the risk of parental divorce as a Boomer child in mid-1960s
  - Three times the risk a Silent child faced in 1950
  - Four-fifths of today's divorced adults profess to being happier afterward
  - But majority of their children feel otherwise

<!-- p. 324 -->

### 13ers as True Children of the 1960s-70s

- **Thirteeners**, not Boomers, were America's true "children of the 1960s" and especially the **1970s**
- Came of age during an awakening era that seemed euphoric to young adults but was actually a nightmare for **self-immersed parents**, **disintegrating homes**, **schools with conflicting missions**, **confused leaders**, and a **culture shifting from G to R ratings**
- Faced new **public-health dangers** and a **"Me Decade" economy** that tipped toward the organized old and away from the voiceless young
- Adult message: **"Grow up fast"** — which they did, graduating early to "young adult" realism in literature and film, and turning into what *American Demographics* termed **"proto-adults"** in their early teens

### The Matter-of-Fact Approach vs. Boomer Experience

- **13ers' matter-of-fact approach to sexuality** is another point that has brought adult complaint
- **First-wavers** were just reaching puberty when adults were emitting highly charged sexual signals in all directions
- When **Boomers were teenagers** (two decades earlier), they had lingered in **"post-adolescence"** well into their twenties
- At every phase of life, **13ers have encountered a world of more punishing consequence** than anything their Silent or Boom elders ever knew

### Cultural Shifts 13ers Experienced

- In elementary school: heard gurus like **Charles Rathbone** say there was "no single indispensable body of knowledge" schools should teach
- Upon finishing school: heard new gurus like **E. D. Hirsch** (*Cultural Literacy*) say yes, there was such knowledge, and they hadn't learned it
- Were told as teenagers to be **"self-reliant, independent, self-actualizing individuals"**
- Learned to watch adults and emulate how they behave — **collectively resembling Tatum O'Neal in *Paper Moon***

### The Beach Metaphor

- Coming to a beach at the end of a long summer: big crowds and wild goings-on
- The beach bunch is sunburned, sand shopworn, hot, full of debris — no place for walking barefoot
- Step on a bottle, some cop cites you for littering
- **13ers feel they've come to cope and survive in whatever territory the Boom has left behind**, at each phase of life

### Early Independence and Its Costs

- Early access to self-expression and independence **stripped them of much of the pleasure of discovery and rebellion**
- Per **Bret Easton Ellis**: "looking up from the asphalt and being blinded by the sun"
- By the time Ellis' peers came of age, the symbolic meanings of sex, drugs, student rights had faded
- What they found instead: **the harsh realities of social pathology**
- **13ers have slowed or reversed these trends** — SAT decline, the youth crime, the substance abuse, the early sex
- But **13ers have felt the full brunt of them** and have borne the ensuing adult criticism

### Contrast with Boomer Experience

- Film *Running on Empty*: **first-wave 13ers** had to cope and survive in Boom territory left behind
- **Boomers** in their twenties had lingered in "post-adolescence" — 13ers encountered far more punishing consequences at every life phase
<!-- p. 328 -->

### Family Complexity and Parental Presence

- **13ers** grew up in the most complex family structures in American history
  - 1980: Only 56% of dependent children lived with two once-married parents
  - 14% lived with at least one previously married parent
  - 11% with a stepparent
  - 19% with one parent
  - One in five had half siblings
  - Far more likely to receive support payments from noncustodial parents than **Boomers**

### Domestic Dissatisfaction and "Latchkey Kids"

- Most dramatic increase in domestic dissatisfaction and workplace surge among mothers of any child generation
- Between 1960 and 1980, among mothers with children aged 5 or under:
  - Proportion with full- or part-time jobs rose from 20 to 47%
  - Number of "latchkey children" under age 14 left alone after school roughly doubled

### Parental Authority and Teen Perceptions

- Late-1980s survey of "teen trendsetters": 48% described their (mostly Silent) parents as "cool"—versus just 7% as "strict" and 1% as "nosy"
- **Irma Zandl** (youth marketer and pollster): **13ers** associate lack of parental authority with family instability
- Observation: "I've never heard any teenager say, 'I wish my father were more sensitive'"

### Education and Grade Inflation

- **13ers** entering high school encountered much less teacher-and-voter indulgence than **Boomers** had received
- **Boomer-era grade inflation** came to abrupt end
- Youths born in 1961 received 10% fewer high school A's and 10% fewer C's than born in 1960
- At ballot-box, first-wave **13ers** were targets of late-1970s **"Proposition 13"** school-tax revolts in California and other states
- During the decade after 1978 (when **13ers** reached age 18):
  - Purchasing power of child-poverty benefit declined
  - Federal minimum wage declined steeply and continuously

### Academic Performance Comparison

- Teachers who taught **Boomers** (mid-1960s) vs **13ers** (mid-1980s) compared in 43 measures of aptitude and achievement
- **Score: Boomers 38, 13ers 4, one tie**
- Teachers scored **Boomers** higher in: academic skills, communications ability, commitment to learning
- **Thirteeners** outscored **Boomers** in: negotiating skills, consumer awareness, adult-interaction skills, and "defenses to prevent extreme dependency on parents or authorities"

### College Education Trends

- **13ers** first generation since the **Gilded** to be less college-educated than elder siblings
- College completion rates fell from 58% for **Boomer** Class of 1972 to 57% for **13er** Class of 1980
- Economic stakes of higher education rose sharply from 1973 to 1986

<!-- p. 325 -->

### 13er Lifecycle Experience vs. Silent Generation

- **13er sexual culture**: Value-neutral, empty houses as trysting spots, parents "equally uncomfortable with notions that sex is evil and sex is groovy"
- Adults removed attitudinal barriers against the libido, leading 13ers to create age-old defense mechanisms: **platonic relationships, group dating, youth culture reminiscent of Lost-era street life** for emotional safety and physical integrity of their friend circle
- Unlike Boomers, 13ers coming of age knowing "the sexual euphoria of the late 1960s actually fed... **the sexual revolution is over, and everybody lost**"

### Inverse Life Trajectories: Silent vs. 13ers

**Silent Generation childhood**: Direct inverse of 13ers
- Silent passed through childhood in era of **parental suffocation and entered young adulthood** just as barriers to youth were loosened
- 13ers face **opposite trend**: Grew up with childlike awe of powerful elders, acquired **adultlike fatalism** about weakness and uncertainty of elders, questioning their ability to protect youth from danger

**Historical context of each generation's birth**:
- First Silent were children: America in throes of depression, at nadir of confidence
- First 13ers were born: America riding high, **G.I. leaders seemed to be achieving everything at once**—but then reached adolescence as nation mired itself in doubt
- Silent entered from their storybook childhood hoping to add nuance/subtlety to culture they found oversimple

### 13er Information Environment

- **Thirteeners** increasingly **grown up** in what teacher and author **Patrick Welsh** describes as "**a world of information overload**"
- Hearing others declare everything too complex for yes-or-no answers, **13ers struggle to filter out noise, cut through rhetoric, and isolate the handful of practical truths that really matter**
- Unlike homogeneous young Silent, 13ers coming of age with **sharply diverging personal circumstances** (what an economist would call a "**spreading bell curve**") in education, family economics, career opportunities
- Where parents once struggled to break free from tight generational center of gravity, **13ers wonder if they will ever be able to find one**

### 13er Survival Instinct

Confronted with these facts of life, 13ers have built **powerful survival instinct**, wrapped around an **ethos of personal determinism**:
- In their world, what a person is, what he looks like, and whether or not he succeeds depend **less on what a person is inside than on how he behaves**
- **Thirteeners constantly told that whatever bad things strike people their age**—from AIDS to drug addiction, suicides to homicides—**are mainly their own fault**
- In this sort of youth environment, staying alert to the physical is **assertion of virtue**

### Class Dynamics Among 13ers

- Unlike Boomers at like age, **low-income 13er probably comes from world of splintered families and general hopelessness**—has little in common with some "**Richie Rich**" out in suburbs
- So kids feel obliged to **dress up** (at age when most Boomers dressed down) to **preserve sense of personal honor and to avoid**

<!-- p. 329 -->

### 13er Generation Economic & Military Characteristics (continued)

- **Economic decline for young workers**: Average inflation-adjusted earnings of young college graduates fell 6%, but for young high school dropouts fell 42%
- **Military service preferences**: By 2-to-1 majority, **13er men prefer military to civilian public service**—sharp turnaround from Boom youth era
- When 13er cohort reached age 19, armed forces began dramatic 3-year rise in quality of new enlistees
- **13ers are the best-educated generation of soldiers in American history**

### Political Alignment & Voting Behavior

- Like **Michael J. Fox** in *Family Ties* (conservative kid of liberal parents), 13ers are by far the most Republican-leaning youths in 60-year history of age-based polling
- **Dramatic political shift**: From Boom to 13th, young voter alignment shifted strikingly
  - From roughly 10-point Democratic advantage to Republican edge in 1985 (reaching 18 points: 52% to 34%)
  - In 15 consecutive polls taken 1981-1988, **13ers gave Ronald Reagan higher approval rating than any other generation—except the Lost**

### Health & Mortality Patterns

- **Disease mortality**: 13er teenagers face much lower risk of dying from disease than Silent teenagers 40 years ago
- **But offset by accidents, murder, suicide**: This advantage almost entirely offset by higher risk of dying from accidents, murder, and suicide
- **Youth homicide crisis**: Roughly 2,000 minors murdered in 1988—**twice the number killed in 1965** (a year of urban riots when America had 6.5 million more youths under age 18)
- **Homicide now dominant cause of youth mortality** in America's inner cities
- Among black males 15-24 years old living in Washington, D.C., murder accounted for **47% of all deaths** in 1987

### Fear & School Absence

- **Fear is pervasive reality** within a generation of urban schoolchildren
- Estimated **135,000 guns** (and six times as many knives) brought to classroom each day
- **8% of urban 7th-12th graders** say they miss at least one day of school per month because they are **physically afraid to go**
- Only way to cope with fear is not to show it
- **Klaus Bornemann** (Bronx junior-high teacher): "The kid who demonstrates fear is raw meat."

### Suicide Crisis

- **13ers are committing suicide more frequently than any generation since the Lost**
- 1976: Child suicide rate rose above previous record set in 1908
- Throughout the 1980s, roughly **5,000 children under age 18 committed suicide each year**—**largest number and proportion ever recorded** for that age bracket

### Incarceration

- **13ers have become the most heavily incarcerated generation in American history**
- From Boom to 13th, proportion of youths in jail rose by roughly **one-third—for whites and blacks, women and men**
- Average length of sentence has risen by **12% during first half-dozen years**

<!-- p. 326 -->

### 13er Self-Perception and Media Representation

- 13ers accept being "disrespected" in real-life scenarios, even taking perverse fun in what a rapper would call "attitude" in being "BAAAD"
- They agree with peers that they're probably a wasted bunch
- **Weak peer competition** isn't such bad news - their cultural artifacts make half-comic reference to their own garbagey quality

**Cultural examples of self-deprecation:**
- **Chris Kreski** (26-year-old lead writer for *Remote Control*, 13er-designed TV quiz-show parody) admits his show is "stupid" (quotes: "If the lingo, words like 'stupid,' 'bad,' or 'random' are words of praise")
- **Bon Jovi song** *You Give Love a Bad Name* became instant hit among teens of the 1980s

**Think-tank research on 13ers (1990):**
- Documented "massive cheating, résumé fraud, assaults on teachers, venereal disease, pregnancies, and materialism"
- Afterward remarked that 13ers themselves seemed to agree with these findings

**Film and media portrayals:**
- *River's Edge*: film evoking how many 13ers look at life, teenage mockingly says to his buddies, "You young people are a disgrace to all living things, to plants even. You shouldn't even be seen in the same room as a cactus."

### The "Patchwork Self" Concept

- As 13ers struggle to preserve what optimism and self-esteem they can, they develop what psychologist **David Elkind** calls the **"patchwork self"**
- Two decades ago, older generations saw great promise in youth; not now—not these youths, anyway
- **First-wavers** find themselves elbowed aside by Boomers seemingly at every turn
- **Last-wavers** lock their radars onto Nintendo in fantasized quest of fortune or death, or join the Spurtlegurgles in singing the lyric of a missionless childhood ("We're here because we're here because we're here because we're here")

> "So many things have already happened in the world that we can't possibly come up with anything else." - 15-year-old **David Peters**, fast-food worker in California

> "So why even live?" - No other generation in living memory has come of age with such a sense of social distance—of adults doing so little for them and expecting so little from them

### 13er Response: Irony and Pop Culture Icons

- Lacking ego strength to set agendas for others, 13ers instead react to the world as they find it
- Proud of their ability to poke through the hype and detail, to understand older people far better (they sense) than older people understand them
- **Take solace in privacy** that affords them

**Pop culture as dark comedy:**
- Delight in the most demeaning images of youth ever crafted by electronic media:
  - **Max Headroom**: beheaded in an accident, imprisoned within TV sound bites
  - **Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles**: flushed down the toilet as children, deformed by radiation, nurtured on junk food
  - **Bart Simpson**: the "underachiever" whose creator likens him to everyone's "disgusting little brother"—the "little Spike-Head" whom William Bennett says he'll "straighten out" with "a couple of soap sandwiches"

**Common thread:** Beyond low self-esteem and blighted minds, what these pop icons all have in common is that they were created and promoted

<!-- p. 330 -->

### 13er Criminal Justice and Incarceration

- **13ers** entered adult criminal justice system in unprecedented numbers
- By **1990**, 13ers were majority of U.S. prison population
- **One in every four black men** between ages 20-29 was in jail, on probation, or on parole

### Economic Decline of Children (1970s)

- **1970s** brought steep decline in economic fortunes of children
- 1950s-early 1970s: **over-65 age bracket** showed highest poverty rates
- Since **1974**: **under-18 bracket** has shown the highest poverty rates
- **Distinction of occupying America's poorest age bracket** passed directly from Lost to 13th generation without touching G.I., Silent, or Boom
- Roughly **one 13er in five** now lives in poverty
- 13ers report most negative generational attitude toward welfare spending—believe if they're poor and unemployed, it's their own fault

### 13ers' Economic Distress Through 1980s

- Economic distress moved up age ladder with 13ers through 1980s
- **1967**: young wage earners in early twenties made **74 percent** as much as older males
- **1988**: ratio had fallen to **54 percent**
- **1973-1988**: median income of households headed by persons under 25 (adjusted for inflation and family size) fell by **18 percent**
- Negative trend not confined to unmarried 13er mothers—even among married couples with children, median income fell by **17 percent**

### Home Ownership Decline (1960s-1980s)

- Proportion of household heads age 18-24 owning their own homes fell by **one-third**—steepest decline for any age bracket
- **1990**: three out of four young men that age were still living at home—**largest proportion since the Great Depression**

### Federal Fiscal Burden Shift

- America substantially shifted federal fiscal burden from old to young since **1972**
- Older generations have deferred paying for **$2 trillion in current consumption** through additional U.S. Treasury debt
- Policy **five times more expensive** (in lifetime interest costs) for average 15-year-old than for average 65-year-old
- Federal tax policy shifted in same direction
- **1990** example (House Ways and Means Committee): young 13er couple—worker, baby, $30,000 wage income—had to pay **five times as much** ($5,055 in taxes) as typical retired G.I. couple with same income from public and private pensions ($1,073 in taxes)

### Decline of Cynicism with Age

- Before 13ers, postwar sociologists assumed **hardening cynicism was function of advancing age**—no longer
- **1965-1990**: share of all Americans under age 35 who look at newspaper daily declined from **two-thirds to less than one-third**—by far the steepest drop of any age bracket
- Late-1980s survey of "Cynical Americans"
<!-- p. 327 -->

### 13er Facts (continued)

- **13th is the most aborted generation in American history**
  - Abortion rate rose sharply during late 1960s and early 1970s
  - Climbed another 80% during the first six years (1973-1979) after Supreme Court's *Roe v. Wade* decision
  - Through birthyears of last-wave 13ers, would-be mothers aborted one fetus in three

- **Parental divorce struck 13ers harder than any other American generation**
  - 1962: Half of all adult women believed parents in bad marriages should stay together for children's sake
  - 1980: Only one in five thought so
  - 13er child in 1980s faced twice the risk of parental divorce as a Boomer child in mid-1960s
  - Three times the risk a Silent child faced back in 1950
  - Four-fifths of today's divorced adults profess being happier afterward, but majority of their children feel otherwise

<!-- p. 331 -->

### The 13er Lifecycle (continued)

**YOUTH: The "Consciousness Revolution" years**

- Most virulently **anti-child period** in American history, producing a childhood **Tom Cruise** recalls as "kind of scattered"
- Sacrificing one's career or conjugal happiness became passé—even had to for kids themselves
- As the 1960s wore on, **silent mothers and fathers increasingly looked at their children as hindrances to self-exploration**
- By the 1970s, 13ers could envision careers without babies (never a hot topic when Boomers were born)
- Adults ranked autos ahead of children as necessary for "the good life," and cost of raising a child became a hot topic
- Flurry of popular books chronicled the resentment, despair, and physical discomfort women endured when bearing and raising 13er children

**Parenting philosophy shifts:**

- ***Our Children and Our Children*** (title revealed priorities through juxtaposition)
- **"Conquer yourself"** ranked ahead of "benefiting our children" as a principle of sound parenting
- Popular parental guides emphasized **why-to-dos over what-to-dos**
- Conclusion: ***doing*** the right thing was less important than parent and child each ***feeling*** the right thing
- To accomplish that, authors like **Thomas Gordon** (in ***Parental Effectiveness Training***) advised parents to teach children to understand behavioral consequences at very young ages
- Popular books by **T. Berry Brazelton** and **Burton White** stressed the **determinism of the early childhood years**, suggesting a child's lifetime personality might be substantially sealed by the time he entered school
- As **Marie Winn** noted: **"early-childhood determinism appeared to be a gift from gods"** for parents with new wanderlust or careerism who conclude that their 6- or 10-year-old children could cope with family trauma well enough, given how carefully they had been tended as tots

**Fear and confusion in 13er childhood:**

- **Divorce** and its attendant confusion and impoverishment became the central fear of the 13er childhood world
- In ***It's Not the End of the World***, **Judy Blume** offered children the tale of a once-happy family disintegrating amid shouting, slapping, and crying
- Hearing these messages, even kids in stable families felt vulnerable and reacted by hardening their shells against adversity
- While parents tried to persuade themselves (like Kyle Pruett in ***The Nurturing Father: Journey Toward the Complete Man***) that family dissolution "freed" parent and child to have "better" and "less constricted" time together, these kids saw things dif-

<!-- p. 328 -->

### 13er Family Complexity and Instability

- No American generation has grown up in families of such complexity
  - 1980: only 56% of dependent children lived with two once-married parents
  - 14% with at least one previously married parent
  - 11% with a stepparent
  - 19% with one parent
  - One in five had half siblings
  - Likelihood of receiving support payments from noncustodial parent declined from Boomer childhood era

### Domestic Self-Sufficiency and Working Mothers

- **13ers** witnessed dramatic increase in domestic self-sufficiency among mothers
- Between 1960-1980, among mothers with children aged 5 or under, proportion with full- or part-time jobs rose from 20% to 47%
- Through 1970s, number of "latchkey" children under age 14 left alone after school roughly doubled

### Teen Perception of Parental Authority

- Late-1980s survey of "teen trendsetters": 48% described their (mostly Silent) parents as "cool" versus just 7% as "strict" and 1% as "nosy"
- Youth marketer and pollster **Irma Zandl**: **13ers** associate lack of parental authority with family instability
- **Zandl observation**: "I've never heard any teenager say, 'I wish my father were more sensitive'"

### Academic Decline in High School Era

- **13ers** encountered much less teacher-and-voter indulgence than had greeted their next-elders
- **Boomer-era grade inflation** came to abrupt end
- Youths born in 1961 received 10% fewer high school A's and 10% fewer C's than born in 1960
- At ballot-box, **first-wave 13ers** were targets of late-1970s **"Proposition 13"** school-tax revolts in California and other states
- During decade after 1978 (when first Boomers reached age 18), purchasing power of both child-poverty benefit and federal minimum wage declined steeply and continuously

### Academic Performance: Boomers vs. 13ers

- Teacher sampling comparing Boomers (mid-1960s) and **13ers** (mid-1980s) in 43 measures of aptitude and achievement
- **Score: Boomers 38, 13ers 4, with one tie**
- Teachers scored **Boomers** higher in all academic skills, communications ability, and commitment to learning
- **13ers** outscored Boomers in negotiating skills, consumer awareness, adult-interaction skills, and "defenses to prevent extreme dependency on parents or authorities"

### College Education Rates Decline

- **13th** is first generation since **Gilded** to be less college-educated than its next-elders
- College completion rates fell from 58% for Boomer Class of 1972 to 57% for **13er Class of 1980**
- Economic stakes of higher education have risen sharply from 1973 to 1986

<!-- p. 332 -->

### Parenting Approaches and Cultural Shift

- **13ers** (Gen X) experienced dramatically different parenting than Boomers
- Where Boomers received prolonged parental sacrifice and "coming-of-age" marriage support, **13ers** dealt with divorce, remarriage, and step-families
- Family culture shifted from *My Three Sons* to *My Two Dads* in the 1970s-80s
- Encountered "step-thises, half-thats, significant others, and strangers at the breakfast table" — unprecedented family complexity
- Reading **Norma Klein's** *It's OK If You Don't Love Me*: 13er children grappled with juggling relationships with mother's lover, mother's former second husband, and father's second wife and children

### The "Parent Without Authority"

> "The parent is usually a coordinator without voice or authority." — **Kenneth Keniston**, 1977

- Parents of the 1970s "hardly ever have... the power to make others listen to them" in homes, schools, courtrooms
- American child-nurturing style completed "a two-decade passage from *Father Knows Best* to the tone of self-doubt in **Bill Cosby's** *Fatherhood*"

> "Was I making a mistake now? If so, it would just be mistake number nine thousand seven hundred and sixty-three." — **Alvin Poussaint**

- Dominant media image: the parent as "pal" who "always understanding; they never get very angry"
- No boundaries or limits set
- Parents portrayed as bungling, not in charge, floundering rather than decisive
- Inadvertent parenting — many-dimensioned, imperfect human beings
- Authors of *Ourselves and Our Children*: parents "are able to give children a more realistic picture of what being a person is all about"

### Silent vs. Boomer Parenting Styles

- **Silent parents**: like Cosby's Cliff Huxtable — gentle, communicative
- **Boomer parents**: expressed ambivalence, sought clear moral answers, abandoned positive future vision, required children to respond to sophisticated real-world problems very young
- Like father and son in *Close Encounters of the Third Kind* — adults became more childlike, children more adultlike

### Growing Cynicism About Adults (1970s)

- Media reinforced view that adults were not especially virtuous, competent, or powerful
- Adult life held no secrets
- TV sit-coms to "breakthrough" youth books — older generations made little effort to shield children from harsh topics
- No attempt to protect child's sense of security and comfort

> "I hate the idea that you should always protect children." — **Judy Blume**, defending her books' realism

> "They live in the same world we do."

- **Mad magazine's Al Feldstein**: "We told them there's a lot of garbage out in the world and you've got to be aware of it."
- "One 'Self-Care Guide'" for latchkey children: "ways you can protect yourself from mugging and assault: Always pay attention to what is happening around you when you are on the street"
- Kids deliberately encouraged to "react to life as you would hack through a jungle: Keep your eyes open, expect the worst, and handle it on your own"

<!-- p. 329 -->

### 13er Generation Economic and Social Challenges (continued)

- Average inflation-adjusted earnings of young college graduates fell 6% for **13ers**, but for young high school dropouts, earnings fell **42%**
- By two-to-one majority, **13er men prefer military to civilian public service**—sharp turnaround from **Boomer** youth era
- Starting when **13er cohort** reached age 19, armed forces began dramatic three-year rise in quality of new enlistees
- **13ers are the best-educated generation of soldiers in American history**

### Political Alignment

- Like **Michael J. Fox** in *Family Ties* (conservative kid of liberal parents), **13ers** are by far the most **Republican-leaning youths** in sixty-year history of age-based polling
- From Boom to 13th, the partisan tone of young voters shifted strikingly—from roughly ten-point Democratic advantage to Republican edge
- By 1985, reached eighteen points (52% to 34%)
- In fifteen consecutive polls taken 1981-1988, **13ers gave Ronald Reagan higher approval rating than any other generation—except the Lost**

### Health and Mortality Risks

- **13er teenagers** face much lower risk of dying from disease than **Silent teenagers** forty years ago
- But **13er advantage** has been almost entirely offset by much higher risk of dying from **accidents, murder, and suicide**
- Roughly **2,000 minors were murdered in 1988**—twice the number killed in 1965 (year of urban riots when America had 6.5 million more youths under age 18)
- **Homicide is now dominant cause of youth mortality** in America's inner cities
- Among black males 15-24 years old living in Washington, D.C., murder accounted for **47% of all deaths** in 1987

### Fear and Violence in Schools

- **Fear is pervasive reality** within generation of urban schoolchildren
- Estimated **135,000 guns (and six times as many knives)** brought to classroom each day
- **8% of urban seventh to twelfth graders** say they miss at least one day of school per month because they are **physically afraid to go**
- At same time, **13ers learn young that the only way to cope with fear is not to show it**
- Says **Bronx junior-high teacher Klaus Bornemann**: "The kid who demonstrates fear is raw meat"

### Suicide Epidemic

- As teenagers, **13ers are committing suicide more frequently than any generation since the Lost**
- In 1976, child suicide rate rose above previous record set in 1908
- Throughout the 1980s, roughly **5,000 children under age 18 committed suicide each year**—the largest number and proportion ever recorded for that age bracket

### Incarceration

- **13ers have become the most heavily incarcerated generation in American history**
- From Boom to 13th, proportion of youths in jail rose by roughly **one-third**—for whites and blacks, women and men
- Average length of sentence has risen **12% during first half-dozen years**
<!-- p. 330 -->

### 13er Economic Distress and Generational Burdens

- **1970s decline in child economic fortunes**: From 1950s-early 1970s, over-65 age bracket showed highest poverty rate; since 1974, under-18 bracket has shown the highest
  - Distinction of occupying America's poorest age bracket passed directly from Lost to 13th without touching G.I., Silent, or Boom
  - Roughly one 13er in five lives in poverty
  - 13ers report most negative generational attitude toward welfare spending—and two-thirds believe that if they ever end up unemployed, it's their own fault

- **1980s economic distress moving up the age ladder**: In 1967, male wage earners in their early twenties made 74% as much as older males; by 1988, that ratio had fallen to 54%
  - Between 1973-1988, median income of households headed by persons under age 25 (adjusted for inflation and family size) fell by 18%
  - Negative trend not confined to unmarried 13er mothers; even among married couples with children, median income fell by 17%

- **Homeownership collapse for young adults**: From 1960s-1980s, proportion of household heads age 18-24 owning their own homes fell by one-third—steepest decline for any age bracket
  - In 1990, three out of four young men that age were still living at home—largest proportion since **Great Depression**

- **Federal fiscal burden shift from old to young**: Since 1972, older generations have deferred paying for some $2 trillion in current consumption through additional **U.S. Treasury debt**—policy five times more expensive (in lifetime interest costs) for average 15-year-old than for average 65-year-old
  - Federal tax policy shifted in same direction
  - In 1990, according to House Ways and Means Committee: young 13er couple with one worker, baby, and $30,000 in wage income paid five times as much ($5,055 in taxes) as typical retired G.I. couple with same income from public and private pensions ($1,073 in taxes)

- **Cynicism declining with age—13er reversal**: Before 13ers, postwar sociologists generally assumed hardening cynicism was function of advancing age
  - From 1965-1990, share of all Americans under age 35 who took at a newspaper daily declined from two-thirds to less than one-third—by far steepest drop of any age bracket
  - Late-1980s survey of "Cynical Americans"

<!-- p. 333 -->

### Approaching Rising Adulthood

- **13ers** reaching late twenties cannot be said to have "come of age" — nothing yet cements them emotionally
- Remains a **splintery generation** — people can find almost anything they want in these kids, far more than older generations
- **13ers** come with myriads of regional subgroups and ethnic minicultures, each thinking its own thoughts, listening to its own music, living its own plans, paying little heed to each other

#### First Signs of Bonding

- First signs of bonding beginning to appear — a common **alienation** visible in 13er art and writing
- Growing awareness of their own economic vulnerability: "Sure we're alienated," admits American University student **Daniel Ralph**. "But who wouldn't be, in our shoes?"

#### Economic Burdens and Realities

- **Thirteeners** coming to realize they bear much of the burden for the **Reagan-era prosperity** that enriched the Silent and G.I.s
- In inner cities, their impoverishment has caused adult alarm; elsewhere, it has been less noticed, thanks to a veneer of family-subsidized teen affluence
- Even in suburbs, **13ers** entering labor force are bearing much of their nation's new burden of foreign competition and debt

##### Industry and Labor Challenges

- In industries where productivity is stagnant, two-tier wage systems hold elders harmless while making the new hires bear the full cost-cutting burden
- Foreign investors bid up price of real estate → current homeowners profit, but would-be young homebuyers pay
- Even as 1980s-era spurt of tax reform lowered the tax rate on high-bracket incomes, **FICA taxes** on after-school wages kept going up

##### Working Conditions

- **13ers** are working younger, longer, later at night, and at more dangerous jobs than any child generation since the Lost
- Federal administrators chart steady rise in child labor law violations
- **13ers** carefully hone their survivalist ethic
- Two-thirds believe they will have to work harder than earlier generations simply to enjoy the same standard of living
- After leaving school, **13ers** face tough choices made all the more frustrating by the adult wealth they see around them

#### Cultural Critiques and Life Paths

- Washington, D.C. youth complained: "The way society presents it, I'll either be strung out on drugs, a manager at McDonald's, or a lawyer"
- Something resembling her middle course is the most frequent path, as many find themselves doing the low-wage counter, delivery, and cleaning jobs Boomers have always found demeaning
- The **"Mefobs"** that **Amitai Etzioni** describes as "more time-consuming, less character-building" than what talented youths used to look forward to
- In most professions—law, medicine, business, the media—**13ers** are encountering less promising promotion paths than the Boom knew at their age, and a smaller likelihood of ever getting a second chance if they fail the first time

#### The 13er Habit of Concealment

- **13ers** have concealed their plight thanks to the distinctly 13er habit of calling as little attention as possible to what they are feeling
- In life, as when they walk down the street with their **Walkmens** and designer shades, they know how to keep others from knowing what they're hearing, watching, or thinking

<!-- p. 331 -->

### The 13er Lifecycle (continued)

**YOUTH: The "Consciousness Revolution" years**
- Most violently anti-child periods in American history, producing a childhood **Tom Cruise** recalls as "kind of scattered"
- Sacrificing one's own career or conjugal happiness became passé for parents—even, by era logic, had no kids themselves
- 1960s wore on, **Silent mothers and fathers increasingly looked at their children as hindrances to self-exploration**
- By the 1970s, they cast an envious eye at young Boomers—who then mainly looked upon babies like headaches, things you take pills not to have
- Adults ranked autos ahead of children as necessary for "the good life," and cost of raising a child (never much at issue when Boomers were born) became a hot topic

**Popular books chronicled resentment, despair, and physical discomfort** women were said to endure when bearing and raising 13er children:
- **In _Ourselves and Our Children_** (whose priorities revealed themselves in juxtaposition of title), "consider yourself" was ranked ahead of "benefiting our children" as a principle of sound parenting
- Popular parental guides emphasized **why-to-dos over what-to-dos**, concluding that _doing_ the right thing was less important than parent and child each _feeling_ the right thing
- To accomplish that, authors like **Thomas Gordon** (in _Parental Effectiveness Training_) advised parents to teach children to understand behavioral consequences at very young ages
- Popular books by **T. Berry Brazelton and Burton White** stressed the determinism of the early childhood years, suggesting that a child's lifetime personality might be substantially sealed by the time he entered school
- As **Marie Winn** would later note, "early-childhood determinism appeared to be a gift from gods" for parents with new wanderlust or careerism who could thereby conclude that their 6- or 10-year-old children could cope with family trauma well enough, given how carefully they had been tended as tots

**Divorce and its attendant confusion and impoverishment** became the central fear of the 13er childhood world:
- In _It's Not the End of the World_, **Judy Blume** offered children the tale of a once-happy family disintegrating amid shouting, slapping, and crying
- Hearing these messages, even kids in stable families felt vulnerable and reacted by hardening their shells against adversity
- While parents tried to persuade themselves (like Kyle Pruett in _The Nurturing Father: Journey Toward the Complete Man_) that family dissolution "freed" parent and child to have "better" and "less constricted" time together, these kids saw things dif-

<!-- p. 334 -->

### 13er Work Attitudes and Career Patterns

- **Workplace behavior**: Leave troubles behind when coming to work, take minds off job when leaving
- Boomer bosses (like **Penny Erikson**) see them as "not driven from within," suited for "short-term tasks" and needing "reinforcement from above"
- **13ers' motto**: "Ask 13ers how they're doing, and as long as life stays reasonably patched together, 'No problem' is their answer"
- Learned to adjust by moving into/out of other jobs as end of jobs approaches
- Look for **quick strikes** over long-term promises
- *Wall Street Journal* describes them as "more willing to gamble their careers than... earlier generations"
- Often best chance for success: striking out on own, finding small market niche, filling it more cheaply/sensibly than older-run businesses

### 13er Entrepreneurship Examples

- **Twenty-fiveish entrepreneurs**: **David Montague** (folding bicycles), **Doug Wadsworth** (plastics recycling)
- **Darryl Strawberry** parallel: Those who hit the jackpot succeed, untold others don't
- Those who smack the minimis ethos believe failure means something must be wrong with *you*
- Rising numbers mask deeper anxieties about "boomeranging" back into parental house after trying to make it on their own

### 13er Urban Youth Culture and Crime

- **"Boomerang" phenomenon**: Inner-city 13ers in especially grim world, killing and maiming for no nothing to offer them
- **Victor Herbert observation**: "Growing malaise that young people suffer from," feeling they're not to be trusted, not good people, don't have to follow inhibitions built up for them, especially when moving in a crowd
- Urban kids have begun **reacting with nihilism** that older generations consider proof of worthless ruin
- **New reactionary style of sexism, racism, soulless violence** has seeped into 13er-penned song lyrics
- "**Tec-T**" raps about "bitches," young thugs commit what elders call "hate crimes" against gays, women, high-achieving ethnic groups
- New breed of young criminal shows **remorseless bent toward killing** and maiming for no serious reason

### 13er Youth Crime Characteristics

- **Prizefighter Mike Tyson** admitted to having "shot at a lot of people... I liked to see them run, I liked to see them beg"
- Boomer youths who assaulted **Silent victims** claimed mitigating reasons for antisocial behavior
- 13ers who attack Boomer victims (as in **Bernhard Goetz** and **Central Park jogger cases**) are condemned in media as "evil" thugs deserving execution or stiff term in boot-camp prison
- **Contrast with 1960s Boomer crime**: Associated with rage and betrayed expectations
- **Today's young 13er criminal**: Strikes elders as emotionally detached—even insensible
- **William Raspberry** accuses them of being "generation of animals," **Stanton Samenow** having "ability to shut off their conscience"
- Kids themselves invented word **"wilding"** to describe their behavior
- Asked why in friends group (New York City youth): "Sometimes they do it for fun, sometimes for money, sometimes they just do it"

<!-- p. 332 -->

### Parenting Philosophies: From Permissive to Protective

- **Thirteeners** knew **Boomers** had once sacrificed for prolonged marriages but were now coping with debris; **American children** went from *My Three Sons* family culture to *My Two Dads* step-family reality in the 1970s
- **Norma Klein's** *It's OK If You Don't Love Me*: adolescent girl juggles sex life while sorting feelings about mother's lover, mother's ex-husband, and father's second wife and children

> "The parent is usually a coordinator without voice or authority." — **Kenneth Keniston** (1977), describing how moms and dads "hardly ever have... the power to make others listen to them" in schools, courtrooms

- **America's parenting style** completed two-decade shift from *Father Knows Best* to **Bill Cosby's** *Fatherhood* philosophy of self-doubt

> "Was I making a mistake now? If so, it would just be mistake number nine thousand seven hundred and sixty-three." — **Alvin Poussaint** on dominant media image of uncertain "pal" parent

- Parents shown as bungling, not in charge; boundaries loose, children shown as savvy and understanding
- Parents who admitted being "many-dimensioned, imperfect human beings" reassured by *Ourselves and Our Children*: "are able to give children a more realistic picture of what being a person is all about"

- **Silent parents** (like **Cosby's Cliff Huxtable**): gentle, communicative
- On the other hand, many expressed ambivalence where children sought clear moral answers, abandoned positive future vision, required children to respond young to sophisticated real-world problems
- Books like *Close Encounters of the Third Kind* made adults expect more childlike, children more adultlike

### Growing Cynicism About Adult Authority (1970s)

- Media reinforced view that **adults were not virtuous, competent, or powerful**
- Adult life held no secrets: from TV sit-coms to "breakthrough" youth books, older generations made little effort to shield children from any topic, no matter its effect on child's security and comfort

> "I hate the idea that you should always protect children." — **Judy Blume** defending her books: "They live in the same world we do"

> "We told them there's a lot of garbage out in the world and you've got to be aware of it." — **One "Self-Care Guide"** for latchkey children advised kids of "ways you can protect yourself from mugging and assault: Always pay attention to what is happening around you when you are on the street" and to **15ers**: "Keep your eyes open, expect the worst, and handle it on your own"

- *Mad* magazine's **Al Feldstein**: deliberately encouraged children to "react to life as you would hack through a jungle"

<!-- p. 335 -->

### 13er Economic Attitudes and Career Outlook

- **13ers** embrace all-business attitude in careers: use calculated violence to protect inventory (smugglers), market share (gangs), customer service (safe houses), accounts receivable (addicts), employee relations (runners), and risk management (cops)
- Young drug-runner says: "navigates in a world where most of us couldn't function, a world where you've got to be cunning, slick, and mentally and physically tough"
- World echoes omnichoice ethos seen in **Breakfast Club**: 13ers slow to criticize/punish but quick to figure out what's going on in their lives

### 13er Consumerism and Risk-Taking

- **"Throwaways"**: word 13ers coined for themselves
- Perceived throwaways might take a few risks: blast cars with boom boxes knowing they're doing wrong
- 20-year-old Ohioan with deafening sound system: "I don't care. I'm young and stupid, I guess. Thirteeners know life holds no special favors, for them at least"
- Harvard student **Mandy Silber**: "I keep hearing this is the best time of our lives. And I wonder—is it all downhill? Where the Silent and Boom at like age had every reason to expect someday to nestle into law partnerships, tenured professorships, and seats on the stock exchange, 13ers see very clearly the dead-end traps of a 'McJobs' economy"

### 13er Job Market Prospects

- **American Demographics** predicts five fastest-growing job fields of early 1990s will be: cashiers, nurses, janitors and maids, waiters and waitresses, and truck drivers
- Anytime 13ers see others celebrate (or moralize), they watch their wallets
- As in **Bangles lyric**: "Trouble is, you can't believe that it's true/When the sun goes down, there's something left for you"

### "Lost Generation" Cultural Echoes

- **Less Than Zero** (Ellis novel): publisher heralded it as "New Lost" generation
- Two youths exchange dialogue: "Where are we going?" "I don't know, just driving." "But this road doesn't go anywhere." "That doesn't matter." "What does?" "Just that we're on it, dude"
- Echoes **Hemingway** and **Fitzgerald** themes of aimless movement, disconnection
<!-- p. 333 -->

### Approaching Rising Adulthood

- **13ers reaching late twenties** cannot be said to have "come of age" — nothing yet cements them emotionally, remain a **splintery generation**
- People find almost anything they want in these kids, far more than older generations
- **13ers** come with diverse regional subgroups and ethnic minicultures, each thinking independently, living on their own terms, having their own plans, paying little heed to each other
- First signs of bonding beginning to appear: common **alienation** visible in 13er art and writing, growing awareness of their own **economic vulnerability**

> "Sure we're alienated," admits American University student Daniel Ralph. "But who wouldn't be, in our shoes?"

### Bearing the Burden

- **Thirteeners realize they bear much of the burden** for the Reagan-era prosperity that enriched the Silent and G.I.s
- In inner cities, their **impoverishment has caused adult alarm**; in suburbs, it has been less noticed due to family-subsidized teen affluence
- **13ers entering labor force** are bearing much of their nation's new burden of foreign competition and debt
- In industries where productivity is stagnant, two-tier wage systems hold elders harmless while making the new hires bear the **cost-cutting burden**
- Foreign investors bid up real estate prices, current homeowners profit, but **would-be young homebuyers pay**
- 1980s-era spurt of tax reform lowered the tax rate on high-bracket incomes, FICA taxes on after-school wages kept going up

### Economic Pressures and Work Patterns

- **Spurred by economic need**, youths are working younger, longer, later at night, at more dangerous jobs than any child generation since the Lost
- Federal administrators chart steady rise in child labor law violations
- **13ers carefully hone their survivalist ethic** — two-thirds believe they will have to work harder than earlier generations simply to enjoy the same standard of living
- After leaving school, **13ers face tough choices** made all the more frustrating by the adult wealth they see around them

> "The way society presents it, I'll either be strung out on drugs, a manager at McDonald's, or a lawyer." — Washington, D.C. youth

- Something resembling her middle course is the most frequent path, as many find themselves doing the **low-wage counter, delivery, and cleaning jobs**

### The "Mefobs" Phenomenon

- Boomers have always found demeaning the **"Mefobs"** that **Amitai Etzioni** describes as "more time-consuming, less character-building" than what talented youths used to look forward to
- In most professions—law, medicine, business, the media—**13ers are encountering less promising promotion paths** than the Boom knew at their age
- Smaller likelihood of ever getting a second chance if they fail the first time

### The 13er Habit of Concealment

- **13ers have concealed their plight** thanks to the distinctly 13er habit of calling as little attention as possible to what they are feeling
- In life, when they walk down the street with their **Walkmen and designer shades**, they know how to keep others from knowing what they're hearing, watching, or thinking


<!-- p. 336 -->

### 13ers in the Post-Cold War Era

**Late 1989 Berlin Wall moment**: East German students poured over the wall; *Washington Post* article described high school kids as "left flat" and "utterly unmoved" by events that brought teachers tears of joy
- Youth attitude strikes elders as blasé, unflinching, realistic from **13er perspective**
- They have trampled through the dirty beach where idealism can lead
- "Freedom" of open classrooms produced noise chaos; now they've learned what others constantly tell them: **be skeptical when barriers break down**

**New wars, bad economic news**: These kids were surprised their peers shattered post-Cold War peace
- American campuses newly fazed—Berkeley freshman Charles Connolly: "If something's really for many when he said, 'I think we should go in there and take care of it, full throttle'"
- Thousands of Connolly's peers throttled off in uniform to keep oil flowing from Saudi Arabia to big American homes and cars
- Few 13ers can imagine buying at same age their parents did

**Complex foreign crises** (Korean War once featured hardboiled Truman-era elders and sensitive MASH-era Silent peers; Persian Gulf crisis features the opposite):
- Silent 60-year-olds assume complex, polysyllabic tasks: satellite communications, multilateral negotiations, peace-process evaluations
- **13er 20-year-olds prepare for available jobs**: sweat, hide, move, hit, kill

**"Silent peers' euphoria over end of Cold War"**: Pollster **Peter Hart** published highly critical report about "Democracy's Next Generation"
- Only 12% mentioned voting as attribute of good citizenship
- 48% percent mentioned personal generosity
- Having grown up in age of anti-institutional feeling, **13ers look at it this way**: "When you vote, maybe you'll waste your time—or, worse, later feel tricked. But when you do something real, like bringing food to homeless, you do something that matters, if only on small scale"
- MIT president likened 13er attitude to that of Le Corbusier: "Do a good deed, leave a silver bullet, and move on"

**Neil Postman**, *The Disappearance of Childhood*: When 13ers were little, adults gave children "answers to questions they never asked"
- Problem still plagues this generation—except now questions are what made you the way you are, and how can we fix it
- **Blue-ribbon Screen committeemen** (like **Paul Volcker**) anguish over how to change their attitude about government and inner-city Boomers (like Washington, D.C. health commissioner **Reed Tuckson**) "look internally" to understand "how we produced these children"
- **But 13ers consider such efforts a waste of time and energy**

<!-- p. 334 -->

### 13er Work Attitudes and Career Approach

- **13ers** leave troubles behind at work and take minds off job when they leave
- **Boomer bosses** like **Penny Erikson** see them as "not driven from within," best suited for "short-term tasks" and in need of "reinforcement from above"
- Ask **13ers** how they're doing: "As long as life stays reasonably patched together, 'No problem' is their answer"
- Learned to adjust by moving quickly into and out of other jobs
- Look for quick strikes ahead of long-term promises
- *Wall Street Journal* describes them as "more willing to gamble their careers than... earlier generations"
- Often their best chance for success: striking out on their own, finding small market niche, filling it more cheaply and sensibly than older-run businesses

### 13er Entrepreneurship and Risk-Taking

- Examples of **twenty-fiveish entrepreneurs**: **David Montague** (folding bicycles), **Doug Wadsworth** (plastics recycling)
- For every **Darryl Strawberry** who hits the jackpot, many others don't
- Those who don't end up masking career problems by "boomeranging" back into parental house after trying to make it on their own
- **Ministic ethos**: failure means something must be wrong with *you*
- Rising numbers masking their problems by "boomeranging" back into parental house

### 13er Urban Culture and Social Attitudes

- No place to "boomerang" to—inner-city **13ers** inhabit especially grim world that doesn't like them and offers nothing
- **Victor Herbert**, director of New York City high schools: "They feel they're not to be trusted, they're not good people, and they don't have to follow whatever inhibitions have been built up, especially when they're moving in a crowd"
- Urban kids have begun reaching with nihilism that older generations consider proof of their worthless run

### 13er Crime and "Wilding"

- New reactionary style of sexism, racism, and soulless violence has seeped into **13er-penned song lyrics**
- "Tec-T" raps about "bitches," young thugs commit what elders call "hate crimes" targeted against gays, women, and high-achieving ethnic groups
- New breed of young criminal shows **remorseless bent toward killing** and maiming for no serious reason
- **Prizefighter Mike Tyson** admitted to having "shot at a lot of people... I liked to see them run. I liked to see them beg"
- When **Boomer youths** who assaulted Silent victims said to have mitigating reasons for antisocial behavior, **13ers** who attack **Boomer victims** (as in **Bernhard Goetz** and **Central Park jogger cases**) are condemned in media as "evil" thugs deserving only execution or stiff term in boot-camp prison
- **Boomer crime** in late 1960s associated with rage and betrayed expectations
- Today, young **13er criminal** strikes elders as emotionally detached—even insensible
- **William Raspberry** accuses them of being "generation of animals," **Stanton Samenow** of having "the ability to shut off their conscience"
- Kids themselves invented word **"wilding"** to describe their behavior
- Asked why in New York City, youth explained: "Sometimes they do it for fun, sometimes they do it for money, sometimes they just do it"

<!-- p. 334 -->

### 13er Generation Characteristics (continued)

- **Generational skepticism about mission**: From their perspective, there's temptation to be cynical about idealistic elder-generation talk, which 13ers see as pointless
  - Example: **Marie Xaviere** (aspiring opera singer) notes "even if you didn't want us, you made us. But we're here, and we're going to make the best of it"
  - Despite criticism and low expectations from elders, **Daniel Ralph** insists this generation "will make a difference"

- **13ers' response strategy**: What 13ers seek from others is to be left alone, have unjudgmental scrutiny, and check out what **Nancy Smith** calls "our 'attitude,'" characterized as:
  - A coolness
  - A seasoned irony
  - Uncommitted approach
  - Question mark at end of every sentence

> "Dial into our style," invites **Miles Orkin** in essay "Mucho Slinkage by the Pool." "It's not like some fully bent tongue from hell or anything."

- **Elder perception gap**: Elders don't fully understand 13ers' worldview, only dimly grasp it, but this streetwise generation brings valuable practical skills that may prove critical when America faces serious challenges

- **Hidden strengths**: More than anyone realizes, this generation has seasoned talent for maximizing difficult situations
  - Take note: **Beaver Cleaver** comparison - "Thirteeners may never have glimpsed Nirvana, but they know how to win"

<!-- p. 338 -->

## MILLENNIAL GENERATION

**Born:** 1982–
**Type:** Civic (?)

### First Wave Arrives (1988)

- September 1988: 5- and 6-year-olds arrive at **Burrville Elementary** in Washington, D.C., for first day of kindergarten wearing brand-new green-and-yellow coats and ties, blouses and dresses
- If Boomer school board member **Nate Bush** gets his way, these kids will wear school-issued clothes all the way through high school, "like it or not"
- Parents exercising authority: "I'm the parent, you're the child, and this is a good idea"
- A year later, Japanese children in trim blue uniforms prompt **Boomer author James Fallows** to suggest America is "promoting some sense of purpose and fellow-feeling at school"
- At Burrville Elementary, 13ers in older grades found the uniforms "slightly humiliating," but younger kids hardly seemed to mind
- These kids in green coats and yellow blouses are the vanguard of **America's MILLENNIAL GENERATION**: Cute. Cheerful. Scoutlike. Wanted.

### Break from Prior Patterns

- Not since the 1910s have adults seen such advantage in making kids look alike and work together
- Not since early 1900s have older generations moved so quickly to assert greater adult dominion over the world of childhood—and to implant civic virtue in a new crop of youngsters

### Historic Timing

- Even the timing of this new generation is historic
- Birthyears will stretch to and probably just beyond **year 2000**, the end of the second millennium
- As 1990s begin, **year 2000** is becoming a national target date, much like **1969 deadline President Kennedy** once set for landing a man on the moon—except this time, the goal aims at the nurture of what some are calling a **"new generation"** whose excellence Americans hope to celebrate when the Millennium arrives

### Educational Goals for Year 2000

- In 1990, nation's governors set ambitious agenda of educational goals for year 2000:
  - **90 percent high school graduation rate** for "Class of 2000"
  - President Bush agreed, promising that by year 2000 **"U.S. students will be first in the world in mathematics and science achievement"**
- Also in 1990, investigations into **child labor practices** found violations at all-time high, prompting some reformers to set year 2000 as goal for removing children from dangerous and exploitative jobs and pushing them back into school and family life

### Civic Nurture Initiatives

- Former **Surgeon General C. Everett Koop** has declared nation's determination to produce the **"smoke-free high school Class of 2000"**
- A Washington, D.C., group describing itself as **"Concerned Black Men"** has launched **"Project 2000"** to provide "young black boys with consistent, positive, and literate black role models" in time for the Millennium

<!-- p. 335 -->

### 13er Generational Attitudes and Worldview

**Cynicism and resignation as defining characteristics:**
- "We can arrest them, but jail is no deterrent," reports Washington Long, chief of police in Albany, Georgia - 13ers tell him "Hell, I ain't got nowhere else to go nohow"
- Washington D.C. police chief Isaac Fulwood: "Oftentimes, they don't say anything. They just sit there and say, 'Officer, do what you gotta do'"
- **Terry Williams** in *Cocaine Kids*: 13er criminals' all-business attitude - use of calculated violence to protect inventory (smugglers), market share (competing gangs), customer service (safe houses), accounts receivable (addicts), employee relations (runners), risk management (cops)
- Fulwood: "navigates in a world where most of us couldn't function, a world where you've got to be cunning, slick, and mentally and physically tough"
- **Tracy Chapman** song: "And, of course, a world in which other choices seem even more hopeless. 'I got no plans I ain't going nowhere,' sings Tracy Chapman, 'So take your fast car and keep on driving.'"

**Suburban hopelessness and risk-seeking behavior:**
- **Christopher Lasch**: "young people in the suburbs are just as hopeless as those in the ghetto... living in a state of almost unbearable, though mostly inarticulate, agony. They experience the world only as a source of pleasure and pain"
- Boom culture quick to criticize/punish 13ers but slow to help them find purpose in their lives
- By one count, their ranks include a half-million family **"throwaways"** - word coined just for them
- Perceived throwaways might as well take risks - punkers blast ears with boom boxes knowing what're doing
- "They tell me it will hurt me down the line," explains one 20-year-old Ohioan with deafening sound system in his car, "but I don't care. I'm young and stupid, I guess"

**Expectations and career outlook:**
- "Thirteeners know life holds no special favors, for them at least"
- Harvard student **Mandy Silber**: "I keep hearing this is the best time of our lives, says Harvard student Mandy Silber. 'And I wonder—is it all downhill?'"
- Where the Silent and Boom saw every reason to expect upward mobility (law partnerships, tenured professorships, stock exchange seats), **13ers see very clearly the dead-end traps of a "McJobs" economy**

**Economic projections:**
- *American Demographics* predicts five fastest-growing job fields of early 1990s will be: cashiers, nurses, janitors and maids, waiters and waitresses, truck drivers
- Anytime they see others celebrate (or moralize), 13ers watch their wallets
- **Bangles lyric**: "Trouble is, you can't believe that it's true/When the sun goes down, there's something left for you"

**"Lost" generation identity:**
- *Less Than Zero*, Ellis novel touted by publisher as heralding a "New Lost" generation
- Two youths exchange: "Where are we going?" "I don't know, just driving." "But this road doesn't go anywhere." "That doesn't matter." "What does?" "Just that we're on it, dude"
- **Hemingway and Fitzgerald** references frame generational comparison

<!-- p. 339 -->

### Millennial Generation (Born 1982 to ?)

**TYPE:** Civic (?)

**Demographics:**
- Projected number: 76,000,000
- Now alive in U.S.: 33,000,000
- Percent immigrant: 12%

**FAMILY TREE:**
- Typical grandparents: Silent
- Parents: Boom and Thirteenth
- Children: (new Adaptive and new Idealist)
- Typical grandchildren: (new Reactive)

**SAMPLE MEMBERS, birth (death):**
- 1982 Hilary Morgan
- 1982 Dooney Waters
- c. 1983 Cecilia Chichan
- c. 1983 Jebbie Bush
- 1985 Jessica McClure
- 1985 Tabatha Foster (1988)
- 1987 "Baby M"

**FUTURE PERIOD OF POLITICAL LEADERSHIP:**
- Plurality in Congress: 2035-2060 (proj.)
- Term of Presidency: 2040-2065 (proj.)
- Majority of Supreme Court: 2050-2075 (proj.)

**PROMINENT FOREIGN PEERS:**
- 1982 Prince William

**HISTORY AND LIFECYCLE:**
- **Age 0-0** (1982): "Class of 2000" born; flurry of books demand protection for children
- **0-1** (1983): Cute-baby movie trend begins
- **0-2** (1984): *Time* cover story proclaiming "The End of the Sexual Revolution"
- **0-3** (1985): U.S. becomes debtor nation; crying-baby antideflect ads
- **0-5** (1987): "Everybody's Baby," **Jessica McClure** rescued; Baby "M" case
- **0-6** (1988): Surge in "cocooning," celebrity pregnancies, school uniforms
- **0-7** (1989): *Webster* case limits *Roe v. Wade*; antidrug crusade grows
- **0-8** (1990): Educational goals set for the year 2000; first Children's Summit at UN

<!-- p. 336 -->

### 13ers' Response to the End of the Cold War

- Late 1989: East German students poured over the Berlin Wall, a *Washington Post* article described high school kids as "left flat" and "utterly unmoved" by events that brought their teachers tears of joy
- Youth attitude that strikes elders as blasé is, from 13ers' perspective, **unflinching and realistic**
- They have tramped through the dirty beach where idealism can lead
- Remembering how the "freedom" of open classrooms produced noisy chaos, they've learned to be **skeptical about what happens whenever barriers are broken down**
- Maybe there will be new wars, maybe bad economic news—at the very least new competition
- These kids were less surprised than their teachers when Iraq shattered post-Cold War peace
- American campuses were hardly fazed—**Berkeley freshman Charles Connolly** speaking for many when he said, "I think we should go in there and take care of it, full throttle"
- Thousands of Connolly's peers throttled off in uniform to keep oil flowing from Saudi Arabia to the big American homes and cars that so few 13ers can ever imagine buying at the same age their parents did
- Where the Korean War once featured hardboiled, Tramanesque elders and sensitive, *M*A*S*H*-like juniors, the **Persian Gulf crisis features the opposite**
- Silent 60-year-olds assume the complex, polysyllabic tasks: satellite communications, multilateral negotiations, peace-process evaluations
- Thirteener 20-year-olds prepare for the **brute, one-syllable jobs: sweat, hide, move, hit, and kill**

### "Democracy's Next Generation" Report

- **Peter Hart** published highly critical report about "Democracy's Next Generation" amid the Silent peers' euphoria over the end of the Cold War
- Only **12 percent** of 13ers mentioned voting as an attribute of good citizenship
- Then again, **48 percent** mentioned personal generosity
- Having grown up in an age of anti-institutional feeling, 13ers look at it this way: When you vote, maybe you'll waste your time—or, worse, later feel tricked
- But when you do something real, like bringing food to the homeless, you do something that matters, **if only on a small scale**
- The president of MIT has likened the 13er civic attitude to that of the Lone Ranger: Do a good deed, leave a silver bullet, and move on

### *The Disappearance of Childhood*

- **Neil Postman** observes that when 13ers were little, adults gave children "answers to questions they never asked"
- That problem still plagues this generation—except now the questions are, in effect, **what made you the way you are, and how can we fix it?**
- Blue-ribbon Silent committeemen (like **Paul Volcker**) anguish over how to change their attitude about government, and inner-city Boomers (like Washington, D.C. health commissioner **Reed Tuckson**) "look internally" to understand "how we produced these children"
- But 13ers consider such efforts **a waste of time and energy**
<!-- p. 340 -->

### Adult Disappointment and Protective Concern for 13ers

- **Boom adults** express disappointment in how **13ers** are turning out, with second thoughts about their own parenting approaches
- Federal judge **Vincent Femía** (1989): "we've lost a generation of youth to the war on drugs. We have to start with the younger group, concentrate on the kindergarteners"
- Critics reflect broader anxiety about past excesses that should not be repeated
- **Karl Zinsmeister** (1990 *Atlantic*): suggests "preventing young criminals from infecting a class of successors" by "putting the full weight of public protection on the side of babies and schoolchildren"
- Reference to rescuing "me generation from the folly of the new feudalism" by former New York mayor **Edward Koch** (1990): a "new generation" could provide "the experience of working successfully with others"
- Film *Parenthood* draws contrast between hardened teenage 13ers and "cute Millennial 'Babies on Board'"

### Rising Protective Crest Over Childhood (Early 1980s-)

- **First-wave Millennials** riding powerful crest of protective concern dating to early 1980s over American childhood environment
- **1981** (year before "Class of 2000" born): volley of books assaulted adult mistreatment of children
  - 13er birthyears: *Children Without Childhood, The Disappearance of Childhood, Our Endangered Children, All Grown Up and No Place to Go*
- Themes: reconsidering human consequences of divorce, latchkey households, value-neutral education
- **1984**: Two kids-as-devils movies (*Children of the Corn, Firestarter*) flopped at box office, marking end of drying genre
- **Mid-1980s**: Studios released child-as-victim movies (*The Shining, Cujo*), cuddly-baby movies (*Raising Arizona, Three Men and a Baby, Baby Boom, For Keeps, She's Having a Baby*)
- New cinematic children help adults—not 13ers, but **Millennials**—sharing parental burdens, reminding parents to cope with life more responsibly
- **1986**: Polls reported tripling in popularity of "staying home with family"
- **Jane Pauley's twins** to **Bruce Willis' Lamaze class**: Boom media elite reinforced new interest in infant nurture
- **1988**: Babies declared "fad" (new "yuppies") in *San Francisco Chronicle*, *New York Times*

### Cultural Shift and Consciousness Revolution's Ebb

- Changing popular culture tone coincided with **ebbing of Consciousness Revolution** in early 1980s
- **First-wave Millennials** arrived in America awash in moral confidence but institutional disrepair
- Social changes: deferred marriage, smallish dual-income households became uncontroversial facts
- Others ("open" marriages, mind-altering drugs) rejected
- Rates of abortion, voluntary sterilization, and divorce plateaued or reversed
- Few legislators began criticizing antichild policy consensus—from unchecked growth in federal borrowing to dwindling

<!-- p. 337 -->

### 13ers' Ironic, Uncommitted Communication Style

- **13ers** tend toward ironic detachment rather than earnest expression—temptation to adopt "**Max Headroom**" computer-programmed "I'm sorry-sorry" persona
- Mostly view such talk as pointless—like aspiring opera singer **Marie Xaviere** who says "even if you didn't want us, you made us. But we're here, and we're going to make the best of it"
- They recognize they are a **generation without an elder-perceived mission**
- Despite criticism and generally low expectations, **Daniel Ralph** insists this generation "will make a difference"
- What 13ers ask of others may be to **lend an unjudgmental ear and check out what Nancy Smith calls "our 'attitude,' a coolness, a detachment"**—to know we speak in ironic, flip, uncommitted way
- **Question mark at end of every other sentence**—"Dial into our style," invites **Miles Orkin** in essay "Mucho Slippage by the Pool"

> "It's not like some fully bent tongue from hell or anything." —Miles Orkin

- **Their elders don't yet see it**—13ers themselves only dimly sense it, but this **streetwise generation brings a bag of savvy tricks for getting the most out of a bad hand**
- May come in handy next time America gets into real trouble
- More than anyone, 13ers have developed **seasoned talent for getting the most out of a bad hand**
- **Beaver Cleaver comparison**: "Thirteeners may never have glimpsed Nirvana, but they know how to win"

<!-- p. 341 -->

### Boomer Parenting Philosophy and Cultural Shift

- **Boomer parents** determined to create "unerringly wholesome environment" for **Millennial tots**
- Where **Silent** had brought 13er kids to R-rated movies *about* them, **Boomers** take Millennials to G-rated movies made *for* them
- Old 13er *Willy Wonka*-style movies stressed individualism and differences among kids; new **Boom-produced films** (*An American Tail*, *Oliver and Company*, *The Land Before Time*) stress **civic virtues**: equality, optimism, cooperation, community
- **Disney animation studios** laid off cartoonists during 13er era, began replenishing staffs during Millennial era—now employ more artists than at any time since 1937 production of *Snow White*
- **Boom scriptwriters** crafting plots with stronger moral lessons and less ambivalent messages about drugs, alcohol, teenage sex

### Generational Reversal: From Permissive to Protective

- **"The '60s Generation, Once High on Drugs, Warns Its Children"** (*Wall Street Journal*, 1990)
- Parents, teachers, prosecutors setting about protecting children from "social and chemical residue of the euphoric awakening they themselves had launched"
- Dinner tables and national agenda: stay away from drugs, alcohol, AIDS, teen pregnancy, profanity, TV ads, unchaperoned gatherings, "mean-streets" aggressive dress or manners
- Boomer conferences where **40-year-old political candidates** try to persuade public they experimented with drugs but "never really enjoyed it"
- **Tipper Gore's** crusade against lyrics; **Michael S** "mother lion"
- **Terry Rakolta** campaigns against sex and violence on prime-time television
- **Barbie's doll band** changes from the old "Rockers" to the cleaned-up "Sensations"
- **Grown-up Boomer radicals** who once delighted in shocking their own moms and dads now surprise themselves with their own "fectionist approach to child nurture"
- Growing numbers of fathers embracing **"daddy-track" work schedules** for more time at home to raise young children
- **Garry Trudeau** in *Doonesbury* strip showed Boomer explaining he raised his girl "like an Asian child... by teaching her the value of discipline, hard work, and respect for others"

### Policy Shifts Favoring Children

- Late 1980s: intergenerational **Transfer of Wealth** toward children
- **KIDS-PAC lobby** formed around children's interests; child-care surged ahead of foreign policy as top voter concern
- **1989**: federal attorneys filing first-ever lawsuit against apartment units that banned children
- **George Bush** admitted being "haunted" by plight of inner-city children; met with Hope to the straight-arrow example of one crack-house child—**7-year-old Dooney Waters**
<!-- p. 338 -->

## MILLENNIAL GENERATION

**Born:** 1982–
**Type:** Civic (?)

### First Day of Kindergarten (1988)

- September 1988 at **Burrville Elementary** in Washington, D.C.: 5- and 6-year-old children arrived in brand-new green-and-yellow coats, blouses and dresses
- **Boomer school board member Nate Bush:** predicts these kids will wear school-issued clothes through high school, "like it or not"
- Parents will exercise authority: "I'm the parent, you're the child, and this is a good idea"
- A year later: **Boomer James Fallows** observed Japanese children in trim blue uniforms, suggested "Americans might also promote some sense of purpose and fellow-feeling at school"
- At Burrville Elementary, 13ers in older grades found uniforms "slightly humiliating," but younger kids hardly noticed
- These kids in green coats and yellow blouses are the **vanguard of America's MILLENNIAL GENERATION**

### Generational Characteristics

- **Cute. Cheerful. Scoutlike. Wanted.**
- Not since the 1910s have middle Missionaries dressed child G.I.s in Boy Scout brown
- Adults see advantage in making kids look alike and work together
- Not since early 1900s have older generations moved so quickly to assert greater adult dominion over the world of childhood
- Goal: implant civic virtue in a new crop of youngsters

### Historic Timing

- Timing of this new generation is **historic**
- Birthyears will stretch to and probably just beyond the year 2000, the end of the second millennium
- As 1990s begin, **year 2000 is becoming a national target date**
- Like **1969 deadline President Kennedy** once set for landing a man on the moon
- This time, goal aims at nurturing what some are calling a **"new generation"** whose excellence Americans hope to celebrate when the Millennium arrives

### Year 2000 Educational Goals (1990)

- Nation's governors set ambitious educational agenda for year 2000:
  - **90 percent high school graduation rate** for the "Class of 2000"
  - **President Bush** agreed, promising that by year 2000 "U.S. students will be first in the world in mathematics and science achievement"
- Also in 1990: investigations into **child labor practices** found violations at all-time high
- Prompted some reformers to set year 2000 as goal for **removing children from dangerous and exploitive jobs** and pushing them back into school and family life

### Keep America Beautiful Campaign

- **Former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop** declared nation's determination to produce the **"smoke-free high school Class of 2000"**
- Washington, D.C. group: **"Concerned Black Men"** launched **"Project 2000"** to provide "young black boys with consistent, positive, and literate black role models" in time for the Millennium

<!-- p. 342 -->

### Shifting Parenting Culture in the 1980s

- **Cosby Show** shifted focus: parents became less "pally" and more authoritative—making punishments stick, telling children "you're too young" for certain activities
- **Dr. Dobson's** advice in *Dare to Discipline* reflected evangelical Boomer parenting approach

### Growing Adult Concern for Child Safety

- **Teddy Roosevelt-era furor** over runaway streetcars: adults made serious efforts to regulate child endangerment
- **1990s child safety anxiety**: New Yorkers expressed deeper anger over nine stray-bullet killings than over much larger number of murders among teenage 13ers
- **Safer suburbia**: parents prioritized child-friendly devices and safety equipment
  - **Gerber drawer latches, stove knob covers, furniture corner cushions, toilet locks, I-See-U car mirrors, Kiddie Kap bicycle helmets** all displayed in "Perfectly Safe" catalogue
- **1980s decade**: states began passing laws requiring infant restraints in automobiles; decade ended with talk of requiring infant restraints in commercial airplanes and **Howard County, Maryland's first-ever bicycle helmet law**

### Rediscovering Public Responsibility for Children

- Adults of all ages rediscovering affection and sense of public responsibility for other people's children
- **1970s Boom's "Big Chill" gatherings**: all-adult affairs
- **1980s gatherings**: started including babies, then small children, now bigger children
- Infant and toddler seats began appearing in restaurants

### High-Profile Child Rescue Cases

- **Baby Jessica McClure** (18-month-old): whole nation anxiously followed her rescue after being trapped for two days in abandoned well in Lubbock, Texas
- **2-year-old Tabatha Foster**: 5 organ transplants made possible by $350,000 in public donations (much from celebrities) and 4-year-old **Cecilia Chichan**, sole survivor from crash of **Northwest Flight 255** in Detroit

### New Generation Treated as Precious

- Children being treated as more precious than their parents
- **Washington, D.C.** recently sentenced pregnant first-time drug offender to jail for explicit reason that her behavior put unborn child at risk
- **New social conception**: data peace parents allow older 13er children plenty of room for self-discovery, while adult society (media, legislatures, courts) now prodding parents to control child environment and enforcing intention with tough new laws
- Parents now potentially **criminally liable for their children's misbehavior**

### California Gang Law and Parental Responsibility

- **New California law** discriminates minors from law that incriminates parents for gang vices committed by children
- **Ellen Goodman** observes lawmakers have "turned the Bible on its head.... They've decided that the sins of the sons shall be visited upon the parents"
- **First time in living memory**: calls are rising for special orphanages, "academies," and **Boys Towns** for small children whose (mostly 13er) parents deemed socially unfit
- Places where "vulnerable" children would be raised and nurtured "under 'strong rules and strong principles'"
- Where 13er kids were previously known as **latchkeys, throwaways, boomerangs**, and other terms

<!-- p. 339 -->

