<!-- p. 343 -->

### Millennial Education and the "New Vocationalism"

- Public education shifting toward **"new vocationalism"** as Millennials reach school age—values and grade-adult assertiveness replacing earlier emphasis on academics
- Kindergartens becoming more academic, elementary schools stressing **"good works"**—emphasis on helping out with family and neighborhood chores
- Education now includes calls for **continence**, replacing earlier carefully nonjudgmental, value-neutral approach
- **Censorship and "search-and-seizure" cases**: G.I.-dominated U.S. Supreme Court reversed two-decade trend toward student rights, strengthening school disciplinarians' hand
- Boom parents and schools seeking higher approval ratings—teachers rising in public esteem and pay
- **Chester Finn** calls this **"a seismic shock"** gripping adult mood toward education, with sharply increasing support for:
  - More homework
  - Longer school days
  - Toughened graduation requirements
  - Greater parental involvement in classrooms
  - Nationally standardized curriculum

> "No way will perfectionist Boomer parents let their tots reach age 17 unable to pass the Ravitch-Finn history and literature test."

### The Childhood Development Clock Slows Down

- **Boom parents and teachers showing down the childhood development clock**—unlike the Silent who sped it up
- From 1976-1988: proportion of students held back in elementary school jumped **one-third**
- In 1989, roughly one of every five kindergarten-eligible children were **deliberately kept in preschool programs**
- **Gesell Test** materials (for determining kindergarten readiness) sales jumped **67 percent between 1984 and 1987**
- Publishers of children's literature revising toward the **"3ser-era"** emphasis on rushing readers to more sophisticated subject matter
- Parents now read **babylike cloth and cardboard books** to Millennial children—books that when 13ers were little had to be imported from Europe
- New story lines like **Oak Tree's Value Tales** focus less on family problems, more on family virtues

### Boom Parents vs. Silent Parenting Styles

- **"Drown the Berenstain Bears"**: Boomer **Charles Krauthammer's** cry against youth literature celebrating the parent as pal (attacking 1950s-60s PTA meetings and school board meetings)
- Boom parents in their thirties often chastise elder Silent for their **permissiveness**
- **Silent approach**: Give kids complete information, let them make their own minds
- **Boomer approach**: More inclined to establish firm boundaries and structure


<!-- p. 340 -->

### Shifting Adult Mission Toward Millennials

- **Palpable disappointment** among Boomers in how **13ers** turned out, causing reflection on childrearing approaches
- **Federal judge Vincent Femia** (1989): "We've lost a generation of youth to the war on drugs. We have to start with the younger group, concentrate on the kindergartners"
- **1990 Atlantic cover story** by **Boomer Karl Zinsmeister**: "preventing young criminals from infecting a class of successors" by "putting the full weight of public protection on the side of babies and schoolchildren"
- Former New York mayor **Edward Koch** (1990): a "new generation" could be provided "the experience of working successfully with others"
- Films like *Parenthood* contrast Boomer **hardened teenage 13ers** with "cute Millennial 'Babies on Board'"

### Protective Crest Over Childhood (Early 1980s)

- **First-wave Millennials** riding powerful **protective concern** dating to early 1980s
- **1981** ("Class of 2000" birth year): volley of books critiqued adult mistreatment of children
  - *13er birthyears*: *Children Without Childhood*, *The Disappearance of Childhood*, *Our Endangered Children*, *All Grown Up and No Place to Go*
- Within couple years, other authors reconsidered **human consequences of divorce, latchkey households, value-neutral education**
- **1984**: Two **kids-as-devils movies** (*Children of the Corn*, *Firestarter*) flopped at box office, marking end of era
- Start of **more positive film depiction of children** through mid-1980s

### New Cinematic Children (Mid-1980s)

- Studios released **cuddly child-as-victim movies**
  - *The Shining*, *Cujo*, and late 1980s: *Raising Arizona*, *Three Men and a Baby*, *Baby Boom*, *For Keeps*, *She's Having a Baby*
- New cinematic children began **helping adults—not, like 13ers, sharing parental burdens**, but reminding parents to cope with life more responsibly on their own
- From **1986**: polls reported tripling in popularity of "staying home with family"
- From **Jane Pauley's twins** to **Bruce Willis' Lamaze class**, Boom's media elite reinforced **new interest in infant nurture**
- By **1988**: babies declared "fad" by *San Francisco Chronicle*, "the new loves" in *New York Times*

### Cultural and Social Shifts

- Changing popular culture tone coincided with **ebbing of Consciousness Revolution** in early 1980s
- **First-wave Millennials** arrived in America awash in **moral confidence** but **institutional disrepair**
- Social changes became **uncontroversial facts of American life**:
  - **Deferred marriage, smallish dual-income households**
  - **"Open" marriages, mind-altering drugs** rejected
- Rates of **abortion, voluntary sterilization, and divorce** plateaued or reversed
- Few legislators began criticizing **antichild policy consensus**—from unchecked growth in federal borrowing to dwindling

<!-- p. 344 -->

### Millennial Trends: Protection and Structure

- **Millennials show signs of generational trends** toward improved education and health care, strengthening families, more adult affection and protection, and a rising sense that youths need a national mission
- **Two-decade animus against children** (mid-1960s onward) cannot reverse itself overnight
  - Polls in mid-1980s still showed adults more self- than child-focused in behavior
  - Though less so than a decade earlier
- **Divorce and abortion rates** are stuck at high levels, if down a bit from early-1980s peak
- **Thirteeners delaying parenthood** even more than Boomers at like age, but showing greater commitment to making marriages last
- **Sex, violence, and alcohol** in media and advertising remain accessible to small children, though proportion of R-rated films has been falling and standards for PG ratings have stiffened
- **American elementary schools still underfunded** compared to other developed nations
  - Tax revolts against fiscal base are gradually cooling off
  - Massive federal budget deficits continue with more evidence of adult guilt over burdens they will impose on today's children
- **Overall trend assessment**: Arguments of those who stress more values, more structure, and more protection in the child's world are strengthening year to year, while arguments of those who disagree are losing ground

### Millennial Facts

- **First-wave Millennials** born after the great 1960s and 1970s plunge in American fertility rates
- **Lowest child-to-parent ratio in American history**
- They arrived at a time when only 2 percent of all kids under age 18 live in families with five or more kids—just one-fourth the proportion of first-wave 13ers

### Perspectives on Child-Rearing

- **William Bennett** (responding to suggestions that the answer to drugs lies in more information): "This child does not need drug education. That child needs protection, that child needs order, and that child needs love."
- **Ellen Goodman** acknowledges "we are now seeing various attempts to put parents in charge, to shore up authority, to foster at least the image and maybe the reality of a traditional family unit"
- Many wonder if offspring of such families will develop the openmindedness we now take for granted in children
- **"What they're learning is that life is black and white"** (columnist Anna Quindlen), without hearing "the long version of answers to life's questions" and without gaining "a measure of empathy and understanding to shade the primary colors of censure"
- **Today's third and fourth graders** "seem more evolved young citizens than we were" at that age, says Quindlen
- She assesses them assimilating society's **"Shalt Nots"** about crime, drugs, pollution, and education with disquieting energy and unanimity

<!-- p. 341 -->

### Boomer Parents' Protective Approach to Millennial Children

- **Doonesbury strip** (1989): **Garry Trudeau**, father of a Millennial, drew strip showing a Boomer explaining he raised his girl "like an Asian child... by teaching her the value of discipline, hard work, and respect for others"
- Boomer parents determined to create "unerringly wholesome environment" for Millennial children
- **Silent Generation** brought 13er kids to R-rated movies made *about* them; **Boomers** take Millennials to G-rated movies made *for* them
- Old 13er *Willy Wonka*-style movies stressed individualism and differences among kids
- New Boom-produced films (*An American Tail*, *Oliver and Company*, *The Land Before Time*) stress **civic virtues: equality, optimism, cooperation, and community**

### Cultural Shift in Children's Entertainment

- **Disney animation studios** laid off cartoonists during 13er era
- Studios began replenishing staffs during Millennial era
- Now employ more artists than at any time since 1937 production of *Snow White*
- Boom scriptwriters crafting plots with **stronger moral lessons** and **less ambivalent messages** about drugs, alcohol, and teenage sex (late 1980s and beyond)

### Boomer Parenting vs. Earlier Approaches

- **Grown-up Boomer radicals** who once delighted in shocking their own moms and dads now surprise themselves with **strictly perfectionist approach to child nurture**
- Growing numbers of fathers demanding "daddy-track" work schedules for more time at home to raise young children


<!-- p. 345 -->

### Millennial Children: Healthcare and Fertility Trends

- Despite small family sizes, **Millennial babies frequently arrive to parents who want them desperately**
- **Abortion rate peaked in 1980**, has shown gradual decline since
- **Infertility treatment and "preemie" care** have become major growth fields in medicine
- **1986-1988**: infertility-related doctor visits quadrupled
- **In 1970, premature infant had 5% chance of living; by 1990, 90% survive** at average cost over $100,000 per child

### Education and Economic Conditions (1980s)

- **Early 1980s**: decisive turnaround in public attitudes toward public schools
- Beginning of **"quality education" as political issue**
- First year most parents approved of local school district performance
- First seven straight years teacher salaries increased faster than inflation (after seven years of real salary decline)

### Child Poverty and Social Indicators

- **Child poverty rate peaked in 1983 at 24.6%**, gradually declined thereafter
- **U.S. divorce rate peaked in 1981**
- **Homicide rate against children age 1-4 peaked in 1982**

### Healthcare Access Expansion

- **Since 1983**: increasing share of children below poverty line made eligible for Medicaid
- **1990**: Congress expanded Medicaid to cover all poor children under 18 by year 2001
- Starting with those born after September 30, 1983, reaching 6 years of age by 1991 (no 13ers need apply)

### Children's Savings and Spending Patterns

- **Per capita savings rate for children age 4-12**: held steady at ~15% from 1968-1984
- **By 1989**: risen sharply to over 30%
- **In early 1980s**: kids age-saved only one-third as much as they spent on candy, soft drinks, and snacks
- **Over last decade**: proportion of child income from allowances (vs. job earnings) has risen steadily
- With parental encouragement, they save more than spend on convenience food

### "Only Eight Years Old" - Atlantic Magazine Feature (1990)

> "Only Eight Years Old," headlines an ad in a 1990 issue of the *Atlantic*, "And *He's* Teaching *Me* About Science!" Twenty years ago, such an ad would not have appeared. Or, if it had, no one would have believed it. Now we do.

- **Boomer parents setting out to produce kids** who are smart, powerful, dutiful
- Children **possessed of rational minds, positive attitude, selfless team virtue**
- **Boomers hope Millennials will build according to great ideals** their parents can only envision
- These children **not being raised to explore inner world** (Boomers figure they can handle that) but instead **to achieve and excel at the outer**


<!-- p. 342 -->

### Shift in Child-Rearing: From Permissiveness to Protection

- **Cosby Show** shift: Parents became "less pally and more in charge"—stricter punishments, telling kids "you're too young" for certain activities
- Evangelical Boomers embracing **Dr. Dobson's** advice in *Dare to Discipline*

### Adult Concern Over Child Safety (1980s)

- **Teddy Roosevelt-era** levels of adult concern over child safety unprecedented since
- **New Yorkers** expressed "deeper anger over nine stray-bullet killings of small children than they had ever felt about the much larger number of murders among teenage 13ers"
- Safety equipment boom: **Gerber drawer latches**, **stove knobs**, **furniture corner cushions**, **toilet locks**, **I-See-U car mirrors**, **Kiddie Kap bicycle helmets** (all displayed in "Perfectly Safe" catalogue)
- **1980s decade**: States passing laws requiring **infant restraints in automobiles**; decade ended with talk of requiring **infant restraints in commercial airplanes** and **Howard County, Maryland** passing nation's first-ever **bicycle helmet law**

### Rediscovery of Public Responsibility for Children

- Adults of all ages rediscovering "affection and sense of public responsibility for other people's children"
- **1970s Boom's "Big Chill" gatherings** were all-adult affairs; **1980s**: Started including babies, then small children, now bigger children
- **Infant and toddler seats** began appearing in restaurants that had never included them

### High-Profile Child Rescue Cases

- Whole nation "anxiously followed the fate of little girls in distress"
- **"Everybody's Baby," 18-month-old Jessica McClure**: Saved after being trapped for two days in abandoned well in **Lubbock, Texas**
- **2-year-old Tabatha Foster**: Five organ transplants made possible by **$350,000 in public donations** (much from celebrities); **4-year-old Cecilia Chichan** rescued from crash of **Northwest Flight 255 in Detroit**

### New Generation Treated as Precious

- Children being treated as "precious—often, more precious than their parents"
- Judge in Washington, D.C. recently sentenced **pregnant first-time drug offender** to jail for explicit reason that her behavior put unborn child at risk
- **Where the media once urged parents to allow their 13er children plenty of room for self-discovery**, adult society (media, legislatures, courts) now prodding parents to **control the child environment** and enforcing intention with **tough new laws** making parents **civilly or criminally liable for their children's misbehavior**

### Shift in Legal/Social Accountability for Children

- **California law** incriminating parents for gang vices committed by children
- **Ellen Goodman** observes lawmakers have "turned the Bible on its head.... They've decided that the sins of the sons shall be visited upon the parents"
- First time in living memory: **Calls for rising for special orphanages**, **"academies,"** and **Boys Towns** for small children whose (mostly 13er) parents deemed socially unfit
- Places in which **William Bennett** says children "will be raised and nurtured" under "strong rules and strong principles"
- **Where 13er kids were best known as latchkeys, throwaways, boomerangs**, and other terms

<!-- p. 346 -->

### The Millennial Generation's Future Potential

- Dreams and wonder about **Millennial children** (just learning to walk, talk, and read) reappear in adult conversations
- **NASA official Thomas Paine** (1988) predicted: "the first Martians are already born and toddling around somewhere here on earth"
- Speculations about what these smart preschoolers might achieve:
  - Great scientists solving cancer
  - Great engineers protecting the environment
  - Great producers ending world hunger
- **Life expectancy projections**: A girl born in 1988 can expect to live into her nineties on average, taking her beyond the year 2080, past **America's Tricentennial**
- Parents gazing into baby's eyes wonder what those eyes will someday see
- Sense of awe and possibility surrounding this generation's future potential

