### Millennial Education and Parenting Shift

- As **Millennial** peers reach school age, public education moving toward "**new traditionalism**" - adult assertiveness replacing adult permissiveness
- Kindergartens becoming more academic, elementary schools stressing "**good works**" - emphasis on helping out with family and neighborhood chores
- Sex education now calls for **continence**, replacing earlier nonjudgmental, value-neutral approach
- In censorship and search-and-seizure cases, **G.I.-dominated U.S. Supreme Court** reversed two-decade trend toward student rights, strengthened school disciplinarians
- **Boomer-era public schools** earning higher approval ratings in public polls
- Teachers rising in public esteem and pay, purpose
- **Chester Finn** calls it "a **seismic shock**" - adult mood toward education shifting with sharply increasing support for:
  - More homework
  - Longer school days
  - Toughened graduation requirements
  - Greater parental involvement in classrooms
  - Nationally standardized curriculum

> "No way will perfectionist Boomer parents let their tots reach age 17 unable to pass the Ravitch-Finn history and literature test."

### Acceleration of Childhood Development Clock

- Boom parents and teachers slowing down the **childhood development clock** - unlike the Silent who sped it up
- From **1976** through **1988**, proportion of students held back in elementary school jumped by **one-third**
- By **1989**, roughly one of every five kindergarten-eligible children were deliberately kept in preschool programs
- **Gesell Test** materials (determining kindergarten readiness) sales jumped **67 percent between 1984 and 1987**
- Publishers of children's literature revising works for **13ers** - rushing readers to more sophisticated subject matter
- Parents and babylike cloth and cardboard books to Millennial children - books that when 13ers were little had to be imported from Europe
- New story lines (like **Oak Tree's Value Tales**) focus less on family problems, more on family virtues

### Boomer vs. Silent Parenting Approaches

- If circa-1990 nurturing trends please the Boom, they repudiate way many Silent raised their own kids
- "**Drown the Bernstein Bears**" became Boomer **Charles Krauthammer's** cry against youth literature celebrating parent as pal
- At school and PTA meetings, **Boom parents in their thirties** often chastise elder **Silent** for their permissiveness
- Where Silent would give kids complete information then let them make up their own minds, **Boomers more inclined to establish firm**
<!-- p. 348 -->

