## Chapter 12: The Past as Prologue

### Crisis Era Optimism (1937-1943)

- **"Tomorrow Is Another Day"** - cultural references from late 1930s/early 1940s reflected optimistic vision during turning-point years of **CRISIS ERA**
  - Songs: "Somewhere over the Rainbow," "The Bluebirds over the White Cliffs of Dover"
  - Exhibitions: 1939 New York's World Fair ("There'll Be Bluebirds")
- During crisis, patterns reflected **total consensus** about society's direction:
  - Material abundance (millions of cars and shoes)
  - Spiritual simplicity (home and apple pie)
  - Struggle requiring **total unity** and **total sacrifice**
- **Generational roles during crisis:**
  - Americans looked to **elders** for strategic vision
  - Looked to **midlifers** for tactical means
  - Looked to **rising adults** for selfless muscle
- Crisis mindset fused with **childlike innocence** - difficult to rekindle in normal times
- **Historical pattern:** Such moods don't arrive often, but recur at specific intervals:
  - 1680s
  - 1770s
  - (Briefly) around 1860
  - Americans braced for "raging storm" each time, hoping the sun would shine afterward

### Looking Back at Outer-Driven Eras

- Moving forward decades from crisis, the future resembles an **OUTER-DRIVEN ERA**
- **Tomorrowland** image from 1950s vision of "a friendly future":
  - Moving sidewalks
  - Soft-hued geometric shapes
  - Futuristic Mu-

<!-- p. 353 -->

### The Cycle of Constellational Moods: A Paradigm

- **Cycle offers hope**: suggests that standards by which Americans measure progress shift from era to era—from material to spiritual, from community improvement to self-perfection, from basic survival to civilized refinement—and then back again
- **Historian James Truslow Adams** (during Great Depression): "the American Dream gives every youth 'the chance to grow into something bigger and finer, as bigger and finer appeared to him.'" So too for every new generation

**Generational endowments and the American Dream:**
- Each generational type has its own special vision of the American Dream
- Each type can fare well or badly in fulfilling that vision
- Each can leave gifts—or harms—to its heirs
- Each generational type gives different "generational endowments"

**Connecting generations to progress:**
- To appreciate the connection between generations and progress, need to build paradigms
- First of the four **constellational moods**
- Then of the peer personality and lifecycle of each generational type

### The Cycle of Constellational Moods: A Paradigm

> "Those who cannot remember the past are condemned to repeat it." —**George Santayana**

**Historical patterns vs. randomness:**
- Many fundamentals of history do seem to repeat
- History not purely random—would be less important if it were
- History leaves telltale traces of certain regularity
- Can learn from parallels between culture, fashions, politics—or simply the **moods**—of different periods

**Identifying constellational eras in American history:**
- Authors identify some of these parallels—call them **constellational eras**
- **Eighteen total constellational eras** in American history (as many as there have been generations)
- In Chapter 2, defined each era as a **generation-long birthyear period** preceding each aligned constellation (which occurs in the year the last cohort of each new generation is born)
- Display these eras in Figure 12-1
- Notice how the **Civil War Cycle** had only three eras (including abbreviated combination of Inner-Driven and Crisis eras)—just as it had only three generational types

**Duration and calibration of cycles:**
- **Constellational era**: typically lasts about twenty-two years
- **Four-era cycle**: lasts roughly eighty to one hundred years, or about the lifespan of a long-lived individual
- To calibrate the duration of America's five cycles, compare them with **five Idealist lifespans** laid end-to-end:
  - **Simon Bradstreet** (1603–1697)
  - **Benjamin Franklin** (1706–1790)
  - **Lucretia Mott** (1793–1880)
  - **Franklin Roosevelt** (1882–1945)
  - **Albert Gore, Jr.** (1948– )
- Each of these individuals witnessed (or in the last case...
<!-- p. 351 -->

### The Shift from Tomorrowland to Pepperland (1960s-1970s)

- Moving into another cycle notch: an **AWAKENING ERA** beginning in the mid-1960s and early 1970s
- American vision of the future shifted dramatically from **Tomorrowland** to **Pepperland**
- **Erector-set affluence** became a ghastly material cancer, publicly disdained and privately taken for granted
- The **outer** (what people did) felt trivial compared to the **inner** (what people felt)
- Americans searched for soul over science, meanings over things
- Explored an inner future without dates or chronology—an **euphoric experience** celebrated by coming-of-age youngsters who sensed the **Millennium** (*Childhood's End*)
- Total holocaust for everything their elders had built (*Ozyfest Green*)
- Historical comparisons: Greenwich Village around 1900, New England communes of the 1840s, Connecticut Valley in the late 1730s
- Puritan flagship *Arabella* in 1630: "I see a new heaven and a new earth," cried Jonathan Edwards 250 years ago

### The Inner-Driven Era (mid-1990s onward)

- A final step forward lands us roughly in the mid-1990s, somewhere near the middle of an **INNER-DRIVEN ERA**
- To understand the future, reflect on where the mood has been heading over the last several years
- According to 1980s-era opinion polls, Americans of all ages emerged from their **"Consciousness Revolution"** feeling terrific about their personal, *inner* lives
- **Never so worried** about the disintegrating foundations of their social, *outer* world
- By 1990, people came to share a disquieting sense of:
  - Fragmenting community
  - Eroding public purpose
  - Institutions that no longer function
  - Mounting financial and environmental liabilities that must someday be addressed


<!-- p. 354 -->

### Figure 12-1: Constellational Eras, Dated by Generational Birthyears

**Table showing historical cycles with four eras per cycle:**

**Pre-Colonial Cycle:**
- Outer-Driven Era: Elizabethan Renaissance (1584-1614)

**Colonial Cycle:**
- Awakening Era: Puritan Awakening (1615-1647)
- Inner-Driven Era: Religious Intolerance (1648-1673)
- Crisis Era: Glorious Revolution (1674-1700)
- Outer-Driven Era: Age of Enlightenment (1701-1723)

**Revolutionary Cycle:**
- Awakening Era: Great Awakening (1724-1741)
- Inner-Driven Era: French and Indian War (1742-1766)
- Crisis Era: American Revolution (1767-1791)
- Outer-Driven Era: Era of Good Feeling (1792-1821)

**Civil War Cycle:**
- Awakening Era: Transcendental Awakening (1822-1842)
- Inner-Driven Era: (1843-1859)
- Crisis Era: Civil War (1859)
- Outer-Driven Era: Reconstruction, Gilded Age (1860-1882)

**Great Power Cycle:**
- Awakening Era: Missionary Awakening (1883-1900)
- Inner-Driven Era: World War I, Prohibition (1901-1924)
- Crisis Era: Depression, World War II (1925-1942)
- Outer-Driven Era: Superpower America (1943-1960)

**Millennial Cycle:**
- Awakening Era: Boom Awakening (1961-1981)
- Inner-Driven Era: (1982-)

### Constellational Eras and Individual Lifecycles

- **Normal lifespan:** Everyone who lives a normal lifespan can expect to witness each constellational era at some point in their life
- Similar exercise could be performed with notable members of other generational types with the same result
- **Every constellational era experienced once:** Everyone who lives a normal lifespan experiences every constellational era once
- **Different phase-of-life perspectives:** Each type witnesses each era from a different phase-of-life perspective
  - **Idealists:** see an Awakening era as rising adults and a Crisis era in elderhood
  - **Civics:** see these two periods from a reversed perspective
- **Age location governs interaction:** Age location governs the two-way interaction between generations and history

### Paradigmatic Mood of Each Era

- Associated with each type of era is a **paradigmatic mood**

<!-- p. 352 -->

### Four Social Mood Constellations and Generational Types

- **Four visions of the future** are component pieces of a broader social mood that accompanies four **constellation eras**: **AWAKENING**, **INNER-DRIVEN**, **CRISIS**, and **OUTER-DRIVEN**
- In each era, mood is determined by the unique combination of different generational types at each stage of life
- Key dependencies to understand social mood changes:
  - Recognize the **Awakening mood of the 1970s**: cannot imagine it without "square" Civics entering elderhood, "spoiled" Idealists coming of age, and sensitive passage-prone Adaptives sandwiched between
  - How can we understand the **Crisis mood of the 1930s** without Civics and Idealists in reversed positions, with gritty Reactives sandwiched between

### Cycles and Historical Progress

- **Cycles and futures are not supposed to be a happy mix**
- When Americans talk of generations, they associate them with hopes for progress—particular to the **American Dream** where each successive generation improves over time
- The concept of a historical cycle may seem to threaten these hopes and the dream of history running in circles, after all, how can it move forward?
- However, **our cycle is perfectly compatible with the progress of civilization** by any standard normally used to measure it—material, spiritual, social, or cultural
- All the cycle explains is **when and why different generations apply different standards in working toward progress**

> "Wherever we use the word 'cycle,' the reader may if he wishes replace it with 'spiral,' with all the opportunity and danger implicit in that word. A spiral turns in a circle while at the same time moving upward—or downward."

### Optimism About the Future

- The cycle (or spiral) may offer more reason to be optimistic about the future than the conventional linear view of history
- **Perspective of many older G.I.s** who came of age during the Great Depression and measure the American Dream by Civic milestones: public order, community purpose, friendly neighborhoods, dutiful families, benign science, and a rapidly ascending standard of living
- Take those milestones, assess trends of past two or three decades, and reflect on what a linear view of history would conclude about America's future—**Now that's**
<!-- p. 355 -->

### Distinguishing Cyclical Recurrences from Linear Trends

- To identify a **mood**, must strip away the cumulative shape of civilization inherited from the past (affluence, technology, basic social mores, established political institutions)
- Must also remove chance events, passing fashions, language, and mannerisms through which a mood expresses itself
- May help to envision a **"spiral"** where the direction of the spiral indicates the cumulative progress—or decline—of civilization
- Random perturbations in the spiral indicate **era-specific events**
- Circle of **constellational moods** driven by repeating overlap of generational types

### Popular Music as Illustration of Cyclical Recurrences

**Steady improvement over past century and a half in music technology:**
- **Progressives** came of age with live ballads and marches by professionals
- **Missionaries** brought home the first widely marketed song sheets for piano play
- **Lost** enjoyed first Victrolas with cylindrical records
- **G.I.s** bought first 78s for songs broadcast on AM radio
- **Silent** listened to stereos with 33-rpm LPs
- **Boomers** played cassettes in their cars and popularized FM radio
- **Thirteeners** love their compact disks
- Today's electronics industry abuzz with talk of new digital technology that awaits **Millennial** teenagers

**Yet over this same period, behind the linear improvement, popular music has reflected the mood of each new era and type of each new peer personality:**

- **Over the Great Power Cycle**, most memorable Missionary songs were spirituals and blues, soulful and angry
- **Lost** had jazz, improvised and naughty
- **G.I.** invented big-band swing, standardized and upbeat
- **Silent** had folk and rock, subversive and infused with social conscience
- **So far in the Millennial cycle**, pattern has repeated—with Boomer music inward-seeking and tinged with fury (adding the "acid" and "Jesus" to rock) and 13er music punkish, prankish, and diverse

### Quantifiable Trends in Constellational Eras (Figure 12-2)

- Most trends resist quantification
- **"Attitude toward institutions"** cannot be measured directly
- Few historians would disagree that prevailing attitudes toward government and family in 1740 and 1975 (especially among **rising adults**) represent opposite extreme from prevailing attitudes in 1700 and 1940
- Examples: frenzied bonfires of young John Davenport vs. crisp "Family Well-Ordered" essays of young Cotton Mather; hippies of Wheeler Ranch vs. Séances of Guadalcanal
- Other trends can be quantified, at least partially
- Growing tolerance for personal
<!-- p. 353 -->

### The Cycle Offers Hope Through Shifting Standards

- The cycle suggests **standards of progress shift from era to era**: material → spiritual, community improvement → self-perfection, basic survival → civilized refinement → back again
- **Historian James Truslow Adams** wrote during the Great Depression that the American Dream evolves with "the chance to grow into something bigger and finer, as bigger and finer appeared to him"
- **Each new generation gets this opportunity for renewal**

### Generational Endowments and the American Dream

- **Each generational type has its own special vision of the American Dream**
- Each type can fare well or badly in fulfilling that vision
- Each can leave gifts or harms to successors
- These are called **"generational endowments"**
- The cycle reveals important differences in the endowments each type gives to the future
- To understand the connection between generations and progress, need to build **paradigms**:
  - First: the four **constellational moods**
  - Second: the **peer personality and lifecycle** of each generational type

## The Cycle of Constellational Moods: A Paradigm

### History's Patterns vs. Randomness

> "Those who cannot remember the past are condemned to repeat it." —**George Santayana**

- Many history fundamentalists seem to repeat patterns *no matter how much we try to remember and learn from them*
- If history were purely random, it would be less important and remembering it would be pointless
- Most historians sense that **history leaves telltale traces of a certain regularity** that we can learn from: parallels between culture, fashions, politics—or simply **the moods of different periods**

### Identifying Constellational Eras

- Goal: identify some of these parallels, focusing on **all the constellational eras in American history**
- There have been **eighteen constellational eras** (as many as there have been generations)
- Chapter 2 defined each **era** as a **generation-long birthyear period** preceding each aligned constellation (which occurs when the last cohort of each new generation is born)
- Display these eras in **Figure 12-1**
- Notice how the **Civil War Cycle** had only three eras (including an abbreviated combination of Inner-Driven and Crisis eras), as if it had only **three generational types**

### Duration of Constellational Eras and Cycles

- A **constellational era typically lasts about twenty-two years**
- A **four-era cycle lasts roughly eighty to one hundred years** (approximately the lifespan of a long-lived individual)
- To calibrate the duration of America's five cycles, compare them with **five Idealist lifespans laid end-to-end**:
  - **Simon Bradstreet** (1603–1697)
  - **Benjamin Franklin** (1706–1790)
  - **Lucretia Mott** (1793–1880)
  - **Franklin Roosevelt** (1882–1945)
  - **Albert Gore, Jr.** (1948– )
- Each of these individuals witnessed (or in the last case...
