### Social Indicators and Generational Cycles

**Crime rates** follow cyclical patterns:
- Rise steeply during **Awakening eras** since the 1730s
- Reach cyclical highs during every **Inner-Driven era** since late 1740s
- *New York Gazette* (1749): "It seems to be now become dangerous for the good people of this town to go out late at night without being sufficiently well armed"
- Pattern repeated in 1840s, 1910s, 1980s

**Substance abuse** follows generational cycles (see Figure 12-2):
- Rises steeply during **Awakening era**
- Peaks near its end
- Falls after Idealists finish coming of age (first-wave Idealists enter midlife)
- **Sharpest alcohol-consumption turnaround**: late 1830s (end of Transcendental Awakening), followed by further decline in 1840s
- **Second-sharpest**: 1900-1910 (end of Missionary Awakening), followed by decline during Prohibition
- **Recent pattern**: Per capita alcohol consumption began accelerating around 1960, peaked around 1980 (end of Boom Awakening), lately been falling
- **Mind-altering drugs** pattern similar: opiates to hallucinogens
- Young **Idealists** get most of the euphoria while society looks on indulgently
- After which young **Reactives** get most of the blame when society begins cracking down
- Historian **David Musto**: "a person growing up in America in the 1890s and the 1970s would have the image of a drug-using, drug-tolerating society; a person growing up in the 1940s—and perhaps in the 2000s—would have the image of a nation that firmly rejects narcotics"

**Fertility** follows generational patterns:
- Tends to rise during **Outer-Driven eras** when Idealists are born
- **Puritans, Awakeners, Transcendentals, and Boomers** all products of birth booms
- Their **Adaptive** next-elders were all products of **Gilded era birth dearths**
- For Missionaries, anomalous **Civil War Cycle** created different pattern: birthrate suddenly fell for war-baby first-wavers (born 1861 to 1865), but thereafter stabilized until early 1880s—only birthrate plateau during otherwise steady downslope that stretched 130 years from Gilded through Silent
- Birthrates ease during **Awakening eras**, either by stabilizing after earlier growth (Liberty babies) or falling sharply (13er babies)

**Immigration** follows cyclical patterns:
- Tends to rise during **Awakening era**
- Peaks during **Inner-Driven era**
- Falls during **Crisis era**
- Each trend reflects different social consensus about pluralism and community
- Most immigrants range in age from mid-teens to late thirties
- **Idealist** and...
<!-- p. 357 -->

### Figure 12-2: Constellational Moods, by Era

**Table showing how generational archetypes align across the four-era cycle:**

**By Life Phase:**
- **Elder:** Civics (Awakening) → Adaptives (Inner-Driven) → Idealists (Crisis) → Reactives (Outer-Driven)
- **Midlife:** Adaptives (Awakening) → Idealists (Inner-Driven) → Reactives (Crisis) → Civics (Outer-Driven)
- **Rising:** Idealists (Awakening) → Reactives (Inner-Driven) → Civics (Crisis) → Adaptives (Outer-Driven)
- **Youth:** Reactives (Awakening) → Civics (Inner-Driven) → Adaptives (Crisis) → Idealists (Outer-Driven)

**Cycle Calendar:** Year 1-22 (Awakening) → Year 23-44 (Inner-Driven) → Year 45-66 (Crisis) → Year 67-88 (Outer-Driven)

**Era Characteristics:**

| **Dimension** | **Awakening Era** | **Inner-Driven Era** | **Crisis Era** | **Outer-Driven Era** |
|--------------|-------------------|---------------------|----------------|---------------------|
| **Nurture of Children** | under-protective | tightening | over-protective | loosening |
| **Sex Role Divisions** | narrowing | narrowest point | widening | widest point |
| **Tolerance for Personal Risk** | rising | high | falling | low |
| **Individualism vs. Community** | rising individualism | maximum individualism | rising community | maximum community |
| **World View** | rising complexity | maximum complexity | rising simplicity | maximum simplicity |
| **Behavior Toward Ideals** | discover | cultivate | champion | realize |
| **Behavior Toward Institutions** | attack | redefine | establish | build |
| **Sense of Greatest Need** | fix inner world | do what feels right | fix outer world | do what works |
| **Vision of Future** | euphoric | darkening | urgent | brightening |

### Immigration Patterns by Archetype

- **Reactive generations** have had foreign-born flavors: **Liberty**, **Transcendental**, **Gilded**, and **13th Boomers** are the only American generations with rising immigrant shares during their next-elder phase
- **Civic generations** show marked decline in immigrant share as they enter rising adulthood during their coming-of-age

