### Experiencing Constellational Eras Across the Lifespan

- Normal lifespan allows individuals to **experience every constellational era** at some point in their life
- Same exercise could be done with notable members of other generational types with identical results
- > "Everyone who lives a normal lifespan experiences every constellational era once"
- **Each type witnesses each era from different phase-of-life perspective**
  - **Idealists** see Awakening era as rising adults and Crisis era as elders
  - **Civics** see these two periods from reversed perspective
- **Age location governs the two-way interaction between generations and history**

### Paradigmatic Moods

- Each type of era has an associated **paradigmatic mood**
- Question raised: What are these moods?

<!-- p. 358 -->

### The Mood of an Awakening Era

**Awakening era characteristics:**
- Society transitions into spiritual awakening after maximum secular intensity of outer life
- Focus on **inner life** intensifies while secular interest in outer life declines
- **Artistic culture** highly innovative
- New social ideals emerge from utopian experiments in individual autonomy and perfect fellowship
- Used to attack and weaken established institutions

**Social dynamics:**
- Society has difficulty coalescing around common goals
- Social efforts requiring collective discipline encounter withering controversy
- Wars are unlikely, and those that occur are controversial when fought and badly remembered afterward
- **Sex role distinctions narrow**
- Public order deteriorates
- Crime and substance abuse rise

**Cultural shifts:**
- Euphoric enthusiasm over near-term spiritual progress eclipses public concern over secular problems
- High tolerance for risk-prone lifestyles
- **Child-rearing** reaches the cyclical point of minimum protection and structure

**Generational dialogue:**
- Era's defining **two-part generational dialogue** between:
  - Coming-of-age **Idealists** (young adults)
  - Aging **Civics** (elders)
- Creates a "noisy clash" that elevates the new values and perspectives

<!-- p. 355 -->

### Identifying Generational Moods Amid Historical Noise

- To identify a **mood**, must strip away:
  - The cumulative shape of civilization inherited from the past (affluence, technology, social mores, cultural norms, established institutions)
  - Chance events and passing fashions, language, and mannerisms
- May help to envision a **"spiral"** where the direction of the spiral indicates cumulative progress or decline of civilization
- The **circle of constellational moods** is driven by the repeating overlap of generational types

### Popular Music as Illustration of Cyclical Recurrences vs. Linear Trends

- Over past century and a half: steady improvement in **technology and marketing of music**
- But popular music has **reflected the mood of each new era** and personality type:
  - **Progressives** (came of age with live ballads and marches by professionals, Missionaries)
  - **Missionaries** (brought first era of sheet music for home piano play)
  - **Lost** (enjoyed first Victrolas with cylindrical records, G.I.s bought first 78s for songs broadcast on AM radio)
  - **Silent** (moved to stereos with 33-rpm LPs, Boomers played cassettes in their cars, popularized FM radio)
  - **Thirteeners** (love their compact disks)
  - **Today's electronics industry** (abuzz with talk of new digital technology that awaits Millennial teenagers)

- Yet over this same period, **behind the linear improvement**, popular music has reflected the mood of each new peer personality:
  - Over the **Great Power Cycle**: most memorable Missionary songs were spirituals and blues, soulful and angry
  - **Lost** had jazz, improvised and naughty
  - **G.I.** invented big-band swing, standardized and upbeat
  - **Silent** had folk and rock, subversive and infused with social conscience
  - So far in the **Millennial cycle**: pattern has repeated—with Boomer music inward-seeking and tinged with fury (adding the "acid" and "Jesus" to rock) and 13er music punkish, prankish, and diverse

### Social Behavior Patterns Coinciding with Constellational Eras

- When we look at history this way, searching for basic patterns in social behavior, can spot several that coincide with the constellational eras (Figure 12-2 lists them)

### Trends That Resist Quantification

- **"Attitude toward institutions"** obviously cannot be measured
- Few historians would disagree that prevailing attitudes toward government and family in 1740 and 1975 (especially among **rising adults**) represent an opposite extreme from prevailing attitudes in 1700 and 1940
- Examples: frenzied bonfires of young John Davenport vs. crisp "Family Well-Ordered" essays of young Cotton Mather; hippies of Wheeler Ranch vs. Séances of Guadalcanal
- Other trends can be quantified, at least partially
- Growing tolerance for personal

<!-- p. 356 -->

### Social Indicators and Generational Cycles

**Crime rates** follow cyclical patterns:
- Rise steeply during **Awakening** eras since the 1730s
- Reach cyclical highs during every **Inner-Driven** era since late 1740s
- Example: "It seems to be now become dangerous for the good people of this town to go out late at night without being sufficiently well armed" (comment from 1749, New York Gazette)
- Same pattern repeated in 1840s, 1910s, and 1980s

**Substance abuse** follows generational cycles:
- Rises steeply during **Awakening** era
- Peaks near its end, then falls after last-wave **Idealists** finish coming of age (mid first-wave **Idealists** enter midlife)
- Sharpest alcohol-consumption turnaround: **late 1830s** (end of Transcendental Awakening), followed by further decline in the 1840s
- Second-sharpest: **between 1900 and 1910** (end of Missionary Awakening), followed by decline during Prohibition
- More recently: per capita alcohol consumption began accelerating around **1960**, peaked around **1980** (end of Boom Awakening), has lately been falling
- For mind-altering drugs, pattern same from opiates to hallucinogens
- Young **Idealists** get most of the euphoria while society looks on indulgently; after which young **Reactives** get most of the blame when society begins cracking down

> "A person growing up in America in the 1890s and the 1970s would have the image of a drug-using, drug-tolerating society; a person growing up in the 1940s—and perhaps in the 2000s—would have the image of a nation that firmly rejects narcotics." — historian **David Musto**

**Fertility** follows generational patterns:
- Tends to rise during **Outer-Driven** eras when **Idealists** are born
- **Puritans, Awakeners, Transcendentals, and Boomers** were all products of birth booms
- Their **Adaptive** next-elders were all products of **Gilded-era** birth dearths
- For the **Missionaries**, the anomalous **Civil War Cycle** created a different pattern: birthrate suddenly fell for war-baby first-wavers (born from 1860 to 1865), but thereafter stabilized until early 1880s—the only birthrate plateau during an otherwise steady downslope that stretched 130 years from the Gilded through the Silent
- Birthrates always ease during **Awakening** eras, either by stabilizing after earlier growth (for **Liberty** babies) or by falling sharply (for **13er** babies)

**Immigration** follows cyclical patterns:
- Tends to rise during **Awakening** era
- Peaks during **Inner-Driven** era
- Falls during **Crisis** era—each trend reflecting a different social consensus about pluralism and community
