| **GILDED** (born 1822-1842) | Transcendental Awakening | Civil War | Reconstruction, Gilded Age | Missionary Awakening |
| **LOST** (born 1883-1900) | Missionary Awakening | World War I, Prohibition | Depression, World War II | Superpower America |
| **THIRTEENTH** (born 1961-1981) | Boom Awakening | — | — | — |

<!-- p. 361 -->

### MIDLIFE: Idealists Enter Political Power

- After **coming-of-age outburst**, Idealists' first instinct is to **retrench** and concentrate on **perfecting the inner life**
- Entering midlife, they gradually reshape institutions around **new values** and assume a **judgmental stance** against what they perceive as the **moral vacuum** of the younger **Reactives**
- Come to political power **slowly but resolutely**, beginning with relatively **weak leaders tolerant of their peers' self-immersed impulses**
- Gradually, **splits emerge and deepen** between **Idealist factions** holding competing moral positions—each insisting on applying **absolute principles** to the outer world, but **disagreeing** with the other factions over what those principles should be

<!-- p. 362 -->

### ELDERHOOD (Idealist Lifecycle)
- One **Idealist** faction ultimately prevails, setting agenda for decisive collective action
- **Prophesying leaders** of great moral authority - **Idealists** impose their will sternly on people of all ages
- Call on younger **Reactive** and **Civic** generations to make sacrifices for principled causes
- Society passes through era of secular crisis—a key historic turning point, possibly a major war
- After crisis, public institutions substantially reflect inner visions of **Idealist** elders, who look upon themselves as vital links to culture and civilization
- From the young, they seek personal obedience and respect more than public power or reward

### The REACTIVE Lifecycle

**Overview of Reactive generational journey:**
- Nurtured as children during awakening, coming of age amid spiritual confidence but secular unease
- **Reactive** generations travel a *pi-caresque* lifecycle
- Early in life, desperately seek to escape or outwit judgments of next-elder **Idealists**
- Late in life, they make unthankèd sacrifices for next-junior **Civics**
- At a distance, we remember **Reactives** best during rising-adult years of hell-raising (examples: **Paxton Boys**, **Missouri Raiders**, **rumrunners**)

### FIGURE 12-4: Reactive Lifecycles

**Historical Reactive Generations:**

- **CAVALIER** (born 1615-1647)
  - Youth: Puritan Awakening
  - Rising: Religious Intolerance
  - Midlife: Glorious Revolution
  - Elder: Age of Enlightenment

- **LIBERTY** (born 1724-1741)
  - Youth: Great Awakening
  - Rising: French and Indian War
  - Midlife: American Revolution
  - Elder: Era of Good Feeling

- **GILDED** (born 1822-1842)
  - Youth: Transcendental Awakening
  - Rising: Civil War
  - Midlife: Reconstruction, Gilded Age
  - Elder: Missionary Awakening

- **LOST** (born 1883-1900)
  - Youth: Missionary Awakening
  - Rising: World War I, Prohibition
  - Midlife: Depression, World War II
  - Elder: Superpower America

- **THIRTEENTH** (born 1961-1981)
  - Youth: Boom Awakening
  - Rising: ——
  - Midlife: ——
  - Elder: ——

<!-- p. 363 -->

### The CIVIC Lifecycle

**Civic generations** are nurtured as children amid **spiritual confidence** and come of age during a **secular crisis**. They travel a **heroic lifecycle**:

- **Early in life**: Civics believe themselves more powerful than older generations
- **Late in life**: All generations see them as powerful


<!-- p. 363 -->

## The Reactive Generation Lifecycle

### Youth
- Child of era with **powerful Civic elders**, **torn Adaptive midlifers**, and **moralizing Idealist rising adults**
- Adaptive approval allows children freedom from strict behavioral norms
- Adjustment to narrowing sex-role distinctions without protective parental guidance
- Limited exposure to real-world anxieties and dangers
- Society immersed in spiritual awakening; youths given little sense of mission or direction
- Adults view them harshly—at best inconvenient; at worst, disappointing or outright wicked

### Rising Adulthood
- Little collective self-esteem from early contact with real world
- Strong survival skills and high hopes for individual success
- **Midlife Reactives** define themselves in cynical opposition to Idealists
- Now starting to govern with increasingly heavy hand
- Youth engage in social and economic entrepreneurship; pleasure-seeking and high-risk behavior
- Reactive adults become cautious in family life and gradually mellow in personality

### Midlife
- Playing to win but half-expecting to lose
- Accept wide gaps in personal outcomes—success or failure treated as private matter
- Gradually learn to abide; no longer fight Idealist stigma against their generation
- Become society's most cunning, pragmatic, and colorful public figures
- Military and commercial managers of great crises; effective leaders for crisis resolution
- Congested by elder Idealists

### Elderhood
- Remain undemanding in post-crisis era when society praises Civic midlifers and indulges Idealist youth
- **Aging leaders** compensate for earlier bingelike behavior by shunning risk and encouraging conformity
- Old Reactives are wary conservatives, "not born yesterday"
- Inclined to warn more than guide; retire into individualist role if neglected

## The Civic Lifecycle

- Nurtured amid spiritual confidence and come of age during secular crisis
- Travel a **heroic lifecycle**
- Early life: believe themselves more powerful than older generations
- Late life: all generations look to them for guidance

<!-- p. 364 -->

### Figure 12-5: Civic Lifecycles

**Table showing lifecycle phases across generations:**
- **GLORIOUS** (born 1648-1673): Religious Intolerance (Youth) → Glorious Revolution (Rising) → Era of Enlightenment (Midlife) → Great Awakening (Elder)
- **REPUBLICAN** (born 1742-1766): French and Indian War (Youth) → American Revolution (Rising) → Era of Good Feeling (Midlife) → Transcendental Awakening (Elder)
- **G.I.** (born 1901-1924): World War I, Prohibition (Youth) → Depression, World War II (Rising) → Superpower America (Midlife) → Boom Awakening (Elder)
- **MILLENNIAL** (born 1982-2003?): [Future phases blank in table]

### Civic Generational Characteristics

**Public perception of Civics:**
- Later generations regard them as uniquely **optimistic, collegial, and competent**
- Remembered best for **collective coming-of-age triumphs**: Glorious Revolution, Yorktown, VJ-Day
- Crowning midlife achievements: Peace of Utrecht, slave codes, Louisiana Purchase, steamboats, Apollo moon launches, interstate highways

### YOUTH Phase
- Civic generation spends childhood during **post-awakening era** of sensitive Adaptive elders
- Values-oriented Idealist parents and **pleasure-seeking Reactive rising adults**
- Idealist parents view them as **special, an instrument** through inner visions can be achieved or defended
- **Child environment perceived as dangerous** → pushed back toward greater protection and structure
- Adults expect children to be **dutiful, smart, and potentially powerful**
- Youths develop **clear collective mission and high ambitions** for cleaning up and rebuilding the outer world

### RISING ADULTHOOD Phase
- Civics develop **activity-oriented peer relationships**
- **Peer-enforced codes of conduct** and strong sense of generational community
- They band together at a **historic moment** and are guided by:
  - Principled wisdom of elder Idealists
  - Realistic leadership of midlife Reactives
- Successfully shoulder a **secular crisis**
- After duty: unselfishly expect, receive, generous praise and reward from other generations
- **Left-brained achievers and instinctive team players**

<!-- p. 364 -->

### Civic Lifecycles

**Table: Civic Generation Phases Across Life Stages**
- **Glorious** (born 1648-1673): Religious Intolerance (Youth) → Glorious Revolution (Rising) → Era of Enlightenment (Midlife) → Great Awakening (Elder)
- **Republican** (born 1742-1766): French and Indian War (Youth) → American Revolution (Rising) → Era of Good Feeling (Midlife) → Transcendental Awakening (Elder)
- **G.I.** (born 1901-1924): World War I, Prohibition (Youth) → Depression, World War II (Rising) → Superpower America (Midlife) → Boom Awakening (Elder)
- **Millennial** (born 1982-2003?): [phases not yet filled in table]

### Generational Memory and Civic Characteristics

**Public Perception of Civics**
- Later generations remember Civics as "uniquely optimistic, collegial, and competent"
- Distance highlights their collective coming-of-age triumphs: **Glorious Revolution**, **Yorktown**, **VJ-Day**
- Crowning midlife achievements: **Peace of Utrecht**, **slave codes**, **Louisiana Purchase**, **steamboats**, **Apollo moon launches**, **interstate highways**

### YOUTH: Post-Awakening Childhood

**Civic Youth Phase Characteristics**
- Childhood occurs during **post-awakening era** of sensitive Adaptive elders, values-oriented Idealist midlifers, pleasure-seeking Reactive rising adults
- Idealist parents view children as "special, an instrument through which their inner visions can be achieved or defended"
- **Child environment perceived as dangerous** → pushed back toward greater protection and structure
- Adults expect children to be "dutiful, smart, and potentially powerful"
- Youths develop "a clear collective mission and high ambitions for cleaning up and rebuilding the outer world"

### RISING ADULTHOOD: Coming of Age

**Civic Rising Adult Characteristics**
- Develop **activity-oriented peer relationships**, peer-enforced codes of conduct, strong sense of **generational community**
- Band together at historic moment, guided by "principled wisdom of elder Idealists and realistic leadership of midlife Reactives"
- Successfully shoulder **secular crisis**
- After fulfilling duty unselfishly, receive generous praise and reward from other generations
- "Left-brained achievers and instinctive team players"

<!-- p. 365 -->

### The ADAPTIVE Lifecycle

Nurtured as children during a crisis and coming of age amid secular confidence but spiritual unease, **Adaptive generations** travel a *genteel* lifecycle. Early in life, Adaptives try to excel in the subordinate tasks given them by next-elder Civics; late in life, they seek approving judgments from next-junior Idealists. At a distance, we remember them best during their quiet years of rising adulthood.

**Historical examples of Adaptive generations:**
- Log-cabin settlers of 1800
- Great Plains farmers of 1880
- Young submarinites of 1960

**In middle years:** Notable, seeking leadership
- Whig "compromises" of **Henry Clay** and **Daniel Webster**
- "Good government" reforms of **Theodore Roosevelt** and **Woodrow Wilson**
- Budgetary and peace "processes" of **Phil Gramm** and **James Baker III**

#### YOUTH: The Adaptive Generation Enters Childhood

**Context of childhood:**
- Surrounded by stern **Idealist elders**, pragmatic **Reactive midlifers**, and aggressive **Civic rising adults**
- A secular crisis erupts
- **Reactive-led families** surround children with an intensely protective, even suffocating style of nurture

**Childhood expectations:**
- Children are expected to stay out of the way of harm—and of busy adults
- Though assured of their collective worth, they are told their individual needs take a low priority as long as the

<!-- p. 365 -->

### Civic Lifecycle - Midlife & Elderhood

**MIDLIFE:** Empowered by hubris of early success, **Civics** reach midlife as builders and doers, defenders of wholesome but conformist culture. After impatiently awaiting their turn atop society, they push aside the aging **Reactives** and enter leadership roles with vigor, certain of their own ability to make things work. They try to institutionalize and rationalize every sphere of social life, from science to religion, statecraft to the arts. Their **midlife hubris** often encourages them to overreach and push secular perfection too far. As Civics begin passing out of midlife, they elicit a stormy crusade of moral purification from coming-of-age **Idealists**.

**ELDERHOOD:** Old age does not weaken the Civic reputation for unusual energy and collective purpose. As elders, however, they grow frustrated at how the new spiritual agenda saps the strength of their powerful institutions, which they fear may not survive without their special competence. They detach themselves from new cultural trends but retain an active role in public affairs. From the young, Civics seek **institutional power and economic reward** more than personal respect or obedience.

### The ADAPTIVE Lifecycle

**Adaptives** nurtured as children during crisis, coming of age amid secular confidence but spiritual unease. **Adaptive generations** travel a *genteel* lifecycle. Early in life, Adaptives try to excel in subordinate tasks given them by next-elder Civics; late in life, they seek approving judgments from next-junior Idealists.

Historical examples at distance: **log-cabin settlers of 1800**, **Great Plains farmers of 1880**, young **suburbanites of 1960** during their midlife years of flexible, consensus-seeking leadership (the **Whig "compromises"** of Henry Clay and Daniel Webster, the "good government" reforms of Theodore Roosevelt and Woodrow Wilson, the budgetary and peace "processes" of **Phil Gramm** and **James Baker III**).

**YOUTH:** The Adaptive generation enters childhood surrounded by stern **Idealist elders**, pragmatic **Reactive midlifers**, and aggressive **Civic rising adults**. A secular crisis erupts. Reactive-led families surround children with an intensely protective, even suffocating style of nurture. Children expected to stay out of the way of harm—and of busy adults. Though assured of their collective worth, they are told their **individual needs take a low priority** as long as the

<!-- p. 366 -->

### FIGURE 12-6: Adaptive Lifecycles

**Table showing four Adaptive generations and their lifecycle phases:**

| Generation | Youth | Rising | Midlife | Elder |
|------------|-------|--------|---------|-------|
| **ENLIGHTENMENT** (born 1674-1700) | Glorious Revolution | Age of Enlightenment | Great Awakening | French and Indian War |
| **COMPROMISE** (born 1767-1791) | American Revolution | Era of Good Feeling | Transcendental Awakening | Civil War |
| **PROGRESSIVE** (born 1843-1859) | Civil War | Reconstruction, Gilded Age | Missionary Awakening | World War I, Prohibition |
| **SILENT** (born 1925-1942) | Depression, World War II | Superpower America | Boom Awakening | —— |

### Adaptive Youth Phase

- **Adaptive youths** inherit a world of widening sex-role distinctions as community struggles for survival
- Grow up well-behaved while wondering if they can live up to powerful elder expectations
- Sacrifice heavily on their behalf

### Adaptive Rising Adulthood

- Taught to pursue acceptance from older generations
- **Come of age emulating successful adult behavior**
- Not old enough to participate in crisis as adults, fail to experience cathartic rite of passage
- **Fail to acquire self-confidence of their next-elders**
- Individually insecure in era of public optimism
- Try conforming to elder expectations, which now means uncertain **Civics'** grand post-crisis edifice
- Meanwhile, probe cautiously for fresher, more fulfilling role
- This effort leads to **cult of professional expertise** (beating Civics at their own game) and critical gestures of conscience and humanism
- Expose the **Civics' spiritual shortcomings**
- Young adults **infuse popular culture with new vitality** and provide encouraging mentors to new youth movements that just too late for them to join

### Adaptive Midlife

- **Adaptives enter midlife while coming-of-age Idealists are triggering a spiritual awakening**
- This new phase poses awkward personal "**passage**" for generation forced to choose between:
  - The outer mission of older Civics
  - The inner mission of younger Idealists
- Post-passage, still searching

<!-- p. 366 -->

### Figure 12-6: Adaptive Lifecycles

**Table showing four Adaptive generations across lifecycle phases:**

- **ENLIGHTENMENT** (born 1674-1700): Glorious Revolution (Youth) → Age of Enlightenment (Rising) → Great Awakening (Midlife) → French and Indian War (Elder)

- **COMPROMISE** (born 1767-1791): American Revolution (Youth) → Era of Good Feeling (Rising) → Transcendental Awakening (Midlife) → Civil War (Elder)

- **PROGRESSIVE** (born 1843-1859): Civil War (Youth) → Reconstruction, Gilded Age (Rising) → Missionary Awakening (Midlife) → World War I, Prohibition (Elder)

- **SILENT** (born 1925-1942): Depression, World War II (Youth) → Superpower America (Rising) → Boom Awakening (Midlife) → [no elder phase listed]

### Adaptive Youth Phase

- Community struggling for survival
- **Adaptive youths inherit widening sex-role distinctions**
- Grow up well-behaved, wondering how (or if) they can live up to expectations of powerful elders who sacrifice so much on their behalf

### Rising Adulthood: Adaptive Lifecycle Pattern

- **Taught to pursue acceptance from older generations**
- Come of age emulating successful adult behavior
- **Not old enough to participate in the crisis as adults** — fail to experience a cathartic rite of passage and fail to acquire self-confidence of their next-elders
- Individually insecure in an era of public optimism
- Try conforming to expectations of elders, which now means **playing the ameliorator to the Civics' grand post-crisis edifice**
- Grope cautiously for a fresher, more fulfilling role
- This effort leads to:
  - **Cult of professional expertise** (beating the Civics at their own game)
  - Critical gestures of conscience and humanism (exposing the Civics' spiritual shortcomings)
- **Young adults infuse popular culture with new vitality** and provide encouraging mentors to new youth movements that just too late for them to join

### Midlife: Adaptive Lifecycle Pattern

- Adaptives enter midlife while **coming-of-age Idealists are triggering a spiritual awakening**
- This new phase of life poses an awkward personal "passage"
- **A generation forced to choose between:**
  - The outer mission of older Civics
  - The inner mission of younger Idealists
- Post-passage, still searching

<!-- p. 367 -->

### Adaptive Midlife Leadership Style
- **Adaptive midlifers** compensate for earlier conformism by engaging in **high-risk political and family behavior**
- Focus on issues **low in substance but rich in personality and drama**
- Leaders who reach positions of leadership tend to rely on **expertise, process, and pluralism**—and postpone unpleasant choices

### Adaptive Elderhood
- Entering old age while a more sober and **values-oriented leadership style** is emerging
- Adaptives remain **personally flexible and culturally sensitive**
- By instinct, elder Adaptives are trusting **liberals—believers in the inherent goodness of man** and his need for **second chances**
- Just as they once took cues from Civic elders, now they adopt the agenda of younger **Idealists**
- Wish to be accepted as **full partners in the new values regime**
- Preserve a **social conscience**, show a **resilient spirit**, and never stop raising new questions

### Figure 12-7: Peer Personalities Summary
- Summarizes the peer personalities of each of the **four generational types**

### Figure 12-8: Leadership Styles Comparison
- Compares the **best-remembered American political leaders** of each type
- Lists **two from each generation** over the first four cycles
- Includes:
  - Those who held a major office colonial governorship for the first cycle
  - **Continental Congress** for the Awakeners
  - **U.S. Presidents** (or, for the Silent, Presidential nominees) thereafter

### Composite Peer Personality Patterns (Figure 12-8)

**Idealist leaders:**
- Have been **cerebral and principled**, summoners of human sacrifice
- Wary of righteous wars
- Early in life, none saw combat in uniform
- Late in life, most came to be revered as much for their **words as for their deeds**

**Reactive leaders:**
- Have been **cunning, hard-to-fool realists**, taciturn warriors who prefer to meet problems and adversaries **one-on-one**
- Include only two Presidents who had earlier hanged a man (**Washington and Cleveland**)
- One governor who hanged witches (**Stoughton**)
- Several commanders who led troops into battle (**Bacon, Washington, Grant, Truman, and Eisenhower**)

**Civic leaders:**
- Have been **vigorous and rational institution-builders**, busy and competent even in old age
- All of them, entering midlife, were **aggressive advocates of technological progress, economic prosperity, social harmony, and public optimism**

<!-- p. 367 -->

### Adaptive Peer Personality (continued)

**Midlife leadership approach:**
- Engage in high-risk political and family behavior to compensate for earlier conformism
- Focus on issues low in substance but rich in personality and drama
- Those reaching leadership positions tend to rely on expertise, process, and pluralism—postponing unpleasant choices

**Elderhood characteristics:**
- More sober and values-oriented leadership style emerges with age
- Remain personally flexible and culturally sensitive
- By instinct, elder Adaptives are trusting liberals—believers in inherent goodness of man and need for second chances
- Took cues from Civic elders, now adopt the agenda of younger Idealists while seeking acceptance as full partners in new values regime
- Preserve a social conscience, show resilient spirit, never stop raising new questions

### Leadership Styles Comparison (Figure 12-8)

**Framework:** Compares best-remembered American political leaders of each generational type—two from each generation over first four cycles

**Examples included:**
- First cycle: Continental Congress for Awakeners, U.S. Presidents for Silent
- Presidential nominees used thereafter
- Each set of eight names reflects common elements forming composite peer personality

### Three Leadership Archetypes

**Idealist leaders:**
- Cerebral and principled, summoners of human sacrifice
- Wary of righteous wars early in life, none saw combat in uniform
- Late in life, most came to be revered as much for their words as for their deeds

**Reactive leaders:**
- Cunning, hard-to-fool realists, taciturn warriors
- Prefer to meet problems and adversaries one-on-one
- Only two Presidents had earlier hanged a man (Washington and Cleveland)
- One governor who hanged witches (Stoughton)
- Several commanders who led troops into battle (Bacon, Washington, Grant, Truman, Eisenhower)

**Civic leaders:**
- Vigorous and rational institution-builders
- Busy and competent even in old age
- Entering midlife, were aggressive advocates of technological progress, economic prosperity, social harmony, and public optimism

<!-- p. 368 -->

