**Matrix of vocational callings organized by dominant vs. recessive generations:**

**Dominant Generations:**
- **Idealists**: Preachers, Writers, Radicals, Publishers, Teachers
- **Civics**: Statesmen, Scientists, Economists, Diplomats, Builders

**Recessive Generations:**
- **Reactives**: Entrepreneurs, Brigands, Industrialists, Generals, Statesmen
- **Adaptives**: Artists, Lawyers, Therapists, Legislators, Statisticians

### Generational Endowments

**Generational legacy concept:**
- Each generation type leaves behind a distinct legacy for its heirs
- Authors call this **"generational endowments"**

**Endowment motivation:**
- Central to a generation's endowment motivation is awareness of what Auguste Comte termed **"morphology"** — its awareness of death
- Most social categories are essentially immortal (racial, religious, geographic groups)
- Not compelled to view the future with special urgency regarding these identities
- Work left undone can be completed later by another member of the group

**Generational difference:**
- Generations are different: each has only a limited time to mark history, keep its peace
- Individuals understand their own time is limited
- But most of the 440 million Americans who have ever lived have had trouble recognizing direct links between their own behavior and the progress of civilization

**National destiny and societal impact:**
- Most Americans have always cared deeply about their national destiny
- Liked to think they are adding to—not subtracting from—the sum total of civilized progress they pass on to heirs
- However, the way Americans have felt and behaved as societal legators has changed substantially from one era to the next
- Each generational type has shown its own special endowment tendencies, good and bad

<!-- p. 368 -->

### Generational Sacrifice and Social Benefaction

- When people make major sacrifices for the future, social scientists puzzle over this behavior as contrary to self-interest (the **"endowment motive"**) or as blind instinctual drive to provide for family/DNA survival
- Nothing seems more plausible than that such motives explain great social benefactors like **Andrew Carnegie** or **Martin Luther King, Jr.**
- As members of generations, we have less difficulty understanding how we steer society's destiny through **location consciousness** in our personal biographies and the currents of history
- **Generational bridging**: Generations connect personal and social goodwill—whatever other reasons we might have to behave well toward the future, our generational membership prompts us to act now rather than later
- Each generation realizes that when it fades, so too will fade **its own way of thinking about the future**

### The Present vs. Future Debate in American History

- From **Robert Beverley** (1710s) to **John Kennedy** (1960s), Americans have agreed that each generation has an obligation to leave a more secure and affluent world than it inherits
- Around the drafting of the **United States Constitution** and debates over national debt, **Thomas Jefferson** argued each generation is "an independent nation" entitled to disclaim any debts from the past
- This view has **always** prevailed—successive American generations have rarely hesitated to bind their heirs through public and private action, producing an impressive record of material and institutional endowments
- This record is **not without peaks and valleys**—the "present versus future" debate has been resolved in favor of the future, sometimes in favor of the present
- Children (and unborn generations) cannot vote, and grand plans for the future often override the urgencies of the moment
- This is especially true in an **Inner-Driven era**, when society trusts values more than institutions (circa-1990 policy paralysis over trade and budget deficits echoes circa-1910 stalemate over urbanization)

### Contemporary Doubts About Future Obligations

- Many Americans today doubt society's capacity/willingness to do anything worthwhile for future generations
- **Polls indicate**: Adults worry increasingly (and rather hopelessly) about harms they're passing on—from massive debts and inadequate schooling to despoiled environment and crumbling infrastructure
- Many flaunt lack of concern in daily lives
- Favorite bumper sticker among **G.I.s**: "We're Spending Our Children's Inheritance"
- **Boomer** favorite: "Whoever Dies with the Most Toys Wins"

### Is America Abandoning Interest in Its Own Destiny?

- The **cycle** suggests America is **not** abandoning interest in its own destiny
- Each **constellational era** has its own vision of what the future needs
- Today's vision is consistent with the mood of an **Inner-Driven** era

<!-- p. 368 -->

### Generational Self-Interest vs. Future Obligation

- Major sacrifices for the future puzzle social scientists—seen as contrary to **self-interest** (the "endowment motive") or blind instinctual drives
- Yet this behavior is not uncommon in great social benefactors like **Andrew Carnegie** or **Martin Luther King, Jr.**
- As members of generations, we more easily appreciate how we steer society's destiny through location in history
- **Generational bridge**: connects personal biography with collective currents of history, linking personal and social goodwill
- **Generational membership** prompts action now rather than later—each generation knows when it fades, its own way of thinking about the future will fade too

### The American "Present Versus Future" Debate

- From **Robert Beverley** (1710s) to **John Kennedy** (1960s), Americans have agreed each generation has an obligation to leave behind a more secure and affluent world
- Around drafting of the **U.S. Constitution** and national debt debates, **Thomas Jefferson** argued each generation is "an independent nation" entitled to disclaim debts from the past
- **Madison** and **Hamilton** believed otherwise—their view has *always* prevailed
- Successive American generations have rarely hesitated to bind future needs through public and private action, creating an impressive record of material and institutional endowments
- This record is not without peaks and valleys—the "present versus future" debate has been resolved in favor of the future, sometimes the present
- **Children (and unborn generations) cannot vote**, so grand plans for the future often override present urgencies

### Inner-Driven Era Characteristics

- In an **Inner-Driven era**, society trusts values more than institutions
- **Circa-1990 policy paralysis** over trade and budget deficits parallels the **circa-1910 stalemate over urbanization**
- Many Americans doubt society's capacity to do anything worthwhile for future generations

### Current Contradictions (circa-1990)

- Polls show adults worry increasingly (and hopelessly) about harms being passed to children:
  - Massive debts and inadequate schooling
  - Despoiled environment and crumbling infrastructure
- Yet many flaunt a lack of concern in daily lives
- Popular bumper stickers reflect this tension:
  - Among **G.I.s**: "We're Spending Our Children's Inheritance"
  - **Boomer** favorite: "Whoever Dies with the Most Toys Wins"

### America and Its Own Destiny

- Is America abandoning interest in its own destiny? The cycle suggests it is not
- Each **constellational era** has its own vision of what the future needs
- Today's vision is consistent with the mood of an **Inner-Driven** era

<!-- p. 372 -->

### Generational Endowment Patterns

- America's enthusiasm for material and public-order endowments currently quite low as aging **Civic generation** passes from power
- This feeling sinking to cyclical nadir on schedule
- Yet other endowments (retooling institutions, pluralism, compassion, fair process) have seen hard work from **Idealist generation** in power
- Society's vision of future shifts with constellational mood, so primary focus shifts from individual activity to phase-of-life positioning of peer personalities

**Key principle:**
> "Throughout its lifecycle, each generation's endowment efforts are concentrated in areas closely connected to its peer personality."

### How Generations Endow Differently

- Generations can endow future in many ways: build airports, establish corporations, write poetry, protect wilderness, fight for liberty, expand rights for handicapped, fund pension plan, teach children spelling, stock physical/natural/human capital, add to ancestral legacy of political/artistic/spiritual capital
- **Different generations think and feel differently** about life—their preference among kinds of endowment will not be uniform or random
- **Idealist generations** don't grow up eager to turn beaches into concrete harbors or Civic generations to turn spiritual cults
- Young **Reactives** seldom daydream about making life failsafe through flowcharts, nor do many young **Adaptives** yearn to vanquish competitors in *Top Gun* dogfights
- **Each generation concentrates on making endowments expressive of its lifelong peer personality**

### Examples of Generational Endowment Focus

- Types of endowments Americans celebrate reflect peer personality on four major national holidays:
  - **Thanksgiving**: celebrate spiritual values of daily life (thanks to Idealist **Puritans**)
  - **July Fourth**: national independence (thanks to Reactive **Liberty**)
  - **Memorial Day**: public becom (thanks to Civic **G.I.s**)
  - **Martin Luther King's Birthday**: cultural pluralism (thanks to Adaptive **Silent**)

### Endowment Behavior and Peer Personality

- Looking through biographies of America's eighteen generations, every generation makes at least some mark in every variety of endowment
- **Important pattern emerges** (Figure 12-10 summarizes): each generational type shows special instinct and talent for certain endowment activity
- As generation matures, its **endowment behavior becomes part of its peer personality**—part of self-image and image in eyes of elders and juniors
- Each generation (and type) tends to stake out matching endowment

<!-- p. 372 -->

### Generational Endowment Patterns

**Key principle**: Throughout its lifecycle, each generation's endowment efforts are concentrated in areas closely connected to its **peer personality**.

#### Endowment Activities Across Generations

- Generations can endow the future in many ways: build airports, establish corporations, write poetry, protect the wilderness, fight to preserve liberty, expand rights for the handicapped, fund pension plans, teach children how to spell
- Can add to accountancy stock of physical, natural, or human capital—or add to ancestral legacy of political, artistic, and spiritual capital
- Different generations think and feel differently about life—their preference among kinds of endowment will not be uniform or random

#### Generational Preferences in Endowment

**Idealist generations**: Do not grow up eager to turn beaches into concrete harbors, nor Civic generations to found spiritual cults
- Young **Reactives**: Seldom daydream about making life failsafe through flowcharts, nor do many young **Adaptives** yearn to vanquish competitors in *Top Gun* dogfights

**Concentration of endowment efforts**: Each generation concentrates on making endowments expressive of its lifelong peer personality
- Types of endowments Americans celebrate on four major national holidays:
  - **Thanksgiving**: Celebrate spiritual values of daily life (thanks to Idealist **Puritans**)
  - **July Fourth**: National independence (thanks to Reactive **Liberty**)
  - **Memorial Day**: Public becom (thanks to Civic **G.I.s**)
  - **Martin Luther King's Birthday**: Cultural pluralism (thanks to Adaptive **Silent**)

#### Historical Pattern

- Looking through biographies of America's eighteen generations: Every generation makes at least some mark in every variety of endowment
- Important pattern emerges (**Figure 12-10** reference): Each generational type shows a special instinct—and talent—for certain endowment activity

**Core mechanism**: As a generation matures, its endowment behavior becomes part of its **peer personality**—part of its self-image and its image in the eyes of elders and juniors
- Each generation (and type) tends to stake out a matching endowment era

<!-- p. 373 -->

### Generational Endowment Activities by Type

**Figure 12-10: Principal Endowment Activities by Generational Type**

**Dominant Generations:**
- **Idealists**: Principle, Religion, Education
- **Civics**: Community, Technology, Affluence

**Recessive Generations:**
- **Reactives**: Liberty, Pragmatism, Survival
- **Adaptives**: Pluralism, Expertise, Social Justice

### Generational Deference and Endowment Patterns

- Generations defer to others for providing specific endowments based on generational type
- Examples from recent decades:
  - Americans of all ages look to **G.I.s** for **technology**
  - Americans look to **Silent** for **fairness**
  - Americans look to **Boomers** for **reflection**
- Historical patterns:
  - Early-19th-century Americans looked to **Republicans** for **institutions**
  - Looked to **Compromisers** for **mediation**
  - Looked to **Transcendentals** for **religion** and **hard-asset wealth**

### Lifecycle Dynamics of Generational Endowments

- Each generation works to achieve endowments with intensity that varies across lifecycle
- **Coming of age**: Generation begins building legacy by fulfilling or challenging endowment expectations of elders
- **Maturing into midlife leadership**: Generation begins to make major contributions on its own
  - First cohorts enter elderhood
  - Typically attain highest leadership posts
  - Realize agenda must be completed or abandoned
  - Activities maximize intensity then fall off
- **Moving beyond elderhood**: Generation of its type is entering youth
  - Generation typically sees its agenda neglected
- Dynamic creates characteristic pattern during each constellational era

### Endowment Behavior Across Constellational Eras

> "The endowment behavior of each constellational era reflects the NEW endowment activity of the generational type coming of age; the STRONG and RISING endowment activity of the type entering midlife; the PEAKING, then FALLING activity of the type entering elderhood; and the DORMANT activity of the type moving beyond elderhood (and moving into youth)."

- Each type pushes certain endowment activity throughout lifecycle
- Pattern gives endowment behavior characteristic signature during constellational era

<!-- p. 373 -->

### Principal Endowment Activities by Generational Type

**Figure 12-10: Endowment Focus Areas**
- **Idealists (Dominant):** Principle, Religion, Education
- **Reactives (Recessive):** Liberty, Pragmatism, Survival
- **Civics (Dominant):** Community, Technology, Affluence
- **Adaptives (Recessive):** Pluralism, Expertise, Social Justice

### Generational Deference and Legacy Building

**Pattern of deference for endowments:**
- Other generations defer to specific generational types for certain endowment activities
- Recent examples:
  - **G.I.s** → for **basic civics**, **fairness**
  - **Boomers** → for **reflection**
  - **Early-19th-century Americans** → looked to **Republicans** for institutions, **Compromisers** for mediation, **Transcendentals** for religion—and later, to the **Gilded** for hard-nosed materialism

### Lifecycle Pattern of Endowment Activity

**Generational endowment intensity varies by lifecycle phase:**

1. **Coming of age** → generation builds legacy by fulfilling or challenging endowment expectations of elders
2. **Maturing into midlife leadership** → begins making major contributions on its own
3. **First cohorts enter elderhood** → typically attains highest leadership posts while realizing its agenda
4. **Completed or abandoned agenda** → activists' maximum intensity reached, then falls off
5. **Moving beyond elderhood** (next generation entering midlife) → typically neglected

**Result:** Each generational type pushes a certain endowment activity throughout its lifecycle, creating characteristic patterns during each constellational era

### Key Principle: Endowment Behavior by Constellational Era

> *"The endowment behavior of each constellational era reflects the NEW endowment activity of the generational type coming of age; the STRONG and RISING endowment activity of the type entering midlife; the PEAKING, then FALLING activity of the type entering elderhood; and the DORMANT activity of the type moving beyond elderhood (and moving into youth)."*

**Four-phase endowment cycle:**
- **NEW** → coming of age generation introduces fresh activity
- **STRONG and RISING** → midlife generation intensifies its focus
- **PEAKING, then FALLING** → elderhood generation reaches peak then declines
- **DORMANT** → post-elderhood generation's activity fades as they move into youth phase
<!-- p. 374 -->

### Figure 12-11: Endowment Behavior by Constellational Era

**Table structure**: Shows how principal endowment activities vary across the four turnings
- Modern example timeline: 1970s (Awakening), 1990s (Inner-Driven), 1930s (Crisis), 1950s (Outer-Driven)

**IDEALIST endowments** (Principle, Religion, Education):
- New in Awakening Era
- Strong and rising in Inner-Driven Era
- Peaking then falling in Crisis Era
- Dormant in Outer-Driven Era

**REACTIVE endowments** (Liberty, Pragmatism, Survival):
- Dormant in Awakening Era
- New in Inner-Driven Era
- Strong and rising in Crisis Era
- Peaking then falling in Outer-Driven Era

**CIVIC endowments** (Community, Technology, Affluence):
- Peaking then falling in Awakening Era
- Dormant in Inner-Driven Era
- New in Crisis Era
- Strong and rising in Outer-Driven Era

**ADAPTIVE endowments** (Pluralism, Expertise, Social Justice):
- Strong and rising in Awakening Era
- Peaking then falling in Inner-Driven Era
- Dormant in Crisis Era
- New in Outer-Driven Era

### Endowment Activity Summary by Era

**AN AWAKENING ERA** begins with **Civic endowment activity** in confident overdrive:
- Society building big things, exploring new worlds, organizing new institutions
- Young **Idealists** emerge with moral claims → spiritual awakening lashes out at society's secular bias
- Suddenly halts and frustrates forward motion
- By era's end: **Civic "progress"** is mired, while old-fashioned fairness- and process-oriented endowments of **Adaptive ameliorators** gain favor
- Old **Reactive** focus on prudence and realism now appears stodgy and old-fashioned

**AN INNER-DRIVEN ERA** begins with **Adaptive endowment activity** reaching high tide:
- Pushing pluralism to the limit
- Infusing justice with process
- Making institutions highly professional and complex
- Coming-of-age **Reactives** apply new survival skills to a world they find harsh
- Values- and morality-oriented **Idealist** endowments gain strength

<!-- p. 374 -->

### Figure 12-11: Endowment Behavior by Constellational Era

**Table structure**: Shows how different types of endowments cycle through phases across four generational eras:
- **IDEALIST endowments** (Principle, Religion, Education): new in Awakening → strong and rising in Inner-Driven → peaking then falling in Crisis → dormant in Outer-Driven
- **REACTIVE endowments** (Liberty, Pragmatism, Survival): dormant in Awakening → new in Inner-Driven → strong and rising in Crisis → peaking then falling in Outer-Driven
- **CIVIC endowments** (Community, Technology, Affluence): peaking then falling in Awakening → dormant in Inner-Driven → new in Crisis → strong and rising in Outer-Driven
- **ADAPTIVE endowments** (Pluralism, Expertise, Social Justice): strong and rising in Awakening → peaking then falling in Inner-Driven → dormant in Crisis → new in Outer-Driven

**Modern example row**: 1970s (Awakening) → 1990s (Inner-Driven) → 1930s (Crisis) → 1950s (Outer-Driven)

### Endowment Activity Summary by Era

**AN AWAKENING ERA** characteristics:
- Begins with **Civic endowment activity** in confident overdrive
- Society building big things, exploring new worlds, organizing new institutions
- **Spiritual awakening** emerges as young Idealists' moral claims lash out at society's secular bias
- This "suddenly halts and frustrates its forward motion"
- By era's end, Civic "progress" is mired, while fairness- and process-oriented **Adaptive ameliorators** gain favor
- Old Reactive focus on prudence and realism now appears stodgy and old-fashioned

**AN INNER-DRIVEN ERA** characteristics:
- Begins with **Adaptive endowment activity** reaching high tide
- Pushes pluralism to the limit
- Infuses justice with process
- Makes institutions "highly professional and complex"
- Coming-of-age **Reactives** apply new survival skills to a world they find harsh
- Values- and morality-oriented endowments gain prominence

<!-- p. 375 -->

### Era Transitions and Generational Endowment Patterns

**Crisis Era dynamics:**
- **Idealist endowments** gradually gain popularity as **Civic endowments** (gridlocked, unworkable) attract little interest until near era's end
- Society prioritizes establishing **consensus of good-versus-bad, right-versus-wrong**
- Near peak of secular crisis, **sharp-eyed, prudential endowments** of midlife **Reactives** emerge
- Energy and teamwork of coming-of-age **Civics** emerge from new chrysalis
- Old **Adaptive sensitivity** to process and pluralism deemed wasteful, even subversive

**Outer-Driven Era dynamics:**
- Begins with **Reactive endowment activity** in popular demand—emphasizing survival, adaptability, establishing new institutions
- Preserves families and tradition from encroachment
- More ambitious **collectivist endowments** of **Civic builders** gradually gain popularity
- Coming-of-age **Adaptives** build expertise
- Tired of moral crusades, society turns back on **Idealist endowments** until near era's end

### The Core Pattern: Endowment Activity Decline

**Key principle:** Most striking pattern = not emergence of new endowment activity (gradual), but **rapid decline of old activity**

- Younger generations grow accustomed to relying on older generation to champion preferred endowment activity
- When not prepared to fill the gap as older generation passes on, society suffers **"tilt" or disequilibrium** from sudden absence of endowment activity

> "In each era, the most noticeable endowment neglect or reversal is likely to occur in the endowment activity associated with the generation currently passing beyond elderhood."

**Crisis Era examples:**
- Due process and fair play fall into disfavor (not only from force of events, but because **the generation that everyone expects to defend them is disappearing**)
- Mid-1930s: Where were **Progressive trust-busters** and champions of due process? Too old to be heard
- Mid-1940s: Where were **Adaptives**? Too old. Similar questions for prior Crisis eras
- Civil War: Where were **Adaptive conciliators**?
- American Revolution: **Compromisers or Enlighteners** too old or discredited

**Outer-Driven Era example:**
- Culturally sterile "end of ideology" decade of 1950s could have used zealous **Idealists** to stir things up—but **Missionaries** were disappearing

<!-- p. 375 -->

### Era Transition Patterns: Crisis and Outer-Driven Eras

- **Crisis Era** begins with **Idealist endowment activity** rising to maximum fury
- Society prioritizes establishing consensus on good-versus-bad, right-versus-wrong
- At peak of secular crisis, this fervor enables sharp-eyed, prudential endowments of midlife **Reactives**
- Energy and teamwork of coming-of-age **Civics** emerges from new chrysalis
- Old **Adaptive** sensibility to process and pluralism becomes wasteful, even subversive luxury

- **Outer-Driven Era** begins with **Reactive endowment activity** in great popular demand—emphasizing survival and stability, establishing new institutions
- Preserves families and tradition from encroachment
- More ambitious and collectivist endowments of **Civic** builders gradually gain popularity
- Coming-of-age **Adaptives** build expertise
- Tried-and-true crusades tire society, which turns back on **Idealist endowments** until near end of era

### The "Tilt" Pattern in Generational Transitions

- Most striking pattern: not emergence of new endowment activity (gradual), but **rapid decline of old activity**
- Younger generations grow accustomed to relying on older generation to champion its preferred endowment
- When that generation unprepared to fill the gap passes beyond elderhood with "one leg jerked away"
- Society suffers **"tilt" or disequilibrium** from sudden absence of this endowment activity

> "In each era, the most noticeable endowment neglect or reversal is likely to occur in the endowment activity associated with the generation currently passing beyond elderhood."

### Historical Examples of the Tilt

**Crisis Era Examples:**
- **Due process and fair play** fall into disfavor—not only from force of events, but because **the generation that everyone expects to defend them is disappearing**
- Mid-1930s: aggressive regimentation of economic and social life
- Mass internment of Japanese-American citizens a few years later
- Question: Where were the **Progressive** trust-busters and champions of due process? Too old to be heard
- Similar pattern in prior **Crisis** eras: Where were **Adaptive** conciliators during Civil War or American Revolution? **Compromisers** or **Enlighteners** were too old or discredited by then

**Outer-Driven Era Examples:**
- Culturally sterile "end of ideology" decade of 1950s could have used zealous **Idealists** to stir things up
- But the **Missionaries** were disappearing

<!-- p. 376 -->

### Generational Endowment Patterns

- Historical parallels of quiescent eras needing awakening:
  - **Jeffersonian era** (early 1800s) felt loss of Awakeners
  - Circa-1880 **Gilded Age** when Transcendentals were fading
  - **Do-It-Now euphoria** pulled America from 1960s into mid-1970s Awakening
  - **Skeptical Reactives** might have sobered things up and spared disappointment later
  - Too late by Model Cities and Woodstock—most Lost had passed

- Modern **Inner-Driven era**: Adaptives adding institutionalist layers, Idealists perfecting new values
  - Missing G.I. living generation that knew how to unify community and accomplish big things

### Lifecycle Endowment Observation

**Key pattern**: Each generation develops a **lifelong endowment agenda** pointing toward the endowment activity that society neglected or reversed during its youth

**The Silent** (Adaptive generation):
- Grew up in crisis-gripped world with little refinement, sensitivity, or fairness
- Lifelong agenda: rectifying such mistakes, raising sensitivity banner
- Example: Silent-dominated Congress awarded $20,000 damages to every Japanese-American interned during WWII

**Boomers** (earlier Idealist generation):
- Grew up during cyclical low tide of spiritual curiosity as children
- Lifelong endowment agenda: infusing society with new spiritual energy
- Boom is the first generation since Missionaries preparing for late-in-life moral crusades

**13ers**:
- Should ask what they will someday sense was missing from their childhood environment
- Most likely: all generations have missed the **active presence of the pragmatic Lost** since mid-1960s

**Millennials**:
- Growing up without something earlier Americans had
- About to miss: active presence of **team-playing G.I.s**

> "As is the generation of leaves, so with men, which alternately come forth and pass away." - Homer

### Endowment as Stabilizing Force

- Endowment behavior reflects **stabilizing dynamic intrinsic to the generational cycle**
- Ensures no one dimension of progress is pushed too long or lies dormant too long
- Each kind of endowment activity has its own season
- Makes cycle of generations a **powerful force for rejuvenation**, a balance wheel for human progress
- **Guarantor of the American Dream**—if all generations play their roles well

> "The past is prologue. Let's turn to the future."

<!-- p. 376 -->

### Generational Endowment Patterns

- Historical examples of cultural transitions: **Jeffersonian era** of early 1800s (losing Awakeners), circa-1880 **Gilded Age** height (Transcendentals fading)
- **Do-It-Now euphoria** propelled America from 1960s through mid-1970s (Awakening era) with need for "splash of ice-water realism"
- Skeptical Reactives might have sobered up and spared disappointment, but **too late** by time of Model Cities and Woodstock
- Most Lost had passed by late 1970s; America entering **Inner-Driven era** with Adaptive adding layers of institutional process and detached Idealists perfecting new values
- **G.I.s** as only living generation that knows how to unify community and get big things done

### Final Lifecycle Observation: Generational Endowment Agenda

> "Each generation develops a lifelong endowment agenda pointing toward the endowment activity that society neglected or reversed during its youth."

**The Silent** (Adaptive generation):
- Grew up in crisis-gripped world lacking refinement, sensitivity, or play-by-the-rules fairness
- Lifelong agenda: rectifying such mistakes, raising banner of **Progressive idealism** dropped in old age by G.I.s
- Example: Silent-dominated Congress awarded $20,000 damages to every **Japanese-American interned during World War II**

**Boomers** (Idealist generation):
- Grew up as children during cyclical low tide of spiritual curiosity
- Lifelong endowment agenda: **infusing society with new spiritual energy**
- Boom generation showing signs of preparing for late-in-life moral crusades

**13ers** (Reactive generation):
- Should ask what they will someday sense was missing from childhood environment
- Most likely will be missing: **active presence of pragmatic Lost** since mid-1960s
- Newly arriving **Millennials** may grow up yearning for something **Americans are about to miss**: active presence of team-playing G.I.s

### Generational Cycle as Stabilizing Force

> "As is the generation of leaves," wrote Homer, "so it is with the generations of men, which alternately come forth and pass away."

- **Endowment behavior** reflects stabilizing dynamic intrinsic to generational cycle
- Ensures no one dimension of progress pushed too long or lies dormant too long
- Like Homer's "leaves," each endowment activity has its own season
- Makes generational cycle a **powerful force for rejuvenation**, a balance wheel for human progress
- Requires **all generations play their roles well** as guarantor of American Dream

**"The past is prologue. Let's turn to the future."**

<!-- p. 377 -->

## Chapter 13: Completing the Millennial Cycle

### Historical Sparks and National Crisis Response

- History contains many sparks—some ignite major conflagrations, others fade without consequence
- Key question: How would America respond to a terrorist attack on New York City?
- Answer depends on **when** the event occurs—specifically, during which **constellational era**

### Crisis Response During Awakening Era

**Hypothetical scenario**: terrorist threat during last **Awakening** (around 1970)
- National response would have been intensely controversial
- Cross-currents of **secular confidence** and **spiritual rebellion**
- Official sponsors would have been intensely controversial in their fifties
- **Leaders** in their fifties, acting as **hubristic crisis managers**, would have downplayed threat
- Public would demand daily life not be disturbed while controlling situation through vigorous technological means
- **Angry young Boomers** would organize behind symbolic and emotional responses
- Would accuse U.S. government of lying and blame it on "some monstrous institutional plot"
- **Thirtyish Silent** would be puzzled why any foreigner could hate America so much
- Evacuation would occur in mood of **collective hysteria** and disbelief
- America would be "at war with itself more than with the perpetrators"


<!-- p. 378 -->

### Hypothetical Terrorist Crisis Response Scenarios (continued)

**Scenario 2: Terrorist strike during upcoming Crisis (early 1990s-early 2020s)**
- Generational constellation would prompt dramatically different response than today's perspective
- **Boomer leaders** in their sixties would not hide rumors but exaggerate threat (compare: "one city" vs "all cities")
- Would unify nation as community, define enemy broadly, demand total defeat
- Human and economic sacrifices would be required and accepted
- Evacuation would be mannerly, cooperative, with **Millennial youths** seeking and accepting orders from elders
- Emphasis on pragmatic infallibility, ensuring no time wasted
- Nation would act promptly, decisively as single organism
- Leaders would risk being vilified in other eras to achieve "just outcome"

**Key insight on terrorist impact:**
- Three hypothetical events, three hugely contrasting responses
- Impact on history comes less from *act of terrorism itself* than from the *response* it would provoke

### Unpredictability of Future Crises

**Fundamental uncertainty:**
- No one can say whether nuclear terrorism will strike
- Cannot predict specific early twenty-first century troubles:
  - Revolution in Latin America
  - Belligerent Third World fundamentalism
  - AIDS
  - Global warming/ozone depletion
  - Fossil fuel exhaustion
  - High-tech genetics abuse
  - Trade wars
  - Debt-fueled financial crisis

**Historical precedent for unpredictability:**
- Around 1745 and 1910, nobody could have predicted:
  - Boston Tea Party
  - Pearl Harbor Day
- All less momentous than those events

**Methodological approach:**
- When experts investigate the future, they rely on **quantitative** pro-

<!-- p. 378 -->

### Hypothetical Terrorist Attack During Crisis (early 1990s scenario)

**Crisis-era response dynamics:**
- By early 1990s (mid-**Inner-Driven era**), quarter-century will have reshaped national response
- Response would emphasize: caution, conciliation, deferral
- **Silent cabinet officers** would consult elderly GIs, form committees, review options, invite public discussion
- Leaders would initiate multilateral negotiations, try to avoid things ("bound to happen sooner or later")
- Would hardly ruffle young 13ers (many might rush forward to sell/volunteer)
- Official evacuation plans: expensive, overcomplicated, offering little public confidence
- Most people would stay calm and make own plans
- Nation would "squeeze by the immediate threat undamaged, but leave its underlying causes either unsolved or, at best, mildly ameliorated"

**Crisis constellation response (year 2020):**
- "Unrecognizable" from today's perspective
- **Boomer leaders** (in sixties) would neither hide nor exaggerate—would "broadly define the threat"
- If bomb in only *one* city, tie it to larger global crisis sense
- Community would "face leaders" and define enemy broadly, demand total defeat regardless of human/economic sacrifices
- Evacuation would be mannerly, with cooperative **Millennial youths** seeking and accepting orders from elders and pragmatic midlife 13ers
- Nation would act "promptly and decisively as a single organism"
- Would be "inclined in other eras to risk catastrophe to achieve what its leaders would define as a just outcome"

**Key insight:**
- Impact on history comes less from *act of terrorism itself* than from *response it would provoke*

### Unpredictability of Future Crises

**Cannot predict specific events:**
- No one can say whether nuclear terrorism will strike
- Numerous scenarios mentioned in predictions about early twenty-first century:
  - Chemical, germ, or nuclear weapons by small nations
  - Revolution in Latin America
  - Belligerent Third World fundamentalism
  - AIDS
  - Global warming trend; ozone depletion
  - Exhaustion of fossil fuels
  - Abuse of high-tech genetics
  - Trade wars
  - Debt-fueled financial crisis

**Historical parallel:**
- Nobody could predict specific problems America would face in 2010s and 2020s
- Just as nobody around 1745 and 1910 could have predicted Boston Tea Party or Pearl Harbor Day
- "Still less the rapid and momentous sequels to those events"

**Quantitative vs. qualitative forecasting:**
- When experts investigate future, they typically rely on *quantitative* pro-
<!-- p. 379 -->

### Generational Cycle and Forecasting Social Behavior

- Experts can project technical problems (bridge collapses, oil shortages, budget deficits) but are helpless before the great mysteries of human nature: how people will **respond** to those problems
- Energy forecasters in the 1970s assumed Americans in the 21st century would act the same as in the "Me Decade" 1970s
  - Same response patterns: government with complex regulation, producers with market chaos, consumers with angry gas lines
  - Economists assumed long-term Social Security projections would hold, with stable political attitudes across retirement age brackets
  - Assumed old **Silent** and **Boomers** would sustain "senior citizen" benefits lobby with same intensity as **G.I.s**
  - Assumed younger **13ers** and **Millennials** would subsidize elder benefits as willingly as Silent and Boom have in recent decades
- **Straight-line projections** can be way off the mark—equivalent of forecasting how the Civil War would be waged by studying the speeches of Henry Clay

> "History tells us one thing for certain about social behavior: It never remains the same for long. The realistic question is not whether it will change, but how and when."

### Qualitative Insight of the Generational Cycle

- The generational cycle helps check out mysterious wild cards of social behavior
- Can assess what other forecasters normally avoid: **future constellational moods** and **the peer personalities of today's generations as they age into new phases of life**

### Historical Examples: Nuclear Terrorism Response

- **Using hypothetical nuclear terrorism** as point of departure
- Examples of how America actually responded to perceived threats against national community at analogous moments:
  - **Great Power cycle** at time of **Chicago Haymarket Riot of 1886** (in an **Awakening era**)
  - Sinking of the **Lusitania** in 1915 (an **Inner-Driven era**; or at the time of the attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941 (a **Crisis era**)
- In each example, history was determined **less by the sparklike event itself** than by **the mood of the constellational era** in which it occurred

### History as Patterns, Not Invariant

- This is **not** to say that history is invariant, with predetermined outcomes
- Any era can bring forward good or bad leaders, good or bad choices
- Key suggestion: **constellational eras and generational lifecycles follow predictable patterns**, within which each generation has a limited choice of scripts
- During social moments—secular crises especially—those scripts become more fateful, more determinative of history, more likely to result in triumph or tragedy

### Extending Generational Scripts into the Future

- Building from the paradigms of the last chapter, we can extend these generational scripts into the future
- The **Millennial Cycle** already began (as all cycles must) with one social moment: the **Boom Awakening** of the late 1960s and 1970s
- The next—what we call the **"Crisis of 2020"**—is due to begin when the **Millennial Cycle** has run about halfway through its course
- The current cycle [continues on next page]

<!-- p. 376 -->

### Limitations of Linear Forecasting

- Experts acknowledge helplessness before mysteries of human nature: how people will **respond** to problems, how they think, behave, and vote
- Energy forecasters examining fossil fuel future seldom ask whether Americans in 21st century will act differently than during "Me Decade" 1970s
- Implicit assumption: forecasters assume same response patterns will continue
  - Government with complex regulation
  - Producers with market chaos
  - Consumers with angry gas lines
- Economists making long-range Social Security projections assume people in pre- and post-retirement age brackets maintain same political attitudes shown in recent past
- Assumption: old **Silent** and **Boomers** will sustain "senior citizen" benefits lobby with same intensity as **G.I.s**, younger **13ers** and **Millennials** will subsidize elder benefits as willingly as Silent and Boom have in recent decades
- **Straight-line projections can be way off the mark**—equivalent of forecasting Civil War outcome by studying speeches of Henry Clay

> "History tells us one thing for certain about social behavior: It never remains the same for long. The realistic question is not whether it will change, but how and when."

### Qualitative Insight of the Generational Cycle

- Generational cycle helps check out mysterious wild cards of social behavior and assess what forecasters normally avoid—**future constellational moods** and **the peer personalities of today's generations as they age into new phases of life**
- **Using hypothetical nuclear terrorism as point of departure** to reflect on how America did in fact respond to perceived threats against national community at analogous moments:
  - Time of **Chicago Haymarket Riot of 1886** (in an **Awakening era**)
  - Time of sinking of **Lusitania in 1915** (an **Inner-Driven era**)
  - Time of attack on **Pearl Harbor in 1941** (a **Crisis era**)
- In each example, **history determined less by sparklike event itself than by mood of constellational era in which it occurred**

### History Is Not Invariant but Follows Patterns

- History not invariant with predetermined outcomes
- Any era can bring forward good or bad leaders, good or bad choices
- **Constellational eras and generational lifecycles follow predictable patterns**, within which each generation has limited choice of scripts
- During **social moments—secular crises especially**—those scripts become more fateful, more determinative of history, more likely to result in triumph or tragedy
- Building from paradigms of last chapter: can extend generational scripts into the future
- **Millennial Cycle** already began (as all cycles must) with one social moment: the Boom Awakening of the late 1960s and 1970s
- The next—**"Crisis of 2020"**—is due to begin when the Millennial Cycle has run about halfway through its course
