### The 1990s Institutional and Cultural Transformation

- As the 1990s dawn, the **generational constellation** will resemble periods of **1910, 1845, 1750, and 1650**
- **"As the 1990s bring?"** - society not facing up to long-term challenges, struggling to concentrate on effective response
- Talk of **"new world order"** felt premature in a society unsure of its own foundations
- With fading presence of **G.I.s**, public confidence in old institutions will wane further

### Institutional Decline and Elder Silent Leadership

- **Elder Silent** leaders will discuss and debate but **never rule out any perceived institutional inequity**
- **Midlife Boomers** will come out of remission trumpeting **moral rectitude**
- Coming-of-age **13ers** will game the system without any pretense of higher principle
- Public life will become more **zealous, less friendly**
- **Social intolerance** will grow, respect for privacy decrease

### New Values Coalitions and Social Movements

- New **"values" coalitions** arise:
  - Older voting blocs based on economic, class, and racial self-interest weaken
  - Child nurture becomes stricter, protective function of schools and neighborhoods attracts growing public support
  - **Senior citizen movement** will weaken and the child lobby strengthen
- **Widening gap between haves and have-nots** increasingly recognized as a problem
- People at both ends of economic spectrum (the **ultrarich/very poor** and the **greedy rich**) will be attacked for lacking acceptable civic virtue

### Boomer-Retooled Justice and Institutional Regulation

- **Boomer-retooled justice** will punish aberrant behavior with growing severity
- Overtones of **moral retribution**
- **Boomer-retooled institutions** will strictly regulate conduct (from drug use to parenting) formerly regarded as matters of **personal choice**

### Three Distinct Generational Cultures Emerging

**During the 1990s, three distinct generational cultures will emerge:**

1. **Silent (elder end)** - struggle to buttress and defend their **pluralist culture**
   - Emphasis on lifestyle tolerance, economic opportunity, and process-protected fairness
   - These efforts will peak before mid-1990s and then decline steeply

2. **Boom's moralistic culture** (displacing the Silent)
   - Emphasis on **ethical absolutes, community values, and accountability in public and private life**

3. **13ers advancing into rising adulthood** - engaged in an **alienated culture**
   - Emphasis on **getting what you can, without excuses**, in a world that (as they will see it) never cared about giving them much

### Aligned Inner-Driven Constellation (circa 2003)

- When America reaches an **aligned Inner-Driven constellation** (sometime around **2003**):
  - **G.I.s** will be very old, **Silent** in elderhood, **Boomers** in midlife, **13ers** in rising adulthood, **Millennials** in youth
  - Generational alignment will match constellations of **1924, 1855, 1766, and 1673**

> "At all four of these moments, Americans perceived their social life to be fragmenting into centrifugal and uncontrollable wildness."

### Boomer and 13er Cultural Polarization

- **Boomer and 13er cultures** will by then be moving into **self-contained camps**:
  - **Loud, moralizing aggressors** on the older side
  - **Atomized, pleasure-seeking victims** on the younger side
- A **vindictive age polarization** America has not witnessed since the **Roaring Twenties**
- Looking down the age ladder, elder Silent will express dismay at growing signs of **tribalism, nativism**

<!-- p. 383 -->

