### G.I. Generation: Fastest-Growing Age Bracket & Lessons for Younger Generations

- **Centenarians** have become America's fastest-growing age bracket—a trend likely to continue through the twenty-first century
- Peak decades for each generation: 2030s for G.I.s, 2050s for Silent, 2070s for Boom, 2090s for 13ers, 2110s for Millennials

**Important reminders from Missionaries and Lost for younger generations (particularly Boomers):**
- How **Missionaries** transformed from brash young reformers to stern elder "Victorians" and transcended the zeal and self-absorption of their youth to produce greatness in old age
- **13ers** could learn from the Lost: how history dealt short-term excitement but longer-term pain; how many "ran on empty" to the point of exhaustion; how life went on and alienation passed
- At critical hours, the Lost exercised **practical realism** as no other generation could
- At life's end, they became **risk-averse conservatives**
- Today's 25-year-olds exhibiting many of the same tendencies as what Fitzgerald termed the "**prewar**" personality of the Lost
- Perhaps **13ers** can match the best of what the Lost became—the Nobel-laureate authors, savvy adventurers, level-headed pragmatists—**with less of the impulse toward self-destruction**

### Completing the G.I. Diagonal

**G.I.s shifting relationship with age:**
- Most of the thirty million G.I. survivors believe they have a lot of living yet to do—six in ten believe they'll live another ten years, one in four another twenty
- This generation that hates the word "old" is beginning to realize it is becoming just that
- G.I.s are drifting beyond what gerontologists (with G.I. blessing) not ago christened the "**young old**" phase into the "**old old**" phase until recently associated with the Lost
- As they coin new names for themselves—perhaps something like "**Super Seniors**"—G.I.s will energize the contemporary image of what it means to be over 80

### Entering Post-Elderhood in an Inner-Driven Era (1991-2003)

**Physical and psychological challenges:**
- Physical decline will come hard to a generation whose definition of self (and virtue) has always been so closely tied to **activity**, to getting things done
- Many G.I.s will feel newly depressed, finding a loss of purpose, sensing a loss of respect
- Yet the core of this generation will try, as always, to **keep spirits up**
- Many will fall into failing health and move from seniors-only condos into member-run "**planned care communities**"—euphemized updates of what the Lost bluntly called "**nursing homes**"
- Wherever G.I.s live, their peer society will remain as **friendly and collegial** as ever


<!-- p. 387 -->

### Completing the G.I. Diagonal

- **G.I. survivors** (~30 million) believe they still have much living to do—they're right
- Six in ten G.I.s will live another ten years, one in four another twenty
- This generation that hates the word "old" is beginning to realize they are becoming just that
- G.I.s drifting beyond **gerontologists' expectations**: christened the "young old" phase, moving into the "old old" phase previously associated with the Lost
- Coining new names for themselves—perhaps **"Super Seniors"**—G.I.s will energize the contemporary image of what it means to be over 80

### Entering Post-Elderhood in an Inner-Driven Era (1991-2003)

- **Physical decline** will come hard to a generation whose definition of self (and virtue) has always been closely tied to **activity**, to getting things done
- Many G.I.s will feel newly depressed, finding a loss of purpose, sensing a loss of respect
