- Wherever G.I.s live, their peer society will remain as **friendly and collegial as ever**

<!-- p. 388 -->

### The G.I. Generation's Changing Relationship with Government

- Mutually supportive relationship between government and **G.I.s** will continue into their deep old age
- Over next 15 years, public attention to senior citizens will shift up the age bracket:
  - Away from issues relevant to 60-year-olds (early retirement, reduced income/property taxes)
  - Toward concerns of 80-year-olds (long-term custodial care, access to life-extending technologies)
- **G.I. lobbies** will argue their generation is "entitled" to best-available health care regardless of income or age
- Like **Glorious Republicans** before them, G.I.s will expect good treatment, juniors will comply with material reward requests
- Long-term costs will be initially underestimated

### The End of G.I. Dominance

- "Please-thank you" relationship with government will become unfamiliar as **Boomers** age
- Giving this generation public rewards was form of future-oriented investment
- **Key difference:** "The G.I.s will no longer be the future"
- Future generations looking on with nostalgia will not see older, wiser elders, but rather:
  - G.I.s will see themselves as nice kids getting public allowance for good deeds
  - Same behavior from two life phases ago (in **Inner-Driven era**) had the feel of investment
- G.I.s did not expect their lifecycle to turn out this way

### The G.I. Lifecycle Story

- **From moment they came of age:** followed elders' instructions to save, invest, build, and be patient
- Pursued **Social Security "deal"** through which G.I.s would be rewarded later in their lifecycle by younger generations
- **Through postwar boom:** everyone assumed juniors would afford the burden with little trouble
  - Thanks to expanding workforce, rising savings/investment levels, and expanding productivity growth
  - **Benefit levels kept rising**, enabling G.I.s to receive back many times what they paid into the system
  - G.I.s assumed their children and grandchildren would enjoy the same pyramiding benefits

### What Actually Happened

- Something went wrong along the way. **Sapped by deficits, inflation, and pro-consumption tax bias:**
  - Savings rates did not rise (they fell)
  - Productivity growth did not speed up (it slowed down)
  - **Younger generations did not have larger families** (they had smaller ones)
- **Public cost of supporting G.I. elders soared** beyond all earlier projections—thanks to mixture of auto-
<!-- p. 388 -->

### G.I. Generation's Future Expectations vs. Reality

**Shift in public attention and support:**
- Mutually supportive relationship between government and **G.I.s** will continue into their deep old age
- Over next 15 years, public attention to senior citizens will shift up the age bracket
- Focus moving away from issues of 60-year-olds (early retirement, reduced income/property taxes)
- Moving toward concerns of 80-year-olds (long-term custodial care, access to life-extending technologies)

**G.I. expectations of entitlement:**
- G.I. lobbies will make case that their generation is "entitled" to best-available health care, regardless of income or age
- Like **Glorious and Republicans** before them, G.I.s will expect good treatment
- Juniors will generally comply with requests involving material reward
- Long-term cost will be initially underestimated

**The critical difference from the past:**
- When G.I.s alone atop age ladder, this "please-thank you" relationship with government will take familiar form
- Forty years ago, when they prospered, America prospered
- Their **Idealist and Reactive** neighbors (**Missionary and Lost**) looked on with approval, even though they shared less in public largess

> "The G.I.s will no longer be the future."

**Changing generational dynamics:**
- During the 1990s, as G.I.s continue to get rewards, their Idealist and Reactive neighbors (**Boom and 13th**) will again look on with little objection
- Will again neither receive, nor expect to receive, like treatment
- Generations looking on with noses pressed against glass will not be older, but younger
- G.I. self-perception will not change at all—they will still see themselves as nice kids getting public allowance for good deeds
- Same behavior that two life phases ago (in an **Outer-Driven era**) had feel of investment will now (in an **Inner-Driven era**) have feel of consumption

**G.I.s' failed lifecycle expectations:**
- Did not expect their lifecycle story to turn out this way
- From when they first came of age, followed their elders' instructions to save, invest, build, and be patient
- Pursued a Social Security "deal" through which G.I.s would be rewarded later in their lifecycle by younger (and presumably wealthier) generations
- Through the postwar boom, everyone assumed these juniors would afford the burden with little trouble—thanks to expanding workforce, rising levels of savings and investment, and heady rates of productivity growth

**What actually happened:**
- Benefit levels kept rising, enabling G.I.s to receive back many times what they and their employers had paid into the trust funds
- G.I.s assumed their children and grandchildren would later enjoy same pyramiding benefits when their own turns came
- But something happened along the way: **Sapped by deficits, inflation, and a pro-consumption tax bias, savings rates did not rise**
- Productivity growth did not speed up (it slowed down)
- Younger generations did not have larger families (they had smaller ones)
- Public cost of supporting G.I. elders soared beyond all earlier projections—thanks to mixture of auto-

<!-- p. 389 -->

### G.I. Generation's Acquiescence and Boom Criticism

- **G.I.s' acquiescence despite criticism**: Despite 1960s-era criticisms, "*The Boom and Silent have always depended on the G.I.s—the generation that in their eyes has always epitomized secular endowment—to defend the ethic of investment*"
- When G.I.s indicated it was okay to feed off the future, other generations followed suit

<!-- p. 389 -->

### G.I. Generational Critique and Boomer Acquiescence

- **Boomers' criticism of G.I.s echoed old Republican-Transcendental quarrels** from early 19th century
- **G.I.s charged Boomers with betraying history** (as aging Jefferson blamed young in 1820s, Gallatin blamed young in 1830s-1840s)
- *What* went wrong per G.I. view: **G.I.s built prosperity but Boomers lacked civic virtues** of their youth
- From **Pruitt-Igoe apartments to debt-leveraged buyouts on Wall Street**, Boomers seemed to grind down more than build
- Boomers appeared to care more about **self than community, consuming more than saving, preserving personal independence** over working toward building families

**G.I. critique of 1960s-1970s Boomers:**
- *When* things went wrong (G.I. view): during **late 1960s and 1970s**
- **True enough:** In coming-of-age euphoria, Boomers **detested material creations of G.I.s** - elders and castigated youth for concept of **deferring current consumption for future rewards** (pathology per G.I. mind-set)
- **Boom Awakening clouded G.I. judgment**: subtly egging on Boomer sense of worldly hubris

**G.I.-Boomer exchange on material progress:**
> "You've made material life effortless, so why bother working at it?"

> "You're right, we have done rather well. Maybe it *is* time to let go."

- **And so they did** - Boomers acquiesced

**Core dynamic:**
> "Much rested on this acquiescence. Despite their 1960s-era criticisms, *the Boom and Silent have always depended on the G.I.s*—the generation that in their eyes has always epitomized secular endowment—to defend the ethic of investment."

- When **G.I.s indicated okay to feed off the future**, other generations followed
<!-- p. 390 -->

### G.I. Generation's Endowment and Future Recognition

- **G.I.s earned their benefits** through wartime sacrifice and civic achievements - little opposition from younger generations to their "deal"
- Boomers willing to pay high **Social Security taxes** with little expectation of equal returns - they gain **personal independence** and ability to redefine social values without interference from politically powerful elders
- G.I.s can take solace: not first generation to see their unique endowment type erode as they move behind elderhood - **Great Society** plan for well-ordered cornucopia now seems out of reach, leaving them nonetheless proud of their accomplishments

### The Erosion of G.I. "Civic" Magic

- As 1990s progress, **G.I.s will notice younger generations starting to miss their "Civic" magic** for making things work
- G.I. peer personality in America badly needs to relearn
- **Generational monuments** like **Iwo Jima** - once symbols of intimidating G.I. power - will become shrines to a Civic spirit remembered, but increasingly perceived as weak and endangered
- People of all ages will look to **Boomers for values**; still look to G.I.s for guidance on secular endowments, deep into the latter's "old old" age
- Thanks to **lengthening lifespans**, significant number of G.I.s will live to see this shift and may be heartened by it

### Intergenerational Obligations and Trade-offs

- If post-elders decide to help America rebuild **teamwork and productive community**, younger generations likely to follow
- If G.I.s suggest their wealthiest members deserve no health/nursing-care subsidies or rank-and-file seniors deserve no discounts below what **harder-pressed 13ers must pay in full** - for property taxes to bus rides - their example may encourage new generation of children to start acting as selflessly as G.I.s did in youth
- If G.I.s themselves support additional investment in education, Boom and 13er parents may join in putting children's needs ahead of their own
- If G.I.s stop tolerating trade and budget deficits that are **(by simple arithmetic) elder-favoring**, younger voters may agree to stop burdening children with debt

> "Will G.I.s relax their collective expectation of late-in-life reward? History..."
<!-- p. 390 -->

### G.I. Generational Endowments and Retirement Security

- G.I.s rest easy knowing no younger generation will take away significant retirement benefits
- G.I.s possess private affluence because they **earned** it—will encounter little dissent from generations who could challenge them
- Boomers willing to shell out high **Social Security taxes** with little expectation of return—gain **personal independence** from parents and ability to redefine social values without interference from politically powerful elders
- G.I.s take solace that they're not first generation to see unique endowment type erode upon moving behind elderhood—happened to previous generations with **Great Society** plan

### Decline of G.I. Civic Magic in 1990s

- As 1990s progress, G.I.s will notice younger generations start to **miss their old "Civic" magic** for making things work
- G.I. peer personality traits (deep sense of community) increasingly perceived as weak and endangered
- Where all ages look to Boomers for values, they still look to G.I.s for guidance on **secular endowments, deep into the latter's "old old" age**
- Thanks to lengthening lifespans, significant number of G.I.s will live to see this and may be heartened by it

### Post-Elder Decision Making and Intergenerational Impacts

- If post-elders decide to help America rebuild **sense of teamwork and productive community**, younger generations likely to follow
- If G.I.s suggest their wealthiest members deserve no health- or nursing-care subsidies or that rank-and-file seniors deserve no discounts below harder-pressed 13ers—**13ers must pay in full** for everything from property taxes to bus rides
- Their example may encourage new generation of children to start acting as selflessly as G.I.s did in youth
- If G.I.s themselves support additional investment in education, Boom and 13er parents may join them in putting children's needs ahead of their own
- If G.I.s stop tolerating **trade and budget deficits that are (by simple arithmetic) elder-favoring**, younger voters may agree—yes, we really *should* stop burdening children with debt

### Historical Question on Collective Expectations

> "Will G.I.s relax their collective expectation of late-in-life reward? History"

<!-- p. 391 -->

### G.I.-Millennial Generational Bond

- The **G.I.-Millennial bond** represents a major question mark in the G.I. lifecycle - they offer the most likely catalyst for a late-in-life repair of senior-citizen endowment behavior
- G.I.s know through their own experience that Civic generations need a positive relationship with governing *starting with childhood*
- G.I.s (like Boomers) were able to ignore rising poverty among 13er children - but they may find **Millennial poverty far less tolerable**
- Raising the Millennials is mainly the task of Boomers, but this will complicate the G.I. task of helping these children
- Today's seniors will never feel comfortable with the Boomer personality—nor the Boom with the G.I. personality
- As the 1990s progress, both generations may begin to realize that much of this antagonism has heretofore rested on their respective phase-of-life positions

### Cross-Generational Appeal

- **Younger Idealists and older Civics collectively repel each other**, but older Idealists and younger Civics attract each other just as strongly
- In **post-elderhood**, G.I.s can make an important discovery about their children: *"that Boomers, in midlife, are coming to resemble the G.I.s' own parents"*—the righteous Missionaries—whose patriarchal persona today's seniors remember so admiringly
- G.I.s know they raised Boomers differently from how they themselves were brought up
- They expected Boomer "yuppies" to behave as dutifully and collegially as they themselves had in the 1930s and 1940s
- Instead, tempestuous Boomers followed the Missionary-led path through rising adulthood—a phase of life during which G.I.s knew their parents only through a child's undiscerning eye

### Boomers as Custodians of Civic Virtue Memory

- As custodians of the memory of great Missionary leaders, **G.I. senior citizens may come to see in Boomers not the embodiment of Civic-type virtues, but the factors of those virtues**
- The *fewer* of those virtues the more G.I.s notice this, the less they may feel inclined to opt out of the world of younger generations
- Or to deplete any more of the endowments they worked so hard for so many decades to build
- In return, Boomers may see in G.I. post-elders a living example of the competence and power they envision for their cherished Millennial children
- This could prove to be a **mutually pleasing finale to the still-simmering G.I.-Boom rift**—much as the midlife Awakener Benjamin Franklin finally grew to respect the "Do-Good" memory of Glorious Cotton Mather, the very symbol of Civic order that Franklin had ridiculed as a young man

### Generational Time and Leadership

- Time—and "their" twentieth century—is running out on this generation
- Yet at this writing, a **G.I. Commander-in-Chief still sits in the Oval Office**

