### Completing the Silent Diagonal

- The **Silent Generation**, like all Adaptive predecessors, have glided through history blessed with economic good fortune
- Spared both outer sacrifices of their elders and inner traumas of their juniors
- Silent have been denied adventure and never felt fully comfortable at any age
- Spent a lifetime realizing two important facts:
  1. They are not **G.I.s**
  2. They are not **Boomers**
- As they age, aging Silent will grow increasingly worried about the fate of the generation they raised—the young **13ers**
- Young 13ers' unromantic outlook on life seems oddly different from what Silent recall of their own early years

### Entering Elderhood in an Inner-Driven Era (1991-2003)

- As 1990s proceed, a new breed of American elder will emerge: the **"high-tech" senior**
- Running life with Macintosh software on investments, leisure opportunities, and eligibility rules
- No American generation has ever entered old age better equipped than the Silent
- **Today's sixtyish men and women** stand at the wealthier edge of America's wealthiest-ever generation
- Poised to take full advantage of generous **G.I.-built old-age entitlement programs**
- Armies of merchandisers and seniors-only condo salesmen will pounce on these new young-oldsters
- They complete stunning two-generation **rags-to-riches transformation of American elderhood**
- Where 1950s-era elder Lost watched offspring whiz past them in economic life, 1990s-era elder Silent will tower over living standards of their children
- In 1960, 35-year-olds typically lived in bigger houses and drove better cars than their 65-year-old parents
- **In the year 2000, the opposite will be the case**
- Were this to happen to any other living generation, it would feel like a triumph
- **But not for the Silent**—in old age, as always, the Silent will carry what **Benita**

