### Completing the Silent Diagonal

- The **Silent generation**, like all **Adaptive** predecessors, have glided through history blessed with economic good fortune
- Spared both outer sacrifices of their elders and inner traumas of their juniors
- Have been denied adventure and never felt fully comfortable at any age
- The Silent have spent a lifetime realizing two important facts:
  - First, they are **not G.I.s**
  - Second, they are **not Boomers**
- As they grow old, they will still be aware of these two facts
- The aging Silent will grow increasingly worried about the fate of the generation they raised—the young **13ers**—whose unromantic outlook on life seems so oddly different from what they recall of their own early years

### Entering Elderhood in an Inner-Driven Era (1991-2003)

- As the 1990s proceed, a new breed of American elder will emerge: the **"high-tech" senior**
  - Running his **Macintosh** with software on investments, leisure opportunities, and eligibility rules for special benefits
  - No American generation has ever entered old age better equipped than the Silent
- Today's **sixtyish men and women** stand at the wealthier edge of America's wealthiest-ever generation
  - Poised to take full advantage of generous **G.I.-built old-age entitlement programs**
  - Armies of merchandisers and seniors-only condo salesmen will pounce on these new young-oldsters
- They are completing a stunning **two-generation rags-to-riches transformation of American elderhood**
  - Where the **1950s-era elder Lost** watched their offspring whiz past them in economic life
  - The **1990s-era elder Silent** will tower over the living standards of their children
- **In 1960**, 35-year-olds typically lived in bigger houses and drove better cars than their 65-year-old parents
- **In the year 2000**, the opposite will be the case
- Were this to happen to any other living generation, it would feel like a triumph
- **But not for the Silent**—in old age, as always, the Silent will carry what **Benita**
<!-- p. 393 -->

### The Silent Generation's Anxiety About Rewards

- **Silent Generation** embodies what Eisler calls "corpse in the trunk" mentality: **anxiety, guilt**, ability to see drought in sunny weather, flood when it starts to shower
- No generation has more difficulty enjoying good things or keen antennae for sensing others' needs
- Once Silent perceive their affluence is **generational** and unlikely to be exceeded by their **13er children**, they will feel genuine hurt

### Silent as "Young Old" - Questioning Past Rewards

- As Silent seniors stare at amber monitors, they wonder whether they deserve such long list of late-in-life rewards
- **The Silent weren't denied jobs** in the Great Depression (new toys and second helpings, maybe)
- **The Silent didn't win any war** (they tied one)
- **The Silent didn't build grand endowments** (they handled the details)
- The very word "entitlement," so comfortably uttered by **G.I.s**, will have newly embarrassing ring
- Silent's core achievements—**civil rights, sexual liberation, mainstreaming** for the handicapped—not the sort to make them feel entitled to pecuniary reward
- From their perspective, mere acceptance of reward calls into question the sincerity of the original undertaking
- Any Silent doubts will be reinforced by **Boomers**, who will say "No, you're *not* entitled!" if question is ever asked

### Erosion of Political Consensus on Retirement

- Silent ascendance into "young old" age category will begin **fateful erosion of political consensus on federal retirement policy**
- Consensus that warded off all challenge since mid-1960s
- Throughout their lives, Silent have been easy targets for scandals—will not change in 1990s
- As media begin to expose **growing number of affluent Silent retirees** (and ex-officeholders) for alleged abuses of public generosity—stories media would never attempt (and public never accept) about **G.I. retirees**
- Long-term forecasts for retirement and health-care programs will become decidedly less sanguine
- **Old-age benefits will become negotiable**, "on the budget table" in ways unthinkable back in 1970s and 1980s

### Challenges to Silent Retirement Benefits

- Cast as defensive and equipped with libertarian sense of equity, Silent will suggest compromises:
  - Nonpoor members get back **Social Security and Medicare money** they once paid into funds, maybe with little interest, but nothing more
  - **Entitlement programs** moving toward "means testing," targeting benefits for non-needy
  - **Fortune-500 pension plans** that once looked attractive to early retirees will begin eroding in purchasing power
  - **Subsidized health care** will be subject to new triage regulations disfavoring the old
  - **Civil service and military retirees** who can lay no claim to G.I.-style heroism will face new challenges against "double dipping," automatic COLAs, and veterans' benefits for non-service related illnesses
  - **Private pension plans** will face public pressure to reduce enormous (largely unfunded) retiree health-care liabilities
  - **Gifts and estates** will be subject to higher taxes by legislators who will consider Silent wealth less "earned" than the G.I. lastminute
- All this will meet with **little effective resistance from Silent-run elder organizations**, which will back away from aggressive, G.I.-
<!-- p. 393 -->

### Silent Generation's Anxiety About Rewards and Entitlements

- **Eisler's "corpse in the trunk" metaphor**: Anxiety and guilt characterizing the Silent—ability to see drought in sunny weather, anticipate disaster the moment things improve
- No generation has more difficulty enjoying good things or keener antennae for sensing others' needs
- Once the Silent perceive their influence is **generational** and unlikely to be exceeded by their own 13er children, they will feel genuine hurt

### Silent as "Young Old" and Erosion of Retirement Consensus

- High-tech seniors staring at amber monitors wonder if they deserve such a long list of late-in-life rewards
- **The Silent's core achievements** (civil rights, racial liberalism, mainstreaming of the handicapped) are not the sort to make them feel entitled to pecuniary reward
- Mere acceptance of reward calls into question the sincerity of the original undertaking
- **Any Silent doubts will be reinforced by Boomers**: "No, you're *not* entitled!" if the question is ever asked

### Political Challenges to Federal Retirement Policy

- Ascendance of Silent into "young old" age category will begin **fateful erosion of political consensus on federal retirement policy**
- Consensus warded off challenges since the mid-1960s
- Throughout their lives, the Silent have been **easy targets for scandals**—this will not change in the 1990s
- Media beginning to expose **affluent Silent retirees** and ex-officeholders for alleged abuses of public generosity
- Stories the media would never attempt (and public never accept) about **G.I. retirees**
- Long-term forecasts for retirement and health-care programs will become decidedly less sanguine

### Specific Policy Pressures Expected

- **Old-age benefits will become negotiable**, "on the budget table" in ways unthinkable during 1970s and 1980s
- Cast on defensive and equipped with **libertarian sense of equity**, Silent will suggest compromise:
  - Nonpoor members get back Social Security and Medicare money paid in, but nothing more
  - Entitlement programs moving toward **"means testing"**
  - "Greedy Slate" and Fortune-500 pension plans that once looked attractive to early retirees will begin eroding in purchasing power
  - **Subsidized health care** subject to new triage regulations disfavoring the old
  - Civil service and military retirees who can lay no claim to G.I.-style heroism will face new challenges
  - **"Double dipping"**, automatic COLAs, veterans' benefits for non-service related illnesses under pressure
  - Private pension plans face public pressure to reduce enormous (and largely unfunded) retiree health-care liabilities
  - Gifts and estates subject to higher taxes by legislators who will consider **Silent wealth less "earned" than the G.I. facsimile**
- All this will meet with **little effective resistance from Silent-run elder organizations**, which will back away from aggressive G.I.-style advocacy

<!-- p. 394 -->

### Silent Generation as Elders (continued)

- **Silent elders** will reject old-style lobbying, take conciliatory approach to young-to-old transfers (except defending very old G.I.s)
- Elder lobbies will become more **self-doubting, pluralist, other-directed, and compromising**
- Will not share **G.I. instinct for peer-group collegiality**—instead look for social activities that bring **content with youth and adventure**
- Unprecedented number will use time, money, talent to **help others**, at home and overseas
- Recalling **Peace Corps** days, Silent will assemble variety of public-spirited "Senior Corps" to channel elder talent toward **solving social problems**
- **Generous gifts and bequests** will usher in golden age of private philanthropy
- Redirecting **Social Security income to charity** (to own 13er children) will become popular trend among wealthy
- Silent will view automatic "senior citizen" discounts as unnecessary, even unfair—and younger generations will agree
- More reluctant than G.I. elders to say "Read my lips—no new taxes" when private sacrifice needed to meet public need
- Most affluent of living generations may **lead call for greater progressivity in tax structure**

### Silent Elders vs. G.I. Trend

- Reversing G.I. trend toward **collective separation**, new-breed elders want to **stay actively engaged** in increasingly Boom-dominated society
- Postwar trend toward ever-earlier retirement will backtrack
- Silent will **insist on right of 70-year-olds to participate** in world of younger people—remain useful, help others, stay employed if they wish
- Early retirees will feel guilty, idle and **rejoin workplace** in people-oriented service jobs—whether they need money or not
- Visual and print media will see increase in number of old columnists and news anchors, bravely resisting weakening of their generation's pluralist message
- **"Seniors Only" living communities** will become more uncommon and controversial, perhaps even objects of legislative or juridical attack
- Boomers who were perfectly happy when G.I.s chose to separate will see reprehensible **antichild (and anti-Millennial) attitudes** in similar Silent behavior—**most Silent will agree**

### "Senior Citizen" Label Rejected

- Powerful, collegial G.I. name **"senior citizen"** will fit Silent peer personality awkwardly at best
- While perhaps continuing to use the term, Silent will look for ways to **humanize it**, make it more personal and accessible
- Silent will feel less the **senior citizen** than the **senior partner**
- May be attracted to simple noun **"senior"** (more modest term when standing alone, evokes image of **sympathetic upperclassman**)
- Nicknames will be quaintly hip, evoking memories of 1950s and making gentle fun of themselves—perhaps something like **"Oldster," "Granddaddy," or "Old Bopper"**
- Will **camouflage new phase-of-life uncertainty** in rich smile of irony, unconcerned about juniors taking over the mantle of power—and powerless to stop it, anyway

### "Old Bopper" Mindset

- **"Old Bopper" mind-set** will combine denial of age with better-late-

