<!-- p. 392 -->

### Silent Generation in Old Age (continued)

**Consumer behavior and marketing:**
- Silent elders will pursue **never-ending search for catharsis** through lifestyle milestones
- Around year 2000, sociologists will discover unsettling new lifecycle "passage" in mid-sixties
- New-breed elders: thinking, acting, looking young; trying hard against appearing old
- Will keep wardrobes within mainstream fashions, undergo face-lifts and tummy tucks
- **Seniors-only tours** will sharply increase in popularity, supplemented by catering to grandparents with grandchildren
- In company of younger people, Silent elders will: scale mountains, ride rapids, hack through jungles, backpack through deserts, parachute from planes—anything with a little high-death-defying risk
- Will keep ambitious checklists of everything they still want to do—examples: see every great Broadway musical, visit every national park, traverse every continent
- **"Senior circuits"** of aging Silent athletes will gain popularity
- Nostalgia for youth and romance will extend to magazines and film: Elvis Presley and Marilyn Monroe will remain powerful Silent icons
- Aging performers like Everly Brothers or Peter, Paul, and Mary will stay popular well into their old age, with rock and roll replacing the G.I. fox-trot at senior sock hops
- **"Wake up Little Susie, Wake up!"** will reverberate in even the most formal of ballroom settings

**Wealth and economic influence:**
- Elder Silent will be wealthy enough to provide **gold mine for targeted products and services**
- Marketers will tap into them by appealing to their sense of irony, earnest sentimentality, and (especially) their thirst for catharsis
- **Old Boomers** will feel unquenchable yearning to be true individuals, to feel alive, to dabble in slightly juvenile adventures in risk and defiance—even retaining lifelong confidence in expertise and attention to detail
- Will continue to emulate whatever Boomers happen to be doing or feeling
- In electoral politics, Silent will be slow to make up their minds, and more swayed than others by candidates with high name recognition, impressive credentials, and proven management skills
- Will be surface they will delight in zany, iconoclastic rhetoric, yet underneath they will insist on **genial, flexible temperaments**

**Family life and living arrangements:**
- Aging Silent will usher in **renaissance of American extended family**
- More than at any other time in American history, 65-year-olds will have parents still living
- Cannot count on own children to leave home once and for all
- Run the 13er **"boomerang"** child syndrome on fast-forward
- Picture continuing stream of young adults abandoning small urban apartments and returning to large homes of their Silent parents
- Sooner or later, many 13er live-in child will drop the hint, parent will relent, and the **master-bedroom coup d'état** will occur
- Typical G.I. parent, who scrimped long years to afford household comfort, would never give in so easily
- Silent are softer touch—having been empty-nesters rather early, will attach less value to privilege of living alone in big home
- Besides, the Silent will be **culturally compatible with their children in ways the G.I.s were not**
- Around turn of century, these 65-year-old rock-and-rollers will get along just fine

<!-- p. 392 -->

### Silent Generation's Elder Phase: Active Affluence & Risk-Taking

**Lifestyle & Consumer Behavior:**
- Silent will pursue **more-than-ever search for catharsis** in elder years
- Around **year 2000**, sociologists will discover unsettling new lifecycle "passage" in mid-sixties
- New-breed elders try thinking, acting, and looking young; try guard against appearing old
- Will keep wardrobes within mainstream fashions, undergo face-lifts and tummy tucks
- **Seniors-only tours** will sharply in popularity, supplemented by catering to grandparents with grandchildren
- Silent elders will scale mountains, ride rapids, hack through jungles, backpack through deserts, parachute from planes—anything with high risk of death-defying danger
- Will keep ambitious checklists: see every great Broadway musical, visit every national park, traverse every continent
- **"Senior circuits"** of aging Silent athletes will gain popularity
- Nostalgia for youth and romance will extend to magazine and film: Elvis Presley and Marilyn Monroe will remain powerful Silent icons
- Aging performers like **Everly Brothers or Peter, Paul, and Mary** will stay popular well into their old age
- Will rock and roll replacing the G.I. fox-trot at senior sock hops
- **"Wake up Little Susie, Wake up!"** will reverberate in even the most formal of ballroom settings

**Economic Position & Marketing:**
- Elder Silent will be **wealthy enough to provide a gold mine** for targeted products and services
- Marketers will tap into them by appealing to sense of irony, earnest sentimentality, and especially their thirst for catharsis
- **Old Boppers** will feel unquenchable yearning to be true individuals, feel alive, dabble in slightly juvenile adventures in risk and defiance—even retaining lifelong confidence in expertise and attention to detail
- Will continue to emulate whatever Boomers happen to be doing or feeling
- In electoral politics, Silent will be slow to make up their minds, will be swayed than others by candidates with high name recognition, impressive credentials, and proven management skills
- On the surface they will delight in zany, iconoclastic rhetoric, yet underneath they will insist on genial, flexible temperaments

**Family Dynamics & Living Arrangements:**
- Aging Silent will usher in **renaissance of the American extended family**
- More than at any other time in American history, 65-year-olds will have parents still living
- Silent cannot count on their own children to leave home once and for all
- **"Boomerang" child syndrome** on fast-forward, and picture continuing stream of young adults abandoning small urban apartments and returning to large homes of their Silent parents
- Sooner or later, many 13ers will live-in child will drop the hint, the parent will relent, and the master-bedroom **coup d'état** will occur
- Typical G.I. parent, who scrimped long years to afford household comfort, would never give in so easily
- But Silent are a softer touch
- Having been empty-nesters rather early, will attach less value to privilege of living alone in big home
- Besides, the Silent will be **culturally compatible with their children in ways the G.I.s were not**
- Around turn of century, these 65-year-old rock-and-rollers will get along just fine

<!-- p. 396 -->

### Silent Generation in Elderhood (continued)

**Personal and Family Life:**
- **Silent elders** will help nurture **new generation of children** with their 35-year-old post-punk children
- Recognize they performed this task "too young the first time around"
- Will professionalize the "art" of grandparenthood and sex, making it subject of countless books, films, plays, songs, paintings
- Will professionalize in seminars, conferences, and global conversations

**Atonement for Past Mistakes:**
- See in extended family life a measure of atonement for damage done to families during **G.I. collectivism** and Boom Awakening years
- Will regret hurried and unprotected upbringing, but while Silent confess easily to mistakes, "they are loath to admit that any mistake is final"
- Like **John Crittenden** or **John Dewey**, will never quit trying to set things right
- In 1990s and beyond, generous help to adult children will offer another chance to do just that

**Late-Life Complexity:**
- Personal lives of **Old Boppers** more complicated than G.I.s
- "Swinging" will occasionally infuriate their juniors
- Like **William Byrd II**, will still "play the fool" in late sixties and beyond, succumb to sexual dalliances and experimental urges
- Always drawn to emotional complexity of life and interested in calm lives of younger people
- Even when health fails, will be reluctant to enter long-term-care facility
- Physical decline will bring surge in at-home elder care, mostly financed by Silent themselves
- Whatever long-term-care subsidies G.I.s win in early 1990s will not be extended to Silent elders above poverty line

**Political and Public Life:**
- Will spend lifetime taking cues by looking up and down age ladder
- In youth, looked entirely up; in old age, will look entirely down
- In government, aging Silent leaders will offer "prayer hues of public administration," deferring rather than solving core problems, only occasionally taking breakaway risk
- Hobbled by locked-in **G.I. artifacts**—budget deficits, low marginal tax rates, uncancellable defense projects, entitlements programs running on autopilot
- Silent will blame political indecisiveness on circumstances supposedly beyond their control
- Like the **Compromiser "Great Triumvirate,"** they will prefer to ameliorate old policies rather than start over from scratch
- Whatever the problem, approach will focus on better process (new budget amendment, new incentive tax scheme, new blue-ribbon commission) rather than on ultimate desired outcome
- To Boom critics, Silent leaders will reply that world is complicated and aggressive solutions are premature—admitting "at the same time, that all points of view must be considered"

**Historical Assessment:**
- Silent seem fated to pass from national power with shortest and weakest tenure since **Enlightener** days of **Alexander Spotswood**

<!-- p. 396 -->

### Silent Generation in Extended Family Life

- **Silent** will see extended family life as atonement for damage they caused through individualistic excess during **Boom Awakening** years
- Many will regret hurried/unprotected upbringing they gave **13ers**, but will confess mistakes reluctantly like **John Crittenden** or **John Dewey** - loath to admit finality, never quit trying to set things right
- In 1990s and beyond, generous support for adult children will offer another chance to do what they missed

### Silent as Old Boppers

- Personal lives of **Old Boppers** more complicated than current **G.I.** associations
- "Swinging" will occasionally infuriate juniors; Silent still "play the fool" in late sixties/beyond, succumb to sexual dalliances and experimental urges
- Always drawn to emotional complexity of life, interested in edgy lives of younger people
- Even when frail health fails, will be reluctant to enter long-term-care facility
- Physical decline will bring surge in at-home elder care, mostly financed by Silent themselves
- Long-term-care subsidies the **G.I.s** won in early 1990s will not be extended to **Silent** elders above poverty line

### Silent Leadership Style: Process Over Outcomes

- Will spend lifetime taking cues by looking up and down age ladder
- **In youth**: looked entirely up; **in old age**: will look entirely down
- Aging **Silent** leaders will offer grayer hues of public administration, deferring rather than solving core problems, only occasionally taking breakaway risk
- Hobbled by locked-in **G.I.** artifacts: budget deficits, low marginal tax rates, uncancellable defense projects, entitlements programs running on autopilot
- Silent will blame political indecisiveness on circumstances supposedly beyond control
- Like **Compromise "Great Triumvirate"**: prefer ameliorating old policies rather than starting over from scratch
- **Approach focuses on better process** (new budget amendment, incentive tax scheme, blue-ribbon commission) rather than ultimate desired outcome
- **To Boom critics**: Silent leaders reply world is complicated, aggressive solutions are premature - admitting at same time that all points of view must be considered

### Shortest National Power Tenure

- Silent seem fated to pass from national power with shortest and weakest tenure since **Enlightener** days of **Alexander Spotswood**

<!-- p. 397 -->

### Silent Generation's Political Future

**Presidential prospects**: With **Boomers** dominating White House and House Republican succession lines, and zero for six in Presidential campaigns since 1968, **Silent** candidates might end up "zero for nine or ten"
- History shows **Adaptive generation** gets best chance to produce charismatic leader (e.g., **Andrew Jackson**, **Theodore Roosevelt**, **Robert Kennedy**, **Martin Luther King, Jr.**) while entering midlife, not while old age

**Silent political strategy**: To win Presidency, Silent would need to:
- Forget old **G.I.-style New Deal coalition**
- Replace cult of expertise with **values-laden campaign style of the Boom**
- Show interest in religion, demanding stern punishment for moral miscreants, displaying anger in public, projecting emphatic sense of community
- **Silent women** may do better than their male peers in presenting such themes

**Best chance for Silent candidates**: If American political system feels either "on hold" or deadlocked
- The more quickly a sense of social or economic emergency arises, the less likely Silent will be able to slow their slide from power

### Congressional Representation Decline

**Silent share of congressmen and governors**:
- Peaked at **68 percent in 1983**
- Declining gradually ever since to **65 percent in 1989**
- Following the usual pattern, will accelerate during mid-1990s
- Will leave Silent with **no more than a 35 percent share after the year-2000 election**

**Silent officeholders' vulnerability**: May fall victim to **Boomer attacks on professionalism**, or alienated **13er mood**, or their own self-doubts—marking abrupt end to enormous electoral success Silent incumbents have enjoyed in recent years

### Silent Elders' Future Role

**Mixed mind about Boom-led social and political trends**: Silent elders will:
- Complain about **Boomers** and **13ers** dismantling their procedural solutions for civil rights
- Fear for the wounded egos of heavily chaperoned **Millennial children**
- Try to calm inner passion of Boomers and lend sensitivity to Boomer crusades
- Assert they are more "liberal" than younger generations—who will find Silent sentimentality and technobabble increasingly rococo

**Similarities to past Adaptive generations**:
- Like aging **Enlighteners**: crypto-ish Silent elite will dislike rising trend toward mean-spirited public life
- Like aging **Compromisers**: will prefer conciliation over crisis
- Like aging **Progressives**: will trust electoral or judicial or legislative process over principle
- **Like all three**: will be mostly ignored

### Silent as Biggest Worriers

As **Inner-Driven era** ends, Silent will age into **America's biggest worriers about the future**—not exactly pessimists (Silent believe there's always a second chance), just worriers

**Never collectively powerful**: Silent have never been and never will be collectively powerful, but will continue enriching others with **gentler kind of endowment**

**Unique Silent capacity**: Until next **Adaptive generation** comes of age (in 2010s), no other generation will press the case for:
- **Other-directed social compassion**
- **Pluralism**
- **Sympathy for the underdog and procedural fairness**
- **Intergenerational understanding**

**Silent can mediate the upcoming cultural**
<!-- p. 397 -->

