### Boomer Voting Patterns and Political Behavior

- **Boomer numerical dominance** peaked in late 1970s during their **pre-yuppie** political detachment phase
- Voting edge eroded in 1980s and will continue declining through successive decades
- By 1990, **13ers outnumber Boomers by 14 percent** in eligible voter population
- Starting 1996, 13ers will eclipse Boomers in raw voting clout
- Around **2016**, Boom generation will slip behind **Millennial generation** as largest cohort of eligible voters

### Generational Continuity vs. Change

- While Boomer fiftysomethings/seventysomethings may repeat teen/twenties behavior patterns, their children would be the **first American generation** NOT to do so
- Boomers will always engage with 1960s music, Vietnam debates, generational "lessons" and watershed moments
- **All generations are steered by coming-of-age experiences**, but none returns there
- The **celebrated Boomer trek from hippie to yuppie** leads to a memorable trajectory, but their children's path will differ

### Entering Midlife in an Inner-Driven Era (1991-2003)

#### Reassessing the Awakening Era

- In early 1990s, some Boomers will look back on their **awakening as a moment of generational trajectory**, propelling them toward a collective destiny
- Others will express **open contempt** for such pretension
- All Boomers will assert their midlife values, examining what the 1960s-70s awakening **did and did not accomplish**—leading to **growing scrutiny**
- Will trigger **stormy peer-on-peer invective** among themselves
- Following script of previous inner-driven eras: Boomers now entering midlife, dating back to first charges and countercharges of **"hypocrisy"** traded among **Winthrop's small wilderness gathering** in 1640s

#### 1990s Boomer Trends

- Fuller development of several **important Boomer trends** from late 1980s
- Though **yuppies** will still be present, **Boomer perfectionism** will express itself less in personal fulfillment, more in **realm of social virtue**
- **Boom politics** becomes more **intensely values-laden**
- Missionaries in their forties and fifties: Boomers grow **disagreeably pompous, intolerant, uncompromising, snoopy, and exacting** of others
- Simultaneously become more **dutiful, principled, and demanding of themselves**

#### End of Political Remission

- The **Boom's era of political remission** will end sometime in 1990s, perhaps around departure of **last G.I. President**
- "**Generational politics**" touted over last two decades will finally start bearing results
- Results will be linked to **inner-world, not outer-world** ends
- Despite current reputation for personal selfishness, **Boomers will not mobilize around appeals to collective self-interest**—for example, around tax, labor, or


<!-- p. 399 -->

### Boomer Voting Patterns and Political Behavior

- Boomers' political edge in raw numbers is **flat-out mistaken**
- Greatest numerical edge occurred in late 1970s, around pre-yuppie peak of political detachment
- Edge shrank gradually in 1980s and will erode further with each successive decade
- In 1990, 13ers outnumbered Boomers by 14 percent
- Starting in 1996, 13ers will eclipse Boomers in raw voting clout
- Around 2016, Boom will slip behind the **Millennials** and become America's third-largest generation of eligible voters

### Generational Continuity vs. Repetition

- Second point: if Boomer fiftysomethings or seventysomethings repeat the behavior pattern of their teens or thirties, theirs would be the first **American generation** ever to do so
- Boomers will always listen to 1960s music, debate the "lessons" of **Vietnam**, and show a weakness for granola and mineral water
- **But**: while all generations are steered by their coming-of-age experiences, none returns there
- History suggests the celebrated Boomer trek from **hippie to yuppie** will lead to someplace still different—someplace their heirs will find far more memorable

### Entering Midlife in an Inner-Driven Era (1991-2003)

- In early 1990s, some Boomers will look back upon their awakening as a moment of generational trajectory, propelling them on a path of collective destiny
- Others will express open contempt for any such pretension
- As all Boomers assert their midlife values, they will subject their coming-of-age awakening to **growing scrutiny**
- Along with scrutiny will come stormy **peer-on-peer invective**
- Boomers should not be surprised to see this happen—they are following the script of every prior **Idealist generation** entering midlife, dating back to first charges and countercharges of "hypocrisy" traded among **Winthrop's small wilderness gathering** in the 1640s

### Boomer Trends in the 1990s

- 1990s will bring fuller development to several important Boomer trends of late 1980s
- Though yuppies will still be around, **Boomer perfectionism** will begin to express itself less in the realm of personal fulfillment than in the realm of **social virtue**
- **Boom politics** will become more intensely values-laden
- Like Missionaries in their forties and fifties, Boomers will grow increasingly:
  - Pompous
  - Intolerant
  - Uncompromising
  - Snoopy
  - Exacting of others
- At same time, they will become more dutiful, principled, and demanding of themselves

### End of Political Remission

- The Boom's era of **political remission** will end sometime in the 1990s, perhaps around the time the last **G.I. President** departs
- The "generational politics" touted by so many over the last two decades will finally start bearing results
- But it will be linked to **inner-world**, not outer-world, ends
- Notwithstanding their current reputation for personal selfishness, Boomers will not mobilize around appeals to **collective self-interest**—for example, around tax, labor, or
<!-- p. 400 -->

### Boomers' Future Political and Institutional Influence

- **Boomer retirement approach**: Will seek "lofty commitments on matters of principle" rather than material security
- Their **moral perfectionism** will seem whiny and mean-spirited to other generations, even hypocritical in context of their past
- Will reflect a "growing generational commitment to solve the unsolved—an attitude that will help revitalize a sense of national community"

### Boomer Assumption of Power (1990s-2000s)

- **Rising institutional control**: Growing share of school districts, state legislatures, corporations will emerge "entirely retooled around Boom values"
- **13ers marginalized**: Will seem "almost Mesozoic in their pristine G.I.-ness or (more often) their fuzzy Silentized G.I.-ness"
- **Path to leadership**: Following Idealist generational pattern, Boomers will work way up to most powerful bodies of national leadership
- **Congressional expansion**: Share of Congress and governorships (21% at time of writing) will expand rapidly in mid-1990s and probably become a plurality by 1996 election
- **Peak leadership timing**: If following Missionary pattern, will reach lifetime peak share of national leadership around 2025, **62 years after birth of first cohort**

### Boomer-Retooled Institutions

- Will **scrap Silent preoccupations** (budget minutiae, "untouchable" entitlements)
- Will **attack political arrangements**: sugar cartel to sweetheart defense contracts recently considered "untouchable"
- **Policy shift anticipated**: May see advantage in:
  - Taxes on consumption
  - Regulation on speculative investment and pleasure-seeking leisure
  - Public intrusions into others' private lives
- **Values-driven advocacy**: Regional planning and consumer groups will assert ethical values about individual self-interest
- **Anti-drug and pro-environmental alliance** may emerge as nation's most potent lobby at all levels

### Boomers and the Abortion Debate

- As Boomers move beyond procreation age and **equate sexual freedom with 13er license**, balance of power in abortion debate may shift
- Growing Boom feminism may shift focus away from self toward progeny
- May acquire view of **aging Transcendental Susan B. Anthony**: abortion is "degrading to women" because it encourages them to "treat our children as property to be disposed of"
- **Predicted parallel**: A decade of abortion prohibition could be for Boomers what alcohol prohibition was for Missionaries

### Electoral Strategy and Political Style

- **Righteous causes** Boomers support will remain hard sell for political/commercial marketers
- **Voting booth behavior**: Fiftyish Boomers will show perversity of fiftyish Silent—more independence, less niceness
- Will disdain **party allegiances**, argue at fund-raisers, hang up on telemarketers
- Generally take far less interest in flesh-and-blood candidates than in abstract issues
- **Required political virtues** to reach them: candor, simplicity, moral rectitude, serenity of soul

<!-- p. 400 -->

### Boomers' Approach to Retirement and Moral Commitments

- **Boomers will prioritize principle over financial security in retirement**
  - Will seek "lofty commitments on matters of principle" rather than focusing on retirement issues
  - Their moral perfectionism will seem "whiny, mean-spirited, even hypocritical" to other generations
  - Will reflect a growing generational commitment to solve unresolved national problems
  - This attitude will help revitalize a sense of **national community**

### Boomers Rising to Power (1990s-2005)

- **Growing interest in real-world institutions will assume new seriousness** in the 1990s
  - Schools, legislatures, and corporations will emerge "entirely retooled around Boom values"
  - Computer technology will seem outdated; their **fuzzy Silentzed G.I.-ness** will be replaced by **pristine G.I. ethos**
  - Following path of every other **Idealist generation**, Boomers will begin with local and grassroots institutions and work up to most powerful national leadership bodies

- **Boomers' share of Congress and governorships**
  - Currently 21 percent (as of writing)
  - Will expand rapidly in mid-1990s
  - Will probably become plurality following 1994 or 1996 election

- **Peak leadership timeline**: If Boomers follow the **Missionary pattern**, they will reach lifetime peak share of national leadership around 2005, just as **Inner-Driven era is ending** (sixty-two years after birth of first cohort)

### Boomer-Retooled Institutions

- **Institutions will grow teeth** with each step forward
- Will scrap **Silent pieties** regarding budget issues, "untouchability" of programs, and attack political arrangements
  - Examples: sugar cartel to sweetheart defense contracts
  - Have seemed impenetrable in recent decades

- **Seeing new virtue in community**: May see advantage in:
  - Taxes (on consumption)
  - Regulation (on speculative investment and pleasure-seeking leisure)
  - Public intrusions into private lives

- **Regional planning and consumer groups** will propel causes by asserting **ethical values** about individual self-interest
- **Antiaging and pro-environmental alliance** may emerge as nation's most potent lobby at all levels of government

### Boomers and Social Issues

- As Boomers move beyond procreation age and equate sexual freedom with **13er license**, abortion debate power balance may shift
- May turn toward **evangelical last-wavers**
- Growing numbers of Boom feminists may shift focus away from self and toward progeny
- May acquire view of aging **Transcendental Susan B. Anthony**: abortion is "degrading to women" because it encourages them to "treat our children as property to be disposed of"
- A **decade of abortion prohibition** could be for Boomers what a decade of alcohol prohibition was for Missionaries

### Political Behavior and Values

- **Whatever righteous causes Boomers pursue will remain hard sell for political and commercial marketers**
- At voting booth, **fiftyish Boomers will show all perversity of fiftyish Silent**
  - More independence and less niceness
  - Will disdain party allegiances, argue at fund-raisers, hang up on telemarketers
  - Take far less interest in flesh-and-blood candidates than in abstract issues

- To reach Boomers, aspiring politicians must demonstrate:
  - **Candor**
  - **Simplicity**
  - **Moral rectitude**
  - **Serenity of soul**

<!-- p. 401 -->

### Boomer Leadership and Corporate Culture

- **Boomer-run corporations** will focus on "bottom line" principles about what companies should mean to employees, customers, and neighbors
- Like **Henry Ford**, Boomer manager-owners will turn firms into agents of public and private virtue
- Well-functioning companies will downsize staffs, defer dividends, shift marketing strategies to achieve values-related goals
- Managerial style will strike **13ers** as humorless, even "puritanical" in return for moral authority
- Boom executives will accept **narrowed pay gap** between themselves and their workers

### Midlife Boom Elite Characteristics

- In contrast to credentialed Silent careerists, **midlife Boom elite** will have highly eclectic backgrounds
- Growing number of **nonlawyers** will enter politics; **non-Ph.D.s** publish in academic journals; **nonpriests** give sermons; even non-doctors give medical advice
- Most promising Boomer politicians (and Presidential candidates) will spring from outside the ranks of law, government, and party politics
- **Boom elite will assiduously maintain individual identities apart from institutions**
- Many Boomers will work for a corporation and have a business (or profit-making hobby) on the side
- **Boomer high-tech home offices** will have same individuating effect on American workplace that the **Missionaries' automobiles** had on the American community

### Career Patterns and Workplace Dynamics

- Feeling in control of their choices, **midlifers will make career switches easily**
- Turnover will rise in top-level jobs
- In Congress, resignations over matters of principle will become more common
- **Silent-style PACs** are weaker, and name recognition and incumbency will lose much of their present-day advantage

### Cultural and Social Trends

- Throughout the top echelons of government and business, interest in philosophy, literature, and the arts will rise
- Interest in "how-to" manuals will fall
- **Midlife Boomers** will concentrate less on infusing perfectionism into their personal lives (today's effete yuppie stereotype) and more on infusing it into their family and public lives
- Will openly insist on enforcing a new sense of **local (and, gradually, national) community**
- Will battle against vestiges of Silent-style pluralism and rights-protected fairness
- Many of today's media experts are predicting that the official "**Millennial**"—**the year 2000**—will trigger a tidal outpouring of **Aquarian weirdness** from fiftyish Boomers, from bacchanals serving homemade wine and Yugoslavian brie to Vedic mantras hummed on
<!-- p. 401 -->

### Boomer Marketing and Consumer Behavior

- Product marketers must adopt appealing, ministerial air rather than expert polish
- Boomers seek **high purpose** in purchases: quality over quantity, uniqueness over comfort, inner satisfaction over outer popularity
- Perfect Boomer products allow **gesture of austerity** while expressing their defiance of material urges—e.g., mail-order and home-delivery services avoiding shopping

### Boomer Corporate Management Style

- **Boomer-run corporations** focus relentlessly on "bottom line"—not profits, but **principles** about what companies should mean to employees, customers, neighbors
- Like **Henry Ford**, Boomer manager-owners turn firms into **agents of public and private virtue**
- Well-performing companies will **downsize staffs**, defer dividends, shift marketing to achieve values-related goals
- **Managerial style** strikes 13ers as ruthless, even "puritanical"—prepares Boom executives to accept **narrowed pay gap** between themselves and workers

### Midlife Boom Elite Characteristics

- **Silent careerists** vs. **midlife Boom elite**: highly eclectic backgrounds
- Growing number of **nonlawyers** enter politics, non-Ph.D.s publish in academic journals, nonpriests give sermons, even-nondoctors give medical advice
- Most promising Boomer politicians (and Presidential candidates) emerge from **outside the ranks** of law, government, party politics
- Boom elite assiduously **maintain individual identities apart from institutions**
- Many will work for corporation **and** have business (or profit-making hobby) on the side
- **Boomers' high-tech home offices** have same individuating effect as Missionaries' automobiles had on the American community

### Boomer Career Patterns

- **Feeling in control of choices**, midlifers make career switches easily
- **Turnover rises** in top-level jobs
- In Congress, resignations over **matters of principle** become more common
- **Silent-style PACs** will weaken, and **name recognition and incumbency** lose present-day advantage
- Throughout top echelons of government and business, **interest in philosophy, literature, and the arts will rise**—interest in "how-to" manuals will fall

### Midlife Boomer Personal and Social Values

- Concentrate less on **infusing perfectionism** into personal lives (today's effete yuppie stereotype)
- More on **infusing it into family and public lives**
- Openly insist on enforcing **new sense of local (and, gradually, national) community**
- Battle against vestiges of **Silent-style pluralism** and **rights-protected fairness**
- Many media experts predict official **"Millennial"—the year 2000**—will trigger **tidal outpouring of Aquarian weirdness** from fiftyish Boomers, from bacchanals serving homemade wine and Yugoslavian brie to Vedic mantras hummed on

<!-- p. 402 -->

### Boomers Entering Elderhood (Around 2000)

- **Boomers** will settle in as a more cerebral "older" generation
- Will seek the classic and the enduring over the faddishly popular
- Will challenge **sex, profanity, and violence in the media**—and will get results
- Like all **Idealist** generations entering midlife, Boomers will mount a relentless attack on all forms of **substance abuse**
- Will strike blow after blow against **tobacco**—taxing, restricting, and humiliating anyone involved in its production and use
- The **alcohol industry** can expect its sternest challenge since **Prohibition**
- The **firearms industry** will fare better thanks to the fact that the Boom will not dislike violence per se, just *meaningless* (read: "13er") violence
- Boom opinions will be nitpicked (but emulated) by the **Silent**, resented (but coped with) by the **13th**

### Boomer Civic and Religious Leadership

- **Boomer civic and religious leaders** will reestablish moral principles and police the world of youth activities with far greater attention to ends than means
- Sharing the Boom cult of community, the midlife black elite will assert moral leadership in troubled neighborhoods that (in their view) need them
- **Inner-city religious leaders** will become sharply intolerant of youth misbehavior
- The **black Boom elite** will back away from procedural mechanisms like affirmative action—and will instead force younger people to build "character" and accept more responsibility for their own condition
- When black Boomers call attention to **white racism**, their purpose will not be (as it was for Progressives and Silent) to galvanize the white establishment to act, but rather (as it was for Transcendentals and Missionaries) to galvanize the **black community to act on its own**
- In the tradition of **Frederick Douglass** and **W.E.B. DuBois**, black Boomers may ultimately make their most enduring contributions in letters and cultural leadership

### Women Entering Public Life

- Like prior Idealist generations, the Boom will produce an **explosion of women into public life**
- By the year 2000, midlife women will surge into boardrooms, media anchor booths, university presidencies, and Congress—and will begin making plausible runs for the **White House**
- Aging Boom women may see in their own peers the apogee of their lifelong struggle for **equality with men**

<!-- p. 402 -->

### Boomer Elderhood: Cultural and Political Leadership (Year 2000 and Beyond)

**Boomers as "Older" Generation Around 2000**
- Will settle into cerebral "older" generation role, seeking classics and faddishly popular culture
- Challenge sex, profanity, and violence in media—achieving results similar to earlier **Idealist generations**
- Mount relentless attack on all forms of **substance abuse**
- Strike blow after blow against tobacco—taxing, restricting, humiliating those involved in production and use
- **Alcohol industry** expected to face sternest challenge since **Prohibition**
- Firearms industry will benefit from Boomers not disliking guns per se, but **criticizing violence**
- Boom opinions will be nitpicked but emulated by **Silent**, resented but coped with by **13th generation**

**Moral Leadership and Social Control**
- Boomer civic and religious leaders will reestablish **moral principles** and police youth activities with greater attention to ends than means
- Share Boom cult of community, the **midlife black elite** will assert moral leadership in troubled neighborhoods they see as needing them
- **Inner-city religious leaders** become sharply intolerant of youth misbehavior
- Black Boom elite will back away from **procedural mechanisms** like affirmative action
- Instead force younger people to build "character" and accept more **responsibility for their own condition**
- When black Boomers call attention to white racism, purpose will be to galvanize the **black community** to act on its own
- Not (as it was for Progressives and Silent) to galvanize white establishment to act
- Black Boomers may make their most enduring contributions in letters and **cultural leadership**, following tradition of **Frederick Douglass** and **W.E.B. DuBois**

**Women's Leadership Ascendancy**
- Like prior **Idealist generations**, Boom will produce explosion of women into public life by year 2000
- Midlife women will surge into boardrooms, media anchor booths, university presidencies, and **Congress**
- Begin making plausible runs for the **White House**
- Aging Boom women may see in their peers the apogee of their lifelong struggle for **equality with men**

<!-- p. 403 -->

### Boomer Feminism and Social Battles

- Like **Lucy Stone** and **Elizabeth Cady Stanton**, Boomer women will rage against younger generations abandoning feminist causes, rewidening sex role distinctions, and pushing women back toward the pedestal of family life

### Criminal Justice and Penology

- Boomer judgmentalism will land heavily on the **criminal justice system**
- Toward the **Silent**, middle Boomers will find it easier to condemn individuals and harder to condemn "society"—a word that for them will mean "Boom society," whereas for the Silent it meant "G.I. society"
- Boomers will define new crimes, from limitations on freedom of speech to new vagrancy statutes for panhandlers who refuse to live in austere shelters
- Criminal juries will be unrelievedly harsh, appeals shortened, sentences lengthened, parole boards weakened, prison life regimented
- Worst offenders executed with a **grim efficiency not seen since the stern tenure of Missionary judges**
- Boomers will develop new **"shaming" approaches** to punishment, emphasizing confession, humiliation, and personal reform where the Silent always thought it fairer to stick to rules
- This will be a sore point for **13ers**, destined to become the leading objects of the harsh new Boom penology

### Tort Law and Personal Injury

- Civil law: Boom judges will show new **sternness**
- Inquiring into culpability rather than "deep pockets," they will be more inclined to grant "punitive" damages than to compensate for pain and suffering
- Litigation will be streamlined and made less costly—and more final
- **Private industry will treat insurance assets as community resources** and limit plaintiffs to stingier awards
- A Boomer jury will resist making the community pick up the tab where it deems an individual to be at fault

### Sexual Behavior and Family Values

- As demanding as this generation will be of others, the Boom will be no less demanding of its own members
- **Grumpy midlifers** will frown on nontraditional sexual behavior, especially where it appears to threaten the family
- **Divorce will become more stigmatic**
- Boomers will not tolerate impure behavior in public life, and will expiate their own youthful excesses through the occasional pillaging of public figures with hippeish pasts
- Those who persist in **Awakening era behavior patterns** deep into midlife (in the mold of the wayfaring Transcendentals **John Humphrey Noyes** and **Henry Ward Beecher**) will suffer the opprobrium of their peers

### Political Disillusionment

- Just as the **Transcendental elite** disdained **Millard Fillmore** and the **Missionary elite** ignored **Warren Harding**, Boomers may well be disappointed with their first cadre to achieve national political prominence
- Their collective power will be stymied by high individual self-esteem (the notion that "I" could do better than anybody who might be on the ballot)
- The "debunkers"—the Boom's Mencken-like challengers from within—will chip away at any early effort to energize the generation into an aggressive political consensus

### Aging and Acceptance

- As Boomers pass through their forties and fifties, **two trends bear watching**:
  1. The **grace with which they accept their advancing years**

