## Completing the Millennial Cycle (continued)

### Boomer Aging and Generational Tensions

- **Boomers** have largely ignored the aging process—reflects spiritual/cerebral focus over physical, plus desire to remain "forever the youngish generation"
- Risk: If **Boomers** cling to youth-fixated narcissism into forties and fifties, **America** will face trouble
- When **Silent** emulated mannerisms of youth, **Boomers** felt bolstered; when older generation has higher collective self-esteem, any midlife "fountain of youth" pose threatens social role of rising adults
- If **fiftyish Boomers** try to look and act thirty, they will endanger effective late-in-life partnership with **13ers** and risk any later crisis turning out badly
- Historical parallel: Best relationships between midlife **Idealists** and rising-adult **Reactives** (**Landon Carter** with **George Washington**, or **Gertrude Stein** with **Ernest Hemingway**) featured **Idealists** who played the repository of culture, reminder of stable values—not the youthful sprite
- Like **Bradstreet, Franklin, Longfellow, or Sandburg**, **Idealist** generations have capacity to age elegantly, in their own eyes and others'

### Second Trend: Boomer Factional Splits

- Watch for strength and behavior of midlife **Boomer** factions, especially split between **New Age** (modernist) and **evangelical** (traditionalist) camps
- Major 1980s-era battles focused on **abortion** and **sex education**
- The search for a **Boom values consensus** will hinge on whether modernism or traditionalism emanates from generation's better-off first-wavers and worse-off last-wavers
- Further widening of economic gap will aggravate values conflicts
- **Boom** may split along geographical lines—urban, bicoastal **New Agers** squaring off against heartland **evangelicals**
- Could prompt talk of **regional secessions**
- If **Transcendentals** demonstrated how sectionalism can rapidly grow into implacable hatred, **Puritans, Awakeners, and Missionaries** proved that an **Idealist** generation, however fragmented early in life, retains capacity to find common principle in times of approaching crisis
- If **Boomers** unify, the initial evidence will be the coexistence of divergent values in the same communities, and emergence of new and seemingly odd alliances like **Missionaries'** pre–World War I "reform trinity" of **fundamentalists, feminists, and western agrarians**
- If **Boomers** reach a midlife consensus supporting cleanup of the **Millennial** child's world, that will bode well for the decades to follow

