- Organized fleetingly in **1989**, this mock-
<!-- p. 413 -->

### 13ers Economic and Cultural Outlook (continued)

- **13ers** will face workplace challenges as most expendable employees, needing to show **bottom-line results** rather than just promise
- In contrast to 1950s-era rising **Silent**, many 13ers will struggle to maintain the quality of life they enjoyed as adolescents
- Those from affluent families will experience "**boomerang**" back to parental homes, dragging out child-era dependency
- Harder-pressed families risk falling into **unpropertied poverty**
- As year 2000 approaches, worries of circa-1990 youth will crystallize into **bleak adult reality**: Theirs may be America's first generation since the **Gilded** to reach age 40 with lower standard of living than their parents had at same age

### Market Shocks and Generational Reactions

- Setbacks will send shock waves through most market-oriented rising generation since circa-1920 **Lost**
- Unlike **Lost** and **Boom**, 13er self-esteem rests heavily on hopes for economic success—effect confirmed by countless youth polls over past decade
- Once perceiving themselves failing in the marketplace and continuing criticism of their cultural and moral deficiencies, 13ers likely to react in same hard-bitten manner as the **Lost** did when they encountered the **Missionary** vice squads
- Many will quietly blame themselves; others will lash out against midlife **Boomers**, who will remain contemptuous of 13er ideals and aspirations (stark contrast with how rising-adult Boomers were treated by then-midlife elders)
- **Boomers** standing in the way of jobs, pay, and promotions will require 13ers to prove themselves in **hotly contested marketplace**—in effect, forcing them to move in what Boomers consider the "wrong" direction to survive
- The Boom's midlife quest to impose moral judgments on grown-up **Breakfast Clubbers** will strike a growing chorus of 30-year-olds as pitiless and **Scrooge-like**

### Cultural Alienation and Generation Gap

- Once alienation sets in, 13ers will accentuate behavior patterns that today strike older generations as frenetic, soulless, and physically shocking—confirming elder judgments that this is truly a "**wasted**" generation
- **Thirteeners** will put their own stamp on American mood: no mass movements or organized plans; instead, they will burst forth with a **hedonistic cross-culture** that will look, taste, smell, sound, and feel **anti-Boom**
- Will be defiantly noncerebral, probing the physical devil where the like-aged Boom once probed the **spiritual sublime**
- Seeking pleasure where next-elders once sought **beatitude**; evoking black prankishness of Halloween where hippie culture once evoked spring rainbow
- Young novelists, filmmakers, songwriters, and columnists will produce works that seem interesting if puzzling to aging **Silent**, wholly inarticulate to **Boomers**, and keenly expressive to 13ers
- Clash of **jaundiced rising adults** with **righteous midlifers** will resemble the 1920s—not the 1960s

### Professional Athletics as Cultural Bellwether

- By late 1990s, **professional athletics** will offer exaggerated example of what will be happening to 13ers throughout economy and culture
<!-- p. 412 -->

