<!-- p. 414 -->

### 13er Economic Landscape and Career Paths

- Economy will be **market-driven and disconnected from organized labor bargaining power**
- **Year-to-year results rewarded more than lifetime achievement**
- Stars who "win, show Ruthian bravado, and fill arenas" will make fantastic sums (enhanced by international bidding)
- Nonstar journeymen will lose ground and attract little public sympathy when they fail
- **Fun in sports will have a brassy quality**, more akin to pure entertainment than civic ritual
- Boomers will view 13er athletes as gladiators and pointedly urge Millennial children to look elsewhere for role models

### Economic Survival Strategies

- Throughout the economy, **13er preoccupation will be "I need"** — personal economic survival
- Clearest path to success: **elder-led institutions and strike out on their own**
- Will seek **market niches where quick deals matter more than big words**
- Will take care of tasks Boomers find distasteful but useful (delivery services, solid waste disposal)
- Such businesses will bring fortunes to a lucky few, most participants will be poorly paid
- Looking for **lightning strike at success**, 13ers will dart from job to job
- **Labor mobility will discourage employers from investing in job training or offering pensions to new hires**

### International Economic Frontier

- International marketplace will provide this generation's **most promising economic frontier**
- Way to take advantage of **underappreciated linguistic and computer skills**
- Young entrepreneurs will engage in **global business activities** that look unpatriotic, opportunist, or traitorous
- Many will **seek their fortune in service of America's creditors**, helping them purchase, manage, or liquidate American assets
- Lucrative opportunities may arise in nations with fledgling capitalist economies (fast food, fashion, entertainment)
- Boomers will regard video stores in Prague as symptom of decadence, Silent will view despairingly
- Contrast with Boomer **Peace Corps days teaching English to Nigerians** vs. young McDonald's employees teaching Hamburger 101 to Muscovites

### Career and Professional Values

- 13ers will never be widely attracted to **public service or the nurturing professions** (teaching, medicine, ministry) in manner of G.I.s, Silent, or Boom
- Instead, whatever careers chosen, **they will aim for opportunities with a bottom line**
- Their **economic realism will strike many elders as unfeeling, selfish, even reactionary**
- Over time, 13ers will shrug off these complaints
- Like all rising-adult Reactives before them, they will see themselves as **nomads driven by necessity** in a world whose economic harshness is not their fault

### Skepticism and Response to New Opportunities

- Even as they scramble after new opportunities, 13ers will **react with skepticism to world events elders hail as promoting human freedom**
- Any euphoria of elder Silent over "breaking down barriers" will remind them of their chaotic childhood—something that felt good to every generation but their own
- If chaos brings new ethnic or economic unrest leading to conflict, it will be their job, not their elders', to fight any war necessary to clean up the mess left behind
- The sort of **"modern war"** (as Hemingway put it) in which
<!-- p. 413 -->

