- 13ers will react with **skepticism to world events** that elders hail as promoting human freedom
- Any euphoria of elder Silent over "breaking down barriers" will remind them of their **chaotic childhood**—something that felt good to every generation but their own
- If chaos brings new ethnic or economic unrest, and if that leads to conflict, **it will be their job, not their elders'**, to fight any war necessary to clean up the mess left behind
- The sort of **"modern war"** (as Hemingway put it) in which

<!-- p. 415 -->

### 13er Generation: Social and Cultural Challenges

**Social alienation and criticism:**
- Any homecoming celebration for **13er soldiers** will be tinged with elder criticism, heightening feelings of alienation
- 13ers bear a major share of the burden for economic or social transitions, but won't be easily suckered
- Like the **"Don't Tread on Me" Liberty of the 1760s**, life's hard knocks will have taught these 30-year-olds to stay away from complicated abstractions of aging Silent and high-minded Boomers

**Political trajectory:**
- As Boom rises to power, 13er voters will turn even more antigovernment than today's Boomers
- Rather than endorsing global crusades, 13ers will turn toward **isolationism**
- Like the **1920s-era Lost**, will take pleasure in revealing elder "lies" in families, communities, and national politics
- 13ers will press to simplify the complex, narrow the bloated, and eliminate the unworkable
- Will be drawn to blunt, nonsense candidates

**Ethnic diversity and conflict:**
- **13er culture** will be far more ethnically diverse than Boom's
- Where the Lost catapulted Eastern and Southern Europeans to prominence, **13ers will do the same for Hispanics and Asians**
- The **Chinese democracy movement** and political controversies in Latin America will provide grist for poignant intergenerational clashes
- With this new ethnic diversity will come a new, youth-propelled racism and a prosperity for **"hate crimes"**
- Lacking a cultural center of gravity, 13ers of all backgrounds—including the white middle class—will feel at risk in ways their Boomer and Silent parents did not
- Most secular young ethnic achievers will encounter a festering racial hostility from their own peers, much as the **Jewish Lost did in the 1920s**

**Economic disadvantage and social problems:**
- Most of the children allowed to grow up poor or unskilled in the 1970s and 1980s will carry their incapacities and pathologies with them into adulthood
- Through the 1990s, **unmarried mothers and the undereducated of both sexes** will remain just as unemployable (and dependent) in their thirties as they were in their teens
- Efforts at adult remedial education will be halfhearted and ineffectual
- Many of today's youth gangsters will ripen into their adult facsimile, waging **Capone-style wars** with police (most of whom, by then, will be canny 13ers themselves)

**Crime and punishment:**
- Older generations will blame the nation's problems of **crime, drugs, and disintegrating inner cities** on their attitude of treating life as a game
- By the late 1990s, as 13ers wholly fill the crime-prone phase of life, street crime will be perceived as evil, and the criminal beyond rehabilitation except through the sternest of regimens
- Once **Boomer judges** go to work, this will almost surely become the **most permanently warehoused (and executed) generation in American history**
- Nor will many 13ers rise to defend their criminal peers
- By their ethos, if you're bad and are caught, you don't complain about your punishment

**Generational self-perception:**
- Rising 13ers will sense they will never gain much collective esteem from others
- Americans who today look upon 25-year-olds as a wasted bunch will, a decade from now, look upon 35-year-olds in much the same way
- Any stroke
<!-- p. 416 -->

### 13ers' Economic Approach and Risk-Taking

- **13ers** will capitalize on market opportunities older generations see as "bad news" (lower housing prices, wage inflation in service sector)
- Their skills: observation, understanding unmet needs, "smooth" and conceal feelings, quick action when timing is right
- Success comes from taking **incredible risks** individually
- Will reject the **(Boom) rules** and "lottery ticket" mentality—prepared to risk loss rather than surrender to chance or rely on kinetic frenzy
- **Thirty-year-olds** will jump at opportunities elders find inconsequential, take on long odds elders find incomprehensible
- Greatest successes in **small businesses** and **enthusiast and artisanale underprice** elder-dominated rivals
- **U.S. Postal Service** may become under-runners attack from new enterprises run by **piecemeal 13ers**: veteran bicycle messengers, delivery drivers, computer hackers—who know how to move information cheaply and reliably

### 13ers Seeking Stability in Family Life

- Economic risk-taking and cultural alienation drive **13ers to seek stability in family life**
- **First-wavers** may continue the Boom trend toward late marriage—not from postadolescent self-discovery, but from **economic necessity** and unwillingness to repeat early-marrying mistakes
- **Heavily divorcing Silent parents** seeing dual-income household as necessary for affluence while knowing from experience the perils of **latchkey childhood**
- 13ers will see **small kids upon working motherhood** as temporary necessity to overcome later in life when income permits
- Many will begin **marriage and parenthood in Silent homes**, enabling substantial elder help with child care
- Once they begin to tire of risk-taking (as Lost did in late 1920s), 13ers will become **more conservative in private lives**
- Turning away from marital infidelity and divorce, they will make great effort to **shield offspring from less pleasant facts of life**

### 13ers as Leading Consumer Generation

- Despite economic problems, **13ers will blossom into America's leading generation of shoppers**
- Thanks to **extended families** or **new shopping services**, will have huge influence on products, styles, advertising—much as **Lost had in 1920s**
- Once marketers realize this, American media will be barraged with messages stressing **bluntness over subtlety**, **action over words**, **physical over cerebral**
- Most successful messages will hint at **13er alienation** and appeal to **sense of dark humor**
- Ads will be **pointedly anti-Boom**
- Example: **Pepsi might hit back at 1990 Coca-Cola ad** showing fortyish jeans-clad Boomers on verdant hillside


<!-- p. 416 -->

### 13er Economic Strategy and Lifecycle

- **13ers** will pursue economic success through **risk-taking** rather than following Boom rules
- Their marketplace advantages (lower housing prices, wage inflation in service sector) will be dismissed as "bad news" by older generations
- Key 13er skills: observing unmet needs, being "smooth" and conceal feelings when necessary, moving quickly when opportunities arise
- Best path to individual success: **taking incredible risks**
- Those following **(Boom) rules probably won't get anywhere**—so they play by their own rules instead

**"Lottery ticket" mentality**: 13ers prepared to risk loss since they'll already be losing for a tiny chance to win big—will act on a kinetic frenzy

- **Thirty-year-olds will jump at opportunities their elders find inconsequential** and take on long odds their elders find incomprehensible
- Greatest successes will come in **small businesses that outbustle and underprice elder-dominated rivals**
- U.S. Postal Service may be staffed by enterprising piecework 13ers (bicycle messengers, delivery drivers, computer hackers)—civil servants who know how to move information more cheaply and reliably

### Marriage and Family Patterns

**Economic risk-taking and cultural alienation** will drive 13ers to seek stability in family life

- **First-wavers** marry early on the Boom trend toward late marriage—not from postadolescent self-discovery, but from **economic necessity** and unwillingness to repeat mistakes of early-marrying, heavily divorcing Silent parents
- Seeing dual-income household as **necessary condition for affluence** while knowing from personal experience the perils of **latchkey childhood**
- 13ers will see sex with partners as **temporary necessity to be overcome** in later life when income permits
- Many will begin marriage and parenthood in **Silent homes**, enabling them to receive substantial elder help with child care
- Once they begin to tire of risk-taking (as Lost did in late 1920s), **13ers will become more conservative** in private lives
- Turning away from marital infidelity and divorce, they will make **great effort to shield offspring from less pleasant facts of life**

### Consumer and Cultural Influence

Despite economic problems, **13ers will blossom into America's leading generation of shoppers**

- Huge influence on products, styles, advertising—thanks to purchases they will make for others (extended families, new shopping services)
- Once marketers realize this, American media will be **barraged with messages stressing bluntness over subtlety, action over words, the physical over the cerebral**
- Most successful messages will hint at **13er alienation** and appeal to **sense of dark humor**
- Many ads will be **pointedly anti-Boom**
- Example: Pepsi might hit back at 1990 Coca-Cola ad showing fortyish jeans-clad Boomers on verdant hillside
<!-- p. 417 -->

### Entering Midlife in a Crisis Era (2004-2025)

- Early in the new century, **fortyish 13ers** watch graying **Aquarians** get "into" national leadership
- They appreciate that whatever bad hand history dealt them, they at least grew up with clear heads
- Their pleasure-seeking era will draw to a close — along with the worst of the **Idealist-Reactive tussle**
- **Boomers** might then start discerning in them the rough-hewn tools needed to achieve lofty Boom visions
- In return, **13ers** might see in Boomers the leadership without which they might never find larger purpose in their own lives

**13er midlife bangover mood:**
- Around **year 2010**, this generation will hit a hangover mood
- Like that of the **Lost** in the early 1930s and the **Liberty** in the late 1760s
- A feeling of personal exhaustion mixed with a new public seriousness
- **Forty- and fifty-**

