## Appendix A: A Theory of Generations

### Opening Epigraphs

- **Homer, Iliad, Sixth Book**: Compares human generations to leaves—wind shakes them to the ground, but flourishing woods give birth to new ones as spring comes; generations of men alternately come forth and pass away

- **Ecclesiastes 1:4**: "One generation passeth away, and another generation cometh: but the earth abideth forever"

### Historical Context of Generational Thinking

- At dawn of recorded history, **standard measure of cosmic time** in nearly all Indo-European cultures was not year or century, but **the generation**

- **Hesiod** (8th century B.C.): When transcribing myths of prehistoric Aegea into verse, rarely used concepts other than generation to measure time's passage

- Hesiod's **sequential "generations"** marked not only the appearance of the gods (Cron us, Uranus, Cronus, Zeus) but also the **five sequential ages or generations of mankind**: Gold, Silver, Bronze, Heroic, and Iron

- **Philo**: Writing of legendary founding of Phoenicia, structured his story with "Genos," the first ruling male god

- **Old Testament**: Begins with "Genesis," the godly act of begetting the universe, and measures time ever afterward with a seemingly

<!-- p. 437 -->

### Defining "Generation" vs "Cohort"

- **Family generation**: the set of all children "brought into being" by a father; used in special terms like "**geneology**" (parent-to-child lineage) and expressions like "third-generation immigrant" or "ten generations of kings"
- The family definition is sometimes perfectly adequate for interpreting myth and history (e.g., Zeus belongs to second-generation descendants of Uranus)

- **Abstract root of "generation"**: always used in a very different sense; *genus* can mean anything new that the cosmos or society brings into being at a single moment in time
  - Includes "**cohort generation**"—a cohort-group sharing an age location in history and a common peer personality
  - When **Hesiod** described five generations of mankind, there was no implicit reference to parentage
  - The new *genos* (translated as "race" or "age") lives at about the same time and possesses a distinct way of life and set of values
  - When **Homer's** ill-aged Achaean heroes sailed home in triumph after sacking Troy, later acknowledged each other as members of "the same generation"
  - Still used today: "new generation" of cars, computers, ideas; "my generation" versus "your generation"

- Age-old expressions like "**a generation of peace**" have meanings that are perfectly ambiguous
- Rather than specify whether they mean family lineages or cohort-groups, most writers—modern as well as ancient—have leaned on the nuances of both

### The "Cohort" Generation Concept

- For millennia, poets and philosophers have sensed that generation connotes ebb and flow of life, of families, and of historical time
- Over last couple of centuries, many writers have grown specifically interested in what we call a "**cohort**" generation
- But so malleable a concept still eludes most efforts to understand it

- Central questions remain unanswered:
  - *What exactly* is a generation?
  - *How* does it develop a distinct peer personality?
  - *Why* do peer personalities tend to arrive in cycles?

- Authors have already summarized core theory of generations in Part I
- This appendix, retracing that ground in more detail, intended for readers interested in the theory's intellectual roots and core logic

- Begin by distinguishing the "cohort" from the "family" generation and by looking at the mixed record of modern writers who have grappled with the generations approach

<!-- p. 438 -->

## Appendix A (continued)

### The Cohort Generation

- **Philip Greven, Jr.** (1970) wrote *Four Generations: Population, Land, and Family in Colonial Andover, Massachusetts* - pathbreaking account of 17th-18th century family life in small New England farming town
- Book uses town records to draw detailed portrait of early New England social life: births, deaths, migration, occupations, property, wills, and households
- Organizes presentation by **four generations** defined strictly in genealogical terms:
  - First generation: group of (mostly) 25-to-45-year-olds who originally settled the town in 1640s-1650s
  - Second generation: consists of first generation's children (grandparents)
  - Third generation: consists of great-grandchildren
  - Fourth generation: consists of great-great-grandchildren

- Greven's generational scheme is **logical and convenient** but limited to purely familial context
- Removes exactly one parent-child link from previous group
- Should discover members of second Andover generation each inherited one defining set of all traits and attitudes from their parents
- Factors like gender, age order, parental strictness may influence children's outcomes

### Limitations of Genealogical Approach

- When Greven seeks to place generations in **historical context**, the scheme becomes useless
- Since women give birth over spread of many years, from late teens to their mid-forties, each successive generation of children has **lifespans that begin and end over ever-longer periods**
- Greven's first generation lived from mostly within a two-decade span
- But fourth generation has births stretched over more than a century
- Several fourth-generation Andoverans already married by **1715**, 60 years before American Revolution
- Several others did not marry until late 1780s, when Madison was hammering out the U.S. Constitution

### The Family vs. Cohort Generation Distinction

- What if we want to focus on another sort of generation - the young Andoverans who fought in French and Indian War?
- Greven has this contingency in mind - scattered throughout his book he tabulates same data by **cohort-group** and somewhere among tables could examine the 1725-1740 war-fighting cohorts
- Most historians who cite Greven also prefer the **birthyear** rather than family numbers
- Most historians want to locate people in history, not in genealogies
- Example of colonial Andover brings us back to the basic distinction between **family and cohort generations**
- Confusion between the two meanings has plagued the word since Homer and Hesiod
- Is one type of "generation" better than the other? Not necessarily - depends on object of inquiry
- The **family generation** is important when we want to examine the link between a

<!-- p. 439 -->

### Cohort Generation vs. Family Generation

- **Cohort generation** has no direct connection to genealogy or lineage
- Defined as everyone who is "brought into being" at the same historical moment—everyone who belongs to the same **cohort-group**
- Fathers, mothers, brothers, and sisters in the same family generation do not necessarily belong to the same cohort generation
- Unlike family generation, all members of the same cohort generation share a common historical moment

### Figure A-1: Distribution of Family Generations

- Visual representation showing overlapping distribution curves for four successive family generations
- **Generation 1**: Sharp initial peak at year 0, declining rapidly
- **Generation 2**: Peak around year 25-30
- **Generation 3**: Peak around year 50-60
- **Generation 4**: Peak around year 80-90
- Demonstrates how family generations overlap and extend over time (up to 150 years shown)
- Illustrates the distinction between birth timing in genealogical terms versus cohort groupings

<!-- p. 440 -->

### Modern Efforts to Define the Generation

- For centuries after Homer, western thought rarely distinguished between **family generations** and **cohort generations**
- In family life contexts (especially with "generation" attached to numbers), judges, clerics, and philosophers assumed the word referred to **lineage**:
  - "Third generation of daughters"
  - "Fourth-generation owner"
  - "Fifth-generation legacy"
- In broader social contexts, meaning shifted to **cohort-group**
  - Chroniclers used "rising generation" or "this generation" to refer to everyone approaching old age
  - King James Bible translators wrote of events affecting "this" or "that" generation of Hebrews and specific groups of adults

- **Key distinction**: Lineage meaning linked to personal pronoun, idiom
  - "To curse a neighbor" and "his generation" meant to speak of his family and children
  - David "served his own generation" referred to his peers

- **Why little effort to distinguish meanings?** Same reason there was scant interest in the underlying concept of the **birth cohort** until the 18th century
- Even educated westerners rarely doubted that:
  - History moved at a **glacial pace**
  - Seasonal rhythms were **timeless**
  - Phases of life passed down unaltered from parent to child
  - Evidence indicated the **lifecycle was universal**

- At special moments (Trojan War, Old Testament prophecies), one could notice a distinct cohort generation emerge
  - But these seemed little need to insist on rigorous definition
  - As time passed, so too would "that generation," and then all would be as before

- Special interest in the **cohort generation** awaited a new worldview—a belief that:
  - History had **speed and direction**
  - Frequent Trojan War-like moments could be expected
- Such belief arrived in the **late eighteenth and early**
<!-- p. 441 -->

### Early Stirrings of Generational Thinking (19th Century)

- **19th-century democratic revolutions**, industrialization, and **rationalism/progress dogmas** shaped modern generational concepts
- **Propagandists of French Revolution** (1780s-1790s): first to attach modern significance to generations—"No connection here"
- **"Philosophes"** wanted to be seen as unique generation, pushing mankind into new age of improvement and new ethics/rules
- Limited interest to "political" generations of like-aged leaders; many sought to define generations beyond locale

#### Thomas Jefferson and Generational Theory
- **Thomas Jefferson** (writing from Paris, 1789): concluded a generation = short-term cohort (~18.2 years)
- **Jean-Louis Giraud** (1809): sliced French history into 15-year periods—crude but mechanical approach
- After **Robespierre** and **Napoleon**, European peers of **Andrew Jackson** helped Western public understand how special a generation could be—and how thoroughly it could change the world

### Mid-19th Century: Emergence of Scientific Interest

- **Victorian era scientists and philosophers**: more serious wave of generational interest
- **Auguste Comte**, **John Stuart Mill**, **Émile Littré**: basic question remained—what role do earlier Parisians' generations play in civilized progress pace?
- **Focus widened beyond politics**: Comte saw generations as complex drivers behind all social change
- **Littré**: character of each generation more complex than calendar evolution—historically evolving (1863)
  - Coined **"cohort"** to explain personality contrasts between French leaders covered by J. Mill
- **J. Mill**: defined generation broadly as "men of their time" who "have been educated, have grown up from childhood, and have taken possession of society"
- **Mill rejected successive "political generations"** influencing each other independently
  - Argued: culture, science, manners, arts mores—**"In the filiation of one generation to another," he noted, "it is the whole which produces the whole, rather than any part a part."**

### The Cohort Generation Concept

- **Cohort generation** remained live subject for rest of 19th century—mostly because few writers could resist guessing its length
- **Antoine Cournot and Ottokar Lorenz**: talked about "three-generation century"
- Few writers had much to say on subject—one important exception: **Italian historian Giuseppe Ferrari**
  - Developed **penetrating model of generational cycles** in 1840s-1870s (received little contemporary recognition)
  - Writings addressed **confusion still clouding "generation" meaning**—**Dithey** insisted word has two separate definitions:
    1. **"Span of time"** that "lasts from birth until age when, on average, new ring of life added to generational tree"
    2. **Term applied to relationship of contemporaneity** between individuals—those sharing common childhood, common adolescence, overlapping peak vigor years—**belong to same generation**

### Post-WWI Perspective Shift

- During two decades following **WWI cataclysm**: generation entered yet another vogue from new perspective
- Rising social thinkers of the era brought fresh approach


<!-- p. 442 -->

### The "Generations Problem" Today

- Modern generational writing has struggled to define "generation" explicitly as **cohort**—bringing definition to western world attention
- **Key success**: The cohort "generation" has reshaped popular understanding of words like "generation" and gained unprecedented legitimacy

**Cohort generation's cultural triumph:**
- **Vocabulary integration**: Entered daily parlance of multiple languages and basic perception of historical change
- **Age confusion eliminated**: Since 1920s, no 20-to-25-year cohort-group has come fully of age in America without encountering attempts to name it
- **Peer identity shift**: Four centuries ago, young person "talking" about grandfather/grandchildren had a story to share; today focus is on peers and how they all came of age and have come to see life
- **Market research dominance**: Cohort generation gained unprecedented legitimacy in polling and marketing industries
  - **"Baby Boom Generation"** became synonymous with cohort-group whose tastes marketers willing to pay millions to understand
  - Thousands of professionals watched precise infant science (study of cohorts) merge with popular idiom (the generation)
- **Expert confinement**: In popular culture, cohort generation confined by experts to

<!-- p. 443 -->

## Appendix A (continued)

### The Problem of Cohort Generation Length

- **Most blame-worthy failure** of generations writing: remaining in the shadow world of unproven hypothesis
- Present-day historians mention "generation" only in passing
- Academics in aging, lifecycles, sociology, and politics hardly touch the word
- Most unfriendly reception comes from hostile writers themselves
- From **Comte** through **Mannheim** and beyond, writings have been colorful, eloquent, and painstakingly empirical—but seldom explanatory
- Three obvious and related questions can be asked of **cohort generations**:
  - How do they arise?
  - Why should they change personality at any particular cohort boundary?
  - And why should they have any particular length?
- Can read endless tomes of generations literature looking for answers to these questions—won't find any

### Varying Definitions of Generation Length

- Expected length of a cohort generation has vexed many writers
- Clearly, to be usable concept, we need to know approximately how long it is
- Common proposals vary wildly:
  - Why not three years? Why not ninety years?
- Generations writers typically resorted to **evasion or nonsense**
- To take **Mannheim** as example—finesse the issue by refusing to speculate on length
- Writers tell us how to find out, in effect, but won't get their own hands dirty
- Most other writers go to opposite extreme: telling exactly how long every generation must be
- Range of proposed lengths:
  - **Lorenz, Cournot**: "precisely" thirty-three years
  - **Comte, Dilthey**: twenty-five years
  - **Littré**: 33⅓ years (literally, or 18.2 years (Jefferson))
  - **Ortega y Gasset**: fifteen years

### Why No Single Answer Works

- Not a single writer justifies either the precision or absolute regularity of these time spans
- **Wroe**: many fail to defend even the approximate number—a failure revealed by their vague reference to the average length (or half-length) of a family generation
- Reinforcing the age-old confusion surrounding the very meaning of the concept
- As recently as 1946, **Johan Huizinga** believed it was a far criticism of the entire generations school to observe that "the generation, biologically speaking, is and always will be a completely arbitrary period of time"
- Small wonder that skeptics have regarded the cohort generation, like astrology, as a provocative idea searching blindly for a reason
- Or that **Bob Dylan** might seem to offer the last word on the subject

### Authors' Approach to the Length Question

- In remainder of this Appendix, authors offer the specifics they see lacking in the writings of others
- Their approach is **consistent with the conclusions of the best generations writers**—including **Littré, Ferrari, Dilthey, Mentré, and Ortega**
- These writers agree that the **length of a cohort generation must be linked to the length of a phase of life, not to family genealogy**
- This also leads to the basic dynamic of the recurring cycle identified in American history

### A Journey to Cohortia

- Authors invite readers on "a journey to the mythical land of **Cohortia**"
- **Cohortia** is a traditional society, largely free from the most serious kinds of historical shocks
- From time to time, Cohortians encounter bloody wars, deadly famines, and charismatic shamans—but not often

<!-- p. 444 -->

## Appendix A: Traditional Cohortia

### Assumptions About Cohortians

- **Social behavior governed by well-defined and relatively unchanging lifecycle**
- Each phase: "good Cohortian" expected to fulfill **cluster of age-based social roles**
- **Cohortian lifecycle** includes four basic life phases, each based on **multiple of the span between birth and coming of age**
- Assumes **twenty-two year life phases** as described in Chapter 2:

### Four Life Phase Roles

- **ELDERS (age 66-87)**: Central role is **stewardship** (supervising, mentoring, channeling endowments, passing on values)

- **MIDLIFE ADULTS (age 44-65)**: Central role is **leadership** (parenting, teaching, directing institutions, using values)

- **RISING ADULTS (age 22-43)**: Central role is **activity** (working, starting families and livelihoods, serving institutions, testing values)

- **YOUTH (age 0-21)**: Central role is **dependence** (growing, learning, accepting protection and nurture, avoiding harm, acquiring values)

### Social Moment and Generational Response

- Phase-of-life descriptions are **suggestive only** - first assumption requires each role be basically different and age-specific roles be reasonably well defined
- Cohortians are ordinary - every society recognizes lifecycle passage points and practically every society acknowledges "coming-of-age" separation between youth and rising adulthood
- These central roles can be performed by only a few people at short notice if divisions are short

**Social moment concept**: Sudden shock (major war or revolution) triggers different behavior
- **Any social moment affects an individual's personality differently according to his current phase of life**
- Triggering behavior conditioned by phase-of-life role:
  - **Youth**: independence (keeping out of the way)
  - **Rising adults**: activity (arming to meet challenge)
  - **Midlifers**: leadership (organizing the troops)
  - **Elders**: stewardship (establishing purpose of war)

### Generational Formation Through Social Moments

- Stress of responding to social moment leaves **different emotional imprint and memory** with each group according to role
- Social interaction furthers, strengthens, records the social interaction within each group
- **Youths** might mirror each other's dread and anxiety
- **Rising adults** might collectively encourage each other's valor and sense of duty
- Four adjacent cohort-groups **separately coalesce into generations**, each with distinct peer personality
- Social moment creates **sharper contrasts between peer personalities**
- **Length of these generations depends on the length of the phases of life** (assumed here to be twenty-two years)

### Post-Social Moment Continuity

- After war/social moment ends, notice the **continuing influence** even twenty-two years later when each generation has risen one phase
<!-- p. 445 -->

### Generational Dynamics and the Trojan War Illustration

- **Cohortian dynamics**: Even without traditional phase-of-life notch, four distinct **peer personalities** still exist based on when individuals were born relative to major historical events
- Post-war example: **Elders** (born before war) vs. **new crop of youths** (born after war) - creates dramatically different **peer personality** from elder generations
- Key assumption: Nothing else happens thereafter - when frozen in time for years, the number of distinct generational types falls to three: **elders**, **midlifers** (war as rising adults and youths), and **everyone younger** than age 44
- After 86 years, only two discrete generations remain as all living **Cohortians** are products of the traditional lifecycle

### Figure A-2: Cohort-Group Lifecycles

- Illustrates **dynamic constellation** of peer personalities and phases of life vertically
- Reveals **cohort-group lifecycles** along the diagonal
- Time measured in years with:
  - **"0"** = first aligned constellation
  - **"22"** = next
  - **"44"** = third
- Each cohort-group given a letter in order of birth
- **Social moments** shown starting before aligned constellation
- **Suppose**: Social moment not fixed catalyst but something akin to **Trojan War**
  - Social moment would start earlier than "Year 0" and rage
  - Each cohort enters each phase of life at different points
  - **Youth cohort**: Certain cohorts come of age during war as they fight in it
  - **Catalyzing moment**: Would then arrive near end of social moment

### Trojan War as Historical Example

- Authors imagine **Cohortia** literally re-enacting the **Trojan War** as illustration of generational interaction
- Introduces **Homer's cast of characters**, each representing a generation

**Table: Homeric Characters and Generational Mapping**

| Cohortian Generation | Homeric Character | Phase of Life During Social Moment | Phase-of-Life During Social Moment |
|---------------------|-------------------|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------|
| **B** | **Nestor** | Elderhood | Stewardship |
| **C** | **Agamemnon** | Midlife | Leadership |
| **D** | **Odysseus** | Rising Adulthood | Activity |
| **E** | **Telemachus** | Youth | Dependence |

### Character Background from the Iliad

- **Nestor (B)**: Ruler of Pilos, somewhere in midlife during prewar constellation (year -22)
- **Agamemnon (C)**: Rising-adult chief of House of Atreus
- **Odysseus (D)**: Child in Ithaca
- **Telemachus (E)**: Not yet born
- Central drama: War itself spans year -10 to +10
- **Odysseus** and coming-of-age peers **Ajax** and **Diomedes** forced by war into **collective giants** - a **triumphant and heroic cohort-group**
- **Agamemnon**: Now haunted figure entering midlife, leads troops
- **Nestor**: In old age, presides with wisdom over Achaean alliance
- Back in Ithaca: **Odysseus' wife Penelope** manages on her own


<!-- p. 446 -->

### Traditional Cohortia and the *Odyssey* Example (continued)

- **Telemachus** as exemplar of the **"air raid generation"**: sensitive, eloquent, pessimistic, cautious
- In the *Odyssey*'s climax, Homer advances the generational cycle: Agamemnon would now be an old man, but was murdered by his wife—not back in Penelope's arms
- **Odysseus** returns to **midlife**; **Telemachus** comes of age; identifiable generations begin to recede
- Presumably, the "dark ages" will reclaim the Greek kingdoms, but heroes will return to gray tradition—not a story that interests the epic poet, at least not until a new social moment
- Reflecting on the *Odyssey*'s last scenes: wondering how cohort-groups (F, G, H, I) in Figure A-2 could revert to traditional **Cohortia's lifecycle and personality**
- Scenario: **Cohort F** youths grow up while midlife leadership roles filled by heroic peers of Odysseus (D); **Cohort G** youths grow up while **Cohort F** fills rising adulthood; same role played by far less confident peers of Telemachus (E)
- Given differing temperaments and leadership styles of two postwar constellations, peer personalities of younger groups will differ from each other and from the traditional lifecycle
- And if they differ, so might cohorts **H** and **I**, and so on
- **Thus far, traditional Cohortia does not allow for this possibility**—authors implicitly assume

### FIGURE A-2: Traditional Cohortia

**Table structure:**
- Columns: Time in Years (Yr -22, Yr 0, Yr 22, Yr 44, Yr 66, Yr 88) across a **Social Moment**
- Rows showing **Phase of Life**:
  - **ELDER, age 66-87**: Cohorts A → B → C → D → E → F
  - **MIDLIFE, age 44-65**: Cohorts B → C → D → E → F → G
  - **RISING, age 22-43**: Cohorts C → D → E → F → G → H
  - **YOUTH, age 0-21**: Cohorts D → E → F → G → H → I

- Circle marks indicate cohort-group entering that phase of life during the social moment
- Shows diagonal progression of cohort-groups through lifecycle phases over 22-year intervals

<!-- p. 447 -->

### Modern Cohortia (continued)

- **Modern Cohortia** eases the power of tradition through two new assumptions about generational life phases

#### First Assumption: Social Moments Shape Personality and Identity

- **A social moment not only shapes personality according to current phase-of-life roles, but also forges an enduring bond of identity between each cohort-group and its role**—an acquired style that redefines both how each group will later regard itself and how it will later be regarded by others

- In modern Cohortia, a **phase-of-life role is no longer totally rigid**, but can be modified by the generational personality passing through it
- If a social moment shapes an active peer personality among rising adults, for example, this cohort-group will take an active role and self-image with it at ages
- Apologies to Homer: **modern Odysseus would not simply return to Ithaca in midlife** with the personality of a war hero
- He and his peers would modify the very definition of midlife according to the same role—by projecting heroic activity into political, cultural, and family behavior
- **Dante and many later writers amended Homer's account** in precisely this fashion, by depicting an aging, hubristic Odysseus organizing new missions and voyages
- A modern **Telemachus and his peers might very well let this happen**, since their role during the war—dependence and emulation—will continue to shape their later behavior and self-image

#### Second Assumption: Biological and Social Limits on Generational Longevity

- **A central role acquired during a social moment can extend into the next life phase—but not into the life phase after that**

- If the **central role of rising adulthood is activity**, a generation shaped by that role can transfer it to midlife, but not to elderhood
- Even a **modern Odysseus cannot, in old age, sustain society's active role** in the face of physiological decline and his approaching awareness of his own mortality
- Nor would society eventually permit him to do so
- The **dependent role of childhood can likewise be transferred to rising adulthood**, but not to midlife
- The time would come when the **modern Telemachus would have to abandon dependence for the role of leadership**, by necessity if not by choice

- Authors **retrace the story depicted in Figure A-2, recast for modern Cohortia**

<!-- p. 448 -->

### Generational Role Transitions and Social Moments

- **Generational lifecycle roles** are not fixed by free choice or predetermined—they are shaped by **social design** within modern **Cohortia**
- The resolution of generational roles depends on **new social moments**—rapid, decisive events where **new generational constellations** emerge
- Critical transition: when original roles (midlife/elderhood) become **intolerable**, new **coming-of-age cohort-groups** (postwar babies aging into sixtyish Odysseus, fierce partners of fortyish Telemachus) will demand active social roles
- At this point, uncertainty exists about which **new type of war** will **reidentify each cohort-group** with original central roles associated with the new lifecycle phase
- Expect: new active role for **now-rising adults (F)** and new dependent role for **new crop of children (G)**
- **Modernity dynamics** in modern Cohortia:
  - Does NOT alter how Cohortia shapes generational personalities through social moments
  - DOES trigger the arrival of new social moments at **two-constellation intervals** instead of single-constellation
  - Creates **two basic types of generational lifecycles**:
    - **Generations D, F, and H** encounter social moments in or entering **rising adulthood** (coming of age) and later in entering **elderhood**
    - These tend to transfer their **active rising-adult role** into midlife
    - Always **dominate major social and cultural change** in Cohortia
    - Called **"dominant"** generations
  - **Generations E, G, and I** encounter social moments in **youth** and later in entering **midlife**
    - Styles tend to be **overshadowed** by more potent personalities of their next-elders or next-juniors
    - Called **"recessive"** generations

### Social Moments and Generational Bonding

- Assumption: positive association between each generation and its expected social role may not always happen
- **Unsuccessful experience** for a dominant, rising-adult generation may **prevent meaningful bonding** with its role during the **social moment**

> "A society must resolve a social moment successfully in order to shape the coming-of-age generation as dominant; otherwise, it will shape the coming-of-age generation as recessive, unable or unwilling to take its active role with it into midlife."

<!-- p. 449 -->

### From a Two-Stroke Rhythm to a Four-Type Cycle

- **Regenerative quality of peer groups**: capacity to grow, wither, fall, and renew themselves—has fascinated philosophers, historians, and dramatists since ancient times
- Greek tragedy structure centers on concept of **age-related hubris**
- Combination of blindness and over-reaching inevitably produces **generational consequences** ("visit the sins of the father on the sons")
- Simple fact: one generation's tragic excesses lead to permanent cycle of destruction and decay
- Reflects the capacity of successor generations to learn from and compensate for mistakes of their elders
- These successors, in turn, then make their own mistakes
- Creates ongoing cyclical pattern of generational learning and error

<!-- p. 450 -->

### Cross-Generational Rejuvenation in Literature and Culture

- **Cross-generational rejuvenation** has been a recurring theme in story and song for the last two centuries
  - Examples: Ivan Turgenev's *Fathers and Sons*, Graham Nash's *Teach Your Children*
- Where tradition is strong, we can observe this dynamic in individual families:
  - Parents unknowingly err in raising their children
  - The children who rise above the setback later compensate by erring in the opposite direction with their own children
- Where tradition is weak and life phases can be redefined by distinct peer personalities, this pattern can be observed happening across entire societies
- In a social context, "parents" and "children" refer not to families but to **cohort generations**

### Returning to the Dynamics of Social Moments in Modern Cohorta

**Key principle:**
> "During a new social moment, each generation will redefine the central role of the phase of life it is entering in a direction that reverses the perceived excesses of that role since the last social moment."

- **Generation-specific styles** forged during a social moment will later become dysfunctional as time passes
- Most people will sense this fact, and given a new social moment, each generation will seek a new style appropriate for its phase of life
- Each generation compensates for past excesses and steers society back on the right course

**Example:** Over the forty-four long years that modern **Odysseus** and his peers have been busy redefining **Cohortian adulthood** in terms of endless martial projects:
- Could imagine a growing consensus that a different sort of style is called for
- Perhaps a search for values and principles that would give such projects a fresh sense of purpose
- When the next social moment arrives, each generation will not only reclaim its generic life-phase role, but will **shift its style in a compensatory direction**

**Near year 44 in modern Cohorta example:**
- Might witness an old **Odysseus** relinguishing all his last worldly agendas
- A midlife **Telemachus** stepping gently into power
- Careful to avoid his father's swagger and hubris
- A coming-of-age cohort-group of zealous **Dionysians** more keen on inner than outer discovery
- A new crop of hardscrabble youths whom no one expects to be obedient

**This impulse to compensate for excess:**
- Shows up not only in the desire of adults to correct past mistakes
- But also in the hope of adults to spare their own children from such mistakes

**Fundamental generational relationship:**
> "Each generation has a formative, nurturing relationship primarily with other two-apart generations (dominant with dominant, recessive with recessive); each tries to cultivate in the second-younger generation a peer personality it perceives as complementary to its own."

### Two-Generation Child Rearing Pattern

- Any generation's children (using 20-to-25-year cohort-groups) typically fall into both of the two next-younger generations
- Yet for the entire period that any generation is situated mostly in midlife—the life phase in which it combines its influence as parents with norm-setting leadership in public life
- The generation then situated mostly in youth will be exactly two generations removed
- **The elder generation of parents will set the nurturing tone for any generation of children**
- As noted in Chapter 3, recent [text continues beyond page]

<!-- p. 451 -->

### The Recurrence of Compensating Peer Personalities

- The recurrence of **compensating peer personalities** is an important force for **regeneration and balance** in human civilization
- Creates a **gravitational orbit** around timeless norms of human behavior, with successor generations moderating excesses of their elders
- Key question: Why is the cycle not a **centrifugal spiral**, with successor generations lunging toward ever more dangerous extremes? We do not know
- The answer may be rooted in a basic social instinct for balance between risk and caution, between reflection and activity, between passion and reason, or between the emulation of mothers versus fathers
- Authors leave such questions to anthropologists and psychologists
- **Whatever the reason, this instinct has worked to mankind's benefit** in the past and enhances prospects for survival and progress in the future

## The Four-Part Generational Cycle

### Historical Foundation

- From the **Hebrew tribes' flight from Egypt** to their founding of a new society in Canaan, the early books of the Old Testament tell the most dramatic story of unfolding

<!-- p. 452 -->

### Four Distinct Peer Personalities in the Exodus Story

The authors identify four distinct generational peer personalities in the biblical Exodus narrative, examining them in choreographed succession:

- **First**: The holy peers of **Aaron** and mother-protected **Moses**—young adults who awakened their people to the spirit of their one true God ("I am who I am"), defied the authority of the most powerful institution on earth (Pharaoh's Egypt), and later—during midlife and old age—led the Hebrews through the wilderness to the threshold of Canaan (their "promised land")

- **Second**: A tough generation of "stiff-necked" backsliders—the worshipers of the golden calf, "murmurers" and "men of little faith"—for whose sins God punished the Hebrews with extra trials and tribulations. Possessed of divided loyalties and split timing, they were too young to have been exalted by Moses' spiritual awakening, but too old not to remember the enticing fleshpots of Egypt

- **Third**: The dutiful soldier-peers of **Joshua**—the children who were nearly all born after Exodus and who first came of age in victorious battles in the wilderness; the young adults whom the patriarch Moses anointed for leadership (none older was allowed to enter Canaan); and the midlifers of martial unity and discipline who succeeded in conquering the natives of Canaan through decades of warfare

- **Fourth**: The original generation of **Judges**—the invisible children whose births were overshadowed by war; the obliging young adults who served the mighty Joshua; and the midlifers whose exercise of power was marked by political fragmentation, petty feuds, and uncertainty about the future

### Generational Rhythm in the Cohortia Calendar

Using the generational calendar of **Cohortia** with twenty years as the length of a Hebrew life phase:

- Members over age 20 were normally "able to go to war"
- This time span can be doubled to take the story from one social moment to the next
- **Eighty years** pass between the Moses-led Exodus and the Joshua-led invasion of Canaan
- Another **forty years** takes us to the death of Joshua and his peers
- Only then do the first Judges climb to leadership ("and there arose another generation after them, which knew not the Lord, nor yet the works which he had done for Israel")

### Oscillation Between Generational Types

The authors identify a familiar oscillation between Cohortia's two basic generational types, **dominant** and **recessive**:

- **Moses' peers**: Type: dominant. Social moment (year 0) as rising adults and again (year 40) as elders

- **Golden Calf peers**: Type: recessive. Social moment (year 0) as children and again (year 40) as midlifers

- **Joshua's peers**: Type: dominant. Social moment (year 40) as rising adults and story end (year 80) as elders

- **First Judges' peers**: Type: recessive. Social moment (year 40) as children and story end (year 80) as midlifers

<!-- p. 453 -->

### The Dynamic of Exodus as a Four-Type Cycle

- **Exodus** represents a **four-type cycle**: first two-part beat triggered by prophets and other-world agendas, then next two-part beat by emergencies and this-world agendas
- In lifecycle timing, these successive dominant or recessive generations have much in common, yet their personalities appear diametrically opposed
- This four-type cycle illustrates a fundamental pattern arising distinctly when generations are left free to develop and express their personalities

**Four-type cycle pattern**:
- Generation shaped young by **inner-driven event** (seeking consolation/meaning) redefines in spiritual terms
- As peer group enters old age, likely leaves behind society divided in moral conviction, incoming generation resolves into unsolved practical problems
- OR reverse: generation shaped young by **outer-driven event** leaves behind (as it enters old age) a rational and secularized world crying out for spiritual rebirth

**Cohortia example** (reviewed):
- Generations shaped by inner-driven event develop adult identities focused on spiritual terms
- Later leave behind divided society in moral conviction
- Incoming generation must resolve unsolved practical problems

### The Rarity and Prerequisites of Four-Type Cycles

**Four-type generational cycles rare in traditional societies** because they require:
1. A **providential moment** (Hebrews' spiritual awakening)
2. **Successful outcome** and temporary loosening of lifecycle traditions (possibly from dislocation of wandering and war)

- Makes the Exodus cycle striking as a rare occurrence

### The Tradition of the Four-Type Cycle

**Not expected in premodern societies**, but Exodus aside, provenance bits and pieces exist:

**Classical historians** (Homer, Virgil, Thucydides, Livy, Polybius) often identify cycles launched by **heroic, Joshua-like generations**

**Ancient religious chronicles** focus more on cycles launched by **spiritual, Moses-like generations** (those beginning with Abraham, Samuel, Christ, or Mohammed)

**Premodern observers knew two basic types of dominant generations**:
1. **Martial or institutions-founding** (heroic)
2. **Spiritual or values-founding**

**Significance of number four**: Whenever observers discuss lengthy generational sequences, the number **four is most often cited as a cyclical endpoint**
<!-- p. 454 -->

### Four-Generation Cycle Theory - Historical Examples

**Ferrari's cycle theory** combines with **Littré's morphology**. Starting with Ferrari's second type and Littré's third, adding brief summary of each role:

- **First, "revolutionary"** (Ferrari) or **"moral"** (Littré) generation forges entirely new array of feelings and values, works to fulfill implicit agenda

- **Second, "reactionary"** (Ferrari) or **"industrial"** (Littré) generation struggles against values emphasis of elders, prefers pragmatism and independence

- **Third, "harmonizing"** (Ferrari) or **"scientific"** (Littré) generation identifies problems, builds social consensus, agrees on rational solutions, works effectively to achieve them

- **Fourth, "preparatory"** (Ferrari) or **"aesthetic"** (Littré) generation perfects and embellishes solution, yet undermines consensus and provides lone forerunners for next values revolution (then cycle repeats)

<!-- p. 452 -->

### The Marías-Huntington Generational Cycle

**Julián Marías** (Spanish sociologist-philosopher) and **Samuel Huntington** (Harvard professor of government) have separately proposed four-part generational cycles:

**Marías's Cycle (1967):**
- Published paradigm in article clarifying **Ortega's** original two-stroke oscillation between "polemic" and "cumulative" types (roughly, "dominant" and "recessive")
- First generation creates and initiates, second fabricates a stereotyped personality, third reflects and theorizes, fourth stylistically challenges forms and customs

**Huntington's Cycle (1981):**
- Developed four-phase model based on social and political change in American history
- Notes alternating pattern between **inner- and outer-driven behavior**
- Period of newly conceived values and "creedal passion" followed by period of effective public action that institutionalizes these ideals
- Calls this the **"I/W" (Institutions versus Ideals")** cycle—a cycle of four parts
- In parts I and III, "moralism" eventually elicits cynicism, cynicism produces complacency, complacency leads to hypocrisy, and hypocrisy in due course reinvigorates moralism
- **Polarities** are inner- and outer-driven behavior
- Huntington finds "gaps" roughly the same length as two life phases
- Lines up American social moments—**spiritual awakenings and secular crises**—almost exactly as we do

**Huntington on Generational Experience:**
- Acknowledges generation as "**experiential and attitudinal group**"
- "Major struggles" take place "between the advance guard of the new generation and the rear guard of its predecessor"
- Interprets American politics in terms of cycles
- Concludes: "I think we can relate cycles to generational analysis"
- Theory is incomplete but combined with Marías creates useful composite

### The Composite "Marías-Huntington Cycle"

Lining up Marías's third phase with Huntington's first creates a four-part cycle:

1. **First**: An **inner-driven, moralistic generation** reflects and theorizes, distills new values and ideas, begins a period of "creedal passion"—that is, a society-wide effort to close the gap between ideals and reality

2. **Second**: A **cynical generation** stylistically challenges forms and customs

3. **Third**: An **outer-driven, morally complacent generation** institutionalizes the ideals identified earlier

4. **Fourth**: A **hypocritical generation** fabricates a stereotyped personality (Then the cycle repeats)

### Similarities to Earlier Cycles

The Marías-Huntington cycle is very similar to:
- The **Littré-Ferrari cycle** (identified a century earlier)
- The **cycle of Exodus**
- Even hints of a full cycle in **Homer's Iliad**

**Figure A-4** summarizes the correspondence of generational types between the authors' own cycle and earlier paradigms

Each of these four types has a distinct lifecycle and special relationship to spiritual awakenings and secular crises

<!-- p. 456 -->

## Appendix A

### FIGURE A-4: Five Generational Cycles Compared

**Comparison table of five major historical cycles:**

| **Our Cycle** | **Marias-Huntington** | **Littré-Ferrari** | **Exodus** | **The Iliad** |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **IDEALIST** | inner-driven moralist | revolutionary moral | Aaron, Moses prophetic | Nestor wise |
| **REACTIVE** | anticustom cynical | reactionary industrial | Golden Calf sinful | Agamemnon cunning |
| **CIVIC** | outer-driven institutionalizing | harmonizing scientific | Joshua heroic | Odysseus hubristic |
| **ADAPTIVE** | stereotyped hypocritical | preparatory aesthetic | Judges fragmented | Telemachus deferential |

**Key insights:**

- Four generational types organize themselves into **four parallel types of constellations**, each with matching era and mood
- **Figure A-4** demonstrates **remarkable correspondences** across theories and myths spanning **three millennia**
- Four-part generational cycle has **never fully emerged from shadowy speculation** into established legitimate intellectual tradition
- Authors suggest: **"Perhaps, in time, it will."**
- The table reveals consistent patterns across:
  - **Western theory and myth** over 3,000 years
  - Different cultural frameworks (biblical Exodus, Greek epic)
  - Historical/theoretical models (Marias-Huntington, Littré-Ferrari)

