## TABLE B-3: National Leadership Share, 1775-1989, by Generation

### Data Structure
- Tracks percentage share of national leadership positions by generation across different end years (1775-1839 shown on this page)
- Birth year categories: **BIRTH YEAR UNKNOWN**, **AWAKENING** (pre-Revolutionary generation)
- Generational columns: **LIBERTY**, **REPUBLICAN**, **COMPROMISE**, **TRANSCENDENTAL**, **GILDED**, **PROGRESSIVE**, **MISSIONARY**, **LOST**, **G.I.**, **SILENT**, **BOOM**

### Key Patterns (1775-1799)
- **1775**: Awakening generation dominates at 31%, Liberty 38%, Republican 11%
- **1777**: Awakening 25%, Liberty 62%, Republican 12%
- **1779**: Sharp shift - Awakening drops to 21%, Liberty surges to 56%, Republican 24%

### Key Patterns (1781-1799)
- **Liberty generation** peaks in 1780s-1790s (62-77% leadership share)
- **Republican generation** rises from 24% (1779) to 69% (1793), then to 83% (1799)
- Birth year unknown percentage declines from 18% (1781) to 2% (1797-1799)

### Key Patterns (1801-1839)
- **Republican generation** dominates through 1820s (70-85% range)
- **Compromise generation** emerges: 4% (1797) → 16% (1803) → 32% (1809) → 52% (1839)
- **Transcendental generation** first appears at 1% (1817-1819), rises to 43% by 1837
- Leadership transitions show generational succession patterns across 60+ year span

<!-- p. 465 -->

### Data Table: Birth Year Demographics by Religious/Political Affiliation (1841-1915)

**Statistical breakdown** of birth cohorts showing percentage distributions across religious and political categories:

- **Birth year unknown**: ranges from 1% (1841, 1861) to highest percentages in earliest cohorts
- **Awaker**: minimal representation across all cohorts (dashes indicate no data)
- **Liberty/Republican**: minimal representation (dashes indicate no data)
- **Compromise cohort**: peaks at 35% (1841), declining to 25% (1843), 22% (1845), continuing downward trend
- **Transcendental generation**: peaks at 75% (1843), 78% (1845), 83% (1847), 85% (1849), 86% (1851), maintaining high percentages through 1850s, then declining: 88% (1853, 1855), 90% (1857, 1859), reaching peak 90% (1857-1859)
- **Gilded cohort**: first appears 1% (1851), rises to 3% (1853), 4% (1855), peaks around 6-12% range through 1860s-1870s
- **Progressive generation**: emerges in 1860s, rising from 12% (1861) to peaks in 1880s-1890s: 79% (1881), 74% (1883-1885), 71% (1887), 63% (1889), declining to 60% (1891), 58% (1893), continuing downward
- **Missionary cohort**: first appears 1% (1873, 1875, 1877), growing to significant percentages by 1890s-1900s: 14% (1891), rising to 48% (1895), 57% (1897), 61% (1899), 60% (1901), 57% (1903-1905), 50% (1907-1909), 47% (1911), declining to 40% (1909), 36% (1913-1915)
- **Lost Generation**: emerges in 1890s: 1% (1891), growing to 4% (1895), 7% (1897), 9% (1899), continuing rise through 1900s-1910s: 13% (1901), 20% (1903), 27% (1905), 26% (1907), peaking around 40% (1909), 56% (1913), 60% (1915)
- **G.I. cohort**: appears only in final year: 1% (1915)
- **Silent/Boom generations**: no representation (all dashes)

**Pattern observed**: Clear generational succession with overlapping birth cohorts, showing gradual transitions between dominant generational types from Compromise/Transcendental era through Progressive, Missionary, and Lost generations.

<!-- p. 466 -->

### Birth Year Data Table: Generational Self-Identification Patterns (1917-1989)

- Statistical table showing percentage of people identifying with specific generational labels by birth year
- Columns track identification rates across multiple generational archetypes: **Awakening**, **Liberty**, **Republican**, **Compromise**, **Transcendental**, **Gilded/Defensive**, **Progressive**, **Missionary**, **Lost**, **G.I.**, **Silent**, and **Boom**
- Data organized by **end year** of birth cohort (1917-1989)

**Key patterns visible in the data:**

- **1917-1919 cohorts**: Predominantly identify as **G.I.** (27%-27%) and **Progressive** (70%-76%)
- **1921-1939 cohorts**: Strong **Progressive** identification (ranging 42%-83%), with increasing **G.I.** identification (reaching 62%-77% by mid-1930s)
- **1941-1959 cohorts**: Shift toward **G.I.** identification (31%-59%) and **Silent** generation emergence (reaching 66% by 1959)
- **1961-1979 cohorts**: **Silent** generation peaks (76% in 1965), followed by emergence of **Boom** identification (rising from 4% in 1961 to 50% by 1977), **Boom** reaches 66% by 1979
- **1981-1989 cohorts**: **Boom** identification remains strong (63%-68%), slight decline toward end of period (65% in 1989)

**Notable measurement points:**
- Birth year **unknown** category consistently shows low identification across all generational labels
- Dashes (—) indicate negligible or zero identification rates
- Percentage distributions show clear generational boundaries and transitions
- Data demonstrates how generational self-identification consolidates around specific birth year clusters

