### Notes on Sources - Chapter 2: Life Along the Generational Diagonal

**Key generational writings cited:**
- **Gail Sheehy**, *Passages* (1976) - ranks among best generational writings for respective cohort-groups
- **Cheryl Merser**, *"Grown-Up!"*: A Generation in Search of Adulthood (1987)
- **Daniel Levinson**, *The Seasons of a Man's Life* (1978)
- **Erik Erikson**, *Childhood and Society* (1950) and *The Life Cycle Completed* (1982)
- **Ellen Lagemann**, *A Generation of Women* (1979)

**Cohort-Group Biography and fallacies:**
- **"Life-course fallacy"** and **"fallacy of cohort-centrism"** - clearly defined in **Matilda White Riley**, "Aging, Social Change, and the Power of Ideas," in Stephen R. Graubard (ed.), *Generations* (1979)
- **Kiley** discusses "Aging and Cohort Succession: Interpretations and Misinterpretations" (POQ, Spring 1973)
- **"Age-bracket fallacy"** - Kiley (1979) calls the "fallacy of age or reification" - Sheehy (1976) quotes **Borges** at the opening of part 1, Levinson (1978)
- **Littré** (1863) first defined "cohort" as everyone born at the same time

**Key definitional sources:**
- **Annie Kriegel**, "Generational Difference: The History of an Idea," in Graubard (1979), *The Generational Diagonal*
- "Aging seems to produce..." is conclusion of **John Crittenden**, "Aging and Party Affiliation" (*POQ*, 1962)
- Nearly a decade later, rebuttals to Crittenden sparked lively debate on aging/generation/maturation/party affiliation
- **"Comment"** and **"Counter Comment"** debates appeared in *ibid.*, 1969-70
- See **Glen and Hefner**, "Further Evidence on Aging and Party Identification" (*ibid.*, Spring 1972)

**1980s aging-Republicanism research:**
- During 1980s, simple aging-Republicanism model at last gave way to **life-alternative hypothesis**
- Perhaps first offered (but little noticed) in **A. Campbell et al.**, *The American Voter* (1960)
- Extent of the early 1930s forged a tie between young adults and the Democratic Party strong enough to withstand advancing age
- Virtually every age-graded political survey taken during 1980s showed persons over age 65 leaning more Democratic than rest of electorate and persons under age 30 leaning more Republican

**Further sources on aging and party affiliation:**
- See *PQ* for best year-by-year summaries of these findings
- See source notes for Chapters 10 and 11
- **Late Life Potential Survey** pathbreaking survey appeared in Schaie, *Longitudinal Studies of Adult Psychological Development* (1983)
- **"Late Life Potential and Cohort Differences in Mental Abilities,"** in Marion Perlmutter (ed.), *Late Life Potentials* (Special Publication Series of the Gerontological Society of America, undated)
- With **Iris Parham**, "Social Responsibility in Adulthood: Ontogenetic and Sociocultural Change" (*Journal of Personality and Social Psychology*, 1974)

**SAT score decline research:**
