## CHAPTER 13: COMPLETING THE MILLENNIAL CYCLE

### Completing the Eras of the Millennial Cycle

- Historical data on life expectancy at age 65: see **SSP**, table 9
- Most recent future projections from **Social Security Administration**, *Annual Report of the Board of Trustees of the Federal Old-Age and Survivors' Insurance and the Federal Disability Insurance Trust Funds* (1990)
- **Gregory Spencer**, *Projections of the Population of the United States, by Age, Sex, and Race: 1988 to 2060* (Bureau of the Census, 1989)
- According to **Census "Middle Series" projections**, life expectancy for men and women at age 65:
  - Will rise from 15.1 and 19.4 years (today) to 16.6 and 21.4 years (in 2020)
  - Further increase to 18.1 and 23.1 years (in 2060)

### Completing the Missionary and Lost Diagonals

- Data and estimates on number of Americans over age 100: see **CPR**, series P-25, no. 153, "America's Centenarians" (Sep 1987)
- Approximate estimate: 1,000 Americans age 109 and over in 1991

<!-- p. 520 -->

### Notes on Sources (continued)

**Social Security and Generational Equity**
- **G.I. Generation** material affluence rising relative to youth/rising adults
- Per capita income, public benefits, numbers of Americans in poverty data by age group from **Peter G. Peterson** and **Neil Howe**, *On Borrowed Time* (1988)
- **Benjamin Franklin** helped his elder brother James **Iampoon Cotton Mather** by writing satirical essays under pseudonym **"Silence Do-Good"** (1722)
- **Cotton Mather's** appreciation of Franklin's efforts in 1784 letter to young **Awakener**
- **Franklin** expressed skepticism about Mather's own "shined" elder generation in *Awakening and the American Revolution: Colonial Thought in the 18th Century* (1971)

**Boom Generation Diagonal**
- **Susan B. Anthony** cited in "Not Every Feminist Is in Pro-Choice Camp," *Washington Times* 7/23/90
- **Social Security Administration** projections of long-term future cost of Social Security cash benefits and Hospital Insurance (**Medicare, Part A**) - accounts for several, demographic, benefits, health-care-cost scenarios
- Scenario closest to actual American experience projects annual cost of **Social Security** cash benefits and **Hospital Insurance** (Medicare, Part A) will exceed 30% of total worker payroll by 2025 and 40% by 2050
- Alternative III projection in **Social Security Administration**, *Annual Report of the Board of Trustees of the Federal Old-Age and Survivors' Insurance and the Federal Disability Insurance Trust Funds* (1990)
- Assumes health-care cost inflation will slow dramatically over next ten years
- Excludes cost of other underfunded federal pension plans (military and civil service retirement) and health care benefit programs (**Medicaid** long-term care and **Medicare, Part B**)
- Total burden would be considerably greater
- **Peterson and Howe** (1988), **Dorcas R. Hardy** and **John L. Palmer** and **Barbara Boyle Torrey**, "Health Care Financing and Pension Programs," in **Gregory B. Mills** and **Palmer** (eds.), *Federal Budget Policy in the 1980s* (1984)
- "Seven in ten" Boomers who doubt Social Security will help them: CBS News poll cited in "Opinion Roundup" (*PO*, Aug.-Sep 1981) and CBS News–*New York Times* poll (Jan 20, 1990)
- **Daniel Yankelovich Group** survey for **IDS Financial Services** (1989): people were if they agreed with statement "I really don't think Social Security will amount to much by the time I retire"
- Of Silent respondents (age 45-64), 36% agreed; of Boomer respondents (age 35-44), 60% agreed—largest generational disparity among all responses to questions about retirement
- "God is in me..." quote appears in **Wallace Stevens**, *Opus Posthumous* (1957)
- "enviable death..." quote from **Winston Churchill**, speech before House of Commons (Apr 17, 1945)

**13er Diagonal**
- Polls showing 13ers place much more importance on financial success than their next-elders at like age
- **UCLA** poll cited in Chapter 5 source notes
- **National Association of Secondary School Principals**, *The Mood of American Youth* (1984), 58-60
- **Roper Organization Inc.**, *The American Chicle Youth Poll* (1987), 18 and 7/4, 1-22
- "But in modern war there is nothing sweet or fitting in your dying. You will die like a dog for no good reason" - **Ernest Hemingway**, "Notes on the Next War," in **George Seldes** (ed.), *The Great Thoughts* (1985), 180
- *Revenge of the Nerds* (film, 1984)

