## Chapter 10: The Silent Generation (continued)

### Generational Identity and Timing

- **Admiral William Crowe** calls them a "transitional generation," **Rose Franzblau** a "Middle Generation"—forever "betwixt and between"
- The Silent boundaries are defined less by what they did than by what those older and younger did—and what the Silent themselves just missed
- First wave came of age too late for war-era heroism but in time to encounter a powerful national consensus—against which young rebels like **James Dean** found themselves "without a cause"
- Last wave graduated just before **Benita Eisler's** "great divide" before the fiery Boom Class of 1965
- Unlike the first wave Boomers, last of the Silent can remember WWII from childhood, and many still took upon the Peace Corps as a generational bond in a way Boomers never have
- 16% of Harvard's Class of '64 joined the Peace Corps (Harvard's top postgraduate destination that year)—whereas next year's graduates began criticizing the Peace Corps amid early stirrings of antiestablishment rebellion

### Life Phase Dynamics

- Silent realize they are generational stuffings of a sandwich between the get-it-done G.I. and the self-absorbed Boom
- Looked to G.I.s for role models in rising adulthood—pursued what then looked like a lifetime mission of refining and humanizing the G.I.-built world
- By mid-1960s, the Silent found themselves "grown up just as the world's gone free-use"
- As **Howard Junker** put it at the time, Silent became fiduciaries of their free-spirited next-juniors, the Boomers
- As songwriters, graduate students, and young attorneys, they mentored the Boom Awakening, founding several of the organizations of political dissent that next-juniors later radicalized
- "During the ferment of the 1960s, a period of the famous 'generation gap,' we occupied, unobtrusively as usual, the gap itself," **Wade Greene** later recognized
- "When nobody over thirty was to be trusted, our age was thirty-something"

### Lifecycle Pattern and Sexual Revolution

- The sexual revolution hit the Silent when most were passing forty, decades after their natural adolescence
- Such awkward timing caused immense problems in family lives and transformed them, said **Franzblau** in 1971, into "a generation of jealousies and role reversals"
- Through the 1970s and early 1980s, the Silent completed the shift from an elder-focused rising adulthood to a youth-focused midlife
- As women turned to feminism, men assembled a mix-and-match masculinity out of fragments from G.I. and Boom
- In *Birth and Fortune*, demographer **Richard Easterlin** labeled his own peer group "the fortunate ones"—whose relatively small size (per cohort) has supposedly given them an edge on life
- Silent have enjoyed a lifetime of steady rising affluence, have suffered relatively few war casualties, and have shown the twentieth century's lowest rates for almost every social pathology of youth (crime, suicide, illegitimate births, teen unemployment)
- Apart from a significant number of divorced women who never remarried, the Silent lifecycle has been an escalator of prosperity, offering maximum reward for minimum initiative

### Philosophy and Values

- No other living generation could half-believe in **Ellen Goodman's** "Woody Allen school of philosophy: 80 percent of life is showing up"
- The outward good fortune of their lifecycle has been denied on a clear blue screen—the banner headlines that they see, at times enviously, so well connected to others
- However much they try, Silent have never succeeded in generating the snap of catharsis felt by G.I.s or Boomers
- Where G.I.s did great things and felt one with history, where Boomers found ravishment within themselves, the Silent have taken great things for granted and looked beyond themselves while worrying that, somehow, the larger challenges of life are passing them by
- So they have been keen on manufacturing points of lifecycle reference around personal (rather than historical) markers
- Whatever phase of life they occupy is fraught with what various Silent authors have labeled "passages," "seasons," "turning points," or other names bearing little or no relation to the larger flow of public events

### Social Impact and Contributions

**Silent strengths:**
- Well aware of their own deficiencies, the Silent have spent a lifetime plumbing inner wellsprings older G.I.s seldom felt while maintaining a sense of social obligation Boomers haven't shared
- Their solutions—fairness, openness, due process, expertise—reflect a lack of surefootedness, but also a keen sense of how and why humans fall short of grand civic plans or ideal moral standards
- Silent appeals for change have seldom arisen from anger or fury, but rather through a self-conscious humanity and tender social conscience
- "Deep in my heart, I do believe / We shall overcome someday"—leading an inside voice, they have adopted the moral relativism of the skilled arbitrator, mediating arguments between others and reaching out to people of all cultures, races, ages, and handicaps
- "We don't arrive with ready-made conclusions so much as a honed capacity to ask and to listen," says **Greene**
- Have helped bridge gaps, be a time of immense, extraordinarily complicated and potentially divisive changes

**The Silent malleability paradox:**
- This very malleability has left the Silent unable to build a secure generational family lives
- "If anything has changed in the last generation," admits **Ellen Goodman**, "it is the erosion of confidence" among parents, "totally uncertain about how we are doing"
- In *Private Lives*, **Benita Eisler** labels hers the generation with "a corpse in the trunk"—the R-rated decade of the 1970s
- That era in which so much seemed to go wrong in America coincided precisely with the Silent urge to influence over national life

### The 1970s Crisis and "Toffler Index"

- In *Future Shock*, the book that keynoted that decade, **Alvin Toffler** foresaw a forthcoming "historic crisis of adaptation"—and called for "the moderation and regulation of change" with "exact scientific knowledge, expertly applied to the crucial, most sensitive points of social control"
- But as Toffler's peers began applying this cult of expertise, they encountered their turbulent passage to midlife—and what **Toffler** labeled the "transience index" began exploding upward
- As the Silent broke and remade relationships, families splintered, substance abuse moved past euphoria to social damage, and American society felt its G.I.-era sensation of belonging fall away
- Entire generation of **Daniel Ellsbergs** pushed to get secrets out (and take clothes off), their **Phil Donahues** and **Ted Koppels** aimed microphones everywhere, hoping more dialogue would somehow build a better society
- Meanwhile, productivity stagnated, the economy sputtered, and the nation endured a series of global humiliations
- In *Zero-Sum Society*, **Lester Thurow** suggested that, increasingly, improvement in the condition of any one group came at the expense of another
- What **Jerry Brown** called "the age of limits" became (in **William Schneider's** words) "the Zeitgeist theme of his generation"

### Reagan Era Transformation

- By time 1970s ended, an elder G.I. won the Presidency in part by ridiculing this midlife mind-set
- Reagan at the helm, the America of the 1980s did in many ways become a Silent-style Tofflerian "ad hocracy" stressing expertise over simplicity, participation over authority, process over result
- Corporations began directing more attention to organization and financing than to the products they made
- Public over- and under-regulation became hot political issues, prompting *Time* magazine to play off memories of *It Happened One Night* by making "The Can't Government" the subject of a 1989 cover story
- Where the word "liberal" had once referred to a G.I.-style constituency nationalism, its meaning transformed into a Silent-style enervator attuned to multitudinous special interests
- "Beware of liberals who came of age politically in the 1930s," warns **George Will**
- Likewise, the definition of "conservative" evolved from a Lost-style cautious stewardship to the faintly hip, high-rolling optimism of the Silent's new easy-Yside school
- Neoliberal to Neoconservative, flexible quotas to Laffer curves, this generation moved toward a cohesive con-age mindset—looking back to the G.I.s as the "hypocrites" supplysiders idolize (the recollection that in their youth, "the old bastards were the conservatives. Now the young people are becoming the conservatives and we are the old bastards")

### Political Style and Leadership

- "Liberal or not, the criterion is whether they get lost in Lonely Crowd musings or stick close to affirmative action, the free market, an incentive tax rate, a UN resolution, or the compromise verdict of some expert panel"
- On both sides of the political spectrum, the Silent would much prefer to discuss processes than outcomes
- In their hands, America has grown more accustomed to deferring or learning to live with problems than to taking aggressive steps to solve them
- Thanks to the size and complexity of the U.S. economy, tenured professors foresee at worst a slow parabola of national descent
- While **Brookings' Henry Aaron** remains confident that "the nation can muddle through without absolute decline," Congressional leaders set priorities through decision-avoidance mechanisms like the **Gramm-Rudman Act** (or its sequel), "**Gramm-Rudman II**")
- The foreign policy trend-setters lean toward **James Baker**-style multilateralism and a deference to international law
- What **Joseph Nye** has called "soft power, the complex machinery of interdependence"
- "Industrialists have been replaced by technologists who manage 'M-Form' corporations, financial holding companies long on flexibility and short on product accountability"
- Businesses run "cultural audits" of their employees, **Ben Wattenberg's** "Gross National Spirit" index charts the nation's feelings, and **John Naisbitt** heralds such "Megatrends" as an "Information Age" of "high-tech/high-touch"

### Cultural Fragmentation

- Endowed with unlimited turn-their-attention to every new personal injustice
- Oil companies portray themselves as nice guys, eager to placate their harshest critics
- A Silent-nominated Judiciary Committee rejects a like-aged Supreme Court nominee (**Bork**) for being too abrasive, while embracing another (**Souter**) for promising that personal opinions would "play absolutely no role" in his rulings on abortion
- The Census Bureau checks bridges and sewers to see that every American is counted
- Under the Silent, America has become more of a finder, more communicative place
- It has also become culturally fragmented and less globally competitive

### The "End of Empire" Anxieties

- Today's 50- and 60-year-olds have been less successful in forging a sense of national or personal direction than any generation in living memory
- Like **Robert Bellah** in *Habits of the Heart*, many Silent feel haunted by a diffuse nectedness they see in American life
- While **Kevin Phillips** describes an America shadowed by an "End of Empire fixation," and **Paul Kennedy's** Imperialist white-collar workforce haunted by a "fear of falling," **Jack Kemp** foresees exhilarating prosperity and **George Gilder** "a global community of commerce... a global ganglion of electronic and photonic media that leaves all history in its wake"
- What mostly emerges is fuss and detail, a world view of such enormous complexity that their own contributions often lack one redeeming description ("perfect but wrong")
- Sensing this, they feel—deep down—a wounded collective ego
- Having grown up playing the child's version of Sorry, the Silent cannot abandon what Sheehy calls this "resignation," a vague dissatisfaction with jobs, families, their children, themselves
- Approaching their own old age, many still find themselves emotionally obliged to struggling children in what **Robert Grossman** terms "Parenthood II"
- "My kids are so early-retirement-bound in mid-life bonanzas that the nation can currently afford simply because (as **Easterlin** accurately predicted) their generation is relatively small in numbers"
- Most aging Silent find themselves wealthier, but more confused as to purpose, than they ever imagined they would be at this phase of life

### Economic and Social Landscape

- As **Toffler** suggests in *Powershift*—and **Tom Peters** in *Thriving on Chaos*—the pace of social and economic change has accelerated beyond anyone's ability to control it
- The best Americans can do, suggests **Toffler**, is to run faster themselves
- The peers of **Gail Sheehy** are thus encountering a new life "passage" that **Daniel Levinson** describes as "a silent despair, a pressing fear of becoming derelict"
- Many also feel that unnerving quality that **Paul Goodman** saw in **Pat Schroeder's** brief run for the Presidency: "a desire to make it to the top" with "a deep concern about how you make it"
- **Fanny, You Don't Look Like a Grandmother**, observes the title of **Lois Wyse's** 1990 book, targeted at Silent first-wavers who are beginning to transform elderhood around a decidedly un-G.I.-like other-directedness

### The "Grandtravel" Generation

- Travel agents report a new boom business in "grandtravel" (grandparent-grandchild trips)
- New interest in "Eldernostels"—reminiscent of the way the Silent toured Europe as youths
- Self-styled "kids over 60" have formed a "SeniorNet" computer network
- In 1989, affluent mid-sixtyish Social Security beneficiaries formed a "21st Century Club" whose members will assign their checks to a philanthropic trust fund
- The Silent-led Virginia state legislature recently raised revenues by limiting tax breaks for Silent (but not G.I.) retirees
- **Ralph Nader** is mobilizing "Princeton Project '55" around the "suppressed crusades among the classmates," many of whom have become financially successful beyond their self-legislate imaginings, but who share an eagerness to join **Nader** in attacking "systemic social problems"
- Their agenda remains large: In 1986, the Union of International Associations catalogued 10,000 world problems awaiting solution—and the Silent Generation is running out of time

### Historical Memory and Legacy

- Nearly four decades after the Korean War, no national memorial exists for its veterans, prompting one fund-raiser to complain how they were being treated "as if they have never lived, never ennobled their time and place, never contributed to destiny"
- Though their own generation is an easy touch for other people's charities, Silent veterans have been slow to assemble funds for this one commemoration to themselves
- Their memorial, if it is built, will have no two lima giants doing great deeds, nor will it make any moral statement like the dark walls of the Vietnam Memorial
- Instead, it will depict thirty-eight life-size soldiers in two slightly crooked columns, walking through a forest to nowhere in particular

### Current Challenges

- "The Silent Generation Is Clearing Its Throat," proclaimed Florida newspaper editor **Tom Kelly** as the 1990s dawned
- "All together now, let's hear it (cordially, please, but with feeling) for the Silent Generation, those overriddled and underdepreciated people"
- This modesty is disarming in a generation two of whose members (**Neil Armstrong** and **Martin Luther King, Jr.**) will likely remain, in some distant epoch, among the most celebrated Americans
- The peers of Armstrong and King may someday be credited at the operational edge of contemporary history, diversified the culture, made democracy work for the disadvantaged, and—as one friend eulogized of **Jim Henson**—struck "a Muppet-like balance 'between the sacred and the silly'"
- "Above all, the generation that took America from grinding bulldozers to user-friendly computers, from the circa-1960 'Nuclear Age' into the circa-1990 'Information Age,' has excelled at *personal communication*"

### Conflict Management and Social Contribution

- The Silent have consistently tried, and often succeeded, in defusing conflict by encouraging people to talk to each other
- "From therapeutic T-groups to family problems to 'Donahue'-style 'global town meetings'" on issues of major importance
- They have thus lent flexibility to a G.I.-built world that otherwise would otherwise have split to pieces under Boom attack—and have helped mollify, and ultimately cool, the Boom's coming-of-age passions
- Indeed, the Silent have been pathbreakers for much of the 1960s-era "consciousness" (from music to film, civil rights to ecology to feminism) for which Boomers too often claim credit
- From youth forward, this most considerate of living generations has specialized not in grand bright institutions to forty ideals, but rather in people, *life-size people* like the statues planned for the Korean War Memorial
- **Barbra Streisand's** agemates would like to believe that "people who need people are the luckiest people in the world"
- But, true to form, they have their doubts

### Looking Forward

- Much of this doubt might be resolved if America can someday inaugurate a new President who wore the blue 1950s-era duckbill-era pompadour, who served in the Peace Corps, who maybe spent a summer with SNCC in Mississippi, and who cried as only 30-year-olds did when Martin and Bobby died
- In 1990, when the mostly Silent U.S. Congress wildly cheered the Czech playwright-dissident-President **Vaclav Havel**, many were no doubt recalling those old coffeehouse days and thinking: Here is exactly the sort of avant-garde President we thought we'd someday give the world
- Until they do, the story of their own generation will read, to them, like the middle pages of a book written mainly about somebody else

## Chapter 11: The Millennial Cycle

### Woodstock Anniversary (1989)

- "Suddenly the Woodstock generation was not wonderfully young, but wonderfully old, somehow, full of wisdom, a kind of Druidic savvy signaled by long hair, walking staffs and face paint accompanied by the thousand-yard squint they'd get after smoking marijuana" —**Washington Post's Henry Allen**, 1989
- One of the many 1989 perspectives making the twentieth anniversary of the 1969 Woodstock Arts and Music Fair at Bethel, New York
- As a smattering of celebrants returned to the historic marker (dubbed "The Tomb of the Unknown Hippie") on **Max Yasgur's** field, the Boomer-dominated media published scores of commemoratives to take stock of the prior two decades
- Twenty years had passed since the late-1960s days of "generational consciousness"—roughly the span of another generation
- Journalists fixated on aging radicals like 45-year-old **Grace Slick** (whose old Jefferson Airplane slogan "Feed your head" she now reinterpreted to mean "Go home and read a book") and 42-year-old **Arlo Guthrie** ("Everybody wears suits more than I thought they would, but that's cosmetic")

### The Emerging Millennial Generation

- But with the passing of two decades, Woodstock had already left a clear legacy—for the three (or what history suggests will be four) generation **MILLENNIAL Cycle**:
- **Grace Slick's** self-absorbed **BOOM GENERATION** (Idealist, then age 29 to 46) included the overwhelming majority of the 400,000 youths in their late teens and twenties who had attended the original event, plus uncounted millions of others who had partaken in the festivals, be-ins, teach-ins, strikes, and assorted other youth gatherings of the Woodstock era

### Thirteenth Generation at Woodstock

- Other notable events of the Boomer coming-of-age years—the Chicago convention riot, People's Park, Altamont, Kent State—had been deadlier and were remembered more soberly, if at all
- By now, Boomers were busy trying to keep their own children from replaying their own youthful exuberances
- Where the original (Silent) production of *Hair* had stripped a Boomer cast of clothes, a twentieth-anniversary (Boom) reissue stripped the musical of offensive lyrics, turning a song entitled "Sodomy" into a saxophone solo
- Boomers remained just as ethics-absorbed as always, but Woodstock's "New Age" heirs now had to share the generational spotlight with their slightly younger evangelical peers, who had glimpsed the original rock concert as grade school or high school students
- Wherever Boomers rented old Woodstock videos to celebrate the occasion, the punkish part-timers behind the checkout counter probably belonged to the **THIRTEENTH GENERATION** (Reactive, age 8 to 28)
- For the most part, these $6-an-hour youths kept their mouths shut while overhearing 40-year-olds revel in their culture of peak having a fix everything ethos—what every person should be around age 20
- To these kids, rehashing Woodstock was a waste of time: Just look at the mess it left behind—for example, the drug-related deaths of seven festival performers (and who knows how many thousands of participants) over the ensuing two decades
- But, never having known anything remotely like these, they never considered themselves lucky they were also aware of the possible Boomer comeback: Okay, so what did you guys ever do together?—invade Grenada? Go wilding? Watch the *Challenger* explosion?

### Millennial Reaction to Boomer Nostalgia

- They wondered to themselves, a few 13ers revealed a rising alienation in their letter-to-the-editor reactions to Boomer commentatives like **John Cunningham**, whose editorial asked "—Deceit, and **Jeffrey Hoogeven**, who pointedly told Boomers "the Sixties are history—history that the rest of us don't need repeated and crammed down our throats"
- **Hoogeveen's** peers had been the forgotten toddlers of the Woodstock era, kids who by now were old enough to check out such hippie-ish videos as *Easy Rider* and *Hair*—and who, like *The Wonder Years'* **Olivia D'Abo**, knew how to imitate or avoid Boomerisms, whichever came in handy

### Birth of the Millennial Generation

- Back in 1969, Boomer festivals had celebrated themselves; twenty years later, their midsummer outings invariably featured the budding **MILLENNIAL GENERATION** (Civic, age 7 and under)
- Where many a Boomer had hitchhiked to Woodstock, taking rides from goodness knows whom and ingesting goodness knows what when they got there (no doubt feeding a few 13er babies some mind-expanding leftovers), their tots traveled there


<!-- pp. 301-316 -->

## Boom Generation (Born 1943-1960)

### Type: Idealist

**Age Location:** Boom Awakening in rising adulthood

### Coming of Age Context

- **1965:** *Time* magazine declared teenagers "on the fringe of a golden era"—predicted they would build blight-proof cities, enrich the underdeveloped world, write poetry finis
- **Boomer prophecies collapsed one by one** as generation became "a surly political powerhouse" capable of sweeping candidates from White House
- **George McGovern (1972):** First tempting candidacy, then demise—**Richard Shlesinger** predicted lifelong "inadequacy" from peer-on-peer competition
- **Annie Gottlieb** (*Do You Believe in Magic?*): Boomers recall "time" as the 1960s, a decade with newfound solidarity over other generations

### Generational Identity & First Wave vs. Last Wave

- **Eighteen years of birth (1943):** First cohort with G.I. optimism rewarded in victory over fascism and election of G.I. President
- **Unlike Silent:** No childhood recollection of WWII, no lingering "victim-of-fate" (from cohort caught in Vietnam War)
- **Unlike 13ers:** All reaching adolescence before draft ended
- **1943 "victory babies"** ranked among most self-satisfied in American history; **last cohorts remembered by college faculties as last pre-Reagan-era students** to show Boomish intellectual arrogance and social immaturity
- **VJ-Day forward:** Cultural and spiritual focal point for American society—childhood America-obsessed, youth youth-obsessed, "yuppie" phase yuppie-obsessed
- **Mission:** Not constructing society but **justifying and purifying it**—G.I.s learned basics, Boomers learned **critical thinking**

> "We are Bomb Babies... We grew up with fallout in our milk." —23-year-old Ronald Allison, 1967

- **Radcliffe senior (1968):** "We do not feel like a cool, swinging generation—we are eaten up by an intensity we cannot name"
- **1980:** 12-point October shift among Boom voters turned Reagan landslide

### The Consciousness Revolution (1967-1980)

- **William McLoughlin:** "Fourth Awakening"—began in earnest 1967 with **Summer of Love**, inner-city riots, San Francisco counterculture
- **Peaked 1970** with Kent State and Days of Rage on campuses
- **Throughout 1970s:** Human potential movement, **Aquarian Conspiracy** (New Age transformation), rise of "Jesus people" and resurgent evangelicalism
- **Awakening ebbed sharply in late 1970s** with growing pessimism—Boomer **Patrick Caddell** labeled it "malaise"
- **Ended 1980** as rates of crime and substance abuse among coming-of-age Americans peaked
- **Reagan's election** (endorsed by Boom) marked acceptance of rising-adult social roles by **no-longer-youthful cadre of 1960s kids**

> "AGE LOCATION: G.I.s in elderhood; Silent in midlife; Boomers in rising adulthood; 13ers in youth."

### Generational Gap and Family Dynamics

- Waged across generation gap between **Boomers and G.I.s**—began within families as revolt against fathers
- Older Americans who studied Young Radicals in late 1960s struck by **attachment to mothers** and **ambivalence** (**Keniston**), **oedipal rebellion** (**Malcolm**), or **Patricide** (**Feuer**)
- Youth fury over Vietnam helped spread **patriphobia** beyond family—most memorable youth symbols were direct affronts against G.I. constructions
- **G.I. over-runner** (whose forerunner had enabled G.I.s to overrun enemy pillboxes) and **long-fingered peace taunt** ridiculed the very symbol of G.I. "victory"
- **Defiant wearing of khaki** (G.I. color of uniformed teamwork) and **desecration of that symbol** in American flag
- **Hippie invasion of Disneyland, burning of Isla Vista Bank, Earth Day burial of automobile**—even as society-wide generational attitudes receded in 1970s, **Boom ethos remained deliberate antithesis** to everything G.I.

### Self and Narcissism

- **Quest for "self"**—**Tom Wolfe:** "voyage to the interior"; **Christopher Lasch:** "culture of narcissism"
- Central theme: Rising adulthood through **Chutzpah** (suspended animation, resisting permanent linkages to mates, children, corporations, professions)
- **Katharine Ross** (*The Graduate*): Boomers approached life after (or nursery, or corporate ladder) and heard something inside scream *"STOP!"*
- **G.I. coming-of-age treadmill** jammed the gears of the Silent-era—Boomers found themselves in social no-man's-land, unable to satisfy perfectionist impulses
- Simply **grazed**, lending no more than casual interest to world around them, applying what sounded like **pick-and-choose idealism**

### Boomer Perfectionism and Consumption

- Desire for ***the best*** within very personal (often financially austere) definition of taste
- If couldn't afford house/family, could at least afford **very best brand of mustard or ice cream**—"Zen luxuriousness" (Katy Butler: maximum possible enjoyment out of minimum consumption)
- Mixture of **high self-esteem** and **selective self-indulgence**—reputation for grating arrogance and **transcendent cultural wisdom**

### Inner vs. Outer Standards

- **Fixation on self** forged instinct to make plans/judgments according to **wholly internalized standards**, based on immutable principles of right and wrong
- Gift for deductive logic over inductive logic—experimentation made Boomers **better philosophers than scientists, better preachers than builders**
- **Highest-testing Boom cohorts (mid-1940s births)** reached age where scientific achievement peaks—**yet Boomers were "very late to win a Nobel Prize"**
- **Thomas Gech** winning first in 1989 (Lost, G.I., and Silent won two, four, and six, respectively)
- Excelled in **occupations calling for creative transcendence over the media**—exalting individual conscience over duty to community
- Have difficulty achieving consensus and mobilizing as unit—**making them far weaker than G.I.s at getting big jobs done**
- Generational identity = **Beatlean "Pepperland"**—zone of parallel play—versus G.I. sense of **"together" people not collectively but *individually***

> "Like Donald Trump, a prototype Boomer sees himself capable of becoming a titan of whatever world he chooses fully to inhabit—providing cover for personal disappointments or (as a Boomer might put it) 'deferred' ambitions." —Authors

### Coming of Age: Inner Catharsis and Spiritual Search

- Sustained **compelling urge for perfection** of rigorous impulses and reducing dependence on physical self
- **Adolescent Boom radicals:** Keniston noted "great intensification of largely self-generated religious feelings"—despite relatively nonreligious childhood background
- **Drug phase:** Transcendence in first wave (passed from), crime in last wave, and **by 1990 stripped of spiritual trappings** by Boomers (coffee-seekers, especially) who didn't enjoy what they repeatedly ingested
- Subsequent search for spiritual euphoria: **flocked from drugs to religion**—"Jesus" movements, ecumenicalism, **New Age utopianism, millennialist visions**
- **Spawned most active era of church formation of the twentieth century**

### Gender and Sexuality

- **Hermaphroditic, pistil-and-stamen quality**—**Wanda Urbanska** (*The Singular Generation*): exalted "self-sexuality," ability to give pleasure to oneself
- **Men:** Intruding into domain of work and nurturance; mainly belonged to **G.I. mothers and teachers**
- **Women:** Invading secular roles once reserved for can-do G.I. males
- Trends made Boomers **more independent of each other** in bonds, yet **more open to isolation and economic insecurity**
- **Concerned male peers may be unreliable providers**, Boomer women wary of peers as husbands—fear **early marriage and family may worsen future household standard of living**

### Schism: First Wave vs. Last Wave

- **Schism between mostly fortyish modernists and New Agers at one edge**, mostly **thirtyish traditionalists and evangelicals at the other**
- **Clash on compromise of matters of principle**—e.g., anti-abortionist **Bill Tickel**: "it's just easier to have blanket absolutes"
- **First wave vs. last wave differences widely noted** by pollsters and marketers at each end
- **"Victory" and "hello" babies of mid-to-late 1940s** were first boomers; **most pampered entirely by G.I.s**, not long after **peak years of parental protectiveness**
- **Babies of conformist late 1950s** were parented mostly by Silent and G.I. protoparents—giving way, came of age at point of **maximum freedom** (some say chaos) in adolescent life
- **Last-wave Boomers faced worse** in educational aptitude, financial security, self-direction behavior
- **First-wave Boomers fared worse in marital stability**—partly because married earlier (G.I. cohorts ended precisely the opposite trends, first wave to last)
- **But measured by inner-life standards, two ends of Boom feel equally serene**

### The "Great American Boom"

- **1946:** *Fortune* declared start of "the Great American Boom"—not just in fertility, but also in education, housing, science
- **Robust achievements and optimism** left lasting mark on children
- **If G.I.s measure worth objectively** (by works they leave behind), **Boomers measure themselves subjectively** (by works they see within)
- Many having difficulty matching parents' like-aged achievements in economic/family life
- **Yet invariably consider their "consciousness" to be higher**—by that yardstick, doing very well

> "If it's by choice and it's not overwhelming, having no money can be a way of entering more deeply into your life." —**Katy Butler**

- **American Dream lives on**—in form of **well-ravished soul**, not worldly standard

## Boomer Facts

### Demographics & Family

- **Roughly half of postwar "baby boom"** attributed to unusual fecundity, **other half to unusual bunching of family formation**
- **Baby bulge 1946-1957** resulted from coincident babymaking of late-nesting G.I.s and early-nesting Silent
- After 1957, most last-wave Boomers (and first-wave 13ers) resulted from larger childbearing of Silent-headed families
- In training, confidence, time spent changing bedsheets, **no generation of American women can match G.I.s for intensity of nurture**
- Boom children: Among preschoolers who had working mothers, **four in five cared for in own homes, usually by relatives**—only 2% attended child care

### Childhood Health & Education

- **G.I. science made sweeping advances** against childhood illness—conquered polio, once-terrible diseases as diphtheria and polio, fluoridated water
- **Pediatrics reached its height** of physical aggressiveness—6 kids had more operations, including **millions of circumcisions and tonsillectomies** that would not now be performed

### Youth Pathologies

- **By almost any standard of social pathology, Boom = generation of worsening trends**
- **First-wave to last-wave teenagers:** Death rates for every form of accidental death rose sharply—rates of drunk driving, suicide, illegitimate births, teen unemployment all **doubled or tripled**
- **Crime rates mounted with each successive cohort**—gave rise after mid-1960s to "crime waves" that seemed to worsen with each passing year
- **During 1970s:** Incidence of serious youth crime grew **twice as fast** as number of youths
- **Criminals in 1982:** Were **more likely than criminals born in 1945 to commit multiple crimes**—and **80% more likely to send victims to hospital or morgue**

### Education Statistics

- **17-year SAT slide spanned nearly entire Boom** (1946 cohort to 1963/13er cohort)—yet **worst years coincided with greatest grade inflation ever measured**
- **1969:** 4% of college freshmen claimed to have had straight-A high school average
- **1978:** That proportion had nearly tripled, to **11%**
- **1969-1975:** Average collegiate grade rose from C+ to A- (in 1971), **three-fourths of all colleges offered alternatives to traditional marking systems**

### Sexual Revolution

- **More a women's than men's movement**
- Comparing 1970s with 1950s, one survey showed **Boomer men with only a 3% increase** in sexual activity over what Silent did at like age—**smallest increase for any age bracket over that span**
- **Proportion of male youths experiencing premarital sex rose only slightly** from Silent to Boom eras
- **By contrast, Boomer women doubled rate of premarital sex** over Silent (from 41% to 81%) and **tripled relative propensity to commit adultery** (from one-fourth to three-fourths the rate for men)

### Vietnam War

- **Effort to avoid service more pervasive generational bond** than service in war itself
- **Only one Boomer man in sixteen ever saw combat**
- Among all rest, **two-thirds attributed avoidance to deliberate dodge**
- One Boomer in six accelerated marriage or fatherhood, one in ten juggled jobs for deferment; while one in twenty-five abused body to flunk physical
- **1% of Boomer men committed draft-law felonies**—ten times percentage killed in combat, **far more than one of every hundred offenders was ever jailed**
- **1943-1947 cohorts** provided bulk of draft avoiders; **1947-1953 cohorts** most of combat troops
- **Median soldier age during Vietnam War (17)** = **lowest in American history**

### Vietnam War Attitudes

- **Boom's only consensus "lesson"**: war was **badly handled by G.I. leaders**
- **Before 1970:** Boomer opinion split roughly 50-50 over basic issue of U.S. presence in Southeast Asia
- **Only after Kent State shootings and "Days of Rage"** did most college-attending Boomers oppose the war
- **Non-college Boomers remained more prowar than any elder group** (college-educated or not)
- **Today:** One Boomer in four considers Vietnam to have been a **"noble cause"** (highest proportion for any generation)
- Generation splits roughly **50-50 between those who think U.S. should have stayed out** and **those who would have fought to win**
- Following **Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990**, Boomers **more inclined than any other generation** to believe sending American troops to Gulf was "the right thing" to do

### Religion

- **During 1980s:** Rising-adult Boomers migrated out of mainline "established" churches, but **surged into New Age and evangelical sects**
- **Overall Boom church attendance rose by nearly 30%** through decade
- **America's fastest-growing church = Assembly of God** (whose membership quadrupled in 1980s)
- **Largest branch of Protestantism = fundamentalist Southern Baptist church**
- Number of "charismatic" or "pentecostal" Catholics has quintupled
- **America now has more Muslims than Episcopalians**
- **Seven Boomers in ten believe in psychic phenomena** (versus five in ten among older generations)
- Within generation, polls show **first-wave Boomers believing more in meditation and reincarnation**, **last-wavers more in "born-again" conversion**, meditative wealth vs. inherent conflict between religion and science

### Political Behavior

- **1988 Presidential primaries:** Boomers gave **greatest generational support to twooveraged candidates** of race—**Pat Robertson and Jesse Jackson** (G.I.s gave them least support)

### Economic Position

- Were it not for employed women (and dual-income households), **Boomer family incomes would be well below what Silent earned at like age**
- **Married Boomer couples are doing slightly better** than their prior-era like-aged elders did; **single women much better**
- **But individual Boomer man is not:** 40-year-old first-waver earns about **15% more than his Silent father at like age**, whereas **30-year-old last-waver has fallen about 10% behind** his Silent father
- **Between age 30 and 40** (where typical full-time G.I. worker enjoyed 63% inflation-adjusted rise in income), **first-wave Boom worker suffered net 1% decline**

### Self-Assessment

- Asked to compare themselves economically with fathers at same phase of life, Boomers evenly split over whether **they are doing better or worse**
- Yet **overwhelmingly consider their careers better** (by five-to-one ratio), **personal freedoms greater** (by six to one), and **their lives more meaningful** (by nine to one)

## The Boom Lifecycle

### YOUTH: Hothouse Nurture

- **G.I. Eda LeShan:** "We wanted our children to be inner-directed... It seemed logical to us that fascism and communism... could not really succeed except in countries where children were raised in very authoritarian homes"
- **Boom children enjoyed hothouse nurture** in intensely child-focused households and communities
- **G.I. dads worked to pay bills, G.I. moms applied "democratic discipline"**—dealing with children "thoughtfully, reasonably, and kindly"
- Seeking advice, moms turned to pediatrician **Benjamin Spock**, who mixed science with friendliness and instructed G.I. peers that "we need idealistic children"

### Permissive Parenting

- **Spock-guided moms applied "permissive" feeding schedule to infants**
- Extending this logic to older kids, can-I-child-say-career moms **invested tremendous maternal time and energy in grade-school classes**
- Hosted Cub Scout meetings, chaperoned field trips to museums, applied **"He'll-clean-up-his-room-when-he's-ready-to-have-a-clean-room" philosophy**
- First-wave Boomers passed through **public schools in their Sputnik-era peak of institutional confidence**—powerful mutual support network between G.I. mothers and teachers
- **Many a child's life in 1950s** preserved in **vintage television sit-coms**
- To eye of Boomer kid, any problem seemed fixable by adults, especially once **white-coated scientists came on the scene**
- To youths like **Cheryl Merser** (especially new-white-collar-scientist class): "Watching over them—God or a saint or a guardian angel or the stars or whatever... the future looked to be 'the way life was on *The Jetsons*'—bright, easy, uncomplicated, prosperous"
- **To most middle-class youths:** Poverty, disease, and crime were invisible—or if not, temporary nuisances that would soon succumb to **inexorable advance of affluence**

### Adolescent Shift

- As successive Boom cohorts passed through childhood, **adult nurturing style leaned more toward tolerance than guidance**
- Parents began **second-guessing sacrifices** they were making for their kids
- **Circa-1970 campus behavior swiftly filtered down to kids in high school, even junior high**
- By now reflecting **Silent ethos**, public schools began losing its **G.I. norm-teacher peer support system**
- **Reform-minded educators** began insisting adults had as much to learn from youths as vice versa
- **Curriculum stressed learning over subject matter, social relevance over timeless facts**
- **New student "rights"** were litigated; old extracurricular activities atrophied
- **Adolescent boy-girl coupling** became increasingly tentative and individualized, where Silent had gone "steady"
- **Boomers went "with" someone**—popular song lyrics gradually turned from Silentish styles (today-we're-numbered as "high" rock) to more Boom-driven pessimism and defiance associated with "hard" (or "acid") rock
- **Silent-era couples-only Saturday-night dance nearly vanished**, eclipsed by **rock concerts** at which dateless teenagers could dance night away all by themselves if wanted
- **First Boomer cohorts came of sexual age with Beatles** (*I Wanna Hold Your Hand*), **middle cohorts with Rolling Stones** (*Let's Spend the Night Together*), **late cohorts with Bruce Springsteen** (*Dancing in the Dark*)
- Whether first-wavers asserting creative role in idealized future or last-wavers attempting more defiant withdrawal from world, **adolescents looked within themselves to find solutions to life's problems**

### COMING OF AGE: Student Rebellion

> "I Am a Student! Do Not Fold, Spindle, or Mutilate!" —Pickets outside Berkeley's Sproul Hall, 1964

- Where student movements had once been work of lonely hero or political purist, **youths began swarming to angry rallies**
- **Coffeehouse poets gave way to bullhorn-toting radicals**, in what Silent activists **Peter Collier and David Horowitz** recall as **generational shift**

> "Those of us who had come of age in the fifties" and "were more comfortable thinking or talking about it" gave way to later-born "second wave of activists" more likely to heed simple motto: "*Do it!*"

- With dawning of Silent-led but **Boom-energized "Free Speech Movement,"** these undergraduates served first notice of what would become **most emotionally intense and culturally influential youth rebellion in American history**
- **Next four years** brought series of angry youth uprisings at schools, military depots, inner cities—joined by **mixture of idealists dressed down, donned unisex clothing**, and **like-minded "nonstudents"** who hung around campuses
- **Wealthy kids dressed down to reject affluence** and ordered family lives of their parents

> "I want everyone to see me and say 'There goes an enemy of the state,' because that's what we are, we are at revolution biz." —**James Kunen**, *The Strawberry Statement*

- **"STRIKE!" became the summons**, clenched fist the emblem, **T-shirts and jeans the uniform** of corporate liberalism
- **"Who are these people?"** asked Silent **Daniel Moynihan**, then on Harvard faculty: "I suggest to you they are Christians arrived on the scene of Second Century Rome"

### Radical Youth Culture

- **Screaming radicals and freaked-out "hippies" represented just 10 to 15% of their generation**, but the righteous often prevailed in youth culture where **purity of moral position counted most**
- In sharp contrast to depression-era days of G.I. student "isms," **organization counted for little**
- **Keniston** notes how the "young radicals" of late 1960s, having grown up with **"feelings of loneliness, solitude, and isolation," were profoundly mature by measures of ego strength and self-esteem**, yet **still childlike in social skills**
- **Collegians could issue "nonnegotiable demands" with little fear** of later consequences—in part because of amnesty they always demanded (and usually received), but also because **supercharged G.I.-led economy offered good jobs to all comers**
- **Arguments of New Left** (led by "red diaper" babies who were waging their own battle against Old Left G.I. fathers) **tended to be moral and cultural**, with virtually no appeal off-campus
- Yet **similar depth of rage welled up among Boomers who showed no affinity with college strikers**
- **Urban black youths sparked deadly riots** in American cities; non-college white Boomers were **twice as likely as their elders to vote for George Wallace** in 1968 election
- Many town-versus-gown scuffles of that era were, in the main, **Boom-on-Boom affairs**

### Vietnam War and Youth Rebellion

- With economy still purring, **youth frenzy congealed around Vietnam War**—policy construction almost perfectly designed to create conflict between **rationalist elders and spiritualist juniors**
- Waging it as **limited, scientifically managed form of internationalist pest control**, G.I. leaders supported morally questionable ally and avoided asking for contribution from noncombatants (LBJ's "guns and butter")
- Thought not pacifist by nature, **Boomers had been raised to question, argue, and ultimately disobey orders not comporting with self-felt standards and ultimate sacrifices**
- As much as Boomers hated war, what they hated worse was **draft**—intrusive on privacy, its aided policy of **"channeling" their lives in government-approved directions**
- With help from **Silent counsel**, Boomers went to good at nullifying it
- For draft, enormous **class bias created festering divisions** between Boomers who went to Vietnam and those who didn't
- For those who came of age in Southeast Asia, **war offered little glory and few fond memories**—the **most celebrated Boom soldiers were G.I. POWs** like **Jeremiah Denton** (or, in film, aging "Green Beret" **John Wayne**), most famous firefight was Hill 937, and most poignant, atrocity, and anti-heroism

### 1969: Peak of Youth Rebellion

- **Vietnam casualties peaked in same year (1969)** that Boom rebellion turned bloody, with **eighteen-month spate of radical bombings and shootings**—and **surge in street violence**
- **Youths then felt what Gitlin described as "tolerance, a fascination, even a taste" for violence**
- According to **Gallup Poll 1970**, **44% of all college students** (versus 20% of age peers at large) believed **violence was justified to bring about social change**
- **Rap Brown** called violence "as American as apple pie"
- **Angela Davis** used it to great media effect; photo of **Patty Hearst** suggests it bank-holding gun
- Older generations fear **latent urges in most normal-looking people** her age
- From Boom perspective, **each successive student rebellion unwanted**—in which **force was either threatened by strikers** (as at Cornell) or **used against them** (by G.I. presidents Kerr, Kirk, and Pusey at Berkeley, Columbia, and Harvard)
- In the end, **unwanted violence broke the youth fever**—killing of six students at **Kent State and Jackson State** briefly mobilized generation in 1970
- Following **"Days of Rage,"** polls showed **campus interest leading nation's list of problems**, and **older generations showed fixation on youth opinion** unlike anything since days of young Missionaries
- **18-year-olds awarded the vote**, and **national political conventions quadrupled number of under-30 delegates**
- In 1970, **Silent Charles Reich** wrote rapturous best seller about how Boom's **"Consciousness III" would lead to *The Greening of America***

### Post-1973: Grinding Pessimism

- Then, as war wound down and draft ended, **Boomers began heeding their Beatle mentors' "simple words of wisdom: *Let It Be*"**
- **When economy went sour in 1973**, youth mood turned to **grinding pessimism**
- Storm having passed, **last-wavers came of age amid gray generational drizzle** of sex, drugs, unemployment, and what **Lansing Lamont** called **"lost civility"** on campus
- In politics, Boom settled in as **more apathetic and just plain illiberal** than their G.I. parents could ever have imagined
- As Boom showed **air of resignation** about government and business, aging G.I.s began acquiescing to youth cult of self—and Americans kept running

## RISING ADULTHOOD: Searching for Inner Meaning

> "I have made no plans because I have found no plans worth making... All too many people are just waiting for life rather than living." —**Berkeley *Daily Californian***, 1971

- Boomers in their twenties remained detached—yet in smaller strokes of day-to-day existence, **began testing what they found within** on the world without
- Many began showing **emotional intensity and zeal** older generations found strange, even compulsive
- **Exercise faddists** searched for "runner's high"; **backpackers** with graduate degrees sparked boom surrounding **unlike anything since turn of century**; **meditative diet faddists** triggered what historian **Harvey Levenstein** terms **"century's Second Golden Age of Food Quackery"**
- Through 1970s, people of all ages still looked to Boomers' values guidance, and **Boom trends soon blossomed into national attitudes**—for example, **as consumer brand loyalties weakened** and "Made in the U.S.A." became passé among cognoscenti

### Workplace Changes

- But **biggest news came in workplace**
- In athletics, first occupation over which they gained leverage, likes of **Andy Messersmith** to **Joe Namath** proclaimed **"Free agency"** after which sporting life grew **more argumentative and less team-oriented**
- A few years later, growing flood of **late-starting Boomers began to spread new traits throughout economy**
- Insisted on having **"meaningful"** (read: un-G.I.-like) careers; by mid-1970s **America's postwar productivity surge came to abrupt end**
- Not drawn to industrial or service jobs, **cutting-edge Boomers preferred smallish, eclectic businesses**
- Homes began bristling with **offices, neighborhoods with support services**—**infrastructure of work piece-by-piece**, so economy was retooling to match Boom's personality

### New Self-Religion

- **Thirtyish first-wavers** also actively designing new concept of self-religion
- **Boom heralded "New Age Man" with "Manifesto of the Person"**, asserting **"our sovereign right of self-discovery"**
- In this **"Human Potential Movement,"** self-described as **"reaction to industrialized, mechanized thinking,"** large numbers of Boomers began dabbling in **psychic phenomena and experiments in communal living**
- Whether immersed in **Tai Chi, Zen, beta waves**, or other New Age mind states, **Boomers built churches** in the privacy of their own heads
- **Urbanska** termed this **"Sheilasm,"** naming it after friend named **Sheila** who had **"this little voice inside" saying "God is whatever I feel"**
- **Conversions to "born-again" fundamentalism** became more common than at any time in living memory
- **Boom religion returned Calvinist notion of "calling"** to its original emphasis on **immediate and subjective**
- Rising adult did not have to spend lifetime preparing G.I. "works" for salvation
- **Boomers viewed spiritual life the way Richard Armour described their consumption:** They wanted it all—**"NOWWWWW!"**

### The Yuppie Phenomenon

- Enter the **"yuppie"**: Literally, word derives **"young urban professionals,"** but that's misleading—**only ~5% of Boom match demographic** (urban, professional, affluent) definition
- Much larger proportion fit **subjective definition**: self-immersion, impatient desire for personal satisfaction, and **weak civic instincts**
- **Everything a yuppie does**—what he eats, drinks, listens to, lives in, and invests-for—sends **aggressive message about G.I.-style culture and institutions**, at time when G.I.s are losing energy to resist
- **Yuppie spurns organized philanthropies** for causes he thinks he has discovered himself
- **Busiest work** occurs in **smallest workplaces**: home, small business, PTA, day-care center, town zoning board, "privatized" governing body
- His method of achieving society's common change—**unassociated individuals**, each acting pursuant to his own compass—is **opposite of the cohesive, peer-pressured G.I. approach**; in like way **word "yuppie"** appeared 1981, just after **most Boomers chose Reagan over Carter**, and **signaled acceptance of adult social roles**
- **Having finished task of reforming the outer world**, this generation gradually **began taking on the outer**

## APPROACHING MIDLIFE: Growing Up vs. New Grown-ups

- Where Silent once prided themselves on ability to **"grow young"** with advancing age, **Boomers look upon themselves as "growing up"** to new sense of responsibility and self-denial—what **P.J. O'Rourke** calls **"new seriousness"**
- One advertising flack labels Boomers **"the New Grown-ups"** and claims they are launching an **"era of less-than-instant gratification"**
- **Cheryl Merser discovered**: "One advantage of grown-up is someone who can buy cookies and not eat the whole package at once"
- **Fastest-track yuppies** showing growing taste for **ascetic self-denial**—preferring effective products names (toothful, noneffeminate, non-aerosol, non-nitrate, even "no-color" mascara) that flaunt what consumer *is not* consuming

### Values and Judgment

- Surveys show **Boomers are more apt to believe that patience is necessary to appreciate value** and more likely to buy products that *are* good than products that *taste or feel* good
- Aging has **nonapologetic quality**—as though now that they've older, they know better
- **More in parallel than collectively**, Boomers asserting **judgments that reflect perfect moral order of Pepperland**
- Although they have grown reasonably comfortable with aging G.I. leaders who adopt their "values" terminology, **Boomers still see themselves as embodiment of moral wisdom**
- In matters of **right and wrong**, most Boomers now care as little for opinions of their 13er juniors as they ever cared for opinions of their G.I. and Silent elders
- At very moment **Boomers patched up rift with parents**, notes journalist **Henry Allen**, **"they saw they still had problems with materialistic Republican reactionaries, except that the reactionaries were twenty years younger"**

> "A generation that when young trusted nobody over 30 now trusts nobody under 30." —**Alan Kors**, Pennsylvania history professor

### New Puritanism and Social Criticism

- Growing chorus of social critics noticing **Boom-led** (and often 13er-targeted) **"New Puritanism"** of circa-1990 America
- **Fortyish Boomers** beginning to police **"politically correct" behavior**, pass **"anti-ugly" zoning ordinances**, punish students for "inappropriately directed laughter," circulate **"Green Lifestyle" guides** and attach **"Green Seals"** to products, ban obscene music, promote "chastity," and support novel forms of **corporal punishment and boot-camp incarceration** that G.I.s would never imagine
- **Abortion debate** rages in deadly earnest, with shades of Boom: **last-wavers imagined pro-wave wave pro-choicers against last-wave pro-lifers**
- **Smoking or regular drinking** (observes *New York Times* writer **Molly O'Neill**) becoming **"new Scarlet Letters"** among ex-flower children
- When G.I.s were forties, **"Buy you a drink?" and "Have a smoke?"** were friendly icebreakers between strangers; now **M.A.D.D.'s Candy Lightner** attacks social drinkers (and **Dick Durbin** airborne smoking) as dangerous, even immoral

> "There is no such thing as being too rude to a smoker." —Boom activist

- **Now gaining real power**, Boomers **do not inherently dislike government**—idea of using state to tell people what to do suits them just fine
- Their task is to **redirect public institutions toward what they consider as socially redemptive purpose**
- Casting aside **Silent preoccupation with process and expertise**, Boomers (when focused) zero in on essentials, **choose between right and wrong**, and act accordingly
- **Boomers of all ideological stripes**—from **Oliver North and Fawn Hall** to "Animal Rights" lab bombers—can be easily attracted to lawless in pursuit of higher purpose
- In **Washington, D.C.**, member of **Mich Snyder** beckons social activists to invite arrest **"in the name of a just and loving God,"** while in California **"Earth First!" eco-saboteurs** apply motto **"No Compromise in Defense of Mother Earth"**
- **New York Reverend Al Sharpton** summons blacks to **"burn the city down"** over alleged injustices, while **Shelby Steele** calls upon blacks to examine **"the content of our character"** and reject racial preferences as **"kindness that kills"**
- When Boom-driven movements produce legislative enactments—such as **Oregon's refusal to spend Medicaid funds** on operations considered too expensive or unlikely of success—**the budgetary result can be less important than the no-pain-no-gain message** to society at large
- **Addressing America's fiscal and social needs**—from crime to health and education, **Boomers are far more inclined** (than other generations) to share **Karl Zinsmeister's** view that **"genuine compassion demands that we

